<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOAP OPERA CONTINUES FOR KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They didn't have to hand out a description of the
injury to tell us it was something to worry about. You could see it
by the way Dr. Norman Scott solemnly knelt by Patrick Ewing's
injured right foot, and you knew it from Ewing's vacant stare. By
now, we know that look and we all know the drill, along with the
familiar sad walk to the locker room and out of another playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   It came six minutes and change into the first quarter, and
everyone who lived through last spring was amazed by the irony.
Game 2, Eastern Conference finals, at Indianapolis. A year ago,
Ewing played with a slight tear of his left Achilles', played right
until he missed a shot at the buzzer that sent the series back to
New York tied at one.
</P>
<P>
   As Ewing left the old Market Square Arena floor that night with
an eerie howl, we didn't know he would not play another minute in
the postseason. This time, his slow limp from the bench Thursday
night offered no long-range clues. The injury, called a sprained
peroneal tendon, is not to the bottom of the foot _ though it turns
out he missed practice on Wednesday with discomfort there as well.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that Ewing has had a high tolerance for pain.
Yet minutes into the second quarter came the announcement that he
was done for the night, and the Knicks went on to lose, 88-84, to
trail the Eastern Conference finals, 2-0. Ewing will undergo an MRI
Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   So here we go again and, when you really think about it, when
you consider the previous series, the Knicks were already on the
same road they roamed last spring. It is always a soap opera with
this team, one thing or another. The last three years with Ewing
have been worthy of a weekly prime-time hour. And the Knicks
without their 37-year-old center, well, they have never been Home
and Garden material either.
</P>
<P>
   If you made some of them take a lie-detector test, you would
probably learn that at least half believe, or want to believe, that
they are better off without him. Sometimes they are, for a night or
two. They did shrug off the big man's departure Thursday night and
dragged the Pacers into one of those physical death struggles that
give Pat Riley goosebumps.
</P>
<P>
   After their 102 points and 10 3-pointers in Game 1, the Pacers
weren't exactly giving a repeat perimeter performance to begin
with. This time, Austin Croshere short-armed so many jumpers you
thought his right arm was going to crack at the elbow. This time,
until the fourth quarter, Rik Smits looked closer to retirement
than he did to the finals, and Dale Davis didn't take a first-half
shot, and the Pacers' jump shooters consequently had more hands in
their faces.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fact that certain areas of the floor open up when Ewing
disappears. Larry Johnson slid into his customary spot on the post
and had himself an ``L'' of a time, spinning into the teeth of the
Indiana defense for a game-high 25 points. Marcus Camby suddenly
rediscovered his high-wire muse. There was even a Chris Dudley
sighting, for those wondering what had become of the $7 million
backup center.
</P>
<P>
   If history is repeating with Ewing, then, of course, the Knicks
will want to believe they can come back against these enigmatic
Pacers, with or without him. They won against all odds last year.
Yet if Ewing's injury isn't a temporary setback, then it should be
obvious to all that the last words the Knicks want to hear from him
is, ``Go get me my ring.'' After last year, they ought to already
know they can't get it without him.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing hasn't been their centerpiece for a long time now. When
he's played, when he's been in shape and in sync with the others,
he has been their missing piece. After 18 rebounds in Game 6 of the
Miami series, after 20 points and the winning basket in Game 7, one
television commentator actually said that Ewing was playing better
than ever. It was, of course, nonsense. This is a player who, in
his youth, would routinely drop 30 on teams in the playoffs. But in
the context of this Knicks team, playing for what it always wants
to believe are championship stakes, Ewing's contributions have
seemed more substantial, more heroic, than ever.
</P>
<P>
   With all the ice packs after every game and practice, with the
rebuilt wrist and scraggly knees, Ewing had been, for him, the
picture of health, at least until this week. When he returned in
December, the debate about whether the Knicks were better off with
him or without him resumed. For the big picture, the championship
the Knicks have not won since 1972, there is no debate. Friday
morning, there is only a soap opera we have seen before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
