<HEADLINE>
MANY LAKES, RIVERS ARE LOW IN KANSAS, MISSOURI BECAUSE OF DRY
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ You won't find many
holiday weekends where most people hope for rain, but this is one.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because as people head outdoors to celebrate Memorial Day, in
the middle of flood season, they'll find many streams and small
lakes withered into shallow, late-summer conditions by a regional
drought in Missouri and northeast Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   So a National Weather Service forecast for possible
thunderstorms in the region today, early Saturday and next week is
another cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're banging around at the all-time low water levels for May
on some (Ozark) streams,'' said Loyd Waite, a hydrologist for the
U.S. Geological Survey. ``We're having August flow levels in what's
normally our high-flow month. It's getting really serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Ozark rivers are still floatable, canoe vendors say. Large
federal reservoirs have plenty of water for boating.
</P>
<P>
   But dry conditions during what's normally the flood season could
spell trouble ahead in summer when evaporation rates increase. The
National Weather Service long-range forecast predicts higher
temperatures and lower rainfall than normal for this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan on Wednesday activated a drought
assistance team for agriculture and environmental problems. North
Missouri rivers and water supply lakes are low. Several Ozark float
streams are at record low levels for May, 3 feet low on the
Gasconade River in Phelps County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely experiencing August-like conditions in May,
not only in water level, but the (water) temperatures are higher
and there's more moss and algae than usual,'' said Stephen Zap, a
Missouri Department of Conservation agent in Phelps County. ``It
really looks like late summer on the river, and a bad late summer
at that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, ponds and community lakes that missed
recent showers are shrinking and leaving pontoon boats on mud
flats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down about three and a half feet,'' said Ken Richcreek,
Lake Waukomis Association president. ``There are some who have
their boats and docks on dry ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Water flows in northeast Kansas rivers are far below normal. The
Kansas Water Office on Thursday announced that some farmers without
first-use water rights could no longer draw irrigation water from
the upper Republican and Delaware river systems until rains
recharge the streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything that can compare with this spring
for dryness,'' said Bill Bunting, a meteorologist at the National
Weather Service in Pleasant Hill, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2.47 inches of rain has fallen at the Kansas City
International Airport this month in scattered showers, compared
with the 5.04 inches normal for May.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas are drier. Bunting's rain gauge at his home in Lee's
Summit, Mo., has recorded less than 0.10 inches this month. A
barely damp May followed bone-dry April's 0.65 inches of rainfall,
a record low. That's after a mild and dry winter, and that's left
Kansas City 8.44 inches below normal for rainfall in the past 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill has issued fewer
than 10 flood warnings this spring for the Kansas City region
compared with 150 last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, if we're going to get rain at any time of year, this
is it,'' Bunting said.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of upper-level disturbances, moist air and cool
fronts today and next week are the area's best chance in some time
for thunderstorms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Few canoeists will complain.
</P>
<P>
   The middle and lower segments of Missouri's float streams have
enough water for canoeists, especially those fed by large springs.
</P>
<P>
   But canoes are crunching across riffle gravel on smaller
headwater streams that are normally flush with water in late
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get in the upper Niangua because you'll have
ankle deep water in some places where normally you have waist-deep
water or better,'' said Alan Daniels, a Missouri Department of
Conservation agent for Dallas County. ``For the 13 years that I've
been here, it's as low as I've seen it for this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said the water level is not critical yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we don't get the June rains, it will be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen can still enjoy pools in the river's upper reaches if
they're willing to drag canoes through riffles, Daniels said, and
the Niangua below Bennett Spring, Mo., has plenty of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those rope swings that hang out over the water,'' he said,
``I'd shy away from them because of the shallow conditions unless
you physically check them.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar across Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Spring-fed streams like the Current River in the Ozark National
Scenic Riverways still have enough water flow for good canoeing,
park officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Canoe vendor Shane Van Steenis is launching float trippers on
both the Current River and the Jack's Fork River below Alley
Spring. But this month he halted floats on the Jack's Fork above
Alley Spring due to low water, something that usually doesn't
happen until mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had much rain,'' Van Steenis said. ``We need it and
we need it bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong rains can quickly rejuvenate stream flow. Although
Missouri needs major rains to return all soil moisture and water
levels to normal.
</P>
<P>
   If the rains don't come, fish kills likely will occur in small
ponds, shallow lakes and some rivers due to low oxygen and nutrient
buildup, said Steve Eder, a fisheries biologist for the Missouri
Department of Conservation. As is, shallow water will allow small
fish to be more easily eaten by predators and reproduction success
will diminish. So fishermen could eventually find fewer fish in
some waters in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The department also had to move 50,000 catfish fingerlings from
its Blind Pony Fish Hatchery near Sweet Springs, Mo., because a
water supply lake was low, Eder said. Fish were moved from cold
water trout hatcheries at parks like Roaring River State Park
during the winter because of low spring water flow, and that may
happen again this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The drought also affects creeks that serve upland areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest concern is if the weather pattern
continues much longer, it could be severe for the fish and wildlife
along those smaller tributaries and ponds,'' said Roger Wolfe of
Topeka, Kan., a regional fisheries and wildlife supervisor for the
Kansas Department of Wildlife and Parks.
</P>
<P>
   As is, more than 140 farmers in northeast and north-central
Kansas will be cut off from irrigation supply until the drought
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flow on the Republican River is running about 11 percent of
normal and on the Delaware River it's 8 percent of normal,'' said
Earl Lewis, an engineer for the Kansas Water Office.
</P>
<P>
   Western and southern Kansas have had enough rains to keep stream
flow normal. But the eastern areas need several rains before the
ground will become saturated enough to provide runoff for streams,
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a couple of days of rain to get well,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not currently in the forecast, only scattered
thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   But Missouri canoe trip operators like Van Steenis will be
watching for dark clouds and hoping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to have faith that it's going to rain,'' he
said. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
