u i BC-PERU-POLITICS-3RDLD-W     05-26 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERUVIAN GOVERNMENT DECIDES TO HOLD VOTE AS SCHEDULED 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 6th graf with updated quote; ADDS with 7th graf with
withdrawal of monitors; EDITS 8th, 11th grafs to conform; ADDS 12th
graf with quote)  
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ The government of President Alberto Fujimori said
Thursday that a runoff presidential election would be held on
Sunday as scheduled despite nationwide protests and calls from
Washington and other allies that it be postponed to assure a clean
ballot count.
</P>
<P>
   Unless reversed, the decision appeared to increase the
possibility of economic sanctions against Peru after it ignored the
recommendations of the Clinton administration, the Organization of
American States and several European and Latin American
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the announcement, violent clashes that had
left several people injured earlier in the day resumed, with
protesters setting fire to a balcony of the presidential palace and
hurling stones at the building and at the police, who responded
with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   During intense negotiations all week, U.S. and Latin American
diplomats had urged Peruvian officials to delay the vote so a
computer system used to count the vote could be overhauled and
rechecked by independent auditors.
</P>
<P>
   A brief announcement that the National Elections Committee had
voted 3-2 to go forward with the election was met with shock by
international observers who had become increasingly hopeful that
Fujimori had decided to given in to international pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are quite disappointed,'' said Eduardo Stein, head of an
election observer team for the Organization of American States,
``because other options were being intensively considered.'' He
added, ``It's been a terrible week.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, the Organization of American States
announced that it was withdrawing its monitors from the election
Sunday, a few hours after the Atlanta-based Carter center said it
was doing so.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. Embassy official said of the Fujimori decision:
``The U.S. government deeply regrets this outcome. Even a
relatively brief delay would have put the Organization of American
States in a position to speak to the integrity of the election
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori had appeared to be going back and forth on the election
scheduling during the past three days, but western diplomats said
that mounting protests had perhaps strengthened the hand of
hard-liners in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Just Wednesday night, Fujimori had said in an interview in the
government palace that ``the possibility for an adjustment of the
election date exists. We are in a fluctuating situation.'' In an
interview Thursday night, Francisco Tudela, Fujimori's vice
presidential running mate, said that the decision was a ``close
call'' and that the electoral commission ``could not escape the
constitution and the elections law.'' Under the law, he said, the
election could not be held more than 30 days after results of the
first-round presidential vote were announced.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral crisis had been gathering momentum since Alejandro
Toledo, the opposition candidate, dropped out of the race last
Thursday, saying there was no reason to compete in a fraudulent
election. He said he would rejoin the contest if it were postponed
by several weeks, with guarantees for a free vote.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing Thursday's announcement, Toledo said, ``This will
bring Peru enormous instability, with totally unpredictable
political and economic consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   A wave of strikes and street demonstrations that followed
Toledo's withdrawal from the race peaked Thursday, and grew
increasingly violent.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of protesters attacked the offices of the National
Elections Commission, the highest government body that supervises
the elections, and broke windows and damaged a door with rocks,
pipes and at least one Molotov cocktail. Scores of people were
arrested in the northern jungle city of Iquitos for blocking roads,
and police used tear gas to clear protesters gathering in front of
the government palace here in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Truck drivers and teachers staged a strike in the Andean city of
Cuzco, a Toledo stronghold. Bands of university students in Lima
and Arequipa repeatedly attacked riot police officers with stones,
and the police counterattacked with tear gas through much of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a growing number of influential businessmen had
warned that holding the uncontested election on Sunday could mean
years of economic sanctions and tensions with Washington that could
impede investment and growth. Their arguments were strengthened
through the week as Peruvian bond and stock prices dropped sharply
and foreign financial institutions issued risk warnings that
threatened to increase interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the government's policies on the campaign and
political process have been inconsistent. Several television
stations allied with the government had begun airing Toledo
commercials and coverage of his rallies, while tabloid newspapers
thought to be directed by Fujimori's intelligence service has
softened their negative coverage of Toledo's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, three unidentified men Wednesday night broke into
the offices of an opposition journalist said to hold incriminating
videotapes of Vladimiro Montesinos, Fujimori's intelligence chief,
meeting with election officials. The journalist, Fabian Salazar,
said the burglars tied him up and tortured him as they demanded
that he reveal his sources within the intelligence service who gave
him copies of the tapes that apparently were made by Montesinos
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar said they cut through his left wrist to the bone with a
saw during their questioning. He was hospitalized after his
videotapes, archives and computer disks were stolen. Human rights
activists said Salazar's descriptions of his ordeal, which were
verified by doctors, may represent the worst example of torture in
Peru in at least two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
