u k BC-EDIT-MEAT-INSPECTION-     05-26 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEAT-INSPECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A THREAT TO MEAT INSPECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, May 26:
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Texas undermined the safety of the nation's
food supply on Thursday by denying the government's authority to
enforce critical regulations setting limits on the amount of
harmful bacteria in ground beef sold to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The case was the first legal test of the Agriculture
Department's power under the Federal Meat Inspection Act to rely on
new scientific methods, as opposed to the old ``poke and sniff''
tests, to protect consumers from food-borne illness. It arose last
year when the department shut down the Supreme Beef Processors'
plant in Dallas after the plant failed three tests for salmonella
contamination over a period of 12 months. The company sued,
contending that the government lacked authority to enforce its new
regulations, which use excessively high levels of salmonella as an
indicator of an unsanitary plant.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Thursday's ruling was not surprising. Judge A. Joe
Smith signaled where his sympathies lay last December when he
ignored public health concerns and extended an earlier injunction
allowing the plant to remain open while the case was being
adjudicated. Still, the judge's rejection of the government's use
of salmonella sampling to determine the existence of serious
sanitation problems at a plant was startling.
</P>
<P>
   Under the judge's strange reasoning, a plant that produces
Supreme Beef's dismal salmonella test results might still be
perfectly clean. The judge was troubled by the idea of penalizing a
plant when the meat may already have been contaminated when it
arrived there. Yet nothing requires a plant to accept dangerous
food, and if it does accept bad meat, its grinders will surely
become contaminated while processing it, posing a risk of
contamination to all other food passing through the grinders. That
seems exactly the sort of hazardous condition the statute was
intended to remedy.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of logic and science, the excessive presence of
dangerous salmonella in any meat turned out by a plant should be
deemed evidence that conditions at the plant are unsanitary. The
vast majority of large beef-processing plants in this country have
systems that keep tainted beef out of their plants and are in
compliance with the U.S.D.A. salmonella standards, so it is hardly
unreasonable to ask Supreme Beef Processors to meet the same
salmonella standard.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department is likely to ask for an expedited
appeal of this misguided decision. But Congress could end the
controversy by passing legislation affirming the government's power
to institute its new system of microbial testing and standards for
policing meat safety. It should do so immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
