<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTE ALMOST BOOTED GAME WITH PENALTY AGAINST MODANO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Had the Avalanche gone on to lose Game 6 of the Western
Conference Finals on Thursday night, Adam Foote would have spent a
long summer replaying his foolish high stick to the face of Mike
Modano over and over.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty, which came away from the puck, gave the Stars a
5-on-3 power play for 73 seconds. With Chris Drury already serving
a tripping penalty, Brett Hull needed only 47 seconds to beat
Patrick Roy from the left crease to tie the score at 1-1 at the
12:37 mark of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dodged a bullet for the first part, a great pass by (Sergei
Zubov),'' Avs coach Bob Hartley said. ``There was not much you can
do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs had taken a 1-0 lead eight minutes earlier on Ray
Bourque's first playoff goal. They had already killed an earlier
Stars power play and were 47 seconds away from killing a second and
retaining the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Foote's penalty drastically changed that scenario. Modano had
passed the puck up ice and was making his way to the Avs' zone
along the left-wing board. Foote, always a physical presence,
inadvertently hit Modano with the butt-end of his stick in the face
going for a body check.
</P>
<P>
   With goals at a premium and the Avs facing elimination,
surrendering any kind of man advantage was not wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't scored enough goals this series and our penalty
kill has to stop their power play,'' Avs winger Dave Reid said
before Game 6. ``Those two factors could change the series.''
</P>
<P>
   It almost did. LOOKING FOR FIREPOWER
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for firepower in the third period, Avs coach Bob
Hartley put wingers Peter Forsberg and Adam Deadmarsh on Joe
Sakic's line. Center Chris Drury was then teamed with wingers Dave
Andreychuk and Milan Hejduk.
</P>
<P>
   That line was on the ice for Drury's game-winner on a shot from
the point by Ray Bourque at the 16:09 mark. POWER PLAY POOR
</P>
<P>
   The Avs continued to perform poorly on the power play. They
squandered three chances in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   How much has the man advantage meant to the Avs in the playoffs?
Against Detroit, five of 13 goals came on the power play and 15 of
39 coming into Game 6. The Stars have held them to 3-for-30 in the
series. TAKING HEAT
</P>
<P>
   Avs center Joe Sakic has taken plenty of heat lately from the
local media. A ``Denver Post'' columnist wondered in print
yesterday if the captain's ``C'' on Joe Sakic's sweater didn't
stand for ``choke.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 20 days since Sakic scored a goal. He has had a
forgettable series, scoring no goals on 23 shots. After coming up
empty on two overtime chances in Game 5, Sakic was asked if he has
ever endured a scoring drought as frustrating as this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, just not in the playoffs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though Sakic has played poorly. He has been one of
the Avs' best players, but has had a hard time putting the puck in
the net.
</P>
<P>
   He assisted the game-tying goal in Game 5 and fed Ray Bourque on
Thursday night with a perfect in-stride pass to the slot where
Bourque beat Ed Belfour high for the 1-0 lead at the 4:30 mark of
the second period. HEJDUK TURNED BACK
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame Avs winger Milan Hejduk if he has Ed Belfour on the
brain. Hejduk has two goals in the series, but he also has been
stoned on some quality scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   His fifth shot of Thursday night's game came with less than four
minutes gone in the third period. It had game-winner written all
over it. Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher turned the puck over along
the board below the net. Avs winger Dave Andreychuk got it and fed
Hejduk on top of the crease for a one-timer.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour blocked it with his chest and the Stars cleared it out
of the zone. AVS GOOD IN 6s
</P>
<P>
   The Avs are 7-3 in Game 6s since moving to Colorado for the
1995-96 season. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
