<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CONFIDENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS CONFIDENT THEY'LL PUT AWAY AVALANCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Stars did everything they needed to do Thursday
night to close the Western Conference Finals. Except win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played pretty well,'' Stars forward Mike Keane said. ``I
think it was a pretty good game all around. We didn't give up many
shots. Our special teams were good. Eddie (Belfour) was strong. So
back in our building for Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado center Chris Drury scored the game-winner on a
deflection at 16:09 of the third period, giving the Avalanche a 2-1
victory in Game 6. But while he killed the Stars' chances of
closing a series for the ninth consecutive time they have had a
chance, Drury's goal did nothing to the Stars' spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars figure that's the way the puck bounces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's why the series is seven games,'' Stars winger
Blake Sloan said. ``Sometimes you get a bounce, and sometimes you
don't. I think (Thursday night) we were on the short end of the
stick, but maybe a couple of the other games we won, maybe we
shouldn't have. I think it all balances out in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a Game 7 for the first time since last season's
Western Conference Finals against the Avalanche _ a 4-1 victory for
Dallas _ the Stars are ready to match Colorado's desperation
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can say or do right now,'' Stars center
Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``You just have to get yourself ready. It's
going to be a lot of heart and determination and whoever wants it
more will win the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the Stars got another goal from Brett Hull, who
has scored five of his team's 11 goals. It came on a 5-on-3, making
the Stars 4-for-25 for the series on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had 27 shots, the most they've had since Game 2, and
held Colorado to 21, the fewest the Avs have had since Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been the best game the Stars have played all
playoffs. It just wasn't good enough to close the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it gives us confidence,'' Stars defenseman Derian
Hatcher said. ``I think we're confident if we do well and put the
same game on the ice, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Stars returned home feeling pretty good about themselves
despite the loss and in spite of the loss of defenseman Richard
Matvichuk to a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   The series is back in the Stars' court, right where they want
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wanted to win (Thursday night),'' Stars center Mike
Modano said. ``We wanted to come here and get that fourth game and
move on, but that's why home ice is so important. Games 4 and 5
were real big games, and to get home ice and make sure we didn't
lose it, we've put ourselves in a great position. It's one game
takes all now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
