<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-DISNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER AND DISNEY REACH CABLE DEAL FOR ABC 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ending one of the most rancorous negotiations in the
history of cable television, Time Warner Inc. and the Walt Disney
Co. completed a deal that allows the cable company to continue
carrying Disney's ABC television stations for the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney stations reach 3.5 million Time Warner Cable
customers in seven cities, including New York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides called the deal mutually beneficial. But the
financial terms were not disclosed and estimates of the value of
the deal for Disney varied from $1 billion to $2 billion. Disney
executives would only say they were ``happy'' with the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at America Online and Time Warner acknowledged on
Thursday that they wanted the cable company to reach a deal as soon
as possible, knowing that Time Warner had made a blunder by letting
the dispute become so open that it drew unwanted attention to the
proposed merger between the companies.
</P>
<P>
   In return for permission to carry ABC's signals through May
2006, the cable company agreed to convert the Disney Channel by
2003 from a service that viewers have to pay extra for to one that
is included in their basic package.
</P>
<P>
   It will begin carrying Disney's Toon Disney and SoapNet channels
on some of its systems and expand its distribution of Disney's ESPN
2 and ESPN Classic sports networks.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner also agreed to consider eventually adding two
unspecified Disney channels, which are currently under development,
to some of its systems.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the tensions, Time Warner had said that Disney
was demanding unacceptably exorbitant fees for its cable channels,
which would have forced Time Warner to significantly raise cable
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives said on Thursday that the amount of money
that was finally agreed upon was acceptable, that both sides had
compromised and that the cable company would not have to
significantly raise its rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for Time Warner, it's good for Disney and it's good
for our customers,'' said Ed Adler, a Time Warner spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had reached an agreement in principle last week
but completed the details late on Wednesday night, after months of
fingerpointing and accusations of bad faith. Tensions hit a peak on
May 1, when Time Warner halted the programming of the ABC-owned
stations for 39 hours and replaced it with a blue screen with the
statement, ``Disney Has Taken ABC Away from You.''
</P>
<P>
   With that move, Time Warner angered its customers, raised
concerns among federal lawmakers about its pending merger with
America Online and gave Disney a rare chance to publicly play the
role of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner did win some concessions of its own. Disney dropped
its demand that the company agree not to discriminate against its
offerings after its merger with AOL is approved. Disney has
expressed fears that the new company will wield too much control
over access to both the Internet and cable distribution.
</P>
<P>
   And Time Warner, which now has long-term deals with all of the
major networks, will not have to worry about losing ABC for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Time Warner was maintaining a position of contrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret the way that the dispute unfolded and that it got to
a point where consumers were caught in the middle,'' Adler said.
``We have put this dispute behind us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY-NYT &LR;      05-26 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE KNICKS, AN UNWELCOME FEELING FROM 1999
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The longer the second half dragged on, the more
uncomfortable the game grew for the New York Knicks. They had
already lost Patrick Ewing to a sprained right foot. And with less
than a minute left _ and their world beginning to resemble Game 2
against Indiana, 1999 _ they were also about to lose their lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller made two free throws with 28 seconds left, putting
the Pacers ahead by two. The wild bunch at Conseco Fieldhouse was
on its feet, screaming ``DEE-fense! DEE-fense!'' One or two more
stops, and Miller and his team could waltz into Madison Square
Garden with a 2-0 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   No one in New York had seen the Knicks at the Garden since their
pulsating comeback against Miami in Game 6 of the semifinal series
last Friday. The players returning home bore no resemblance,
especially after this deflating 88-84 loss.
</P>
<P>
   On their last offensive possession, Latrell Sprewell backed the
6-foot point guard Travis Best down into the post and, with Jalen
Rose sprinting to double team, released a shot that bounced high
off the back rim with 5.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Davis rebounded and was immediately fouled. Now, Davis
being a poor free-throw shooter and all, the Knicks were hoping to
get some kind of prayer play to work at the end. But they could not
even get to that point because they botched one of the most
fundamental plays in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Missing the first free-throw badly, Davis also missed the
second. But with only Allan Houston and Sprewell positioned on the
blocks to grab a rebound, Davis went over the top of Charlie Ward,
grabbed his own miss and fed Jalen Rose as the building nearly
imploded with noise.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, one of the league's most resilient teams, had forgot
to block out the shooter. Unreal. No one got the shooter.
</P>
<P>
   After it ended, Sprewell slammed the basketball to the floor.
Camby grabbed the ball and ricocheted it hard off the backboard.
Having come so close to persevering in Ewing's absence again and
pulling off a victory with their grit and heart, they fell victim
to brainlock.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson and Camby and Kurt Thomas turned in great
supporting performances, the kind they will need to duplicate if
Ewing is in fact out for any length of time.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, everything went through Johnson on offense, and it
appeared that was enough for New York. He would back the gangly
Rose into the post, using his brawn and guile to score inside on
left-handed layins or rise for a short fall-away jump shot or draw
a foul and get to the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   He was making every big play imaginable, finding cutting
teammates, moving the ball around the perimeter until someone was
open. But the Pacers kept close, never trailing by more than six in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson finished with 25 points and seven rebounds. Houston,
too, hit several clutch jumpers in the face of Miller, shots that
could have easily demoralized the Pacers. But they showed their
character, too.
</P>
<P>
   Camby awoke from his Game 1 slumber and began hitting the boards
with purpose. He made only 3 of 7 shots, but kept Austin Croshere
in check and made good on his word to become more active and
passionate about going to the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than any other Knick over the next week, he will
have to morph into a special type of player, slide along the
baseline and follow missed shots, find a way to go up and over
Indiana's frontline.
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing is out, Camby, Johnson, Thomas and Chris Dudley used
sparingly is all they have.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was recently asked if he had thought about attending Pete
Newell's Big Man Camp in Hawaii. The summer clinic, whose alumni
include pivots like Bill Walton, Hakeem Olajuwon and Shaquille
O'Neal, is geared toward improving the skills of the
7-foot-and-over crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he said. ``Hawaii's too far. I'll stay out here and
work with the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby was asked because it's no secret he could use a few
low-post lessons, develop a baby hook, a drop step, anything
resembling a go-to move. The Knicks' 6-foot-11-inch dynamic young
forward has gradually gone from the unknown phenom of the 1999
playoffs to the player who has been included in everyone's game
plan this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk on the court was, `Make sure you block out Marcus,'''
Camby said the day after he was neutralized by Indiana in Game 1 of
the Eastern Conference finals. ``They know what I did last year
cost them a trip to the finals. They're not going to let me do the
things I did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after skying over Indiana's frontline and changing shots
and his team's travel plans, Camby needs a go-to move.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pacers have truly figured out the Knicks _ and it seems
as if they are off to an impressive start _ Hawaii does not seem
such a faraway place to go find it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
