<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6168 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-COLLIN-AZR &LR;      05-26 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM TO WALK IN THE SUNSHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BARBARA YOST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(GILBERT, Ariz.) - For the first time since he was 5, Collin
Cassinat is walking in sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with a genetic disorder that makes him hypersensitive
to the sun, the 11-year-old has lived much of his life in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Windows in his home are tinted and covered with blinds. The
family van is outfitted with blackout curtains. When Collin goes to
school, he dashes from car to classroom covered with a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   He waits until sundown to play outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Collin received the gift of freedom - a pale blue
garment that covers him head to toe and blocks ultraviolet rays.
Cooled by ice packs fitted into the suit, the boy now can venture
outdoors even at high noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll give him a little more independence, and it will give
him a little more of a normal life,'' said his mother, Cindy
Cassinat. ``He won't have to be on the inside looking out.''
</P>
<P>
   The clothing came from the HED Foundation, a Virginia-based
agency that aids children suffering a variety of disorders,
including sensitivity to sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Collin's condition is called xeroderma pigmentosum. Only about
130 cases of XP are known in the United States, with an estimated
1,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the grandmother of two English boys with a related
disorder challenged the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration to design a protective garment. Using space
technology, NASA made its first suit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more than 50 children have received the
UV-protective clothing. The $2,000 cost of each suit is paid
through donations, said HED Foundation president and founder, Sarah
Moody.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, talk show host Rosie O'Donnell orchestrated a
$100,000 contribution from Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freedom we have given these children you would not
believe,'' Moody said. ``It's given them a quality of life they
would not have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Collin's first adventure outdoors was a romp in his yard. Then
he walked down the street to visit his friend Kevin Dompier. That
felt ``cool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Greenfield Elementary School, he could join his classmates at
recess instead of playing in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   There have been longer trips - an outing to Home Depot with his
dad, Tony, and to big brother Christopher's late-afternoon
graduation from Gilbert High School.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing her son gamboling outside during the day - even in
clothes designed to protect him - has left Cindy Cassinat a little
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The suit's soft fabric, called Sun Weave, seems so flimsy, she
said. Accustomed to covering every inch of her son's body for so
many years, she cinches the hood tight around his eyes underneath
goggles and makes him wear an additional hat.
</P>
<P>
   She has had to put her faith in NASA technology, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit isn't a perfect solution. Putting on the whole outfit -
including pants, jacket, gloves, socks, veil and goggles - takes
about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Collin gets hot despite wearing a bulky cooling vest.
</P>
<P>
   And dressed in a suit that he says makes him look ``bluey,''
Collin attracts attention. At Christopher's graduation, some kids
teased him. Even adults stared.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy remains concerned about the suit's protective powers. She
fears letting Collin lift the veil to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Given the severity of the boy's disorder, her fears are well
founded. Exposure to sunlight for just minutes would cause his skin
to redden, burn and blister. An overdose could kill him.
</P>
<P>
   He has had several operations to remove skin cancers.
</P>
<P>
   But for special occasions, the suit will free Collin from his
daytime confinement. Tony Cassinat wants to plan outdoor family
excursions.
</P>
<P>
   Collin's friends think he looks good and a little ``scary'' in
his suit. They're glad he can play outside now even if it's just a
walk down the street to hunt rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never got to go out in the day. He could only play at
night,'' said buddy Jare LaRiviere, 9. ``It's pretty cool for
Collin.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Barbara.Yost(at)ArizonaRepublic &QL; 
.com or (602) 444-7936. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
