<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-WHISKEYTOWN-GRAVEYARD     05-26 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISKEYTOWN-GRAVEYARD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NORTHERN CALIFORNIA CEMETERY MAKES NO BONES ABOUT UNUSUAL GRAVES  &HT;     By KEVIN FAGAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHISKEYTOWN, Calif. _ Louis Orwell must have been one feisty
cowboy, because he sure as heck got the last word.
</P>
<P>
   Orwell was planted backside-up in this historic little Gold Rush
ghost town's cemetery, and this was no grave-digger screwup. His
headstone, a cut-and-welded sheet of iron decorated with carved
cowboy figures, explains:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanted to be buried face down, so the whole world could kiss
his a_,'' the marker reads, right alongside a picture of a
potbellied Orwell, Stetson hat on his head and a grin on his face.
``June 19, 1931 to Nov. 4, 1991.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the row a piece from him is Indian Mike's headstone, a
motorcycle molded from plastic. On it is the laminated picture of a
muscled, long-haired biker astride his machine, lips set firm
beneath ebony shades. What must have been his favorite beer-can
holder sits alongside _ a full can of suds jammed tight inside, the
top popped open for Indian Mike's ghostly refreshment.
</P>
<P>
   There are graveyards in California filled with headstones of
Hollywood stars, others that run videotape loops of the departed,
even some only for pets. And then there is Whiskeytown Cemetery _
the most wonderfully weird spot in the state in which to bury your
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Set deep in the mountains above Redding and Whiskeytown Lake,
this is where the bones of 19th century pioneers take eternal sleep
beside babies, farmers, bikers, cowboys and other recently departed
inhabitants of the modern world. There are about 800 graves in
colorful profusion in this free-form arena of grief, but it is so
isolated that most people do not even know it exists.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors know, though. And since 1963, when the pioneers'
graves were dug up and moved from what became the bottom of the
soon-to-be-filled lake, they have known that this is the place
where you can pay a few hundred bucks to Shasta County and bury any
body any way you want.
</P>
<P>
   That means  &UR; any  &LR; way _ there are folks buried in coffee cans,
upside-down on their heads, double-stacked, you name it. The
headstones are hand-done, in shaky handwriting chiseled or painted
onto wood, saw blades, chunks of concrete shaped like animals or
houses, or just about any conglomeration you can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we can tell, there is no other cemetery that is
quite like this in all of California, or even sounds like it comes
close,'' marveled Tracey Weatherby of the state Cemetery and
Funeral Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   What strikes you first as you stroll through the entrance gate
in the pole fence is the wacky stuff, like the biker and cowboy.
Over here is a teenage wrestler's headgear, nailed to a stump above
a pile of whiskey and beer bottles, and a motorcycle tank turned
into a headstone; over there is ``Dad's garden,'' a wood-chip patch
sporting a tiny redwood toolshed, complete with miniature rake and
hoe.
</P>
<P>
   Then you look closer. And you see the rest.
</P>
<P>
   You see the tiny graves, the ones with rotting teddy bears and
rattles and baby toys carefully arranged next to tombstones bearing
words so freshly aching you can almost see tears alongside the
letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all these months you've been there, just on the other
side, we tried so hard to touch you, but you were way too shy,''
reads the shakily done inscription on one pink wooden mrker cut
into the shape of a heart. ``... You've gone away to the other
side, but soon we plan to see you there, so honey, please don't
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The name on the marker is Alyssa Marie McCollum. There is just
one date, June 23, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Lilialani, 1 month old when she died on Jan. 17, 1995,
lies beneath a white plastic plate set in cement. Set meticulously
atop her 3-by-4-foot grave is a display of the things that must
have filled her little world: dolls and teddy bears, a red-and-blue
jump rope, three key-shaped rattles, a plastic Christmas picture of
the three kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our beloved daughter is in God's hands now,'' the plate reads.
</P>
<P>
   Other kids rest in elaborate wooden shrines with benches,
photos, shelves holding their favorite toys or excerpts from the
poem, ``Footprints,'' the greeting card staple about God carrying a
beloved one through hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, it is the children who had to memorialize their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sue'' chose to send her 77-year-old father, Page Lermill, into
the beyond with a headstone fashioned from a sawmill blade and an
accompanying poem laminated on wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for being there, unconditional love ... Sunday walks
for ice cream and comic books ... the truth about the ``Man in the
Moon'' and ``Falling Rock'' ... for loving my mother and telling me
often,'' she wrote. The grave is rimmed with 4-by-4 boards, and
figurines of deer and squirrels guard the saw blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you could say it's ... different,'' allowed Bob Schwan,
a Shasta County coroner's deputy who helps oversee the graveyard.
``As long as it's not offensive, we let anyone do whatever they
want. It lets them work out their sorrow creatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Works out real good for everyone involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwan said that when the county moved the original Whiskeytown
Cemetery out of the reservoir bed, the new site was intended only
for indigents. And for years, it did serve only the poor, ``but
eventually it got too popular, so we opened it up to anyone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have millionaires, homeless people, normal folks, kids, all
sorts there now. Everyone's welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are a county resident, the cost is $500 per plot.
Nonresidents add a $150 surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the attraction is being laid to rest in true nature,
with nothing to crowd the mountainous view but pines, blue skies
and the occasional bald eagle. And there is the comfort of knowing,
too, that you share space with genuine pioneers whose only other
visible legacies are a few scattered, ghostly houses on the other
side of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll find any spot on earth this pretty, this
wild, for a graveyard,'' Schwan said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what drew George Mills, 62, to the cemetery in October
when it came time to bury his 84-year-old wife, Lorraine. And
recently he was back, spray-painting the iron-grate fence he built
around her grave and tidying up the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to the lake for vacation in 1976, fell in love with it
and came back every summer after that,'' said Miller, brushing a
finger tenderly across the words, ``Mrs. Whiskeytown,'' painted on
a green sign on the fence. ``She's happy here, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills lived in South San Francisco until he and Lorraine moved
to nearby Shingletown a month before she died. He is never leaving,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I die, they're going to cremate me and just put me in
that same hole with Lorraine,'' Mills said. In the meantime, he
plans to make a marble headstone with words he can read as he sits
on the little steel-pipe-and-cedar bench he built in front of
Lorraine's fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'll say on the stone,'' Mills said, a faraway
look creeping into his eyes: ``God looked down on the Earth one day
and saw Lorraine's beautiful face...'' He stopped, scuffed a toe at
the mounded dirt and began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Mills said quietly when he found his voice again.
``If it wasn't for this place, this beautiful little place where I
could lay her down just the way I wanted...'' He stopped short
again, but this time brightened after a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for small favors like Whiskeytown,'' Mills said,
peering into the pine trees overhead with a smile. ``Thank God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
