<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT &LR;      05-26 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDOZA AND YANKS END TRIP ON UP NOTE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Ohio)  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The New York Yankees' world spins faster than any
other in baseball, from brilliance to darkness to brilliance. After
experiencing moments of ignominy on this road trip, they will
return in full gleam to Yankee Stadium on Friday, to play the
Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees thrashed the previously undefeated Chicago pitcher
James Baldwin and the White Sox Thursday night, 7-0, and moved into
a first-place tie with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, under the inspection of scouts sent here
specifically to see him, needed only 100 pitches to throw the
Yankees' second shutout of the season, and Ricky Ledee _ who will
lose his spot in the lineup if the Yankees make a trade _ drove in
three runs.
</P>
<P>
   From darkness to brilliance: The Yankees won the final two games
of the road trip and improved their record to 26-17. They are on a
pace to win 98 games. And Derek Jeter, the shortstop who is on the
15-day disabled list, is expected to play two minor league games
and be activated in time for Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch fielded a grounder and flipped to first for the
final out of the game, and catcher Jorge Posada tapped Mendoza on
the back of the neck. It was easy to forget that in the seventh
inning Wednesday, it looked as if the Yankees would lose their
fourth consecutive game and fall two games behind the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last three innings Wednesday and the first three
innings Thursday, the Yankees' offense erupted _ 18 runs and 21
hits over those six innings _ for back-to-back victories to finish
the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin had been 7-0 and had a chance to become the first
American League pitcher to accumulate eight victories. Quite
simply, this was just one of those nights when Baldwin's stuff was
lacking, when his command was poor. He kept falling behind in the
count.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee doubled home a run in the second. Scott Brosius came to
the plate, feeling better about his swing. In an attempt to prevent
his front side from flying open in his swing, Brosius had all but
eliminated his stride forward, and had a couple of hits Wednesday.
Facing Baldwin Thursday night in the second, Brosius took a pitch
out of the strike zone and blasted a high changeup for a two-run
homer. Yankees 3, Chicago 0.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer singled with the bases loaded in the third inning
and Paul O'Neill ran home, before Ledee rolled a two-run single to
give Mendoza a six-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts from the Cincinnati Reds and the Kansas City Royals came
to watch Mendoza. The Yankees have been asking around for
left-handed hitters, like the Reds' Dmitri Young and Michael Tucker
and the Royals' Johnny Damon. There was no telling what the scouts
would see in Mendoza. The right-hander, after all, had not started
a game in 18 days, and his control sometimes suffers _ his sinker
ball sailing high _ when he has too much rest. He struggled with
this in the early innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendoza, emboldened by the Yankees' early lead, managed to
throw strikes, lots and lots of strikes, getting ahead in the
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to pitch,'' Mendoza said through a translator. ``They
gave me the ball to pitch, and thankfully, I did well.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre said: ``He really didn't get in any trouble.
He really didn't stress at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who allowed only four hits and a walk, is 5-2 and has
more victories than any other Yankee starter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
