<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MATVICHUK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATVICHUK SUFFERS CONCUSSION; LEAGUE TO REVIEW HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER_ Colorado forward Dave Andreychuk's elbow to Richard
Matvichuk's head in the first period Thursday night sent Matvichuk
out of the game with a mild concussion and a red flag to the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been asked to take a look at it,'' NHL commissioner Gary
Bettman said. ``So since we're taking a look at it. It wouldn't be
appropriate to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL may not be talking, but the Stars were after their 2-1
loss to Colorado at the Pepsi Center in Denver, tying the Western
Conference Finals at three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it was an elbow in the head pretty simple,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said. ``Rules should be simple. If Matty is out, so
should (Andreychuck).''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate effects of Matvichuk's absence meant some more
lineup shuffling and extended minutes for Derian Hatcher, Dave
Manson and others. The extended effects, if Matvichuk does not
return, potentially could be devastating to one of the best
defensive tandems in the league and more controversy for the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Andreychuk hit (Matvichuk's) jaw, and I think his head
hit the glass,'' Hatcher said. ``Am I surprised? No. Andreychuk, if
you look through the series, has done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the season, the NHL has tried to come down on such
hits and has usually handed down suspensions accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The) coaching staff had meetings with the supervisors and the
referees and they talked about there is a time limit on hitting
guys once they make a pass,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``I
don't know, but I think the puck was at the blue line when
(Matvichuk) got hit and (Andreychuk) was coming from the red line.
So, I think he had one intention and one intention only and that
was to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, naturally, didn't see it quite that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bench, it seemed like a very fair hit,'' Avs coach
Bob Hartley said. ``This is the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also on to Game 7 where the Stars could be playing without
their most active defenseman in the series. Matvichuk has one goal
and three assists, including the assist on Joe Nieuwendyk's
overtime goal in Game 5. He also has 17 hits and 14 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   With him out, fewer players log more ice time. If he does not
return for Game 7 on Saturday, Hitchcock said that either Jamie
Pushor or Brad Lukowich could dress in Matvichuk's place.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Hatcher and Sergei Zubov saw more than 30
minutes of ice time. Stars assistant coach Rick Wilson still called
it their best defensive game in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had a pretty big effect,'' Hitchcock said. ``Matty plays
the second-most minutes on the team. But I thought we played a
great game and this is typical of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   If Matvichuk does return, he will embody a slogan written on the
Stars locker room board: ``The body will go anywhere the mind takes
it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
