A6174 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-SCHOOLS-CRITIQUE &LR;      05-26 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-CRITIQUE </SLUG>
  
 RESEARCHERS SAY DAVIS PLAN FOR SCHOOLS WON'T WORK  &HT;     By NANETTE ASIMOV 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A scathing critique of the state's strategy for improving
schools _ the strategy Gov. Gray Davis hopes will ``restore the
greatness of California education'' _ says the plan resembles a
broken jigsaw puzzle and is unlikely to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The damning conclusions are found in a thick report to be
released Friday by researchers from the University of California at
Berkeley and Stanford University who formed a group 17 years ago
called PACE: Policy Analysis for California Education.
</P>
<P>
   The report, written by respected academics, is the most
comprehensive criticism to date of California's multiyear attempt
to turn student achievement around. It reinforces earlier warnings
that state politicians in the 1990s acted hastily and did not
create a cohesive, thoughtful plan to reform public education in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms were prompted by the embarrassment and long-term
consequences of California children posting some of the worst test
scores in the nation. The initial legislation, enacted under former
Gov. Pete Wilson, was meant to be a clear formula for success:
</P>
<P>
   Create strong academic standards, then give teachers the books
and training to teach to those standards, and, finally, test
students on their progress and hold schools accountable for the
results.
</P>
<P>
   But the new critique says the plan's creators never coherently
linked the pieces. As a result, most teachers do not teach to the
standards, and a mishmash of different exams does not reflect them,
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, the state's system fails to provide a long-term
solution for the growing shortage of qualified teachers. It ignores
children of preschool age and appears to forget that colleges and
universities are the final link in the chain, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   School reform programs by the state resemble ``pieces of a
jigsaw puzzle just dumped from the box,'' the researchers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes at a time when state lawmakers are considering
new educational programs even as existing programs have yet to
trickle down to the classroom, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop the mad scramble to add more programs when we
don't know what is working,'' said co-author Elizabeth Burr of UC
Berkeley. ``You don't hear much talk about building in an
evaluation plan for these new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-author Mike Kirst, an education professor at Stanford and a
former president of the state Board of Education, predicted that
California students will become so fed up with the many disparate
exams they are expected to take _ many of which have little
connection to classroom instruction or college admissions _ that
they will refuse to take them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assessment system may just break down from a lack of
student participation,'' Kirst said. His report recommends a
simplified testing system.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were immediately rebuted by Ann Bancroft,
spokeswoman for Davis' education secretary, Sue Burr (no relation
to researcher Elizabeth Burr), and John Mockler, executive director
of the California Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Both said the report does not consider that Davis has just
recommended a $1.8 billion infusion of school money not earmarked
for specific programs, the largest one-time educational funding
boost in state history.
</P>
<P>
   To hear state officials tell it, California is in the middle of
its first intelligent school improvement strategy in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Davis became governor last year vowing to continue the program
and this year has presided over the start of a school rating system
that promises rewards for schools that improve and threatens state
intervention for those that do not.
</P>
<P>
   Mockler also defended the governor's attempts to attract and
retain qualified teachers. He said Davis has proposed an array of
bonuses and other incentives _ ``even home loans, for God's sake''
_ to entice skilled teachers to work in low-performing schools
where their efforts can do the most good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plans are interesting,'' Mockler said. ``But in the end, it's
the laws we make that distribute the funds. And if you track that,
you'll see an extremely focused agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirst said the state should not junk its reforms but do four
things to knit them together:
</P>
<P>
   -- Provide a timetable for tying academic testing to standards
and training teachers to teach to those standards.
</P>
<P>
   -- Create a plan that gets students _ from preschool to
university _ ready for the next level.
</P>
<P>
   -- Clarify the instructional system for about 25 percent of the
state's 6 million students who need special help in learning
English.
</P>
<P>
   -- Overhaul the education financing system so that local school
districts can have far more say over how they use state money.
</P>
<P>
   State Superintendent of Public Instruction Delaine Eastin said
that while the idea of greater spending flexibility is appealing,
money for specific programs is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those programs came about because there was a
class of students who weren't being served,'' she said, citing
programs for special education and gifted students as examples.
``Those programs each have a constituency. You just try to take
them away. Those are some of the most aggressive parents in
America. People in academic institutions sometimes forget that we
have a political process and that there is a reason why these
programs get established.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirst finds it encouraging that state testing officials are
working to make the test reflect the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's got potential,'' he said. ``We'd like to hear more
about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
