r s BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-26 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPORTUNITY KNOCKED, STARS DIDN'T ANSWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The score was tied. The clock was ticking. Bodies kept
tangling and scuffling in the corners.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had the Colorado Avalanche right where they wanted
them.
</P>
<P>
   Been there. Seen that. One unforgettable night, almost 12 months
ago _ it seems like 12 years _ they won a Stanley Cup on such a
smothering, shoulder-to-shoulder night.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the Stars didn't.
</P>
<P>
   This time opportunity knocked _ and the clatter only served to
wake up Colorado's Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there will be a Game 7 in this series that deserves a
dramatic final chapter. On a Chris Drury deflection off a Bourque
slap shot that was headed wide, with less than four minutes
remaining to play, the Avalanche prevailed, 2-1, at the Pepsi
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hey. That's the Stars' old script.
</P>
<P>
   A golden opportunity lost?
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a hockey game,'' Hitchcock said. ``On the road, I
guess, you're going to have to score more than one goal to win. But
we had chances, quality chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the game of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock chose to look at the broader picture. His team had
come into a noisy, partisan arena, and played a talented, desperate
team off its feet for more than 56 minutes. It nearly pulled it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing our way,'' the coach said. ``We're playing a
gritty, in-your-face hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we won a couple where they played well and were just
unfortunate, and now they've won a couple where we were
unfortunate. So I think this series is exactly where it should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but since when do the scales of justice have anything to
do with this?
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity knocked with a golden invitation Thursday night. And
the Stars couldn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   For once in this series, the shot numbers were going the
defending champs' way. The battle had been joined, as Hitch likes
to say. The Stars were winning faceoffs. Brett Hull, to use another
Hitchism, had ``taken a huge bite of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   On nights like this, you have to win. Hockey's semi-nightly
playoff drama doesn't guarantee another golden chance.
</P>
<P>
   For one, there is this thing called momentum. In the NHL
postseason, the concept well may not exist. But an absence of
momentum can be conspicuous, as the Avalanche displayed just
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in front of a boisterous, expectant home crowd, the Avs
appeared to come out anxious and uncertain. The only elixir that
seemed to unloosen them came when Dave Andreychuk slammed the
Stars' Richard Matvichuk into the glass with a right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's hockey. But it went unpenalized, even as Matvichuk
lay face-up on the ice, motionless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good,'' Hitchcock reported later. ``It was an elbow
to the head. So it's simple, right? If Matty is out, so should `38'
(Andreychuk's number).''
</P>
<P>
   The blow lingered in more ways than the ringing in Matvichuk's
head. Colorado coach Bob Hartley took advantage of the shuffling
and longer-shifting that Hitchcock was forced to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It left a big hole at their blue line,'' Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   The loss became doubly damaging when the Rip Van Winklesque
Bourque suddenly stirred. Acquired from Boston just to deliver
moments like this, Bourque had been wounded, silent and scoreless
before this night.
</P>
<P>
   But he put the Avs on the board first when he was left to walk
down the slot in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great performance,'' Hartley said. ``Tonight he carried
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   He carried them, as it turned out, back to Dallas, where an
anxious Game Seven awaits.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars should have never let it come to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
