<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' ABBOTT SURVIVES BROKEN BAT IN FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The pitcher's worst nightmare isn't blowing a save
or giving up a grand slam or even walking in the winning run in the
bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   No, the worst nightmare is much more personal, and it visited
the Mariners Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Abbott, scrambling to glove a grounder hit by the Orioles'
Harold Baines, was hit on the right side of the head by a hefty
fragment of Baines' broken bat in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   It could have cost Abbott an eye, but he caught a break. The bat
hit him flush rather than hitting him with either of the pointed
ends. He suffered cuts requiring eight stitches and a slightly
broken nose, but he was breathing and seeing effortlessly after the
Mariners' 5-1 loss to Baltimore. And that was enough to take a
little of the sting out of the game, in which the Orioles completed
a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott didn't want to go on TV afterward, but he was otherwise
cheerful, joking and laughing after having dodged a major bullet.
He had both X-rays and a CAT scan, and no major damage was seen,
although the right side of his head sustained considerable
swelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel lucky, very lucky,'' Abbott said. ``I have to be,
because all I ever saw was the ball. I never saw the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Rick Griffin came sprinting out of the Seattle dugout as
Abbott slumped to the ground, swollen and bleeding. He was joined
on the field by every member of the Mariners, plus manager Lou
Piniella, pitching coach Bryan Price and the next scheduled batter,
Baltimore's Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be there in less 10 seconds, and the swelling already
was considerable,'' Griffin said. ``That was extremely fast
swelling. But he never lost consciousness, and he kept talking,
which was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in pain and blood loss, Abbott never lost his sense of
humor. With the entire Mariners lineup gathered around him, he
broke up his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Jay Buhner that after this, Harold Baines better at
least give me an autographed bat,'' Abbott said, grinning slightly
at the recollection.
</P>
<P>
   As Abbott made his way from the trainer's room to his locker at
the far wall in the visitor's clubhouse in Camden Yards, he made
slow progress. It wasn't because he couldn't walk, it was because
many of his teammates and coaches came up to him to shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was the most emphatic, shaking Abbott's hand, then
giving him a big-league bear hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad to see you're OK, son,'' Piniella said. ``I
was really, really worried about you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to make a judgment about Abbott's next appearance
on the mound. The medical advice that Griffin shared with Abbott
was that after two days off, the pitcher could resume throwing.
Theoretically, that means Abbott could face the White Sox in
Seattle next week, but the Mariners will play it cool.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mariners were able to think about how lucky one
of their own had been, a fact that overshadowed a third consecutive
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll guarantee you that every pitcher's heart started pounding
to see that,'' fellow pitcher Brett Tomko said.
</P>
<P>
   All pitchers on both sides of the field have been there. The
winning pitcher Thursday, Mike Mussina, almost lost an eye on May
14, 1998, when he took a line drive from Cleveland's Sandy Alomar
just above his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen that happen before in real life,'' Mariners
pitcher Jamie Moyer said. ``But I've woken up in the middle of the
night having a nightmare about it. There's no worse nightmare for a
pitcher, really. If a line drive comes back at you, you can see
that. But when the ball and the bat are both coming at you, and the
bat's broken, that's trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Mussina knows about that. We all do.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Dan Wilson, one of the first to the scene, was also one
of the first to see that Abbott was still conscious and talking.
Wilson had been fearing the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he takes the point of that bat instead of having it hit him
the way it did, it would have been a disaster,'' Wilson said. ``Or
more of a disaster than it turned out to be. I'm just glad he's
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   On another night, the word ``disaster'' might be thrown loosely
to describe the Seattle offense. The Mariners got just one run
Thursday and just six runs in three games. But such word usage in
the wake of what happened to Abbott would be at the best trivial
and at the worst demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners didn't hit Thursday and fell from first place to
third place in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   So what? As Scarlet O'Hara reminds us, ``Tomorrow is another
day.''
</P>
<P>
   One that Paul Abbott will be lucky enough to see with both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
