<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS     05-26 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ For a while, the Indiana Pacers were beginning to
think the summer rerun season had arrived.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After working so hard to get the home-court advantage in the
Eastern Conference finals against the New York Knicks, the Pacers
were on the verge of blowing that edge for the second straight
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers rallied in the final minutes to pull out a tense
88-84 victory Thursday night in Game 2 of the conference finals.
The win, which came before a sellout crowd of 18,345 at Conseco
Fieldhouse, gives the Pacers a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven
series, which resumes Saturday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks were very well-prepared for this game,'' said
Reggie Miller, who finished with 19 points, including a pair of key
free throws with 28 seconds left in the game that put the Pacers up
by two points. ``They wanted a game in the 80s, and they got it.
But we can't rest on this. It's better going there (to New York) up
2-0 than 1-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what happened last season when the Pacers, just like
this year, had worked all season to gain the home-court advantage,
only to blow it right off the bat in the conference finals by
allowing the Knicks to walk off with a split in the first two
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers scored the final six points Thursday, with Dale Davis
capping his second 16-rebound game of the series by grabbing his
own missed free throw and dishing the ball to Jalen Rose for a
game-clinching dunk with 2.4 seconds left, the last of his
team-high 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the biggest game in Pacers franchise history,'' said
Rose, who played the entire 48 minutes despite getting a tooth
knocked out by a stray elbow. ``We were just trying to do what we
need to do to get to the next round. But then Patrick Ewing went
out of the game, and I was thinking, `Oh, no. Here we go again.'
When he's out, they (the Knicks) have a different look.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the Knicks, Thursday's game looked exactly like last
year's Game 2 because Ewing was again lost to an injury. Last
season it was a torn Achilles' tendon that knocked Ewing out of
action, an injury that sidelined him for the rest of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was a strained peroneal tendon in his right foot,
knocking him out of the game after playing just seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what happened,'' Ewing said of his injury.
``I made a play to go to the basket, and I just felt something
pull. It happened right when I took myself out of the game (with
5:29 left in the first period).
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they (team doctors) are basically saying it's a
sprain. It's ironic that I got injured in Game 2 of last year's
series and then Game 2 of this year's, too. But hopefully I won't
have to miss the rest of the series. I'm going to go back and get
an MRI (today), and hopefully I'll be able to play on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will need his offense.
</P>
<P>
   Already in a state of rigor score-tis after going seven games
with Miami in the conference semifinals, the Knicks were further
handicapped by Ewing's injury. So Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy
decided to reduce the game to the basketball equivalent of a
pitchers' duel, slowing the pace to a crawl and hoping to somehow
pull out a win.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Knicks usually play.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Pacers are more known for their offense, Miller
said things are going to have to be different for Indiana against
the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is going to win this series,'' he said. ``Everybody's
been talking about our 3-point shots and the way we move the
basketball, but that's not what's going to win this series. Defense
is going to win this series. I think that's what got us back
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That and the fact center Rik Smits finally showed up for the
game. Smits, who missed six of his seven shots through three
periods, scored 10 of his 12 points in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Smits got them to the doorstep, but Miller and Rose made the
final push for the Pacers. Rose hit a 17-foot jumper with 55.5
seconds left in the game to tie it at 84, and after a miss by New
York's Allan Houston, Miller hit a pair of free throws with 28
seconds remaining after being run over by Houston and Larry Johnson
as he set up on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks got the ball to Latrell Sprewell (10 points, 3-of-14
shooting) for one last shot, but his fadeaway jumper skipped off
the rim. Davis seized the rebound and was immediately fouled.
</P>
<P>
   Davis missed the first free throw, but the Knicks set up for the
second with two guards _ Sprewell and Houston _ on the blocks for
the rebound. When the 6-11 Davis missed the second, he swooped in
for the rebound and quickly passed to Rose to clinch the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that if I did miss,'' Davis said, ``I would have a
real good chance of getting the rebound over the small people
because I could jump over them.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was crushing for the Knicks, who got superb
performances from Johnson (25 points), Kurt Thomas (10 points,
eight rebounds) and Chris Childs (12 points).
</P>
<P>
   But not as crushing as a loss would have been for the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard to get this home-court advantage, and we need
to take advantage of it,'' said Indiana coach Larry Bird. ``I can't
say it enough. New York outplayed us tonight. We got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
