<HEADLINE>
MODANO OK DESPITE TRICKY FOOTE WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD, CHAREAN WILLIAMS AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Dallas Stars, who already had lost defenseman
Richard Matvichuk to a concussion in the first period, survived a
big scare in the second period Thursday night when center Mike
Modano injured his left knee at 11:50.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche defenseman Adam Foote used the slew foot on Modano.
While high-sticking Modano, Foote cut Modano's legs out from
underneath him. Foote received a two-minute penalty for
high-sticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's tried to (do that) all series,'' Modano said. ``I
don't think it's a real mystery what those guys are trying to do.
It's just something at this time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of locked knees, and the stick caught me in the
chin. It wasn't anything major _ a couple of bruises. I felt fine
once I got up and got moving a little bit. He leads with his stick
and his hands a lot. He just caught me good there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Modano was in the locker room, the Stars scored a goal on
a five-on-three power play at 12:37. Modano returned to the ice at
16:01.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we want to do something about it, you have to use
your head,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``I think we did (do
something about it). We scored a goal.'' SPRAIN FOR LANGENBRUNNER
</P>
<P>
   An MRI exam of Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner's right knee
revealed only a sprain, Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner was injured when he tangled with Avalanche
defenseman Aaron Miller in the first period of Game 5.
Langenbrunner has not skated since but will be re-evaluated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said after the game he doubted Langenbrunner could
play in Game 7. ``If we had a couple more days maybe, but right now
he is still limping and until he can become really pain-free, I
don't think there is any way we can play him,'' Hitchcock said.
CARBONNEAU STILL TOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Guy Carbonneau has earned a reputation as one of the NHL's
toughest defensive centers, even at 40.
</P>
<P>
   He showed it again early Thursday night when he got into an
extended tangle with Colorado forward Peter Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   Near the blue line, the two went down when Carbonneau proceeded
to push, grapple and shove with the Avs forward. A little later,
Carbonneau was checked into the boards, where Forberg skated by and
gave him a soft kick to his head. FERNANDEZ'S FUTURE ELSEWHERE
</P>
<P>
   Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez hasn't played a game in
almost two months. So he finds it odd that anybody is talking to
him, much less about him to him.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants to know where he thinks he'll be playing next
season.
</P>
<P>
   While the topic sounds harsh, it isn't anything anybody didn't
know.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the playoffs, Fernandez likely won't be a Stars
player anymore. He'll either be exposed in the expansion draft or
traded before it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of those summers I think,'' Fernandez
said. ``What makes it worse is (goalie) Roman (Turek) got traded to
a pretty good team (St. Louis), and I think (Stars general manager
Bob Gainey) might be worried about doing the same thing again.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing has been on the wall since the Stars signed goalie
Ed Belfour to a three-year contract on opening night. This season
has basically been an audition for Fernandez, who finished the
season with an 11-8-3 record, a 2.13 goals-against average and a
.920 save percentage backing up Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of stuff to prove to myself this year, and I'm
happy with my season,'' said Fernandez, who said he didn't really
know if he's ready to be a No. 1. ``Maybe, I am. We'll find out if
I get the call. ... I think it's pretty boastful to go out and say
`Yeah, I am. I'm not that Roman type. Roman for a year used to say
`Well, I want to play. I want to play. I want to be traded. I want
to be No. 1.' I'm not like that.'' SLOAN GETS THE CALL
</P>
<P>
   With Jamie Langenbrunner out with a sprained right knee, Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock had to decide whether to replace him with Blake
Sloan, who had played in the series but been benched for Games 4
and 5, or Jon Sim, who had yet to play a minute in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock decided to go with Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   And while Sloan didn't petition, he really wanted to get in.
Game 3 left a bad taste in his mouth. He played only 3 minutes, 36
seconds all game and almost none at all in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want that to be your last game,'' Sloan said. ``You
want to go out, play well and help the team.'' ABOUT TIME
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano did not have a shot on goal in Games 3,
4 or 5. The three-game shotless streak was a personal record for
him.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first shot in four games at 9:35 of the first period
of Game 6. The Stars were short-handed when goalie Patrick Roy
turned over the puck to Modano. BETTER THAN '99
</P>
<P>
   Avs winger Dave Reid has now seen Stars goalie Ed Belfour from
two perspectives, last season as an teammate and this season as an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   So is Belfour playing better this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Reid said. ``I think he played great last
year. I think he was the main reason the Stars won the Cup last
year. I don't know what his stats are in comparison, but they have
to be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Not close. Better.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour had a 2.05 goals-against average against Colorado in the
Western Conference Finals last season. He had a 1.75 goals against
average through five games this season. THE BEST
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull has proven to be the Avalanche killer this series. He
entered Thursday night's game with three multipoint contests in his
past four games.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five games, Hull scored four of the Stars' 10
goals. He scored the Stars' only goal Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do, other than keep him out of the slot
and don't let him shoot the puck,'' Aaron Miller said before Game
6. ``I mean, the guy can score goals. He's done it his whole
career. He's definitely doing it right now.'' nn
</P>
