<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROYALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN'S BIG CATCH, BUNT CRITICAL IN RANGERS' WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Rangers went trolling for an outfielder a
few weeks ago and wanted to land either Ron Gant or Todd
Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   They settled for Scarborough Green, a minor-leaguer from their
own system who has never hit enough to merit serious big-league
time. But for one night at least he was just what they needed: an
outfielder with terrific speed and a great glove.
</P>
<P>
   His spectacular catch saved starter Esteban Loaiza from disaster
in the sixth inning and his bunt single started a three-run seventh
that carried the Rangers to a 5-3 victory against the Kansas City
Royals on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Green was a last-minute replacement in center field for Ruben
Mateo, who was scratched from the lineup after suffering a slightly
strained ribcage muscle in his right side. Green's play proved
decisive even on a night when Rafael Palmeiro homered in the second
and delivered the two-run single in the seventh that put the
Rangers ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez also went 3-for-5, putting him atop the
American League batting leaders with a .381 average, and John
Wetteland recorded his 10th save in May, tying the club record for
most saves in a month. But this night belonged to Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``The star of the game,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any success is gratifying, but that's kind of my role,'' Green
said. ``Not playing every day, I have to get my work in, get
focused and keep my body in good shape so I can pitch in when I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   He did so in the sixth with the catch, a play that was set up by
singles by Mark Quinn and Carlos Beltran, putting runners at first
and third with one out and the score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Johnson then crushed a line drive to deep center that sent
Green racing back to the warning track. He was turned to his right
as the ball sailed over his left shoulder but he twisted his body
at the last moment and lunged to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``An amazing catch,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Said right fielder Jason McDonald, ``I knew Scarborough can run
and I knew it was staying in the park so I thought he had a shot at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said he was playing shallow in case he had a shot at
throwing out Quinn on a short sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good drop step, took three or four hard steps, found
the wall, then looked up and found the ball,'' Green said. ``I work
hard every day on fly balls over my head, so a catch that looks a
little harder for some people is easier for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn tagged up and scored easily, but Beltran, who was rounding
second and would have scored too, had to scamper back to first.
Loaiza then struck out Rey Sanchez to get out of the inning
trailing by just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play of the game,'' Oates said. ``How do you catch that?
That saved the game; that catch kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's offensive contribution came with one out in the seventh
against reliever Jose Santiago. Green bounced a first-pitch bunt
off the plate and high into the air. Santiago came off the mound to
get it but threw to first base before second baseman Jeff Reboulet
could get there. The ball sailed into right-field foul territory,
and Green dashed all the way to third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting on base is first and foremost on my mind,'' Green
said. ``Knowing the pitcher is not quick to the plate, I thought I
could steal on him if I got on base. It worked out pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alicea scored him with a single to left, making it a 3-3
game. After Chad Curtis popped out, Ivan Rodriguez lined a one-hop
double off the right-field wall that was touched by a fan, moving
Alicea to third. The umpires, on fan interference, have the right
to let Alicea score if they think he would have anyway. Oates
argued he would have, but the umpires disagreed and kept Alicea at
third.
</P>
<P>
   The five-minute argument didn't matter, because Palmeiro
followed with a single to right to score both runners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
