<HEADLINE>
HOUSING BOOM `OVER' IN PHOENIX AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Phoenix area homes sales tumbled 5 percent in April,
confirming forecasts that the seven-year housing boom is virtually
over.
</P>
<P>
   The news Thursday, May 25, was the same nationally: Sales of
existing homes fell 7 percent in April, the National Association of
Realtors reported.
</P>
<P>
   The culprits in both cases are the same: interest rates at
five-year highs, rising home prices and a falling stock market that
has shaken potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest-running housing boom in the Valley's history is
about to end,'' said home-building analyst R.L. Brown, who tracks
home sales here. ``The Fed has been telling us what the grand plan
is for months. The market is going to slow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve hiked interest rates for the sixth time in
less than a year last week to tame runaway growth and curb
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The move sent mortgage rates soaring, prompting many analysts to
forecast a 9 percent home loan in the next few months. That rate is
the psychological barrier that will keep many buyers out of the
home market. The average 30-year mortgage rate was 8.62 percent,
almost even with last week.
</P>
<P>
   A slowing is even more evident in the Phoenix area's new-home
market. It's down 15 percent from a year earlier, after being
second only to Atlanta for new housing construction since 1997,
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in home sales comes despite continued job growth in the
Phoenix area. Phoenix's unemployment rate hit 3.6 percent in April,
a 31-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a higher degree of uncertainty among consumers and
definite hesitation in the market among home buyers,'' said Brad
Inman, chief executive officer of the Internet real estate site
HomeGain.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 21,000 existing houses in the Phoenix area changed
hands for the first four months of 2000, vs. 23,000 in the first
four months of last year. The market set a record high last year
with nearly 70,000 resales.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 250,000 new homes have blanketed the Phoenix area
since 1993, and nearly double that many existing ones have sold.
</P>
<P>
   Escalating home prices play a part in the slowdown. The median
resale price in metro Phoenix recently hit $122,000, rising twice
as fast as personal income growth during the 1990s. Median
household income in the Phoenix area is about $40,000 a year. At
current mortgage rates, a family earning that much could afford a
$100,000 house with 10 percent down.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the current rate, Phoenix's slowing housing market would
still rate as hot by most cities' standards: At least 50,000
existing homes would change hands this year and 30,000 would be
built, or 136 closings and 82 housing starts a day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Catherine.Reagor(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602)444-8040. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
