<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE BEATS STARS, FORCES GAME 7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A second consecutive trip to the Stanley Cup Finals was
so close the Stars could almost reach out and touch it in the third
period Thursday night at the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   And then in a second, yesterday's chance was gone.
</P>
<P>
   In that second, a shot that looked to be sailing wide bounced
off Colorado forward Chris Drury's knee and past Stars goalie Ed
Belfour for the game-winning goal in the Avalanche's 2-1 victory in
Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, with three minutes and 51 seconds remaining, ensured
another game. Yes, the Stars will have to win Game 7 on Saturday
for another chance at the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I thought we dominated the third period, the
period we ended up losing,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said.
``It's one of those plays where the puck is going two feet or a
foot wide, and it hits in off someone. That stuff happens. Now,
it's a one-game deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars might have to play that game without one of their best
defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Matvichuk suffered a mild concussion 8 minutes and 47
seconds into the first period, when Colorado winger Dave Andreychuk
got his elbow up as he drove Matvichuk into the boards behind the
Stars' goal. Matvichuk's helmet popped off on contact, and his bare
head went crashing into the unforgiving glass. The Stars said he'll
be re-evaluated Friday morning, but they didn't sound optimistic
about his chances for Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It pretty
simple. Rules should be pretty simple. If Matty is out, so should
No. 38.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he surprised there was no penalty on Andreychuk, No. 38?
</P>
<P>
   ``Shocked would be the word,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   NHL commissioner Gary Bettman said the league is reviewing the
hit at the request of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive game the Stars lost a key player
in the first period. They were already playing without one of their
top six forwards, Jamie Langenbrunner, who sprained his knee in
Game 5, and isn't expected back for Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this series is going to a Game 7. From the moment the
Stars and Avalanche took the ice almost two weeks ago you could
feel this one coming. The Avs' victory Thursday night simply
ensured the inevitable. The fight-for-every-inch-of-space,
no-victory-is-easy series now becomes a one-game, winner-take-all
affair to be held at 6 p.m. Saturday at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, everybody is talking about the season being long
but that's the only reason you play 82 games,'' Stars center Guy
Carbonneau said. ``Bonuses and the ice advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason they're playing is as simple as a couple of feet.
That much space, maybe less, was between Stars defensemen Darryl
Sydor and Sergei Zubov, and, through this opening, Avs defenseman
Ray Bourque's shot passed, deflected off Drury's knee and past
Belfour, who stopped 19 of 21 Colorado shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had 27 shots, but Avs goalie Patrick Roy stopped 26 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the first time in a while we outshot them and
probably outchanced them, too,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said.
``It was our game to win. Maybe, they feel like they had some they
could've won. It's just the way the series has gone. It's been
tough hockey. (Friday) we'll wake up and realize we have one game
left. It's our building, our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is they could've woke up Friday morning and started
getting ready for the Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   In a game the Stars could've won, the Stars couldn't get the
shot, the bounce, the goal to end it. So the Avs did. It's the
first time since 1997 that the Stars have lost when they had a
chance to close out an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some great chances late, but that's playoff hockey,''
Stars winger Mike Keane said. ``Sometimes you deserve to win.
Sometimes you don't. So back in our building.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time since 1964 both Eastern and Western
conference finals are going to Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia and New Jersey are tied 3-3 with Game 7 tonight in
Philly. And now, the West will take seven games to be won, too.
</P>
<P>
   It almost was over. The Stars looked to have all the momentum
when winger Brett Hull scored his NHL-leading ninth goal of the
playoffs, a five-on-three power-play goal at 12:37 of the second
period. Zubov sent a cross-ice pass to Hull, who whistled a classic
one-timer that went between Roy's legs.
</P>
<P>
   With Drury already in the penalty box for tripping, referees had
whistled Adam Foote for his high stick to the face of Mike Modano.
Foote and Modano also had an ankle-to-ankle collision that caused
Modano to land awkwardly on his left leg. He left the ice at 11:50
of the second period, but returned five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just locked knees and the stick caught me in the chin. It
wasn't anything major, a couple of bruises,'' Modano said. ``I
think he's tried to all series. I don't think it's a real mystery
what those guys are trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars converted on the five-on-three but couldn't take
advantage of the one minute and 14 seconds left in Foote's minor so
the game went into the second intermission tied at 1-1. The Avs'
goal was created by the most-criticized man in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado captain Joe Sakic had been a ``no show'' for most of
this series.
</P>
<P>
   He quieted that crowd in Game 6. Colorado's first goal began
with Sakic blocking a shot, carrying the puck down the ice and
making a perfect pass to a wide-open Bourque streaking into the
slot.
</P>
<P>
   All Bourque did was whistle a shot past Belfour at 4:30 of the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the series returns to Dallas
</P>
<P>
   ``I love our position,'' Avs coach Bob Hartley said. ``In
tonight's game, we generated momentum. We played a solid two-way
hockey game. We won lots of battles.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one more battle left to be won, though, and the Stars
say they feel confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said it after the game `One game on our home ice,'''
Hatcher said. ``Sure, I like our chances. If I didn't like our
chances, I wouldn't play.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
