<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-H     05-26 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The four-homer part of the script was believable, especially
considering the Astros' offensive firepower, not to mention the
likelihood of multiple home runs being hit at Enron Field.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Joe Slusarski closing the game with three scoreless, almost
perfect innings was a surprise ending, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros outgunned the Philadelphia Phillies 10-6 Thursday
night in a game that featured seven home runs, including three
two-run shots by the Astros, who won a series for only the fourth
time this season and just the second time at home.
</P>
<P>
   But even in triumph, not all the news was good for the Astros.
Roger Cedeno fractured the fourth and fifth metacarpals on his left
hand and ruptured a tendon in his left ring finger while sliding
into first base on an infield single in the fourth inning. Cedeno
is headed for the disabled list and will be lost for six to eight
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to miss him,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio
said of Cedeno, the Astros' starting right fielder and leadoff
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   While Cedeno's specialty is speed, the Astros' offense
emphasized power Thursday, with Jeff Bagwell, Ken Caminiti and
Mitch Meluskey each hitting two-run homers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo added a solo shot in what amounted to a slugfest
thanks to subpar starting pitching by Astros righthander Scott
Elarton and his mound opponent, Andy Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton's outing _ he allowed six runs in six innings _ was
masked by a well-rounded offensive attack and a redeeming
performance by Slusarski, whose clutch effort came at a time when
the bullpen needed it most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense was good enough to score more than Elarton gave
up,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``We had a good offensive
game, but Slusarski was the biggest story of this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Slusarski's ERA dropped to a team-low 2.70 after Thursday's
performance. And to think he was deemed unworthy of a roster spot
at the end of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely moving up in the pecking order,'' Dierker said
of Slusarski, who was promoted from Class AAA New Orleans on May 5.
``He's doing what the others aren't. He's hitting corners.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first save of Slusarski's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to get the job done,'' he said. ``The bullpen
has gotten a lot of criticism, and most of it has been deserved.
We're going through a spell right now. Hopefully, this is something
that will pick us up.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory represented a milestone for Dierker, who became the
fastest manager to reach 300 victories in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just hoping I can remain the manager for a
while,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, despite a 9.00 ERA in his last two starts, improved to
3-1 as the Astros won for just the second time in their last 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good,'' Elarton said. ``I don't think the results are
reflective of the way I felt. I just made too many bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies took a 2-0 first-inning lead on Bob Abreu's third
homer in as many at-bats, dating to Wednesday. The former Astro's
latest bomb, a two-run shot into the right-field seats, extended
his hitting streak to five games.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's two-run homer tied the score in the bottom of the
inning, and the Astros took a 3-2 lead on Hidalgo's sacrifice fly.
The fast start at the plate was nothing new for the Astros, who
have scored 18 runs in the first three innings of their last five
games.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton retired 10 of the next 11 batters he faced after Abreu's
home run, then created trouble for himself with a pair of two-out
walks to Kevin Jordan and Mickey Morandini in the fourth inning.
Desi Relaford made Elarton pay with a triple into the
right-center-field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo's team-leading 15th homer tied the score 4-4 in the
fifth, and the Astros added two more runs on Cedeno's infield
single and a subsequent throwing error by Phillies rookie first
baseman Pat Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros stretched their lead to 8-4 on Caminiti's two-run
homer in the fifth. Caminiti had only one hit in his 10 at-bats
prior to the home run, his 11th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell atoned for his fourth-inning error with the first homer
of his big-league career in the sixth. His solo shot off the train
tracks and a solo homer by Relaford pulled the visitors within 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros reclaimed their four-run lead on Meluskey's
eighth-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to be getting excited,'' Meluskey said of the
Astros' winning two of three from lowly Philadelphia. ``The
Phillies are struggling, too. Let's see what we do against the
Braves this weekend. Let's try to get seven or eight out of 10.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
