<HEADLINE>
BULLPEN CRISIS LINE GIVES MARINERS FANS AN OUTLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Hello.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Seattle Mariners Bullpen Crisis Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Please choose from among the following menu options.
</P>
<P>
   This call may be monitored for revenge purposes by franchise
ownership in the event of playoffs and your need for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have encouragement to offer Mariners relief
pitchers, please press 1.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have concerns about relief pitching, please press
2.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you wish to utter curses and threaten physical mayhem
regarding relief pitching, please call the bullpen number at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you think Cubs fans were on to something, please hang
up so we can call 911 with your number from caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you are able to convert feet to meters, please press
3 for Kazu Sasaki and leave a message after the tone explaining
fence distances in American ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have information about why washed-up relief
pitchers come to Seattle to end their careers, please press 4.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have information that Bobby Ayala, Norm Charlton,
Heathcliff Slocumb, Mike Timlin, Paul Spoljaric and Jose Mesa are
the same person, please mark your call as urgent and press 5 to
leave a message for manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you are Lou Piniella, please get your messages
immediately by pressing pound-5.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you wish to work on the campaign for Initiative 666,
a measure that would repeal state law prohibiting employment of
relief pitchers in their prime, press 6.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you speak sufficient Japanese to translate the
expression, ``Another walk-off homer and the Redmond GameBoy
factory has a broom with your name on it,'' please press 7 to fax a
resume.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have information on the total baseball payroll
invested in the bullpen in the last seven years, the Federal Trade
Commission asks you to call its consumer-fraud hotline.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you are Philadelphia's Mike Jackson, now on the
disabled list at 35 with a bad shoulder and a big contract, please
press 8 for your Seattle reporting instructions.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you are Jose Mesa, will you please get a blasted
breaking ball over the plate to set up your fastball?
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)Since we're on it, how about a little movement on that
heater, huh?! That thing comes in fatter and straighter than a '65
Lincoln!!
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)And what is this business about being lousy at home and
OK on the road? Seattle has the world's nicest fans! Get over us
already!! It's not as if we use a lot of exclamation points, or
anything!!!!
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If we have digressed, place us on hold a moment while we
calm down ... thank you.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you are Tonya Harding, please press 9 and leave a
message describing the location of your hubcap for use by Arthur
Rhodes in his matchup with Jose Canseco in Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)For autographed copies of Piniella's book, ``Everything
I Know About Pitching I Learned from Martha Stewart,'' please press
star-1.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have had this number on auto-dial for the past
seven years, please consider the mental-health implications of
repeating an action endlessly to no apparent purpose.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)If you have reached this number in error and meant to
call the Mariners College of the Bunt, please be advised that class
is filled, and no graduation vacancies appear imminent.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
