 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, May 26.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ How the Republicans pulled out the
larger-than-expected victory on the House passage of the China
trade bill and a look forward at possible difficulties in the
Senate. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NUKES (Washington) _ News Analysis: Gov. George W. Bush's
proposal this week to consider unilateral reductions in the
American nuclear arsenal was a bold break with decades of strategic
doctrine that may foretell the end of traditional theories of arms
control. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-NASRALLAH (Cairo, Egypt) _ With Israel abruptly gone
from southern Lebanon, the militant Islamic group Hezbollah stands
at a crossroads. The man who straddles it, with the authority to
determine what direction his country and his movement take, is a
chubby-cheeked 39-year-old Shiite Muslim cleric named Hassan
Nasrallah. A profile by Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-HONGKONG (Hong Kong) _ For a city that has prospered
as an intermediary between the Chinese economy and the outside
world, Hong Kong has lobbied hard to help China win full membership
in the world's club of trading nations. Now the U.S. House of
Representatives has voted to give China permanent normal trade
status, bringing normalized trade relations closer to reality and
easing China's accession to the World Trade Organization. A China
more open to commerce with the outside world, many experts say,
will jeopardize Hong Kong's historic role as a trading post. By
Mark Landler. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ When leaders of Japan's governing party
met secretly seven weeks ago to choose a successor to Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, who was felled by a stroke, the idea was not
only to ensure a quick transition but also to perpetuate the
party's long hold on power. But to the growing consternation of
party members, through a series of gaffes and provocative
statements the new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, has presided
instead over a steep decline in the government's public support,
recent opinion polls indicate. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASH-RWANDA-DANCE (Purdy, Wash.) _ The National Ballet of
Rwanda, in its first visit to North America, has danced everywhere,
from the Seattle Children's Festival to a women's prison here. By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Tucson, Ariz.) _ The growing likelihood that Pat
Buchanan will become the presidential nominee of the Reform Party
is producing a backlash from some party members and leaders around
the country. Efforts are under way to derail him and even those who
recognize the inevitability of it all wonder what the party will
look like in the future. Some want Ross Perot to run again,
although that appears unlikely; some like Ralph Nader; and some
think the party should have no nominee at all this year. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-CORZINE (Trenton, N.J.) _ In a vivid glimpse of the
ever-escalating role of money in politics, Jon Corzine has already
spent nearly $25 million on his race for the Democratic Senate
nomination, more than three times as much as anyone has ever spent
on a Senate primary and within striking distance of the most money
ever spent on an entire Senate election. By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND-HOUSING (Dallas) _ For a growing number of affluent
home buyers, high-speed broadband Internet connections are becoming
as important as a two-car garage. Recognizing this, some developers
and builders are jumping into the telecommunications business.
Either by building and owning their own neighborhood networks, or
joining with telecommunications companies, they are offering
high-speed Internet connections, bundled with cable and phone
service, at discounts of up to $20 a month from what this would
otherwise cost. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TAKEOVERS (Paris) _ The cutthroat tactics of the 1980s,
with vulture investors searching the landscape for takeover prey,
have fallen somewhat out of fashion in the United States. But this
phenomenon, it turns out, did not die, but migrated across the
Atlantic. In the thick of this trend is one of the brashest and
most feared of the old-style raiders, Asher B. Edelman, who is
trying to outwit a venerable French family institution, Taittinger,
the Champagne maker, luxury-goods producer and top-of-the-line
hotel company. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-LYNCH (New York) _ A look at some internal changes in
the company. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   CONSECO-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Say this for Stephen C.
Hilbert, the master salesman who built Conseco Inc. into a giant
insurance company even as critics dismissed it as a house of paper
sure to collapse some day: He believed his own sales pitch. Hilbert
was paid $119 million, not counting stock options, in the 1990s,
and $53 million more when he was ousted last month. But both he and
Conseco are now scrambling for liquidity as lenders grow nervous.
By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   TV-AD-COLUMN (London) _ The four major broadcast networks have
booked sharp increases in advance sales of commercial time for the
2000-01 season. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
