u s BC-BBN-BOS &LR;      05-26 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Another new ballpark won't cure game's problems  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox need a new house. The majority of New Englanders
will not dispute that. They may not agree on the cost _ ``$627 mil?
For a new place? Can't you find something cheaper?'' And they may
not agree on the prioritizing _ ``The Sox aren't the only folks in
the city who'd like to move and can't afford to do it by
themselves.'' But if you were to argue the usefulness of
88-year-old Fenway Park, you'd eventually find yourself arguing the
inarguable.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every current Sox player can say, without exaggeration,
``Fenway is older than my grandmother.'' The place is beyond
needing new drapes, new paint, and, this year, a new (and
underused) center-field scoreboard. Standing next to Fenway, my own
Flappers Era granny looks like a GenX rapper. And, yes, she would
also say it's time to move.
</P>
<P>
   John Harrington and Dan Duquette have convinced me of that. But
I doze when they try to persuade the public that a new park is
needed. To me, it's like telling someone that they can find a lot
of green space at Boston Common. What gets my attention, though, is
the annoying and hypocritical section of the plea. The essence of
that argument usually develops like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the park to remain competitive . . . Other teams in
baseball are using revenue streams from new parks to gain a
competitive advantage and we can't keep up . . . The Yankees are
going to lap us.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Sox are right about the sad financial dynamics of
baseball. What they don't say is that they have benefited from the
system's Have and Have Not imbalance. They are understandably
protesting it now, because the system is wacked. But if they were
honest with themselves, they would acknowledge the problem they now
face has more to do with baseball's administrative offices in New
York rather than political offices on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   I may have missed the monologue, but I didn't hear any Sox
executives urgently speaking about the divide between baseball's
upper and lower classes in 1997 and 1999. That divide is the only
reason Pedro Martinez and Carl Everett are in Boston today. If
baseball had its financial house in order, there is no way the
Montreal Expos _ one of the game's faces of abject poverty _ would
have traded a Cy Young Award winner for a couple of minor leaguers
in '97. If baseball had something sensible, such as revenue sharing
and/or a salary cap, you wouldn't see the Houston Astros trade
their No. 4 hitter (Everett) for a kid (Adam Everett) who is now
trying to hit his weight in Triple A. And the Astros have a new
park this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most owners will tell you that this classism results from a
powerful and inflexible players' union. They tell you that the
players bristle at a salary cap because they believe it will limit
how much they can earn. The candid owners also acknowledge that
everyone in management does not endorse revenue sharing.
</P>
<P>
   If you put the aforementioned scenes together, you have a short
horror film. The significant new revenue of which the Sox wistfully
speak may not seem so significant to them in five years. Two years
from now, their payroll will exceed $100 million (it's close to $80
million now). It could be as high as $130 million by the time their
park opens. If that keeps up, a new park alone is not going to save
them. Instead, we'll see the Red Sox trying to raise additional
funds via car washes and Girl Scout cookie sales.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Sox need a new park? Of course. I am short and even I
struggle to find leg room in Fenway's tiny aisles. Take comfort out
of it and, if you are interested in actually seeing the game, you
might be better off watching at home rather than sitting in some
obstructed-view seats. There are other problems (purists call them
``idiosyncrasies'', but they are problems), but it would take an
entire column to enumerate them.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I am too optimistic, but I expect to see the new
40,000-plus-seat Fenway long before Chelsea Clinton tries to become
the first president's daughter to make a run for the White House.
But what will the new park do for the Sox if baseball doesn't have
a new way of doing business by then? It's good that 26 of the 29
teams will have a new home or blueprints for one by 2003. Who
doesn't enjoy going to a new home and saying to the host, ``So,
give me the tour!'' But if the majority of teams have new parks and
new revenue, won't they run into the same class issues if the
owners don't get the deal they want when this labor agreement
expires in 2001? The Tigers and Giants have new homes this year,
but it seems improbable that either of those teams will ever have
the Gateslike payroll of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington and Duquette speak as if a new park will solve their
problems, as well as yours; I am skeptical. Harrington says the
Sox' ticket prices are higher than he would like. The suggestion is
that they are high because the Sox have the oldest and smallest
park in the league, forcing them to inflate prices to generate
income. Does that mean fans can anticipate middle-of-the-pack
prices when the new home is in place? And what of the parking
garages the Sox want built? If the garages are supposed to be part
of a public-private marriage, does that mean fans will not need
payment plans in order to park in Sox-run facilities?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that baseball is a fractured game, financially.
Pouring millions of dollars into stadia may stem some of the
problems. It won't stop them. Teams such as Minnesota and Florida
are on a Buck-a-Book budget when they attempt to pay players (The
Martinez brothers have a higher combined salary than the Twins'
entire payroll). If Harrington and Duquette want to have a frank
dialogue about what it takes to remain competitive, they should
talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, there needs to be a compromise to ensure that everyone
gets the most out of their money. Lawmakers should give the Sox the
cash they seek; the Sox should try to fix their dilapidated game.
If the game is not repaired, you may not see Sox executives with
their hands out, but you'll still feel their oppressive pull on
your purses and wallets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
