<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-BOS &LR;      05-26 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Blue Jays beat Red Sox
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Blue Jays11Red Sox6
</P>
<P>
   Well, you couldn't ask for more drama. Of course, the Red Sox
could have done without quite as much.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of their fourth loss in five games, an 11-6 pasting
by the Toronto Blue Jays at Fenway Park before 32,716 restless
fans, the Sox flew to New York Thursday knowing that when they
landed, they would have company in first place in the American
League East.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, meanwhile, blasted the White Sox, 7-0, in Chicago
and thus erased Boston's one-game lead. That leaves the Sox with no
margin for error this weekend at Yankee Stadium when the blood
rivals clash for three games in the Showdown of the Century (so
what if the century is less than five months old?).
</P>
<P>
   Talk about excitement . . . actually, most of the Sox didn't
want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't talking about New York,'' said center fielder Carl
Everett, shooing away the pestiferous press. ``Skedaddle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early,'' said pitcher Tim Wakefield. ``It's the first
series. It's May still. If it was September, I'd be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just another team to us,'' said catcher Scott
Hatteberg. ``We're not saying, `Oh my God, it's the Yankees.' No
one in this room is even thinking about them.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the man in the adjacent room, the manager's office,
was. But Jimy Williams was willing to acknowledge New York's
existence only because it's the next stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on our schedule; now we can start thinking about
them,'' he said. ``Yeah, we've got to get ready for the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, the Sox can't forget those interlopers from
the north. By taking two of three here, the Blue Jays climbed
within four games of first place. Which, to the Sox' dismay, has
another occupant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they'll beat the heck out of each other in New
York,'' said irrepressible David ``Boomer'' Wells, who notched his
league-leading eighth win against two losses, allowing 10 hits and
four runs in seven innings plus. ``Boston has a great team. New
York has a great team. We have an OK team right now. But I don't
mind being the sleeper. I'll take that every time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, fitness freak Wells had reason to puff out his beer
belly as he overcame his dismal Boston track record. Along with his
generous gut, he lugged in a Fenway career mark of 6-10 and a 5.71
earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done well here,'' said Wells. ``I'm cursed. It's
the curse of the Boomer. Boston always beats my ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. Wells was the beneficiary of a Boston beating for
a change as the Blue Jays pounded out 17 hits against loser Pete
Schourek (2-4), Tim Wakefield, John Wasdin, and Tim Young. They
beefed up their league-leading home run total to 81 as Shannon
Stewart and Todd Greene went deep off Schourek, who left beneath a
4-1 deficit after four innings, and Carlos Delgado tagged
Wakefield, who was bullied for six hits and five runs in two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart added a double and triple as he just missed the cycle;
Delgado knocked in three runs and Tony Batista drove in two; Darrin
Fletcher went 3 for 5, including a triple; and Craig Grebeck and
Jose Cruz contributed a pair of hits each as Toronto gave the Sox
something to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to change their thinking,'' said Batista of
the New York-Boston hubbub. ``They're pretty good teams. We are,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd get no argument from Wakefield, who is just recovering from
a sore throat and fever that forced him to leave the park early a
couple of days ago, and wished he'd stayed in bed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no excuse,'' Wakefield said of his health. ``I pitched
like (expletive). Pete doesn't deserve the loss; I do. I should
have been able to hold them for two or three innings and I didn't
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Wells, who had been tattooed _ and we don't mean the
ones depicting his family members that he wears on his right arm,
above his left breast, and across his back _ in his last start when
the White Sox collected 10 hits and six runs at his expense in just
3 1/3 innings, endured no such indignity this time.
</P>
<P>
   He was facing a lineup that Williams appeared to have poured out
of a blender. With Jose Offerman idled by a left groin injury
suffered Wednesday and Trot Nixon sitting out against the
lefthander, Williams made good on his perpetual vow to ``play 'em
all; they're major leaguers and they're here for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff batter Darren Lewis (2 for 5, 2 runs), normally a right
fielder, played left as Williams tried to save wear and tear on the
ailing left hamstring that had idled the veteran since last week.
Donnie Sadler, who has been pitching in for the disabled Nomar
Garciaparra at shortstop, took Nixon's place in right and moved
from ninth to second in the order. Jeff Frye (3 for 4, 1 run),
starting his second straight game at second base, was the unlikely
No. 3 hitter. Another lefthanded batter, Brian Daubach _ hero of
Wednesday's palpitating marathon with a three-run 11th-inning homer
that produced a 6-3 victory _ gave way to Mike Stanley (2 for 5, 2
RBIs) at first base and in the cleanup spot. Both catchers, Jason
Varitek and Hatteberg (1 for 4, double), were on duty, Varitek as
the designated hitter. Wilton Veras (2 for 5) replaced John
Valentin at third base, and Manny Alexander was at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   This patchwork assemblage provided the most production Boston
has received during the homestand, collecting 13 hits, including
Everett's 14th homer, a two-run garbage-time shot in the ninth. But
they didn't harm Wells when it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 1-0, in the second, Wells stranded runners at second
and third by striking out Alexander. After the Jays put him in Fat
City by opening a 6-1 lead in the fifth, Wells was staring at a tie
game in the bottom of the inning when the Sox pushed across a run
and loaded the bases with two out. This time he struck out Varitek
as the unsparing Boston crowd booed; what would they have done if
they hadn't been watching a first-place team?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a habit of getting out of jams and also getting into
them,'' said Wells.
</P>
<P>
   He left the Sox in a rut _ they dropped back-to-back series (to
bottom-feeder Detroit and Toronto) for the first time since the
opening trip of the season. Meanwhile, the Blue Jays made amends
for losing two of three to Boston last week in SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked the (expletive) out of us up there, so it was nice
to do the same thing to them down here,'' said Wells. ``We made a
little statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is something the Sox and Yankees would be well
advised to ponder during their summit meeting: It's a three-team
race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
