u s BC-HKN-BOS &LR;      05-26 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Bourque, Avalanche force Stars to Game 7  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ray Bourque's dream, which only 48 hours before was
fading toward oblivion, Thursday sharpened focus and turned into a
fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   After earlier scoring the night's first goal, the former Bruins
captain fired off a 55-foot pass that Chris Drury tipped home with
3:51 remaining in regulation, leading the Avalanche to a 2-1
victory over Dallas in Game 6 of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, now 21 years into his pursuit of the Stanley Cup, will
lead the Avalanche into Dallas for Game 7 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I came here,'' said the Boston icon, dealt to the
Avalanche at the trading deadline, wanting to get at least one more
viable shot at winning the Cup. ``I don't think I've been as
aggressive as I'd like to be, but games like this you want to go
out and do more _ play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was out of character when he nailed in the go-ahead goal
with 4:30 gone in the second period. After Joe Sakic blocked a shot
in the netural zone and broke over the blue line, right wing,
Bourque came barreling down the slot as the trailer and collected
Sakic's soft dish. Closing toward Eddie Belfour, Bourque took aim
as if it were the NHL's midseason shooting accuracy contest,
breakable plates festooning the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The targets are a lot easier than shooting at Belfour,'' said
Bourque, laughing at the comparison. ``Belfour covers a lot of net,
and I didn't see any plates hanging back there. No targets. I
really didn't shoot it that hard. It was the quickness, I think,
that did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were back with the equalizer a little more than eight
minutes later, legendary sniper Brett Hull finishing a 5-on-3 power
play with a doorstep one-time slam off a Sergei Zubov feed.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Stars, who lost defenseman Richard Matvichuk
early in the first period when ex-Bruin Dave Andreychuk delivered
an elbow to his head, controlled much of the play after scoring the
tying goal. From the start of that 5-on-3, they went on to roll up
a 14-7 shot advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play as well tonight as maybe we did in Games 4 and
5, but we lost those games,'' said Bourque. ``All this is only
about winning, that's all. You take it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was fresh off the bench, rushing to his customary spot
at left defense, as the winning goal developed. Drury, the ex-BU
star and Hobey Baker winner, missed on a shot that caromed around
the boards and went to Bourque. Editor's note: This is not a Disney
script. Bourque retrieved it just inside the blue line and wristed
it back toward the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be 8 feet off the net,'' said Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't. It was in the net. Camped near the right post
like some security dog, Drury muscled closer to Belfour and got
something _ a knee, a stick, a four-leaf clover _ on it and
deflected it past Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have nicked my stick,'' said Drury, with face from
all-night poker match. Hitchcock was convinced it hit Drury's knee.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of the night, though, was Bourque's goal. After
seeing it nestle into the top right corner and drop behind the goal
line, Bourque curled back into the slot, dropped to a knee, and
began pumping his right arm in conquest _ the old warrior
transformed as if a teenager once more, all adrenaline and joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any who watched me in Boston over the years,'' said Bourque,
``know that I sometimes like to bring the pump out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ex-Bruin, Avalanche winger Dave Reid, marveled at the
goal and the assist, but was equally impressed by a vintage Bourque
play that came after the winning goal. With about two minutes to
go, Hull was alone in front, puck within his grasp, and Bourque
galloped back to knock it to the junkyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was winding up for a shot,'' said Reid, knowing how lethal
those Hull blasts can be. ``But that's Ray _ the great goal, the
great assist, and still getting back to make the perfect defensive
play.''
</P>
<P>
   One more victory and Bourque will be back in the finals for the
first time since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what's going on,'' said Drury, referring to the
blanket awareness of Bourque's Cup pursuit. ``We don't talk about
it every day, and no one's making rah-rah speeches _ but everyone
wants it for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
