<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 850-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; THE MAKING OF A STATESMAN: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by Brent Scowcroft, George Shultz and Henry Kissinger,
George W. Bush promised both a substantial reduction in America's
nuclear-weapons arsenal and a rapid development of a national
missile-defense system that would also protect America's allies.
The presence of Colin Powell increased speculation that the general
would join a Bush administration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MISSING YEARS: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bush went AWOL during his last 18 months of service in the Texas
National Guard. Records show that he rarely even turned up for the
drills required of a part-time guardsman. Bush points out that he
was given an honorable discharge when he left the Guard. (Boston
Globe, May 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEUD OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the American Israel Public Affairs Committee, an
influential Jewish group, Bush suggested that the Clinton White
House had tried to interfere in the recent Israeli election and
``make Israel conform to its own plans and timetables.'' The next
day, Vice President Al Gore reminded the same group that ``unlike
our immediate predecessors (i.e., Bush's father), we chose to get
intimately involved'' in the Middle East peace process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NRA QUOTE OF THE WEEK (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say those fighting words for everyone within the
sound of my voice to hear and to heed, and especially for you, Mr.
Gore: From my cold, dead hands.'' (National Rifle Association
chairman, Charlton Heston, brandishing an antique musket at their
annual convention) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NRA QUOTE OF THE WEEK (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got Gore a million more votes right there, holding up
that gun.'' (George Stephanopoulos on Charlton Heston's
performance, ABC, May 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; W STANDS FOR WOMEN: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate that Bush is gaining popularity amongst
married women, while Gore is still doing well amongst such niche
voters as the ``Allys'' (young urban professionals) and the
``Erins'' (environmental activists). (Dallas Morning News, May 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPIN OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take out Texas, then it's a dead heat.'' (Donna
Brazile, Gore's campaign manager, explaining the polls that show
him losing badly) &QL;
</P>
