<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GUN-SHOWS-$ADV28-COX     05-26 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-SHOWS-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'GUN SHOW LOOPHOLE' KEEPS BILL BOTTLED UP IN CONGRESS
 &HT;    With GUN-SHOW-LIST. For release Sunday, May 28.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a matter of time: the difference between a few
minutes and a few days is a key point in the congressional standoff
on guns.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and gun control advocates want a
waiting period of up to 72 hours to allow background checks on
buyers at gun shows. The National Rifle Association and gun show
operators support an ``instant check'' that can be as quick as
three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say their position is non-negotiable. And without a
compromise, gun legislation is unlikely to emerge from the
House-Senate conference committee where it has been stuck for
months.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood Caraway, who runs gun and knife shows throughout
eastern North Carolina, said that for his business, the waiting
period is a matter of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to make a law saying that they have up to
three days to approve the background check,'' Caraway said, ``that
would probably shut the gun shows down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the guy can't come there and pick his gun up and leave with
his gun, it's going to kill the show,'' said Caraway, who has owned
and operated S&AMP;D Promotions for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the checks would drive up the price of guns,
eliminating the main reason people buy at gun shows. With the
72-hour check, many out-of-town vendors would have to pay someone
locally to to deliver the gun once the purchase is approved, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control groups say the fears of gun show operators are a
result of scare tactics by the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be the end of gun shows. ... They are just
going to be better off at stopping prohibited purchasers from
getting guns,'' said David Bernstein, a spokesman for Handgun
Control Inc., the leading gun-control advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said that 95 percent of gun-show purchases are
completed in less than two hours, including a background check.
Those who need more time for the check are 20 times more likely to
be disqualified from purchasing a firearm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people will get their guns in a matter of minutes,'' he
said. ``This affects the people who are most likely to be
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the 72-hour check also say the instant checks
don't provide enough information and don't allow for a
``cooling-off'' period so people don't buy guns in a moment of
anger.
</P>
<P>
   Under the instant check system, vendors access a national
database to see if the purchaser has a criminal record or other
disqualifying factors.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-hour check would allow time to search local and state
records when necessary. Those records, which contain information
such as domestic violence offenses and mental health records, are
mostly not available on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   If law enforcement can't access records, it ``gives the
potential criminal the benefit of the doubt,'' Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In a January 1999 report, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms estimated that there were more than 4,000 gun shows
nationwide in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The gun shows, usually held in public arenas, civic centers and
fairgrounds, are extremely popular weekend attractions in many
states. Typically, each vendor rents a table from the promoter for
a fee ranging from $5 to $50. The number of tables at shows varies
from 50 to as many as 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Arms Shows, which represents many of
the show promoters, estimates that more than 5 million people
attend gun shows each year, generating billions of dollars in
sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, the ATF found that 25 to 50 percent of the
vendors at most gun shows are unlicensed or private dealers. These
dealers are not subject to the Brady Act, which requires the
background checks on the national database.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``gun show loophole'' is the biggest sticking
point in the congressional impasse over tighter gun restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last year passed a crime bill that included stricter
background checks, as well as requiring safety locks on guns and a
ban on importing large-capacity ammunition clips. The bill would
also bar juveniles with serious criminal records from possessing
guns for life.
</P>
<P>
   A similar House bill did not include the gun provisions, and a
compromise between the two versions has eluded negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, an exchange of letters between the chairman
and the ranking member of the House Judiciary Committee hinted at a
possible compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., wrote to Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich.,
informing him he was willing to change the definition of a gun show
to ensure that it would include any event ``used to facilitate the
sale of firearms.'' He also appeared willing to expand the pool of
potential buyers subject to the three-day background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers and other Democrats said that previous compromise plans
offered by Hyde made it too easy for gun sellers to claim they were
not holding a gun show and thus would not be subject to background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers, in a response to Hyde, commended his willingness to
engage in substantive negotiations on the issue. Closing the gun
show loophole, he said, was ``an exceedingly modest proposition''
that Congress should be able to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   The House-Senate conference committee, put together to resolve
the differences between the two chambers' juvenile justice bills,
has not met since August.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Congress to move on gun-related legislation was a
major theme of the Million Mom March that drew several hundred
thousand marchers to the Washington Mall on Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.handguncontrol.org, www.nra.org,
www.arms-shows.org
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso can be reached by e-mail at
eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-STUDENTS-0527-C     05-26 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-STUDENTS-0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE STUDENTS HOPING OPEN TRADE LEADS TO OPEN RELATIONS WITH
WEST
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As China prepares to join the elite club of global
trading powers, college sophomore Joe Zhou is most excited not by
the unprecedented array of new opportunities that awaits him, but
rather the elevation of China's status in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has been developing and improving in the last 10
years,'' he said. ``Now, along with the United States, Japan,
Russia and Europe, it will be one of the five powers of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   While Zhou's generation will likely reap immense benefits from
China's agreement to open up its markets to more foreign
competition than ever before, he and other students interviewed at
the University of Foreign Languages here view accession to the Word
Trade Organization not just as a path towards increased trade and
business, but more broadly, as a way for China to join the global
village.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, China was isolated from the world,'' he said.
``But it's come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage of a trade bill Wednesday in the U.S. House of
Representatives permanently normalizing trade relations with China
will speed its entry into WTO as well as eliminate the annual
review of its trade status. The latter process has been marked by
scolding and criticisms of just about everything in China, from
religious freedom to workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Following the contentious vote, students were glad that yearly
ritual would finally come to end and expressed hope that Chinese
and American people, through increased business and cultural
contacts, would be able to get to know each other better.
</P>
<P>
   ``China and America need communication,'' said Yang Wangping, a
freshman majoring in English. ``The top-level officials
communicate, but we need more at the people-to-people level.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Edmond Zhu said Westerners know very little about
Chinese people and think of them as ``stiff and dull.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese seem dull, he explained, because they're afraid of
getting hassled if they say the wrong thing to a foreigner, so to
play it safe, they keep their conversations benign.
</P>
<P>
   ``But students feel pretty free,'' he said, then proceeded to
scoff at his own government officials to explain why Chinese appear
stiff. ``When you see the foreign ministry spokesperson on TV, he
has no expression. Nothing on his face is moving except for his
lips.''
</P>
<P>
   He hastens to add, though, that the top leaders, such as
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji, do quite well on
television.
</P>
<P>
   But other televised images of China are too stereotyped, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Hong Kong TV, whenever the foreign programs show China,
it's always Tiananmen Square and a bunch of red flags, as if we're
still in the Cultural Revolution,'' said Zhu, who is majoring in
French.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes in this country of 1.2 billion have been
dramatic since that turbulent decade, when all things foreign were
denounced as capitalist and young people were sent to get an
education not at universities but from peasants in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1978, a couple of years after the Cultural Revolution
officially ended and when the current group of college students was
just starting to come into the world, China's door to the outside
has been opening wider and wider. While it has not torn down all
the walls, change is all this generation has known.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to stand here 20 years ago to interview me, I
don't think I would've dared,'' said Zhou, who is majoring in
Italian. ``Two years ago, E-mail seemed like such a distant thing.
Now, Internet cafes are everywhere. People always ask for your
E-mail address when they want to get in touch with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, all college students were assigned jobs upon
graduation. The University of Foreign Languages was primarily a
feeder school to the ministries of Trade and Foreign Affairs. With
more foreign companies doing business in China, graduates have had
an increasing number of career choices.
</P>
<P>
   Having witnessed such drastic reforms in their short lives, none
regarded entry into the WTO as such a revolutionary event. In fact,
almost to a person, ``inevitable'' was the word they used to
describe it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, passage of the trade bill giving permanent normalized
trade status to China was seen as a natural development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Congress changed its path from idealism to
pragmatism,'' said Zhou Zhihua, a junior majoring in Arabic. ``If
it didn't pass, I would've been very surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it comes to political reforms, they know China does
not act quickly, but nor do other countries, they say. Several
students mentioned slavery in the American South and the long
period it took for black Americans to gain some measure of
equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't use American standards on an ancient country with
5,000 years of tradition and history,'' said Zhou Zhihua. ``We have
to be patient and tolerant.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, the French major, said he was happy with the pace of
democratization in China. In fact, there are some aspects of
Western democracy he hopes never to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't have that kind of campaigning with politicians
making speeches all over the country,'' he said. ``China doesn't
need that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more on WTO in China:
</P>
<P>
   www.chinaonline.com, an independent publisher of business news
in China.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
