<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-STUDENTS-0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE STUDENTS HOPING OPEN TRADE LEADS TO OPEN RELATIONS WITH
WEST
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As China prepares to join the elite club of global
trading powers, college sophomore Joe Zhou is most excited not by
the unprecedented array of new opportunities that awaits him, but
rather the elevation of China's status in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has been developing and improving in the last 10
years,'' he said. ``Now, along with the United States, Japan,
Russia and Europe, it will be one of the five powers of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   While Zhou's generation will likely reap immense benefits from
China's agreement to open up its markets to more foreign
competition than ever before, he and other students interviewed at
the University of Foreign Languages here view accession to the Word
Trade Organization not just as a path towards increased trade and
business, but more broadly, as a way for China to join the global
village.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, China was isolated from the world,'' he said.
``But it's come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage of a trade bill Wednesday in the U.S. House of
Representatives permanently normalizing trade relations with China
will speed its entry into WTO as well as eliminate the annual
review of its trade status. The latter process has been marked by
scolding and criticisms of just about everything in China, from
religious freedom to workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Following the contentious vote, students were glad that yearly
ritual would finally come to end and expressed hope that Chinese
and American people, through increased business and cultural
contacts, would be able to get to know each other better.
</P>
<P>
   ``China and America need communication,'' said Yang Wangping, a
freshman majoring in English. ``The top-level officials
communicate, but we need more at the people-to-people level.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Edmond Zhu said Westerners know very little about
Chinese people and think of them as ``stiff and dull.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese seem dull, he explained, because they're afraid of
getting hassled if they say the wrong thing to a foreigner, so to
play it safe, they keep their conversations benign.
</P>
<P>
   ``But students feel pretty free,'' he said, then proceeded to
scoff at his own government officials to explain why Chinese appear
stiff. ``When you see the foreign ministry spokesperson on TV, he
has no expression. Nothing on his face is moving except for his
lips.''
</P>
<P>
   He hastens to add, though, that the top leaders, such as
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji, do quite well on
television.
</P>
<P>
   But other televised images of China are too stereotyped, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Hong Kong TV, whenever the foreign programs show China,
it's always Tiananmen Square and a bunch of red flags, as if we're
still in the Cultural Revolution,'' said Zhu, who is majoring in
French.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes in this country of 1.2 billion have been
dramatic since that turbulent decade, when all things foreign were
denounced as capitalist and young people were sent to get an
education not at universities but from peasants in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1978, a couple of years after the Cultural Revolution
officially ended and when the current group of college students was
just starting to come into the world, China's door to the outside
has been opening wider and wider. While it has not torn down all
the walls, change is all this generation has known.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to stand here 20 years ago to interview me, I
don't think I would've dared,'' said Zhou, who is majoring in
Italian. ``Two years ago, E-mail seemed like such a distant thing.
Now, Internet cafes are everywhere. People always ask for your
E-mail address when they want to get in touch with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, all college students were assigned jobs upon
graduation. The University of Foreign Languages was primarily a
feeder school to the ministries of Trade and Foreign Affairs. With
more foreign companies doing business in China, graduates have had
an increasing number of career choices.
</P>
<P>
   Having witnessed such drastic reforms in their short lives, none
regarded entry into the WTO as such a revolutionary event. In fact,
almost to a person, ``inevitable'' was the word they used to
describe it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, passage of the trade bill giving permanent normalized
trade status to China was seen as a natural development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Congress changed its path from idealism to
pragmatism,'' said Zhou Zhihua, a junior majoring in Arabic. ``If
it didn't pass, I would've been very surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it comes to political reforms, they know China does
not act quickly, but nor do other countries, they say. Several
students mentioned slavery in the American South and the long
period it took for black Americans to gain some measure of
equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't use American standards on an ancient country with
5,000 years of tradition and history,'' said Zhou Zhihua. ``We have
to be patient and tolerant.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, the French major, said he was happy with the pace of
democratization in China. In fact, there are some aspects of
Western democracy he hopes never to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't have that kind of campaigning with politicians
making speeches all over the country,'' he said. ``China doesn't
need that.''
</P>
