<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ While the courtroom drama over
San Francisco's two newspapers winds down, the controversy over
whether The Examiner's editorial pages were used to smooth the
Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the Chronicle is just getting started.
On Thursday, James A. Finefrock, editor of The Examiner's editorial
pages, issued a blistering attack on a Bay Area media watchdog for
alleging that a ``subtle but troubling shift'' occurred in the
newspaper's editorial-page treatment of Mayor Willie Brown after an
Aug. 30, 1999, lunch with Examiner Publisher Timothy O. White. By
ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSTAMANTE-PARDON (San Antonio) _ It's been eight years since
Albert Bustamante strolled the chambers on Capitol Hill,
glad-handing with fellow congressmen as a San Antonio
representative to the U.S. House. But last week, Bustamante, in his
second year out of prison after serving 32 months for federal
racketeering and bribery convictions, was back on the House floor
shaking hands, this time trying to drum up support from his former
colleagues in an effort to secure a presidential pardon. By MATT
FLORES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-AWARDS (Undated) _ The talk going into the 1999-2000 season
was about diversity, or the lack thereof, on network television.
Broadcasters scurried to add color to their casts, but the problem
they couldn't solve was how to stop a summer show that exploded
into a yearlong phenomenon: ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' the ``Show of the Year'' in my ``Tube Awards.'' By
MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SHANGHAI (Undated) _ An amiably dopey western action
comedy, ``Shanghai Noon'' is a nice alternative to the
testosterone-powered ``Mission: Impossible 2.'' A Jackie Chan
vehicle, this kung fu horse opera trumps his last Hollywood outing,
1998's ``Rush Hour,'' by giving him a much better foil in the
surprisingly funny Owen Wilson. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HAPPENED (Undated) _ Back in 1956, 18-year-old Kevin
Brownlow had an idea for a movie. He and his friend Andrew Mollo
would reconstruct mid-1940s England from the invented perspective
of an England occupied by Nazi Germany. The film is now showing at
art houses. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-PASSION (Undated) _ The story in the new love film
``Passion of Mind'' involves two women, Marty and Marie, having
dreams about being each other. One lives in Provence; the other in
Manhattan. Both women are played by Demi Moore, who appears to be
caught in the headlights of this ``see, I'm still on the Hollywood
radar'' vehicle. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PRODUCTION-MEXICO) _ (Real de Catorce, Mexico) _ This town
that time left behind is being shoved into the 21st century by an
American movie. A film crew of nearly 200 has descended onto the
narrow, cobbled streets of this village located in a remote wrinkle
of the Sierra Madres. And the money and influence flooding in
promises to change Real de Catorce forever. By BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   TV-LIMBAUGH (Undated) _ ABC caved and gave Rush Limbaugh an
audition for the ``Monday Night Football'' job. Why should this
surprise us? NBC decided the entirety of its coverage of the Sydney
Olympic games will air on tape-delay. Why, again, should we be
taken aback? These are just two more examples of how little the
broadcast of a sporting event has to do with the final score or the
winning time. It's high time we all accept it and move on. By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-TOYOTA (San Antonio) _ What is the world's best-selling car
ever? Most of us have a favorite or two we think ought to be on
that list, but to make such a list, the car would have to be a
mass-market vehicle rather than just a niche car such as the
Chevrolet Corvette, America's sports car. The winner, in a news
flash announced recently by Toyota, is the compact Toyota Corolla.
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-MUSTANG (San Antonio) _ Let's face it. Nothing is quite as
exhilarating as driving along winding country roads in a
convertible with a big V-8 engine and the top down. And almost
nothing is quite like the 2000 Mustang GT convertible to take on
just such a drive. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SPORTS-MODELS (San Antonio) _ It's easy to lust after exotic
cars such as the half-million-dollar Ferrari or Lamborghini, the
$130,000 Mercedes-Benz SL600 convertible, the $82,000 Jaguar XKR
convertible, or even the more realistically priced Chevrolet
Corvette soft-top, at just over $45,000. But some automakers are
making sure we have a chance to own affordable yet sporty cars that
put smiles on our faces as we cruise down city streets or along
country roads. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SEASHELLS (Undated) _ Seashells are not only home to mollusks,
they can also be used to decorate. Seashells arranged in
geometrical or floral patterns embellish objects such as picture
frames, boxes, mirrors and tables. They can also be arranged to
form pictures or strung for hanging plants. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEINS. (For release Sunday, May 28.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ As a former member of the
National Rifle Association (as a kid learning to shoot my .22) and
supporter of the right to keep arms (if not bear them under one's
coat), I wonder who's giving the NRA's Wayne LaPierre and Charlton
Heston business advice. Open an NRA gun-theme restaurant in Times
Square? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
