<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Come and listen to my story about a man and stray dogs
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ A guy came by my office a while back with a
problem. It was his wife.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves the possibilities wide open, I know. For a fact, if
you are female and were to switch the word ``wife'' and put in
``husband'' the range of problems could stretch forever.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not forever, because this guy's problem was that is
wife was too attractive.
</P>
<P>
   (I wonder how many wives have husbands that are too attractive?
Please, don't all of you speak out at once.)
</P>
<P>
   The guy even showed me a picture of his wife and he was right.
Blonde hair, blue eyes. She could have been a California girl, but
she's really better. She was born in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I was having trouble understanding his problem and he launched
into a tale of woe.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that every night his wife goes out walking in an effort
to keep her youthful figure. Her husband doesn't join her because,
truth to tell, even when he was youthful he had no youthful figure.
He never lost his baby fat.
</P>
<P>
   But the woman's youngest son, a teen-ager, does accompany his
mother. Living in the country, it is a pleasant walk almost any
time of the year. The guy told me sometimes mother and son walk
four or five miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   So one day the woman decided to vary the walk. Who could have
known the result? Who could have told the future?
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the road less taken, the woman and her son soon came
upon some figures a distance up the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that?'' the son asked.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to determine. It was a wild pack of dogs,
ten or more. The woman stopped in her tracks. This could be
serious. Wild dogs in the country can be mean. A whole pack of them
can be absolutely dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The woman decided it was time to turn around. The dogs still
came, of course, baying as they got closer. When they were in plain
sight, the boy picked up a rock and chunked it at the nearest dog.
The dog sniffed the rock, then picked it up. He wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and son were relieved to know the dogs weren't dangerous,
but they continued their walk home. Oddly, though they weren't
playing with them, the dogs followed as well.
</P>
<P>
   As she got closer to home the woman tried to shoo them away a
couple of times but it didn't work. They all arrived home en masse.
</P>
<P>
   The hound dogs took up as if they'd always lived there, finding
places on the porch or under trees that made the woman's house look
like the Clampett residence the day before ol' Jed went a-huntin'
for some food. Indeed, besides looking like Elly Mae, the wife
seems to have the same sort of skills with animals.
</P>
<P>
   The woman ordered her son not to feed the dogs a single scrap,
though she couldn't stop him from giving them all names. I think
there were enough dogs to cover all of Santa's reindeer and the
seven dwarfs.
</P>
<P>
   A few times the woman came outside to try to get them to go
away, but they were tired from the walk and it was a pleasant day
just to sun on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   The woman had given up by the time her husband came home with
his truck. There was no way to get the dogs away other than taking
them back where they came from. The dogs willfully got into the
truck _ though they barely fit _ one of them laying his head on the
son's knee as if they'd had a life-long relationship. He took the
dogs back ``home'' and a little beyond.
</P>
<P>
   When he last looked in the rearview mirror, they were simply
standing there, looking for a place to lay down.
</P>
<P>
   So the guy and his wife thought the matter was done. Thought so
until the next morning when they stepped out on the front porch and
saw Donner, Dancer, Dopey, Sneezy, Rudolph and the rest laying
there as if they'd never left. The guy tells me all of them wagged
their tails vigorously when they saw his wife walk outside.
</P>
<P>
   So the guy loaded them in his truck again thinking about, but
ultimately rejecting, a suggestion by his son to put a tiny
blindfold over each dog's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Again they went down winding country roads, again they dropped
them off where they'd originally came from. Again, the guy doesn't
have much faith that they won't return. He's thinking the dogs see
this as a kind of elaborate game of hide-and-seek.
</P>
<P>
   And all of it, he says, is his wife's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but I'd suggest they just keep the dogs. It will save
on gas and energy trying to drive them away. Besides, the guy may
find out he can hunt better than he ever thought. It worked for the
Clampetts.
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
