<HEADER>
A6351 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD27-COX     05-26 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digging up solutions to a hole-y problem
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An interesting problem gleaned from the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this beautiful old bureau that I've stripped down to
the original wood only to find that over the years various knobs
and pulls have been applied to the drawer fronts. Any suggestions
on the best method to hide the roughly 1/8-inch plastic wood-filled
holes that show?''
</P>
<P>
   One gentleman responded with, ``Drill the holes and hammer golf
tees into them, and then saw them off flush.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. That might suffice if you're going to paint the drawers,
but otherwise it will merely highlight the holes.
</P>
<P>
   There's no simple answer for dealing with this problem in
well-aged wood. Basically, the best way to fill unwanted holes is
to take a scrap of the same wood and, using a plug cutter in a
drill press, produce plugs of the proper size.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have any plug cutters, you should be able to find
them at any woodworker's store. They aren't expensive, and they can
be a lifesaver for repairing all kinds of damage in addition to
unwanted screw and bolt holes.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, enlarge the holes so that the plugs you make are a
perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   Since the plugs show side grain at the surface, reasonable care
in matching the grain should result in a fairly invisible repair,
although if a number of repairs have to be made in fairly close
proximity invisibility may be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   The point, however, is to repair side grain with side grain.
Plugging side grain with end grain isn't going to make a very neat
repair.
</P>
<P>
   The problem this gentleman has, of course, is trying to get new
wood (the plugs) to match the old wood of the drawer fronts.
</P>
<P>
   I should add that among the advice he got was the simplest, and
in general perhaps the best, method _ use a drawer pull with a big
base plate, large enough to cover the holes. Alas, he reported, the
holes are way too far apart to be covered this way.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, if you have a tiny hole to fill, and you don't
want to drill it out so that you can cut a plug to fill it, try
this:
</P>
<P>
   Take a matching piece of wood and with a backsaw or a dozuki,
cut a tiny cross-grain square sliver and carefully sand it to a
point. This is problematic, of course, because it's going to break
very easily, but it doesn't have to be long. It just has to be thin
enough to get started into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   With a wooden or rubber mallet, tap the sliver in until it fills
the hole. However square it may be to begin with, it will expand to
fill the round hole. Cut any overhang with a knife, then plane it
flush with the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Jack Warner at jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
