A6357 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX     05-26 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox a less ordinary celebrity
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ This is a story about the day in 1985 when I sat
side by side on a couch, in a hotel room with Michael J. Fox. His
cobalt blue eyes locked onto mine _ at last, a cute guy my same
height! _ as he spoke with passion and fervor.
</P>
<P>
   The story up to this point is 100 percent true. But, alas, Fox's
wife Tracy Pollan had nothing to worry about, then or now.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, then 23 and on the brink of Back to the Future
superstardom, had come to Cincinnati to attend the national
convention of the Spina Bifida Foundation. As national awareness
spokesman for the group, Fox was stepping into the role he recently
has been acclaimed for embracing: Advocate.
</P>
<P>
   He cared deeply about the cause because his nephew, Jeffrey, had
been born with spina bifida. Foreshadowing his Parkinson's disease
activism, Fox called the Spina Bifida Association and said, ``Use
me. Abuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   My brief acquaintance with Fox comes in handy when I'm speaking
to schoolchildren. When they start to wiggle and deploy paper
airplanes, I deploy the Famous Person Emergency Backup System.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I try to get them excited about journalism by telling
them, ``The best part of my job is going out and meeting people _
ordinary people who find themselves in extraordinary situations.''
</P>
<P>
   I tell them about the young woman who fought back, and fortified
her faith, after losing half her body in a devastating car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   I tell them about the home that is unfailingly brimming with
love and good cheer, even though two of their four children were
born with a degenerative disease. Even though they lost their
youngest at 3, after a bone marrow transplant that might have saved
her.
</P>
<P>
   I tell them that everyday people are the most amazing people I
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Adults nod appreciatively at this sentiment. But kids are a
tough audience. The very toughest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a reporter, you do sometimes get to meet famous
people,'' I tell them. This snaps them to attention immediately.
Hands start flailing in the air. ``What famous people have you
met?''
</P>
<P>
   They are profoundly disappointed that I have never met Michael
Jordan. They are nonplussed by Pete Rose and have never heard of
Saul Bellow or Toni Morrison. If my friend the sportswriter were
here, I know I'd be in the dust. Thank God for Michael J. Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what struck me then was how natural, how downright regular,
he was. Only a few years ago distant from the days when he couldn't
afford a telephone, he laughed delightedly at the whole absurd
notion of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   When he tried out for the role of Alex Keaton on Family Ties, it
``was just another audition,'' Fox told me. ``It was kind of
unusual in that I said that I didn't want to do sitcom.'' He seemed
determined to enjoy the ride, however long it lasted: ``I enjoy the
celebrity. There's an instant review of how well you do your job
every time you go out on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he is stepping off the ride to expend his stardom on
something far more meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Good for him, and good for all of us. You wonder why more
celebrities, blessed with clout and capital, don't do the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, my ``prize celebrity'' doesn't seem so much like
a celebrity after all.
</P>
<P>
   Even after nearly 20 years of stardom, he still seems more like
an ordinary guy in an extraordinary situation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
