<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIM PREVIEW OF HTML VIRUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I was recently advised, in the wake of the Love
Bug virus, to disable the preview pane of Microsoft Outlook
Express. I thought infection could be avoided as long as the file
attachment was not opened. Is it possible to acquire an infection
from the basic e-mail message?
</P>
<P>
   _ Toxic Mail
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TOX: I give up. Let's just unplug all our computers and
leave them off until it's safe, maybe during the next ``Star Trek''
convention, when these losers who think it's funny to bring systems
around the globe to a crawl will be busy wearing rubber ears and
telling knock-knock jokes in Klingonese.
</P>
<P>
   In the good old days, the pond scum would simply attach a virus
to an e-mail, and it triggered when the recipient opened it. If you
delete those without opening them (they usually have .VBS, .JS or
.EXE extensions), you'll be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Now the weasels exploit the most useful features of popular
e-mail programs to deliver their payloads. That preview pane was a
great idea until some Poindexter figured out he could send a letter
full of HTML, the Web-page design language. The pane displays the
HTML the same way a browser would, and that means you can receive
something as innocuous _ and irritating _ as a letter playing a
background song or as malicious as an embedded virus script.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the preview pane closed should protect you, but you're
still not totally safe. There are viruses such as the KakWorm,
which is attached to a letter like a signature file. Maybe the
geeks at Microsoft and all the other companies should just strip
out every useful or innovative feature from their mail programs,
and we'd all be able to sleep better.
</P>
<P>
   About all you can do is be careful about what you open, and run
virus protection software. And keep that software up to date.
Microsoft releases security patches whenever a problem is found,
and the antivirus people respond to new threats within hours.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I send free greeting cards on the Internet. Is
this why I'm getting all this spam?
</P>
<P>
   _ Deluged
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DEL: Yes. Did you think they were letting you send those
things out of the goodness of their hearts? Just like any other
business, these people build mailing lists to identify possible
customers. On the other hand, nobody says you have to give them
your ``correct'' name and e-mail address, if you get my drift.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: About two months ago, I wrote to you about a
small problem I was having with my system. Since I never heard from
you, I gave up and bought myself a brand-new one. I then sent my
existing system to my daughter via the U.S. Postal Service. After
carefully packing it in bubble wrap and newspapers, I insured it
for the same amount I paid for my new system. When it arrived at
her house, it looked like it had been run over by a dump truck. I
took the insurance money and bought her a brand-new system. Ha! Two
for one. I just wanted to thank you! Had you responded to my
problem, I would still be stuck with the old system, and my
daughter would have none. Thank you so much for ignoring me!! I am
very grateful!
</P>
<P>
   _ Thanks for Nothing
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NOTHING: It was the least I could do. Truly.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's hope no postal inspectors are reading this. They tend
to take a dim view of overinsuring easily damaged parcels. Good
luck with the interrogation!
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay promises to not help
you, too, although he offers occasionally accurate advice about
most things electronic. He can be reached on Internet at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817) 390-7257.
In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
