<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-PASSION-H     05-26 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PASSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A PASSIONLESS, MINDLESS `PASSION OF MIND' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story in the new love film ``Passion of Mind'' involves two
women, Marty and Marie, having dreams about being each other. One
lives in Provence; the other in Manhattan; both have some of the
most criminally noxious dialogue this side of NBC's ``Providence.''
Both women are played by Demi Moore, who appears to be caught in
the headlights of this ``see, I'm still on the Hollywood radar''
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Moore sounds bored when meant to express rapture, as if
nauseated by notions of happiness. If she's blinded by the monotony
here, what chance do we have? It's a performance of such
accidentally exposed blandness that one wants to taunt ``I see
London, I see France. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes in, I was having a tough time locating either
passion or mind, but the outlandish supply of couture housewares
seems endless. ``Passion of Mind'' has been co-written by Ron Bass
(``Waiting to Exhale,'' ``Snow Falling on Cedars'') as the stuff of
pure Harlequin swill. Some of it makes Judith Krantz read like
Edith Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it seems unfair that the opening helicopter shot
that pores over the French countryside doesn't feature Fabio
superimposed over it with Moore's raven locks and one side of her
face buried in his breasts. Instead, we get a certain unkempt
realism in the casting of the two men in her life, played by
Stellan Skarsgard and William Fitchner, two fine, if creepy, actors
willing to be bullied by the dictates of this paperback story.
Skarsgard, playing a French writer, is particularly engaged by all
of this.
</P>
<P>
   Moore can't help but be rotten. She has no grace and little
nuance, which is why she's always best as a hard-ass in movies by
directors with a problematic grasp of a lady's strength like Adrian
Lyne's ``Indecent Proposal'' or Ridley Scott's ``G.I. Jane,''
which, thanks to her, is still a compellingly sweaty two hours. But
Skarsgard? From the moment he enters the film as William, the
French writer to whom Marie's daughter wanders by accident, he
seems too pleased to be here.
</P>
<P>
   She panned his book; he brings candy and flowers for her two
girls. Still, she's skeptical about his advances. ``Sometimes I
wish you didn't look like you do,'' he says. ``People that look
like you have learned not to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, this is called acting, but is there anyone who can bring
off a conversation like that without consulting Douglas Sirk first?
Still, Skarsgard doesn't let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make love to you,'' William tells Marie. ``All my
life, sex never really brought me closer. (It's) the beginning of
the end. I don't want this to end.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a masochist and a fool. But in the truest sense of the
genre's pretenses, William is a sustained Harlequin erection, which
is to say he'll do anything to untie Marie's apron and sweep her
into his arms, make love to her, then leave her in an existential
funk. In the film's cruelest/funniest scene, Demi/Marie lies in bed
and asks, ``Can I have that much mystery?'' And Stellan/William
just rests beside her staring at the ceiling saying/thinking
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Manhattan, Marty has just started seeing an
accountant (Fitchner), in whom she's confided her dreams about
Marie. All she wants is his friendship, but he's given her a pair
of Brooklyn Bridge earrings. And her heart can seem to say no. But
there's something unsettling about Fitchner's druggy demeanor that
leads you to believe that he's turned on by the idea that he's
sleeping with two women. He should be afraid that he's taken up
with a chick who is dressed like one of Prince's ``Purple Rain''
courtesans and whose apartment looks like the Metropolitan Museum
of Art and Sotheby's took turns throwing up in it.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing we'll miss the Marie/Marty connection, director Alain
Berliner, the Frenchman who made the film about a 9-year-old drag
queen, ``Ma Vie en Rose,'' shows Marie the Francophile sucking on
Orangina and does things like juxtapose one woman rising as the
other goes to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The film's conceit is that it's meant to be a tribute to Krystof
Kieslowski's ``The Double Life of Veronique.'' But this is just a
slow dance on the director's grave. If there's any justice, the
folks at Oxygen will develop some ``Mystery Romance Theater 3000''
show to jeer love this bad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
