<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6379 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-HAPPENED-     05-26 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HAPPENED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WARTIME FILM GAINS FORCE WITH RESTORED FOOTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1956, 18-year-old Kevin Brownlow had an idea for a
movie. He and his friend Andrew Mollo would reconstruct mid-1940s
Britain from the invented perspective of a Britain occupied by Nazi
Germany. They would cast amateur actors and borrow period military
and hospital uniforms and equipment to create a country under siege
by outside forces and undermined by its own philosophical naivete
and apolitical urges.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of considerable upheaval and with film stock
donated by Stanley Kubrick and Tony Richardson, ``It Happened
Here'' was released in a deal struck between Brownlow and Mollo
with United Artists. The studio was disturbed by one of the
passages involving a repugnant Jews vs. Aryans lecture by the
British Nazi Colin Jordan and had it omitted in a censored version.
It was an attempt to sanitize a film already steeped in visceral
and ideological ugliness.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years later, Brownlow has reinstated that critical
scene. And for the past 18 months, ``It Happened Here'' has been
making a provocative return to the world's art houses. A preeminent
film restorationist and cinephile _ it's rumored that he began
building his film library when he was 11, and there were no VCRs
then _ Brownlow orchestrated the famously painstaking
reconstruction of Abel Gance's silent five-hour classic,
``Napoleon,'' among other works. That he redirected his passion for
restoring others' films to one of his own, is a boon for us.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in black-and-white in London years after the blitz, ``It
Happened Here'' visits entire lots reduced to rubble and hungover
with an ashen, grayed sullenness.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlow and Mollo decided to tell the story almost entirely
from the point of view of Pauline (Pauline Murray), a nurse and war
widow, whose life has been ruptured by the Nazis and by the British
liberation factions.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline simply wants law and order restored to her country.
Seeking work, she naively joins the British-Nazi occupation forces,
under the presumption that she'd be nursing sick soldiers. All
along Pauline believes that because her decision is apolitical, so,
too, should the implications of her actions be, as though there's
an unread copy of Hannah Arendt's ``On Violence'' in her medicine
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline looks distantly like Greer Garson, the saintly, overly
charming '40s star, only tired, lacking radiance and untouched by
romance, Max Factor or a lucid sense of ideology. It's a complex
characterization of a smart woman making a foolish choice,
oblivious to the nightmare she's gotten herself into. The
revelation of what Pauline is being consigned to do at some remote
care facility is shot in scary too-tight close-ups. It's the kind
of thing you feared was going on. Its disclosure is a satisfying,
frightening plot twist that later shows up in numerous medical
potboilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It Happened Here'' is shockingly true to its historic
fictional time in the vein of Aldous Huxley and George Orwell. Its
re-release seems perfectly timed to evoke the
territorial/ideological disputes raging in places like Ethiopia and
Eastern Europe and remind us what ridiculous twilight zones they
are, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
