<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AWARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `MILLIONAIRE' CAPTURES A NATION, AND `SHOW OF YEAR' AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this time last year, the question would seem sarcastic at
best, psychotic at worst, but more than likely just plain stupid:
</P>
<P>
   Who or what can stop the juggernaut that is Regis Philbin?
</P>
<P>
   The talk going into the 1999-2000 season was about diversity, or
the lack thereof, on network television. Broadcasters scurried to
add color to their casts, but the problem they couldn't solve was
how to stop a summer show that exploded into a yearlong phenomenon:
ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' is responsible for adding ``Are you sure?'' and
``Is that your final answer?'' to the popular lexicon, all while
hogging multiple Top 10 ratings slots. While copycat efforts by the
other networks failed, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' endured,
and is an easy pick for SHOW OF THE YEAR in my annual ``Tube
Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the rest of the best, worst and otherwise
notable shows, events and people from the just-concluded television
season.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SHOW: ``The Sopranos,'' HBO. This is a much closer call
than last year, when the freshman drama rocked television. While
this season failed to rise to that standard (too many uneven
moments), ``The Sopranos'' at its best is far superior to anything
else on TV. At its worst, it still beats most network fare.
</P>
<P>
   WORST SHOW: ``The Mike O'Malley Show,'' NBC. The year's first
ratings casualty, this sitcom debuted Dead on Arrival. Didn't
anybody learn from Brian Benben? Don't name a show after yourself
if it stinks. O'Malley (who can be funny) has been rewarded with a
new CBS sitcom for next season, proving conclusively that there is
life after death, on the networks at least.
</P>
<P>
   MOST VALUABLE SHOW: ``WWF Smackdown,'' UPN. The Universally
Panned Network was on the verge of oblivion before it sold what
soul it had to Vince McMahon and the World Wrestling Federation.
UPN certainly got its money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   BEST NEW DRAMA: ``The West Wing,'' NBC. This Aaron Sorkin drama
sometimes dips too deep into the sentimental well and veers back
and forth from the political left, but sharp writing and a great
ensemble cast makes this White House drama a bipartisan hit.
</P>
<P>
   BEST NEW SHOW NOT TO MAKE IT: ``Freaks and Geeks,'' NBC. Fox
bailed early on the funny Hollywood satire ``Action,'' but they
knew they were taking a chance with such an inside show. But
``Freaks and Geeks'' was a by-the-book drama, extremely well
written but ratings-challenged.
</P>
<P>
   BEST NEW COMEDY: ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' Fox. This is a
smart, sharp sitcom, combining some of the low-brow elements of
``Married ... with Children'' with the wit of ``The Simpsons.''
``Malcolm'' has been a saving grace in a horrible season for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   BEST FINALE: ``Frasier,'' NBC. Niles and Daphne running away
together on her wedding day, just as it seemed the fussy doctor had
lost her forever, was a great ``The Graduate'' twist to a very
funny and moving season-ending episode.
</P>
<P>
   BEST FINALE RUINED BY A STUPID ENDING: ``The West Wing.'' What a
missed opportunity: Lose the assassination attempt at the end (memo
to writers: The presidential motorcade would never park in a
concrete canyon that amounted to a sniper shooting gallery) and you
would have had one of the best finales.
</P>
<P>
   BEST CANCELED SHOW: ``Sports Night,'' ABC. HBO might pick it up.
If not, chalk up another great show dying a ratings death. Who
cares _ just add more Regis, right?
</P>
<P>
   BIGGEST TRAIN WRECK: ``The Early Show,'' CBS. Retooling the
Bryant Gumbel show won't do it. Rehauling? Nope. Retiring? Yeah,
that's it.
</P>
<P>
   BEST EXIT: Michael J. Fox, ``Spin City,'' ABC. Spend time
looking for his bad side; you won't find one. Classy departure,
classy man.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PUNCHING BAG CRITICS WILL MISS: ``Veronica's Closet,'' NBC.
Once a Top 10 show thanks to its slot on Thursday night, the series
plummeted in the ratings when it was moved to Mondays before being
canceled. The show's title was perfect shorthand for bad
television.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MORNING KIDS SHOW: ``Zoboomafoo,'' PBS. A combination of
live action, claymation and puppetry, this morning outdoor show
introduces children to the animal kingdom, featuring good enough
cornball humor to make adults laugh.
</P>
<P>
   WRITER OF THE YEAR: Sorkin, ``The West Wing'' and ``Sports
Night.'' Sorkin unseats David E. Kelley as the most gifted
executive producer in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MINISERIES: ``The Corner,'' HBO. Further proof of the
necessity of cable, this incredible but downbeat short series never
would have aired on a broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   BEST NETWORK MINISERIES: ``Jesus,'' CBS. Daring yet devout.
</P>
<P>
   BEST TREND: Older women actually existing on television. In the
``Logan's Run'' world of Hollywood, that means anyone over 30. Call
it the Sela Ward factor (``Once and Again,'' ABC).
</P>
<P>
   BEST MOVIE: ``Annie,'' ABC. It's still fun even after the 27th
viewing with your 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   BEST '60s SITCOM NOT CHRONICLED IN A BEHIND-THE-SCENES MOVIE:
None.
</P>
<P>
   MOST IMPROVED SHOW: ``King of Queens,'' CBS. Kevin James has
emerged from the shadow of his buddy, Ray Romano.
</P>
<P>
   LOW POINT OF THE SEASON: ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multi-Millionaire?'' Fox. You would think they couldn't sink lower.
You would be wrong, of course.
</P>
<P>
   BEST NETWORK TO WATCH INSTEAD OF WRITING A YEAR-END AWARDS
STORY: TV Land. ``Emergency!'' just gets funnier and funnier every
day.
</P>
<P>
   BEST GUILTY PLEASURE SHOW: ``Third Watch,'' NBC. The characters
are underdrawn, the plots are predictable and the acting is a hair
above fair. But I still watch (please don't tell anyone). It must
be a Kim Raver thing.
</P>
<P>
   EVENT OF THE SEASON: The millennium, all channels. From live
coverage of parties from around the globe to ``Three Stooges''
marathons, what was thought to be the mother of all party nights _
New Year's Eve 1999 _ turned out to be the night to stay in front
of the tube. After all, you haven't lived until you've seen a new
century dawn over Newfoundland. You wonder what they will do next
New Year's when the new millennium really arrives.
</P>
<P>
   EVENT OF THE SEASON (Runner up): The Elian Gonzalez saga. This
bizarre tale of geopolitics, a father's rights and colorful
relatives has all the makings of a made-for-TV movie. Or two. Or
five ...
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD DID NOT END AWARD: Willow announces her lesbian love
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' WB), and Dr. Jack McNeil said ``s---
happens'' on ``Chicago Hope'' (CBS). Somehow, television and
Western civilization survived.
</P>
<P>
   BEST QUOTES, EXECUTIVES: A tit-for-tat between Les Moonves of
CBS and Scott Sassa of NBC regarding two Jesus-based miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Jesus is better than your Jesus,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Les tell you he invented the Bible?'' Sassa countered.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OFF-SCREEN QUOTE, ACTOR: Martin Sheen of ``The West Wing,''
when asked facetiously how it felt to be the poster boy for
diversity _ ``Well, I'm Latin by birth and Irish by trade, so ...''
</P>
<P>
   WORST LOCAL COMMERCIAL: Virtually all lawyer television spots.
``If you've been bitten by a mongoose on public transportation on a
weekend holiday, you should have money coming to you.'' For these
guys, ``class'' is just another type of lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
