r l BC-DIRECTORY_NONASSISTAN     05-26 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTORY_NONASSISTANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE I REACHED THE PERSON TO WHOM I AM SPEAKING? PROBABLY NOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am a little cranky about this thing called directory
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   I am cranky because half the time I call it, I'm given the wrong
number. I am cranky because a quarter of the time I call it, I'm
told there's no such listing. And I am cranky because every time I
call it, the phone companies tempt my slothful side by offering to
dial the number for me. (Message to AT&AMP;T: Stop it! I need that 50
cents way more than you do.)
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, I love the phone book. I have five at my desk, and I
use them as often as I can. But for out-of-town calls, I, like many
people, am at the mercy of directory assistance. I need numbers. I
need them fast. I dial the dreaded 555-1212.
</P>
<P>
   When I first decided to write this, I wondered whether these
things happened only to me. Whether directory assistance had
improved since our newspaper last wrote a story about how
lamentable it was (1997). Whether, perhaps, I somehow mysteriously
attract inept phone service. So I sent an e-mail seeking input from
friends and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, I had a record number of replies.
</P>
<P>
   The operator couldn't find Mineral Wells, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The operator couldn't find TXU Electric &AMP; Gas.
</P>
<P>
   The operator couldn't find the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be fair. This usually isn't the fault of the poor shlub
answering the phone. ``It all has to do with them (i.e., the
government) opening the market to competition,'' says Janee
Briesemeister of Consumers Union's southwest regional office in
Austin. (Consumers Union publishes Consumer Reports magazine.)
``The (phone) companies don't want to give each other the numbers
of their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hello? Isn't sharing one of those make-the-world-a-better-place
behaviors we learn in kindergarten?
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, directory assistance isn't a local enterprise
anymore. There was a time when the operators actually lived and
worked in the area codes they processed. What a concept! Now I call
for a number in Boston, and I get a guy in New Mexico: ``Fenway
Park? Is that a business or a residence?'' (No, that didn't really
happen, but would it have surprised you?)
</P>
<P>
   I remember when I first moved to Chicago, sitting in a bare dorm
room and needing to call a restaurant in town. I dialed
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T, this is Mr. Winkler speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Winky?!'' I shouted. It was my friend Steve, who lived no more
than a 20-minute drive north. How much more neighborly can you get?
And what if the restaurant I wanted to call had just closed, or
moved, or served its steak tartare medium-rare? Theoretically,
Steve might have been able to warn me. Now THAT'S information.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we get operators who haven't even heard of the places
where we live. We call for a phone number in Trophy Club and they
balk: ``Is that really a city?'' We can see a grocery store from a
bedroom window, and they tell us there is no such place. We ask for
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, and they
ask us to spell Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   All true stories.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't just rely on anecdotes from friends. I personally
experimented with directory assistance, calling places for which I
had the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   My first request: The Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   What I got: (817) 429-2655.
</P>
<P>
   I've worked at this newspaper for four years, and I have never,
ever heard of this phone number. (Turns out, after some digging,
that it's our metro number.)
</P>
<P>
   I call for two numbers in Illinois, one in Dallas and one in
Boulder, Colo. The operators get them all right. But in between
those success stories are these: I request Salon magazine in San
Francisco, dial the number and am nearly deafened by the
high-pitched beep of a fax machine. Three times, I call for the
General Cinema Theatres headquarters _ NOT the movie theater,
please! _ in Chestnut Hill, Mass., and three times I get the movie
listings at the local General Cinemas multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   After two operators tell me there's no such business as Smith,
Bucklin &AMP; Associates in Chicago, I call the number I have for
Smith, Bucklin and ask why directory assistance has no listing for
them. ``I don't know,'' says the receptionist. ``Maybe you had a
dumb operator.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the phone companies blew it half the time _ and cost
this newspaper $14.12 for wrong, or no, numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my suggestion: Get bad phone service, give bad phone
business. Don't use directory assistance unless you absolutely have
to! Dial your own numbers when you do! And call the state Public
Utility Commission to let it know which phone companies are giving
you permanent hearing loss and which are going out of their way to
be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   I'll even save you a buck and a potential throbbing headache:
</P>
<P>
   Your toll-free number for the PUC is (888) 782-8477.
</P>
<P>
   Happy complaining.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
