r e BC-TV-LIMBAUGH-HNS &LR;      05-26 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIMBAUGH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A RUSH JOB FOR `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL'? NOT LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ABC caved in and gave Rush Limbaugh an audition
for the ``Monday Night Football'' job. Why should this surprise us?
</P>
<P>
   NBC decided the entirety of its coverage of the Sydney Olympic
games will air on tape-delay. Why, again, should we be taken aback?
</P>
<P>
   These are just two more examples of how little the broadcast of
a sporting event has to do with the final score or the winning
time. It's high time we all accept it and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Putting sports on television merely for sports' sake is
shortsighted thinking. Why should a game or an event appeal only to
those who are genuinely interested? Let's throw the net out a
little wider and see if we can attract the casual fan, the couch
potato without a life or _ dare we dream? _ women.
</P>
<P>
   With that mandate, hiring Limbaugh, a man whose appeal (or lack
thereof) extends beyond the borders of sports, isn't that much of a
stretch. Nor is floating names like Jesse Ventura or Billy Crystal.
With that mandate, NBC can justify turning half of its Olympic
schedule into a Christina Aguilera video and the other half into a
three-hankie Lifetime movie of the week.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about demographics, which is just a fancy word for
people who buy stuff. Advertisers like to put their commercials on
shows where a lot of people who buy stuff will be watching. And
those people apparently want entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   Giving sports a little entertainment value used to mean showing
the cheerleaders or featuring the marching band at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore, not if you can fly in Calista Flockhart and give
her good seats down the third base line or have Ted Danson stroll
by the booth and chat with the guys at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you can hire someone to sit in the ``Monday Night
Football'' booth who will represent ``the fan,'' no matter how much
it bends the credibility of the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you can take a competition that happens once every four
years _ an event that oozes with inherent drama _ package the
pertinent details, add colorful graphics, cut out the extraneous
elements (i.e., any competitor from another country) and set it to
music.
</P>
<P>
   There are silver linings to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh isn't likely to get the job at ABC, which is just happy
the publicity has temporarily disguised the fact that there are no
truly good candidates out there to sit next to Al Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   And NBC has added a couple of cable networks to carry all the
sports it rendered unwatchable to the masses in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Fox begins the fifth and final year of its deal as the network
carrier for Major League Baseball on Saturday with a predictable
matchup: Boston vs. New York Yankees at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports President Ed Goren is confident that the network will
re-up with baseball when negotiations begin in the next few months.
After paying $575 million the last time around, the price tag is
sure to go up, and NBC and CBS are certainly going to be interested
in getting in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner (Bud Selig) and (MLB TV committee chairman)
Paul Beeson have expressed what the relationship with Fox has meant
to the game over the last four years,'' Goren said. ``When we came
in to pick up the baseball contract (in the post-strike year of
1995), baseball was going through some tough times. We stepped in
at a time when not everybody was willing to step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty probably means that Fox is going to end up in the
picture once again, but it's not going to do a thing to hold down
the price.
</P>
<P>
   For all the buttons and whistles that the folks at Fox like to
use _ you know, ``Catcher-cam'' and ``Sounds of the Game'' _ they
have done a good job with their broadcasts, mixing energy and
enthusiasm for the game with insight and information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
