<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; SATURDAY, May 27, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Beirut) _ Developments: A U.N. peace envoy said
that Lebanon has agreed to accept U.N. certification of the
withdrawal. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON-BORDER (Dateline to come) _ A dramatic
face-to-face moment unfolded Friday as Hezbollah guerrillas
celebrated along the border and Israelis ventured to the fence out
of curiosity. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-TAIWAN-CHINA (Beijing) _ After talks with Chinese military
leaders and diplomats, a U.S. official said Friday that he sees
hope that China and Taiwan can resume a dialogue over their
differences. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Lima) _ Developments: The head of the
Organization of American States election monitoring group has left
the country in protest, opening the possibility of sanctions in the
future. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-POLITICS (Belfast) _ Members of the 870-member ruling
council of the Ulster Unionist party convene here on Saturday for a
crucial vote that will either give new life to the Northern Ireland
peace accord or likely finish it off. By Warren Hoge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-TAX (Islamabad) _ ``WARNING!'' scream the big ads in
the newspapers. ``All taxpayers are warned that a comprehensive tax
survey is being launched soon in which your concealed income and
assets will be unearthed.'' In many countries, such an admonition
might strike fear among the minority who forget, fudge or outright
refuse to file. But here in Pakistan, where taxes have yet to join
death as one of life's inevitabilities, the warning applies to just
about everyone. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
