<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-26 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUST DON'T BITE THE BULLET AT THE NRA CAFE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a former member of the National Rifle
Association (as a kid learning to shoot my .22) and supporter of
the right to keep arms (if not bear them under one's coat), I
wonder who's giving the NRA's Wayne LaPierre and Charlton Heston
business advice.
</P>
<P>
   Open an NRA gun-theme restaurant in Times Square?
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre, the NRA's executive vice president, floated that idea
at his organization's national convention a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson oil on salads. Browning all meats. Marlin as
safety catch of the day. Colt platters of Kalashnikov kasha and Sig
sauerkraut, with .357 Magnums of Champagne. Full metal jackets
required.
</P>
<P>
   It's too damn easy.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre and Heston, the NRA president, should realize that if
they were a 25-yard pistol target, they'd be the proverbial side of
a barn.
</P>
<P>
   No, they're not even that hard to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a shot at the LaPierre-Heston NRA is like shooting at a
barn from the inside with the door shut. Why more shooters don't
find Heston and LaPierre embarrassing, I haven't a clue.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the media conspiracy, with a family history of
gun ownership dating back to the Revolutionary War musket over the
fireplace, here's some free advice for LaPierre and Heston. It
doesn't come from a mountaintop, just the top of my media-savvy
head.
</P>
<P>
   Thou shalt not wave guns in the air and yell bumper sticker
slogans.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Heston did at the NRA convention in Charlotte, N.C.,
choosing a reproduction Revolutionary War musket and the bumper
sticker slogan ``I'll give up my gun when you take it from my cold,
dead hands.''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how many editorial writers could stick their pens
into Heston before he could load the first musketball.
</P>
<P>
   There's a scene in ``Red Dawn,'' by conservative filmmaker John
Milius, in which a Soviet paratrooper invading Colorado (don't ask)
takes a .45 from the cold, dead hand of a man lying beside his
``cold, dead hand'' bumper sticker.
</P>
<P>
   Milius, by the way, made the once-exotic .44 Magnum popular by
giving one to Clint Eastwood in the scripts he wrote for ``Dirty
Harry'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, an actor, should realize the power of an image. It's one
thing to carefully level a gun in a movie the way Eastwood did. But
you don't want to be caught in the news waving a gun unless you're
a member of the Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we were taught never to handle a weapon that way in my
NRA gun-safety course.
</P>
<P>
   Thou shalt not let children casually handle guns, especially at
an NRA convention with a news photographer present.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the photo of Heston waving the musket at his convention
was a photograph of an 11-year-old boy sighting down the barrel of
a big stainless-steel Beretta while a woman smiled at him.
</P>
<P>
   These things aren't toys. What the hell are all these people
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   That's what the average newspaper reader thinks, and if a
photographer snaps that picture, Heston should know it will be in
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Need I go on? Or is this too easy? The Heston-LaPierre NRA
doesn't seem to have figured it out. And for a powerful political
pressure group, these guys are awfully impolitic.
</P>
<P>
   Thou shalt not accuse the president, any president, of being
``willing to accept a certain level of killing to further his
political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement in March by LaPierre about Bill Clinton even
brought a condemnation from George W. Bush, who said the NRA ``had
gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has been going too far for years, on everything from
``cop-killer bullets'' (the name coined by media-savvy opponents
for rounds that can penetrate body armor) to their opposition to
any palliative suggested by publicity-hungry liberal opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Background checks at gun shows? Mandatory gun locks? How did
these get to be big political issues?
</P>
<P>
   The gun control issue is a standoff between two gangs that can't
think straight, with most of the townspeople stuck in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are those who think one or two more gun laws will
lead to Attorney General Janet Reno kicking in their doors. On the
other side are those who want to melt down all of the hundreds of
thousands of guns in America.
</P>
<P>
   In between are some politicians playing for votes, a bunch of
cops who don't want to knock on the doors of angry gun owners, and
the majority of Americans who know the issue is complicated, but
think something should be done about gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   A few too many guns have been pulled on a few too many
politicians in this country. It's the kind of stuff that could get
Al Gore elected _ unless Bush is smart enough to keep saying the
NRA is going too far.
</P>
<P>
   I'd hate to dine in any restaurant the NRA would run, and not
just because of the birdshot in the roast quail. They'd overdo
everything.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
