<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6419 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-FRANKEL-MEDIA-CENTERP     05-26 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKEL-MEDIA-CENTERPIECE-ADV28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV28 
 MEDIA MONOPOLY MAYDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28, or thereafter.)  
 By MAX FRANKEL  
 c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, I expected to live out my life without
adopting a firm theory of monopoly. The subject, confounded by the
obfuscation of economists and lawyers, always struck me as
impossibly difficult. Fair competition in capitalism seemed to be
like the strike zone in baseball _ a matter of considerable
discretion and best left to the regulation of umpires.
</P>
<P>
   I even thought that some monopolies were useful; securely
profitable newspapers obviously behaved more responsibly than
economic weaklings. And big was not automatically bad: corporate
giants needed giant rivals to feel challenged and checked. I
pronounced flexibility a virtue and relied on government umpires to
protect our markets and the public interest. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   When the Time Warner cable monopoly in Manhattan chose on May
Day to deny me Peter Jennings, Regis Philbin and Ted Koppel merely
to squeeze some more millions out of Disney Co., I realized that
the umpire had been much too lax, refusing even to demand payment
for use of the broadcast spectrum or to get some free television
time for decent election coverage. All this was proof that the
media monsters will never put a public interest ahead of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner had for too long controlled not only the cables into
my home but also many of the channels and programs passing through
its wire. It was hogging both my medium and my message, and the
combination virtually guaranteed anticompetitive behavior. Now Time
Warner wants to merge with AOL and control my cable access to the
Internet as well. And still the umpire seems distracted or asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the May Day blackout was entirely Time Warner's fault.
It pulled the trigger but not without provocation from the Mickey
Mouse moguls. Because Disney, too, had been allowed to grow too fat
and to swallow up media properties like ABC and ESPN, it felt
directly threatened by the AOL Time Warner combine. Disney had also
threatened me with a blackout, showing equal disregard for my
prepaid viewing rights.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the ambitions of Disney and Time Warner are so
complementary that they are bound to find an eventual
accommodation. But their peace, like their war, will be at my
expense. If not soon reduced in size, all the overgrown media
monsters will follow in the path of Microsoft, abusing their
control over both the conduits and contents of communication to
destroy competitors and elude regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The media news in recent weeks confirms the trend. Viacom
swallowed CBS to gain control of 41 percent of the broadcast market
(and began maneuvers to overcome the frail regulatory limit of 35
percent). AT&AMP;T moved to complete its acquisition of MediaOne so as
to seize command of more than a third of the nation's cable
industry. And the five major American music companies virtually
confessed to having colluded to cheat their disc customers of more
than $500 million with various price-fixing schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Some newspapers were also caught up in these antics, an
uncomfortable reminder that the monopolistic arts antedate the Web.
Hearst Corp. was shown at trial to be finagling to kill its own San
Francisco Examiner so that it could acquire the paper's more
profitable partner, The Chronicle, and dispense with even nominal
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony revealed the use of crude promises of editorial
support for Mayor Willy Brown if he would drop his opposition and
help to gain federal approval for the scheme. The Examiner and The
Chronicle had already been merged for all functions except news
gathering under an antitrust exemption that the newspaper industry
pushed through Congress 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   These ``joint operating'' deals have done much less for
journalistic enterprise than for profits. But in any case they only
disguise and delay the drift toward print monopolies. Even before
the Hearst trial ended, a famous rivalry between The Post and The
Rocky Mountain News in Denver ended in yet another such
``joining.''
</P>
<P>
   So I have learned three things about the evolving media
business:
</P>
<P>
   1. The commendable but all-consuming prosecution of Microsoft by
the Justice Department seems to have exhausted or distracted the
umpire and left the rest of the field unguarded.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Clinton administration's repeated claim that the lure of
monopolistic profits can stimulate giant corporations to innovate
is unproved and probably wrong. As William Safire observed with an
African proverb after the May Day blackout, ``When elephants fight,
it is the grass that suffers.''
</P>
<P>
   3. The hope that the new technologies will democratize the
commerce of communication is, on present evidence, naive. The
world's half-dozen conglomerated merchants of information and
entertainment control so many conduits and so much content that
they will inevitably rig the market to favor their own
transmissions and services and to disadvantage all others.
</P>
<P>
   In some distant future, it may become possible for Americans to
get their Web-based news, fun and education by many competing
routes, including interactive cables, telephone wires, wireless
radio and satellite dishes. But for the foreseeable future, the
path of choice will be the cables that already carry TV images into
three of every four homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is the lure of owning cables that inspired AOL to offer
billions to acquire Time Warner and AT&AMP;T to mortgage itself to buy
MediaOne. They well understand, even if the umpires don't, that the
complex ``architecture'' by which small packets of data travel to
and from the Web now permits the owners of cable lines to enhance
the speed and quality of their own messages and to shortchange
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Just months ago, when America Online had reason to fear that
AT&AMP;T's new cable prowess would be used against it, AOL begged the
courts and Congress to intervene to forbid all discrimination. Yet
now that it hopes to own Time Warner's cables, AOL no longer begs;
it actively opposes government regulation. To facilitate
Washington's approval of their marriage, AOL and Time Warner
promise fair access for ``multiple'' _ if not all _ Web services.
As an alert White House should know, this all depends on what
``all'' means.
</P>
<P>
   It was fear of cable discrimination that drove Disney toward the
May Day shootout. Similar disruptions are inevitable if the media's
quasi-monopolies go unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   By far the best way to achieve openness would be to require
media corporations to choose between the business of conduit and
the business of content, between managing the lines of
communication and designing the messages and services to be
transmitted. Hoarding both functions confers monopolistic power to
rig the market and to diminish competition. The emerging
concentrations of power risk a May Day every day.
</P>
<P>
   (Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. Frankel now writes this ``Word &AMP;
Image'' column for The New York Times Magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
