<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6420 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SPORTS-NARCISSISM-CEN     05-26 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NARCISSISM-CENTERPIECE-ADV28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV28 
 TO AN ATHLETE DYING YOUNG
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, May 28, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By WILL BLYTHE  
 c.2000 Will Blythe  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every week or so on an asphalt court in Queens, my
buddies and I play a high-spirited if rather gimpy version of
pickup basketball. You would never need to watch our moves in slow
motion. Real time, sadly, is desultory enough. After the game, we
unwrap our Ace bandages, slide off our knee braces and pat down our
own bodies like cops to make sure all the parts are still there.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when the real dramatics begin. That's when we launch
into our Homeric chronicles of bodily degeneration. How lovingly we
narrate our twinges and spasms, the harrowing sagas of bum knees
and frayed rotator cuffs and tender ankles. Like cartographers of
the 15th century, we map out whole continents of pain, heretofore
unvisited regions of ache and bruise. To listen to us, you'd think
we had double-parked our wheelchairs in a spot of sun down in Miami
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just age catching up with us. (Some of us are
barely old enough to grow silly goatees.) It's the age. The whole
culture is transfixed by the travails of the body. Men used to be
pretty stiff-lipped about pain. Our bodies were these dumb pack
animals that lugged our lunchpails to the factory or the field and
then home again. They weren't very smart but they didn't complain
very much either. Now we live in a time when our bodies are _ or
are supposed to be _ temples to Narcissus. There at those
well-chiseled altars we beseechingly leave our offerings of
Gatorade and PowerBars and creatine.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that our increasing body consciousness is one reason
that accounts of injuries have become one of the central tropes of
sports journalism. (That and the fact that the seasons are too
long.) This isn't to say they haven't mattered in the past: witness
Willis Reed's hobbled glory in the 1970 NBA finals or the funereal
coverage of Joe Namath's rickety knees throughout the rest of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   What is different is how commonplace such reporting is now. At
times, the NBA playoffs have seemed less like basketball games and
more like particularly athletic episodes of ``E.R.'' (Paging Dr.
J.!)
</P>
<P>
   The plot lines read as follows: Will Tim Duncan, 24, recover
from his knee injury in time to prevent the defending champion San
Antonio Spurs from being ignominously bounced in the first round of
the playoffs? Answer: No. Can Patrick Ewing's clattering knees and
Larry Johnson's battered back survive the rigors of yet another
season? Answer: So far. Will the soft tissue _ and have we ever
heard those two words in relation to a basketball game before? _ of
the foot of the Miami Heat point guard Tim Hardaway, 33, bear up
sufficiently for a series with the Knicks? Answer: He played, but
the Knicks prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Every week USA Today issues a full page of injury reports for
major league teams in baseball, football, basketball and hockey.
It's a rather grisly if deadpan catalog of all the ways a body can
come apart under the duress of high-performance athletics: ruptured
spleens, bruised kidneys, brain concussions, torn biceps,
disintegrated ACL's, separated shoulders, even the relatively
petite-sounding turf toes (which actually hurt like hell).
</P>
<P>
   The real drama for me last football season was not whether the
Miami Dolphins would get to the Super Bowl, but whether their aging
quarterback Dan Marino, 38, would be able to lift himself off the
grass after another year of vicious pounding by opposing teams. In
baseball, it's a matter of high suspense to see whether the arm of
Boston's Bret Saberhagen, 36, recovering from its third surgery,
can pitch its way off the disabled list this season without flying
off into the grandstand at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, athletes simply face their mortal limits earlier and
more publicly than the rest of us, and in doing so, presage our
own. A year ago, one sportswriter called Patrick Ewing ``a relic in
need of grease and oil.'' He was a mere 36. The gymnast Shannon
Miller, who retired two years ago to pursue mature activities like
college and marriage, is making a ``comeback'' at the elderly age
of 23. Nothing makes you feel more decrepit than being a spectator
of the new demisport of competitive physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, sports stories have always been about the
triumphs and failures of the body in relation to the will. Some of
these narratives of injury attest to the glories of modern
medicine, the way new surgical techniques have prolonged careers
that would have ended precipitously as recently as a decade ago.
They're also a byproduct of the Infotainment Age, wherein an
ever-expanding media must find ever more to report.
</P>
<P>
   But even more important, these point to the way American men are
starting to look at their bodies quite differently from generations
past. They're discovering the same sort of unfortunate drama
inherent in aging that women have agonized about for decades. It's
amusing, of course, that sports, a formerly male domain, should
insinuate anxiety into men in a way that contradicts the old notion
that men age gracefully, women just sag.
</P>
<P>
   As men these days watch and play sports, they're no longer just
released back into the childhood pleasures of games, of winning and
losing, but faced as well with the novel terrors of present and
future ruination. What's true for the most spectacular athletes in
the world is also true for their fans. We're all now scrutinizing
our bodies for the next sign of decay. My shoulder hurts just
thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   (Will Blythe is the literary editor of Men's Journal.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
