<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY-IMMIG-CENTERPIECE _ In Silicon Valley, the very
notion of reflecting upon what has happened, rather than what will
be, seems to violate the laws of physics. Having grown up there,
the author's sense of disorientation is underscored by the
magnitude of the changes that have swept through this once-sleepy
flatland at the foot of the San Francisco Bay over the last 20 or
so years. The biggest change prosperity has wrought, however, is in
the faces of the people who live here. Today, thanks largely to a
wave that has brought nearly 160,000 immigrants into the area in
the last decade, whites are now a minority. The 1.6 million people
who live in the county are 49 percent white, 24 percent Hispanic,
23 percent Asian and 4 percent black. By Jeff Goodell.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Goodell, a contributing editor at Rolling Stone, is the
author of ``Sunnyvale: The Rise and Fall of a Silicon Valley
Family,'' to be published in July.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-NARCISSISM-CENTERPIECE _ Men used to be pretty
stiff-lipped about pain. Our bodies were these dumb pack animals
that lugged our lunchpails to the factory or the field and then
home again. They weren't very smart but they didn't complain very
much either. Now we live in a time when our bodies are _ or are
supposed to be _ temples to Narcissus. There at those well-chiseled
altars we beseechingly leave our offerings of Gatorade and
PowerBars and creatine. An essay. By Will Blythe.
</P>
<P>
   (Will Blythe is the literary editor of Men's Journal.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA MONOPOLY MAYDAY
</P>
<P>
   FRANKEL-MEDIA-CENTERPIECE _ Until a few weeks ago, I expected to
live out my life without adopting a firm theory of monopoly. Fair
competition in capitalism seemed to be like the strike zone in
baseball _ a matter of considerable discretion and best left to the
regulation of umpires. But when the Time Warner cable monopoly in
Manhattan chose on May Day to deny me Peter Jennings, Regis Philbin
and Ted Koppel merely to squeeze some more millions out of Disney
Co., I realized that the umpire had been much too lax, refusing
even to demand payment for use of the broadcast spectrum or to get
some free television time for decent election coverage. By Max
Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   (Max Frankel is the former Washington bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times.)
</P>
