<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK TO THE OLD TESTAMENT FOR IDEAS ON WOMEN'S ROLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HARRAL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about the time my denomination fades from the news, someone
somewhere stirs things up. The latest is whether women should serve
as pastors.
</P>
<P>
   A revision to the Baptist Faith and Message Statement _ the
official, though nonbinding, declaration of what Southern Baptists
believe _ probably will say that they shouldn't serve as pastors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed statement to be considered at the June convention
in Orlando, Fla., says: ``While both men and women are gifted and
called for ministry, the office of pastor is limited to men as
qualified by Scripture.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the denomination told women that they should be
submissive to their husbands. That also was based on interpretation
of Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a lifelong Baptist _ and the Baptists' record on women is
mixed, even though there is scriptural evidence of their
significance in the ministry of Jesus and in the early churches.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that much of the church's work is done by women.
That's certainly true in Baptist churches, and I imagine that it is
true in religions where people sit in the mud, grunt and eat ants.
</P>
<P>
   And there is good evidence of strong and significant women in
the Judeo-Christian tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Tamar, the daughter-in-law of Judah. Her story is found
in Genesis 38.
</P>
<P>
   Judah, after conspiring with his brothers to sell Joseph into
slavery, married a Canaanite woman. They had three sons, the oldest
named Er.
</P>
<P>
   But Er died leaving his wife, Tamar, without child. Following
Jewish law, Judah sent his second son to her, but he, too, died
without fathering a child. Judah's only got one son left, and he's
unwilling to risk him. So he urges Tamar to go live with her
father.
</P>
<P>
   After Judah's wife dies, he's on a journey, and Tamar learns of
it. She discards her widow's clothes, covers her face with a veil
and waits for Judah beside the road.
</P>
<P>
   Judah does not recognize her, and they strike a business deal,
if you know what I mean. He's short of cash and leaves some
personal possessions as assurance that he will send a man with
proper payment. But by then, Tamar has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Judah hears that his daugher-in-law is pregnant, and he
orders that she be burned. But she sends the things he left with
her, saying that the father of the child is the owner of those
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hath been more righteous than I; because I gave her not to
Shelah my son,'' Judah says.
</P>
<P>
   Tamar had twins. One was named Zarah and the other Pharez.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   The Book of Ruth reports that during a famine a man, his wife _
Naomi _ and their sons left Israel and went to Moab to live. The
sons married Moabite women: Orpah and Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi's husband died, and later so did both her sons. Neither
Orpah or Ruth had children. Naomi wanted to return home and
suggested that her daughters-in-law return to their mothers because
she had nothing to offer. Orpah did so, but Ruth accompanied Naomi.
</P>
<P>
   Her declaration to Naomi in Ruth 1:16 is such a strong statement
of love that it is often read, sung or recited at weddings:
``Entreat me not to leave thee, or to return from following after
thee: for whither thou goest, I will go; and where thou lodgest, I
will lodge: thy people shall be my people, and thy God my God.''
</P>
<P>
   You know the story. Ruth meets Boaz. He's a kinsman to her
husband, and ultimately they marry.
</P>
<P>
   But this is only part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Boaz was the great-great-great-great-great-grandson of Pharez,
the child born to Tamar. And the child born to Boaz and Ruth was
named Obed, and he was the grandfather of David, the greatest
Jewish king of them all and, Christians believe, a direct ancestor
of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more.
</P>
<P>
   The late Isaac Asimov, famous writer of Bible commentary as well
as science fiction, argues that the Book of Ruth is not fully clear
to us since we don't completely understand the phrase ``Moabite
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a bit of a clue in Numbers 25:1-5.
</P>
<P>
   Israel was marching toward the Promised Land, and one of the
nations in the way was Moab. The king of Moab became quite nervous
and sicced the nation's women on the men of Israel. The Bible tells
it like this: ``While Israel was staying at Shittim, the people
profaned themselves by playing the harlot with the Moabite women.''
</P>
<P>
   Asimov's point is that to an Israelite of the fifth century
B.C., to be labeled a Moabite woman was a serious insult, and the
meaning of the Book of Ruth cannot be understood until we
substitute our most personal bias for the word ``Moabite'' in the
phrase: ``Ruth, a Moabite woman.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that image fixed firmly in your mind, remember that the
person you are visualizing is a direct ancestor of King David of
the Jews and to Jesus of the Christians.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a lesson we learned from women in the Bible. What
could we learn from modern women if they are allowed to preach to
us?
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is vice president and editorial director for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
harral(at)star-telegram.com; (817) 390-7836; or P.O. Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
