<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL ABUSE LEAVES SCARS FOR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She is still wearing her workday clothes _ a white polo shirt
tucked in a pair of jeans _ when she enters the coffee shop and
orders a tall cup of iced latte.
</P>
<P>
   She is a small woman, not more than 5 feet tall, with dark skin,
dark hair and dark eyes too afraid to trust.
</P>
<P>
   I notice the tattoo on her wrist.
</P>
<P>
   It is a red heart and gold cross with a green teardrop at its
base. On either side are the words ``I Am Loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the tattoo, though, are the scars that remain from the
night she cut her wrists with a razor blade after her lover left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I cut, the pain in here went away,'' she says,
lifting her hand to her heart.
</P>
<P>
   That was two years ago, one more moment of rejection piled on
top of nearly a dozen years of sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It started when she was 5 years old and her older brother
fondled her. Her step-grandfather did the same thing once. And so
did a neighbor who lived down the street. But most of the time, it
was her brother. By the time she was in fifth grade, the fondling
had turned to sexual intercourse. It stopped only when her brother
left home.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the damage had been done. She was drinking until
she blacked out, experimenting with drugs, anything to forget the
guilt and shame.
</P>
<P>
   As she sips her latte near a window looking out on Pipeline
Road, she tries to recount those years. Only bits and pieces remain
in her memory. She remembers the curtain over the door to the room.
She remembers how big her step-grandfather was against her small
frame; she remembers the neighbor reaching over her to turn off the
light. She remembers how the sun's rays shone through the window
where she fixed her gaze as her brother had sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers that sometimes, the sex would be rough and she
would bleed. She can still see herself standing, pulling her
panties up each time and walking away. And she remembers fearing
what would happen to her if her parents ever found out.
</P>
<P>
   When the memories are too much, she slumps, and tries to catch
the tears. I realize that, but for the grace of God, this could be
me. I search the faces of the other women around me, wonder if
perhaps they know this pain. If they ever will.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Women's Center of Tarrant County, one in every
three women in the nation will be sexually assaulted in her
lifetime; one in four girls (25 percent) will be before they turn
18. In Tarrant County, Texas, half of the victims seen at
rape-trauma clinics are children.
</P>
<P>
   Abused women don't fit a certain profile. They don't look a
certain way; they don't come from one particular ethnic or
socioeconomic group.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, the numbers don't begin to tell the whole story.
They don't tell you, for instance, about the gastrointestinal
disorders or chronic-pain syndrome that women who have been
sexually abused often develop. Nor do they tell you about the teen
pregnancies or alcohol and substance abuse linked to the sexual
assaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things we look at in isolation,'' said Karen Perkins,
executive director of the Women's Center. ``But if you begin to
pull back the layers, abuse is at the root.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman in the white polo shirt and jeans is 46, the mother of
a 23-year-old woman and grandmother of a 5-month-old she helped
usher into the world.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes light up when she remembers the birth of her
granddaughter, the same way they do when she says, ``I've been
clean six years now.''
</P>
<P>
   These may be the only truly happy moments she has known. For
sure, they are the only ones she can recount without a fountain of
tears.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, she says, she felt empty. She once went from
120 pounds to 85 in a few weeks. Had it not been for her love for
her daughter, and a referral to the Women's Center, she might be
dead.
</P>
<P>
   She says her brother and the other rapists stole the better part
of her life. The Women's Center gave it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after I told my story, I (could) hold my head up for
the first time and know I was not to blame,'' she says. ``It's been
a long, hard process, but I believe I'm worth something now.''
</P>
<P>
   And she is no longer anonymous. Her name is Carmen.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
