<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JOHNNYCASH-LEGACY-TEX     05-26 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNNYCASH-LEGACY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THREE FACES OF JOHNNY CASH, ON THREE CDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many lives does Johnny Cash have, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   More than most of us, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Rockabilly contemporary of Elvis and Jerry Lee Lewis, country
star, drug addict, influence on rock stars such as U2 and Bob
Dylan, TV show host, scourge of the Grand Ole Opry, family man,
movie actor, born-again Christian, retro-country icon in the '90s
via ``American Recordings'' and ``Unchained'' _ Cash has been all
these during the 45 years since he began recording music.
</P>
<P>
   He was busted for bringing pills over the U.S./Mexico border in
his guitar case (1965); performed at the Nixon White House; subbed
for Bono as U2's lead singer for one song in 1993; and, last year,
was honored on a TNT special by everyone from the Mavericks to Lyle
Lovett to Wyclef Jean to the Boss.
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, this is a wild ride. But again and again,
through times fat and lean, he's come back to three major themes _
romance, salvation and often violent death _ and has sung about
them with bone-hard, sometimes-chilling directness.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes his new three-CD boxed set, ``Love God
Murder,'' a unique and timely project, one that reminds us of the
68-year-old singer's indelible place on the American landscape: 48
songs divided into the three themes of the title, with brief essays
by Cash, wife June Carter Cash, Bono, and bad-boy director Quentin
Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   This is, first of all, a brilliant idea: The songs range from
some of his earliest recordings for Sun Records _ 1956's ``Folsom
Prison Blues'' _ to several he cut in the '90s for ``Unchained''
and ``American Recordings.'' It's hard to imagine an artist more
perfectly suited to such treatment, and hearing Cash address the
same topics over the decades broadens a listener's understanding of
how his perspective has changed with time.
</P>
<P>
   It also deepens our appreciation of him: Like Hank Williams,
Cash has never done anything in half-measures. He addresses the big
topics, sings with boundless conviction _ and like Williams, his
work can be loved or hated, but never trivialized.
</P>
<P>
   He and Williams share this, too: They sing about being tossed
into jail, killing someone and being saved on a Sunday morning with
the knowledge of one who has lived a life of extremes, of fierce
joy and sadness and anger, and took something away from every
experience, whether soul-soothing or horrific.
</P>
<P>
   ``LGM'' should not be seen as a definitive Cash retrospective _
according to Jeff Jones, senior vice president of Legacy
Recordings, Cash didn't intend it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny just called us one day in 1998 and asked if we could do
this,'' Jones says. ``We said, `Let's go.' It's here to focus
people's attention on three very spiritual parts of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Cash worked with Legacy VP of A&AMP;R Steve Berkowitz and producer
Al Quaglieri to shape the box's song selection and running order.
The choices for the essays suggested themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most obvious one was June,'' Jones says. ``And we thought
of the relationship Bono has had with him over the years. And since
a lot of songs have images you might find in one of Quentin's
films, and he's used Cash's music in his movies, we thought of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The result may refocus the public's attention on his actual body
of work, rather than just his legend status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny Cash is like Stonehenge _ he'll always be with us,''
says Steve Dean, owner of Austin's Under the Sun, a vintage
clothing and records shop and performance space. ``Any reissue by
him is time to rejoice, in my book. We know a lot of people getting
into older country, and Johnny Cash is bigger than people realize _
he's an icon to the kids. A lot of them are only acquainted with
the Sun stuff, so they'll hear things they haven't heard before.
The themes are a great idea _ country music is so bad these days,
and this is a testament to his greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a testament to his resiliency. Cash has had severe
health problems over the years, the most pressing being coping with
Shy-Drager Syndrome, a progressive, and incurable, disorder of the
brain and spinal cord. On the TNT tribute last year, Cash looked
puffy, unsteady and frail.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not done making music. He recently told ``Billboard''
that he's recording a new CD, again with Rubin, that will include
Randy Scruggs, Marty Stuart and Norman Blake, as well as vocals
from Merle Haggard. And, he said, he will definitely be recording
``The Mercy Seat,'' a song by British rocker Nick Cave. The new CD,
Jeff Jones says, may be out as soon as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard a note, but I know he's not just resting on
his laurels,'' Jones says. ``He's an active artist who still wants
to create.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
