<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-PRODUCTION-MEXIC     05-26 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PRODUCTION-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOLLYWOOD SCORES A HIT FOR SOME RESIDENTS OF MEXICAN TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REAL DE CATORCE, Mexico _ The town that time left behind is
being shoved into the 21st century by an American movie.
</P>
<P>
   A film crew of nearly 200 has descended onto the narrow, cobbled
streets of this village located in a remote wrinkle of the Sierra
Madres.
</P>
<P>
   And the money and influence that has cascaded in promises to
change Real de Catorce forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican,'' an action-comedy starring Brad Pitt and Julia
Roberts, is the first Hollywood movie to be shot in this former
silver mining village in the north-central state of San Luis
Potosi.
</P>
<P>
   For generations the town had but a single telephone line. The
film production company, which plans to wrap up its work by the end
of May, brought in 39 more.
</P>
<P>
   While an inadequate water system remains a challenge for Real de
Catorce's 1,200 inhabitants, the film crew has spent just over
$10,000 to replace old pipes and tap a spring in the abandoned
silver mine.
</P>
<P>
   Pistolero Productions made those upgrades for its own needs,
said Benjamin Suarez, the company's location manager. But those new
pipes will be left behind for the town to use.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the company has taken pains to avoid drawing on the
community's already-strained water system, Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Santa Claus,'' he says. ``But we are trying to be
sure the town is in better shape when we leave than when we came.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term at least, the production is reaping dividends
for many locals.
</P>
<P>
   The town's half-dozen hotels are booked until June, and the
local grocer has seen his sales increase 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 residents have temporary jobs as extras and
construction workers earning about $12 a day. That's a respectable
sum by local standards, though minimal compared with the $20
million Roberts and Pitt each will take home for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But benefits today sometimes come with costs tomorrow, as
another small Mexican town has discovered.
</P>
<P>
   When 20th Century Fox filmed the blockbuster film ``Titanic'' in
the tiny fishing village of Popotla, just south of San Diego, Baja
California economic development boosters and residents alike
heralded the U.S. studio for pouring money and hundreds of jobs
into the community.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years, however, Popotla fishermen say their catch
declined by one-third. They blame Fox for chlorinating the local
water and causing damage to marine life that could take years to
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Few films, of course, can match ``Titanic'' for excess. In ``The
Mexican,'' instead of a doomed ocean liner, the transportation
focal point is a royal-blue El Camino.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mexican'' of the title refers to a priceless, allegedly
cursed antique pistol. Pitt's role, described as that of a
reluctant thief, centers on retrieving the gun, while his
girlfriend, Roberts, wants him to quit the criminal life.
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of Steven Spielberg's DreamWorks Pictures and
Newmarket Group, ``The Mexican'' also features Gene Hackman and
Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow tape has cordoned off several blocks of Real de Catorce
since filming began in mid-April. Local children in communion dress
who run squealing nearby are shushed by production assistants
wearing cordless headsets. Diesel-powered generators grind through
the night on streets usually silent except for the braying of
burros.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade many Europeans and Americans have found Real
de Catorce to be a tranquil place to open quaint hotels and
restaurants. Dreadlock-wearing artists selling jewelry and crafts
round out the population.
</P>
<P>
   But with Hollywood in town, security guards have muscled
artisans off the streets, and travelers seeking an offbeat
adventure have found no place at the inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little annoying, frankly,'' said Jo Moise, 36, a London
jewelry designer and a frequent visitor to Mexico. ``I can't get a
hotel; I can't get a shower.''
</P>
<P>
   She had heard the city was housing a film crew, but given Real
de Catorce's funky reputation and compact size, somehow, ``I just
thought we'd get a room and be hanging out with Brad Pitt.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before the town became a hipster's paradise, it was one of
the richest cities in Mexico, according to the state tourist board.
</P>
<P>
   Silver was discovered in 1772, and mining reached its peak in
the late 1800s. With a population near 40,000, well-to-do citizens
built exquisite homesteads, vaults for minerals and money, a
Baroque-style church and an amphitheater for viewing cockfights and
other spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   But in a few short years Real's fortunes would dramatically
reverse. The swooning value of silver on international markets
ground the economy to a halt. Those who didn't leave with the bust
fled when violent waves of the Mexican Revolution swept over the
town.
</P>
<P>
   By 1910, just 2,700 people inhabited the city.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 20th century, Real de Catorce gained a reputation
as ``un pueblo fantasma.'' People called it a ghost town, and not
just because of its dwindling population.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Huichol Indians make pilgrimages from hundreds of miles
away to nearby mountains they consider sacred. And thousands of
Christians flock here annually to pay homage to Saint Francis,
venerated with gusto in the local church.
</P>
<P>
   Local boys lead tourists on horseback to commune with spirits of
another sort. It is said that if you listen closely when out in the
distant ruins, you can hear the cries of miners who gave their
lives to ripping silver from the earth.
</P>
<P>
   But under a blazing sun in May 2000, the phantoms most residents
are whispering about are the elusive stars of the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   Chatter about Pitt and Roberts is constant, but actual sightings
are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age girls clutching cameras have spent recent weeks chasing
Pitt's dark blue Chevrolet Suburban (with tinted windows) from one
end of town to another. A security team confiscated film from one
young woman who managed to snap an image of the male lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is no fault of Pistolero Productions, but it is striking to
walk just two blocks from the spruced-up hotel where Roberts is
staying and find Maria Carillo, a young mother of three who said
she has not had running water for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Carillo said she paid her $2.50 bill April 15, expecting the
water that is supposed to flow through a single slender pipe every
Thursday. She plans to pay this month's bill, too, even though she
had had no running water since before Easter.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Carillo is draining the murky water from an
open cement cistern on her rooftop for washing and cooking, and she
shook her head with a smile when asked if she was upset about the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just how it is,'' she said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing municipal leaders for long-awaited water system upgrades
is a struggle village residents will have to pursue long after the
equipment trailers roll back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, many say they appreciate the upgrade Pistolero
is leaving behind: new light bulbs in the mile-long mountain tunnel
leading to the town, and an agreement from the national phone
company, Telefonos de Mexico, for service that municipal leaders
have tried, in vain, to win for years.
</P>
<P>
   How is it that Hollywood could succeed where local politicos
could not?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the power of money,'' Suarez said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; (Contact Bonnie Pfister by e-mail at
bpfister(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
