<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-SMYERS-BOS &LR;      05-26 1827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SMYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMYERS ON COURSE TO TRIUMPH OVER TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Mass. _ She is a two-time world champion, won the
Hawaii Ironman, and has twice been named United States Olympic
Committee Triathlete of the Year. She is a Pan American Games gold
medalist, an icon of the sport, and held the national title six
years in a row beginning in 1990. For years, she has been beloved
for her generous spirit, admired for her sunny outlook, and feared
for her race-day nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Karen Smyers approaches Saturday's Olympic Trials, it's
the window and the truck that have put her in the spotlight. And,
especially, the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do find it ironic,'' said Smyers, 38, who has been a
professional triathlete since 1985 and has been waiting her entire
career for the triathlon to finally make its debut as an Olympic
sport, which will happen in September in Sydney. ``I've gotten more
media in the last two months than I've gotten in 16 years. I used
to think it was something you earned by your performances, but
that's not necessarily true. You have to have a good story. I guess
being a poster girl for disaster has turned me into a good story.''
</P>
<P>
   She repeats the tale with characteristic affability. For most
people, facing what she has stared down over the past three years,
the simple act of living would have become a grueling endurance
event by now, an Ironman without a finish line. Smyers, on the
other hand, still insists she inhabits a charmed space that has yet
to be burglarized.
</P>
<P>
   Among the oldest competitors at the Trials, Smyers might have
been considered a long shot in the biggest race of her life even
without the string of misfortune that began almost three years ago
and culminated in a cancer diagnosis last fall.
</P>
<P>
   --In June 1997, Smyers was changing a storm window when it
shattered and slashed her left hamstring. Facing months of
rehabilitation, Smyers and her husband, Michael King, decided it
would be a good time to start a family; after 48 hours of labor and
a caesarean section, Jenna was born May 1, 1998. Two months later,
Smyers resumed competition.
</P>
<P>
   --On Aug. 12, 1998, Smyers was clipped by an 18-wheel truck
while biking near her home and sustained six broken ribs and a
separated shoulder when she crashed and skidded into a ditch. ``I
really, literally, thought she was dead,'' said training partner
Glenn Cunha, who had been riding behind her. ``Finally, she just
let out this big sigh.'' She resumed competition in April 1999,
winning in her first race back.
</P>
<P>
   --Last September, during a checkup while she was battling
bronchitis, tests indicated she had thyroid cancer. Smyers found it
hard to believe after she finished second in the Hawaii Ironman
(2.4-mile swim, 112-mile bike, 26.2-mile run) in mid-October,
leading for much of the race. ``I thought, there's got to be a
mistake,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   --In November, she broke her collarbone when she crashed her
bike over a fallen competitor during a triathlon in Mexico. Days
later, further tests confirmed the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   --On Dec. 18, Smyers had a cancerous thyroid gland and two lymph
nodes removed at Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For a few days, she and King thought her Olympic quest might be
over; that the fatiguing effects of the immediate radioactive
iodine treatment being recommended would destroy her ability to
train in the few months remaining. But in further consultations,
several endocrinologists said there would be no harm, and might
even be some benefit, in delaying treatment of the slow-growing
cancer, which has a cure rate of better than 95 percent, until
after the Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all I needed to hear,'' said Smyers.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that was all anyone else needed to hear. Soon, NBC's
``Today'' show came calling. So did ``Good Morning America'', and
ABC's ``World News Tonight'' with Peter Jennings. If it wasn't
Sports Illustrated at the door it was the Chicago Tribune; if the
phone call wasn't from Newsweek it was from US Weekly or the
Washington Post or Fox Sports or USA Today, twice. A reporter from
Asahi Shimbun, the Japanese mega-newspaper with a circulation of 8
million _ sat on Smyers's sofa earlier this week. Oprah Winfrey's
new TV-Internet venture, Oxygen, filmed her on a recent training
weekend in New Hampshire. Two-year-old Jenna can hardly get put
down for a nap these days without the aid of klieg lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more cameras!'' the toddler demanded recently.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a squadron of sociologists to explain the
magnetism of Smyers's saga. ``Clearly, triumph over adversity is
one of the oldest stories in the world,'' said Paul Slavin,
executive producer of ``World News Tonight.'' ``We're always
looking for heroes, and what is a hero except for someone who
overcomes the odds?''
</P>
<P>
   Put even more simply: ``Most of us can't picture going to work
when we have the flu,'' said Nova Lanktree, president of Lanktree
Sports Celebrity Network. ``We give Dennis Rodman publicity; how
refreshing to see a story like this. There's something extremely
compelling about what it is in the human spirit that creates this
kind of human being.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No booster shot needed
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it's certainly nothing Smyers came up with
recently. Kim Ratcliffe has known Smyers since 1979, when they met
as freshmen at Princeton. Back home in Weathersfield, Conn., Smyers
had been a high school swimmer, gymnast, and tennis player. At
Princeton she focused on swimming and began running as part of her
training. Soon enough, she was on the track team, too. By their
sophomore year, Ratcliffe and Smyers were roommates as well as
track teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways she stuck out like a sore thumb at Princeton,''
said Ratcliffe, a former amateur triathlete who urged Smyers to try
her first triathlon back in 1984, and who now lives in Carlisle.
``She didn't really get too upset about anything.'' Come to think
of it, Ratcliffe said as she pondered a friendship in its fourth
decade, ``I can't really think of a time she was visibly upset or
depressed in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Smyers's husband backs her up. ``As much as I'd like to say I've
been a good psychological booster, Karen is pretty good on her
own,'' said King, an independent film producer and amateur
triathlete who was co-owner of the now-defunct Eliot Lounge. If she
needs any courage, those who know her said, she draws it from Scott
Carlson, a former training partner who is battling the ravages of
Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just not a `why me' kind of person,'' said Cunha, also a
friend of Carlson's. ``She really feels she's been dealt a great
hand, and she's going to do everything she can with that hand.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she has graciously told her story to anyone with a
notebook or microphone even though, she said with a chuckle as
Jenna motored around the room chattering, she sometimes wishes
they'd find someone else's story so she could spend more time
training. ``The thing I have to be careful about is letting all the
media I'm getting make me believe all of a sudden that I'm better
than I am,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much danger of that. ``I couldn't think of a better
spokesman for the sport,'' said Mike McCarley, the former
communications director of USA Triathlon now with nbcolympics.com.
``She never told me `no' and I don't think she'll ever say no to
anyone. It could be the local pennysaver and it could be NBC, she
treats everyone with the same amount of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunha echoed McCarley's words. In 1991, while he and some
friends were mulling whether to try a triathlon, someone suggested
they talk to Smyers, who worked out at the same pool. A few weeks
after peppering her with the endless questions of a beginner, Cunha
was in a bike store and was stunned to see her photo on the cover
of a magazine, having just been named its triathlete of the year
after winning the 1990 world championship. She had given him no
clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really is just one of the gang,'' said Cunha, now a fellow
member of the training group Team Psycho.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inspirational role model
</P>
<P>
   Among the many other triathletes Smyers has encouraged are
Maryellen Powers, Jennifer Gutierrez, and Siri Lindley. Powers of
Dover, N.H., was a fired-up volunteer at one Cambridge race when
Smyers urged her to take up the sport; Powers will be on the
starting line at the Trials. Gutierrez is already on the Olympic
team, having won her spot at a race in Sydney last month (Smyers
was the fourth American), while Lindley is among the favorites to
claim one of the remaining two berths on the team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't make the team and they do,'' cracked Smyers, ``at
least I'll get some vicarious pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindley, a Connecticut native and Brown University graduate,
said Smyers is ``totally responsible'' for her turning pro after a
pep talk on a beach in Mexico after an event in 1995. ``For me,
she's been a role model in every way. You can't not like Karen,
there's just no way.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Lindley warns, anyone who disregards her over the .9-mile
swim, 24.8-mile bike, 6.2-mile run in Dallas will do so at their
peril. ``There are a couple of people out there who can do some
damage, and she is one of those people,'' said Lindley, who enters
the race as the third-ranked American while Smyers is No. 8. ``You
can never, ever count Karen out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although sponsors Nike, Oakley, Timex, and Trek have all stood
by Smyers during the three years in which she has seen little
action, the rules of the sport have not. With drafting now allowed
on the bike, Smyers has been handed a disadvantage unrelated to
injury, illness, or age: Good on the bike and great on the run, her
weakest link has long been the swim, and now it's more important
than ever to come out of the water near the leaders to get into a
good bike pack. To that end, she has spent a lot of time in the
pool since January after missing two months with that broken
collarbone, sometimes doubling her usual monthly mileage. (``In the
five months she's had to train she's done everything right,'' said
King. ``Whether that's enough or not, we'll find out.'')
</P>
<P>
   At a recent race in St. Croix, she chalked up her second-best
time there in 10 appearances. ``I have to take that as a good
sign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it might not matter. ``Just because the mind is willing
doesn't mean it's going to happen,'' she said. ``I know I could
have my best race, and still not make it. Maybe I can't imagine
what the disappointment would be like, but looking at it right now
I feel it's important, but certainly not the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, regardless of the outcome the day before, Smyers will
go off her thyroid-hormone medication to prepare for the
radioactive iodine treatment she hopes will wipe out any hidden
traces of cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
