<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER D-DAY IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORK, Ireland _ The man everyone fears was a 36-year-old
electrician, a bachelor, known to no one but a few co-workers,
relatives, and shadowy pals until the cops laid bare an ironclad
case.
</P>
<P>
   When the accused was sentenced to seven years in a Dublin
courtroom last week, he waved a clenched fist salute and shouted a
Gaelic slogan. His crime? He had stashed 50 pounds of Semtex, the
terrorist's explosive of choice, plus enough incendiary devices,
timers, and detonators to wreak urban havoc. Throw in some odd guns
and ammo, and he was custodian of one of the largest caches of
explosives ever seized here. He was ready for war. The court ruled
he had hidden the stuff for the Provisional Irish Republican Army.
Men like the jailed electrician _ and the threat of a renewed IRA
terror campaign _ dominate the climactic meeting Saturday of the
Ulster Unionist Council.
</P>
<P>
   This is an unwieldy 860-member conclave of the largest
Protestant political faction in the six counties that comprise
Northern Ireland. David Trimble, the Unionist chief who shared the
Nobel Peace Prize with Catholic moderate John Hume a year ago, is
trying to persuade his party's recalcitrant rank-and-file to
re-enter the stalled peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Troubles have been kept alive by the bitter-enders of both
traditions, in a scarred backwater where outrages committed 800 or
so years ago are ignited afresh with daily doses of political
kerosene. After the Good Friday peace deal, the IRA and its spruced
up mouthpiece of a political party, Sinn Fein, began playing games
with the commitment to turn over its armaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decommissioning'' is what it's called here, but dissembling is
more like it. The issue of removing bombs, guns, and mortars from
the political dialogue matters greatly to the hard core of ``hard
men,'' possibly no more than 300 or 400 in all in the IRA and
perhaps a few more on the Protestant extremist side. Ireland's is
Europe's hottest economy _ 8 percent annual growth _ but jobs are
not desired by the hard men of both extremes. Bandits, tailgaters,
small-time hoods, and shakedown artists, they have little prosect
of becoming software engineers or peddling pricey salmon dishes to
well-heeled tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But playing the rebel card, or waving the bloody rag of
Protestant ascendancy, is still the endgame for the men who have
nowhere to go in the new economy. This is the core of the
bloody-minded intransigence of the opposing parties in the North.
On Saturday, the Unionists who want to keep Ulster lashed to some
barnacled notion of what Britain used to be debate among themselves
whether they will remain in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble seems to have staked his future and survival as leader
on his ability to eke out a majority of the 860 party leadership
for his showdown with the hardliners. Trimble wants to re-enter
peace talks, and challenge the IRA to make good on a vague promise
to put its weaponry ``beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else in that blighted province, words become
symbols, symbols become subterfuge, and the cycle of mistrust turns
into another round of partisan braying and political breakdown.
Playing his customary role of blustery provocateur is the Rev. Ian
Paisley, who has been marginalized to an extent by Trimble's
emergence as a leader of the Protestant coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's argument: ``We can either decide to put the IRA to the
test or we can take the seemingly easier route and let them off the
hook. Saying `no' to this (peace process) will only serve to
consign Unionism to the political wilderness, and who knows for how
many years?'' Paisley, a padre to whom insult is always closer than
a prayer book, counters: ``(Trimble) is now not just a Provo
salesman but a Provo spokesman as well. How many times must he be
suckered before he faces up the reality he is being played for a
fool by the IRA.''
</P>
<P>
   In a land where backstabbing is literal and assassins operate
freely, Trimble's gamble has drawn the admiration of some of his
fiercest critics in the nationalist community. Standing up to the
diehards on your own side is the hardest act in politics, anywhere.
Every dawn new threats from the nationalist camp, the mostly Roman
Catholic claque of descendants of anti-British patriots who
starved, fought, or bombed their way through eight or nine
centuries (who can keep track?) of antagonism to British
colonialists.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Republican Army gunmen and the Sinn Fein party
microphone-wielders who propagandize for them exploit the
breakdowns in the process, tossing in fresh layers of conditions.
Each side plays to its core constituency. Cast as exasperated
peacekeepers are the elected officials of England, the Irish
government in the Republic, and the United States. All three
governments have done just about everything anyone can think of to
end the armed standoff in the North. The threat of random terrorism
hangs in the air like a stench that rain won't wash away. The
antique smallmindedness of the conflict would be laughable anywhere
else. But 50 pounds of Semtex is no joke.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
