   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ In an important advance against
diabetes, researchers in Canada are reporting that transplants of
insulin-producing cells have enabled 8 patients with a severe form
of the disease to stop taking insulin injections. Two to 14 months
after being transplanted in a simple procedure resembling a
tranfusion, the cells are still working in all 8 patients, half of
whom were treated almost a year ago at the University of Alberta,
in Edmonton. The patients, who had Type 1 diabetes, in which the
body produces little or no insulin of its own, no longer have any
symptoms of the disease. By Denise Grady.
