<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHANGHAI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN-STYLE WINNER FROM JACKIE CHAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI NOON &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Directed by: Tom Dey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Alfred Gough, Miles Millar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Jackie Chan, Owen Wilson, Lucy Liu, Brandon Merrill,
Roger Yuan, Xander Berkeley &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 110 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (action violence, some drug humor, language and
sensuality) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shanghai Noon'' is the movie ``Wild Wild West'' tried to be
last summer. Essentially, it's ``Wild Wild West'' with a tiger in
its tank. Well, two tigers. Jackie Chan handles the acrobatics and
fight scenes, while Owen Wilson handles the smart-mouthing. Since
Chan's acrobatics are the closest thing movies offer to guaranteed
entertainment, and the verbal acrobatics in this case contribute as
much to the fun, it works out pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   With a plot loosely borrowed from Akira Kurosawa's ``Hidden
Fortress'' by way of ``Star Wars,'' the movie features Chan and
Wilson teaming up as a pair of scruffy lowlifes rescuing China's
kidnapped imperial princess in 1881. Chan's character, Chon Wang
(say it a few times and you'll get the joke), tags along from
Peking's Forbidden City to carry the bags of the three imperial
guards sent to Nevada to ransom the princess for a trunkful of
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, as a train robber who attaches himself to the rescue
mission when he learns how much gold is involved _ after botching
the robbery of the train carrying it _ hinders Chon Wang more than
he helps him. For one thing, he's chased by what's left of his gang
of thieves. For another, he puts a gleam in the eye of a
duplicitous sheriff named Van Cleef (an homage to Sergio Leone's
favorite heavy).
</P>
<P>
   But he's always there drawling an ironic wisecrack when we need
one, which is whenever Chan, with his limited arsenal of English,
isn't windmilling his way like a chopper blade through a bunch of
bad guys. Chan is pushing 50, but he still moves with the best of
them, and he manages to put a sunny face on whatever he does. He
peaks here in a sequence involving a rope and a horseshoe, and you
wouldn't want to take him on in a game of pick-up-sticks, either.
</P>
<P>
   The film consists of a series of reinvigorated Western set
pieces, including the inevitable entrance by Chan (in a pigtail and
embroidered gown) into a saloon where the focus quickly shifts from
swinging doors to swinging fists. As usual, there's plenty of
invention and exuberant vigor in the chopsocky, and Wilson's cool,
ironic drollery provides the perfect foil for Chan's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Liu spices the mix as the princess who is anything but a
passive victim. Newcomer Brandon Merrill suggests a Native American
Catherine Zeta Jones as the bride to whom Chan's character wakes up
to find himself married inside a friendly tepee. ``Shanghai Noon''
may be little more than Chan recycling shtick, but it's great
shtick, the kind that put the motion in motion pictures in the
first place. Nobody could careen through it as entertainingly as
Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will know not to jump out of their seats and leave when the
story ends, but to wait for the outtakes. These outtakes, which
show stunts going wrong and Chan always coming up smiling, of
course aren't outtakes at all. They're an integral part of every
Jackie Chan movie. They make him appear even more likably human,
remind us of how difficult it is to do this stuff, and end up
enhancing the we're-having-fun feeling that makes every movie he
makes such a high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
