<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG GUNS PUSH A NEARLY FIZZLED NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to selling books, William Goldman's famous adage
about Hollywood holds true: Nobody knows anything. A case in point
is the novel ``Pay It Forward,'' by Catherine Ryan Hyde.
``Forward'' tells the story of a 12-year-old boy, Trevor McKinney,
who attempts to better the world through random acts of kindness.
For a school project, McKinney performs favors for three people,
and urges each one to ``pay forward'' the good deeds. It sounds
squishy, but has a bracing denouement.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster launched ``Forward'' in February, supposedly
backing it up with a $250,000 promotion budget. The book fizzled.
Nationwide, the reviews were mixed, but the crucial New York Times
review was short and dismissive: ``Hyde created a savior, but
forgot to make him human,'' the reviewer concluded. The book
appeared on a bestseller list in San Francisco, near Hyde's home in
Cambria, Calif., and on no others.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost four months after its formal publication date,
``Forward'' is taking off. Microsoft Corp. has decided to purchase
100,000 electronic copies as free downloads for buyers of its
just-introduced Pocket PC. The book is thriving on Amazon.com,
where reader comments _ yes, authors salt the site with puffery,
but Hyde insists she hasn't _ are wildly enthusiastic. Book groups
like it, and they'll probably like the lower-priced paperback
version, due out in the fall, even more.
</P>
<P>
   One Boston reader has helped ``Forward'' along. Spontaneously
enthused by the book, author/filmmaker Tom McCann sent copies to
about a dozen friends, including former Mintz Levin lawyer Ken
Novack, who happens to be the vice-chairman of America Online.
Novack also loved the book, and was in a position to do something
about it. Warner Brothers, which AOL recently acquired in the
Time-Warner deal, had already started editing the Kevin
Spacey-Helen Hunt film version of ``Forward,'' set for release in
October. With AOL and Warner behind the book, the simultaneous
movie/paperback launch promises to be quite auspicious.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. Movie producer J.P. (Rick) Guerin, who brought
the book to Warner Brothers, has set up a charitable foundation
``to keep the spirit of Trevor McKinney alive in today's youth.''
The foundation hopes to fund enrichment programs in schools and in
youth detention centers. Guerin has made an initial contribution,
and he and his co-trustees McCann and Hyde are busily shaking the
Microsoft, AOL, and Warner Brothers trees, hoping for some green to
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Car talk
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Belmont optometrist Leo deNatale pulls his BMW 323 ic
convertible up to a stoplight, people honk and laugh. The reason:
he's attached a plastic lemon to the top of his radio aerial, with
the figure ``$40,000'' written in magic marker. Since buying the
car last summer, deNatale has been trying to return it to the
dealer, Foreign Motors West, using the state's ``lemon law.''
Rebuffed, he has taken his campaign to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   DeNatale, who is clearly a finicky car owner _ he successfully
used the lemon law to return a Subaru Forester last May _ says his
car has several worrisome knocks. He took it back to the dealer
three times, as required by law, and he says the knock never went
away. Furthermore, his car was in a crash while on the Foreign
Motors lot. The dealer offered to exchange the car for a pricier
model, and charge DeNatale $5,000. ``Why should I have to pay
$5,000 because they damaged my car?'' our man asks.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Motors says deNatale lowered the value of his car by
having an outside repair shop fix some dents. ``BMW has made a very
generous offer to compensate Dr. deNatale and repurchase his car,''
says Foreign Motors service chief Lance Mitchell. Furthermore, the
law does not apply to defects that are merely ``annoying'' and do
not compromise safety, or the car's value. But why would an
image-dependent company like BMW want this guy roaming the streets,
slathering them in bad publicity? Only the lawyers know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   She said, she said
</P>
<P>
   Get out the Texas death cage! It's the battle of the lady
professors, Round Two.
</P>
<P>
   On the Atlantic Monthly's Web site, theatlantic.com, Harvard
gender studies maven Carol Gilligan finally gets a chance to defend
her scholarship against charges leveled by Christina Hoff Sommers
in the venerable magazine's May issue. (TGIF, May 19). Gilligan
says she's on the level. In a none-dared-wish-it-longer 22-screen
rebuttal, Sommers invokes such gender dignitaries as Susan Faludi
to reaffirm her conviction that Gilligan is full of beans. Must
reading for the herstory crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The print version will appear in the August issue of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
