<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ROCK-WATTS-BOS &LR;      05-26 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-WATTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUMMER WATTS EXPLORES THE WORLD OF TECHNO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hardened pro like Charlie Watts suddenly into techno
world-beat music? It seems unlikely that Watts _ the drumming
engine of the Rolling Stones _ could make the leap from his
famously organic sound to a techno-spiced production, yet he does
it with surprising effectiveness on the ``Charlie Watts/Jim Keltner
Project'' album that came out this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music in it is made up of drums, percussion, and
samples,'' says Watts by phone during a recent visit to New York.
``To make it more musical, I added a string bass in places and a
piano player (fellow Rolling Stone Mick Jagger is on one song).
That was the norm of it. The rest I wanted to be as techno, if you
like, as it would go.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a brave new world when Watts, whose side projects to
the Stones are usually purist jazz albums, takes a walk on the
techno side. But it came at the prodding of Keltner, another drum
legend (known for studio sessions with everyone from Bob Dylan to
Joe Cocker, and currently backing Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young on
tour), who had a series of sequenced tracks that he wanted Watts to
play on.
</P>
<P>
   The two drummers collaborated during Watts's time off from
Stones sessions for ``Bridges to Babylon'' three years ago in Los
Angeles. Watts later took the tapes to Paris and worked with
programmer Phillipe Chauvineau to add more rhythmic samples (from
cowbell, congas, shaker, and surdu to oud, flute, and kalimba), not
to mention samples from an African choir, to complete the songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the world of modern technology,'' Watts explains. ``I
would have loved to have had 18 Africans in the room singing, but
it's very difficult to do that. I'm sure a lot of singers are going
to go, `Oh yeah?' But I don't care about that. It's all electronic.
It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The result suggests a kind of ambient, Blue Man Group flavor on
some of the tracks, even though neither Watts nor Keltner has seen
Blue Man Group. No matter. The music is often quite original _ and
quite unexpected given the two drummers' pedigrees.
</P>
<P>
   Each song is named for a jazz drummer (``Max Roach,'' ``Art
Blakey,'' ``Airto,'' and ``Kenny Clarke,'' for example), though the
music is meant only as a broad tribute to them without specifically
mimicking their styles. The energy and conviction of each drummer
is summoned on the individual tracks, rather than the notes or
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   The African choir comes in on ``The Elvin Suite,'' a tribute to
Elvin Jones, who played with John Coltrane's '60s quartet. A samba
beat with sampled bandoneon and strings marks the core of
``Airto,'' a tribute to Brazilian percussionist Airto. Burundi
beats underscore ``Art Blakey,'' while a rocking dance remix
characterizes ``Roy Haynes'' and laid-back synths enrich ``Tony
Williams.'' The latter is an elegant, muted requiem to Williams,
who died shortly before the recording sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The main constant is Watts's backbeat, played on his regular
Stones drum kit. That's the primary instrument, for there is almost
no guitar (except for a Keith Richards guitar insert on ``The Elvin
Suite'') and no saxophone.
</P>
<P>
   The Watts/Keltner Project evolved from Keltner's telling Watts,
``I really wish you would play on a couple of my little sequence
tunes.'' Watts complied, after hearing some of the sequenced sounds
that Keltner had put together from various sound sources such as
pipes, steel shelves, fish steamers, and boiled-egg cutters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did about four or five songs from those,'' says Keltner.
``And then the rest were built by Charlie out of these grooves that
we did. And Charlie emerged as a great producer. I didn't realize
he had those kind of chops, but he's a great producer.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts and Keltner had first met in the early '70s when the
Stones were touring Europe. Keltner hung out and traveled with
them. ``I watched Charlie every night and I was floored,'' says
Keltner. ``I became an instant copier, or tried to be a copier of
Charlie, like all drummers have, except that I had the good fortune
of being able to watch him up close _ which still didn't do me any
good as far as trying to copy him!''
</P>
<P>
   However, because Keltner was busy on another gig after the
initial recording sessions, Watts had the task of taking their
joint tapes to Paris, where he teamed up with programmer
Chauvineau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Programmers work in tiny little rooms and never see the light
of day,'' Watts says with a dry laugh. ``They have these speakers
up and big stacks of samples and a screen. I just said, `Will you
help me chop this up?' So we did that and did it a lot quicker than
I thought. I thought it would take three months and I'd be out of
there. It was a lot quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Watts and Keltner won't tour behind the album.
Keltner is still on the road with CSN&AMP;Y, while Watts needs a rest.
He also has no plans to work with the Stones any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to Mick and Keith,'' he says. ``If I said, `Yes, I'm
going in the studio next year,' but Mick and Keith aren't ready,
then we're not going into the studio, are we? So that's their
world. They get it together, then propose a time. It's too soon to
know what's happening there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
