<HEADLINE>
PATTI SMITH ROARS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patti Smith is on the telephone from her home in New York, and
the background noise alone is a window on her world. Oliver Ray,
Smith's 26-year-old guitarist and lover, is working out a new song
on electric guitar, and the loud chords play like a soundtrack to
Smith's gravelly, carefully chosen words. Her 12-year-old daughter
Jessie interrupts to announce that the cat, who has recently eaten
a clove of garlic, is throwing up. ``Don't worry,'' Smith murmurs.
``We can always clean it up.'' Seems it takes more than a sick
kitty to ruffle the high priestess of American punk-rock.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's new album, ``Gung Ho,'' is a visceral return to the
revolutionary poetry and nervy, grand-scale music that earned her _
over a 25-year career _ that well-deserved title. The new songs are
swollen with a sense of power and purpose. It's a spiritedness _
both musical and personal _ that Smith hasn't played with, or for
that matter felt, in a long while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel it represents me, and the band, in a position of
strength,'' Smith says. `` `Gone Again' (recorded following the
sudden death of her husband in 1994) came from a place of sorrow.
`Peace and Noise' came from a position of struggle. I was trying to
bring myself back up, reenter the world, reclaim my abilities. It's
really nice to offer something that is strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The album is the result of a long period of study, says Smith,
now 52, during which she immersed herself in the Declaration of
Independence, the American Revolution, and the lives of Mother
Theresa and Ho Chi Minh. ``The title is an obvious play on words
for Ho Chi Minh,'' whose life Smith examines in the title cut.
``It's also an old Chinese phrase that means `working together.'
It's apropos for this album because it's a very heightened
collaborative piece of work,'' explains Smith, who is touring with
her longtime band _ guitarists Lenny Kaye and Ray, bassist Tony
Shanahan, and drummer Jay Dee Daugherty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gung Ho'' tackles large social and moral issues, and Smith
hopes to bring her message to a broad audience _ an about-face from
her early days courting fans who, like herself, were far left of
center. ``When I did `Horses,' I was targeting, maybe
unconsciously, the fringe,'' she says. ``I wasn't much concerned
with people at large. But I think that we are in a time where
spirituality is an endangered species. So is political activism. So
I'm trying to wake people up, remind them of their worth, their
voice, how important their individual energy is as well as the
collective energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she feels that she's become, as a recent New York Times
article suggested, the de facto custodian of the Beat aesthetic
(along with Bob Dylan and Lou Reed), Smith is graciously humble.
``If in any way any aspect of that is passed through me, it's an
honor I wouldn't take lightly. I'll do the best I can. I was very
close with William (Burroughs) and Allen (Ginsberg). They counseled
me a lot, and I learned a lot from them in terms of work and being
a human being. William had great patience and compassion. Allen had
such active fervor, tremendous energy, and was so charitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Her circle of influential friends has indeed been vast; Smith is
writing a book about her early collaborator and close companion,
the late artist Robert Mapplethorpe. She describes the project as
``joyful/painful.'' After touring in support of ``Gung Ho'' Smith
will part ways with Arista, her label since she began her recording
career in 1975. Although it's been widely publicized that Smith is
leaving to protest the dismissal of Arista chief Clive Davis, it's
simply ``coincidental timing,'' Smith explains. ``My contract for
eight albums has been fulfilled. But to me it is apropos. Clive
served as a patron as well as my record company president. I never
sold a lot of records, but he continued to release them, and
release them the way I wanted. So I think the timing is a good
thing. No one has to be challenged,'' she laughs. ``No one has to
ask me to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The future is uncertain. Not just for Smith personally _ she
hasn't given much thought to her next professional move _ but for
the entire human race, she says. ``I understand it would be more
realistic to be pessimistic, but what would the point be? I'm
always optimistic, for two reasons. I love living, and I have
children. (Son Jackson is now 18.) Pessimism makes people withdraw.
So I'm always writing songs. Because people accounting for
themselves is its own reward.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and Pieces _ Tina Turner has sold out her FleetCenter shows
June 8-9, but will return for a third night on Sept. 20, kicking
off the fall leg of her tour with Joe Cocker opening. Tickets on
sale June 5. . . . Boston producer Mike Denneen is in Fort Apache
studios remixing Fountains of Wayne's ``Too Cool for School,''
which will be part of the soundtrack to the movie ``Scary
Movie.''... Sinead O'Connor has been added to next Saturday's
Kiss-108 concert lineup at the Tweeter Center in Mansfield. . . .
Concert promoter SFX has pulled out of Hanson's planned summer
tour; sales of the band's new album, ``This Time Around,'' have
been dismal. . . . Performance artist Laurie Anderson and
singer-songwriter Chantal Kreviazuk will score silent movies for
``Women Film Pioneers,'' a tribute airing in August on the Turner
Classic Movies cablechannel. . . . Rocker Chris Isaak has inked a
deal with Showtime to star in his own television show chronicling
the musician's ``showbiz adventures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
