<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO `PASSION' IN THIS PSYCHOLOGICAL DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASSION OF MIND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Alain Berliner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Ron Bass, David Field &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Demi Moore, Stellan Skarsgard, William Fichtner, Peter
Riegert, Sinead Cusack, Joss Ackland, Eloise Eonnet, Chaya Cuenot &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (scenes of sexuality) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion of Mind'' is a throwback to the days when Hollywood
was avidly, glossily discovering psychotherapy. It's Demi Moore's
first film in several years, and with this role she has grown into
new dimensions of warmth and softness as a woman living in parallel
worlds, leading two rich, full lives. In one, she's a widowed mom
living with two young daughters in a comfortable house on a French
hillside. In the other, she's a high-powered Manhattan literary
agent. In each life, she's aware of her other existence. Which is
real and which is the dream? As she says to one of her two
psychiatrists (one in France, the other in New York), ``I don't
know who I am anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up her problem in this psychological drama, her European
shrink, played by Joss Ackland, says, ``You're riding two horses.
And your mind is not able to do that without breaking apart.'' It's
easy to see why she might have a difficult time making a choice. In
each world, she leads a fulfilling life and has a man who's crazy
about her. In France, it's Stellan Skarsgard's writer, who stalks
her in a pleasant, charming way, ingratiates himself into her life,
and is good with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, it's William Fichtner's accountant, whom she meets
during the course of her work. The details of each romance veer
toward fantasy. The accountant is so smitten that he pays her the
ultimate compliment a workaholic can give. He takes a day off from
work to be with her. So passionate is the writer, he doesn't mind
that she wrote a review panning his novel in The New York Times.
Perhaps the fantasy set in France is greater, given the fundamental
disparity between real estate prices in the French countryside and
compensation levels for book reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, she's kept on track by a therapist played by Peter
Riegert. In France, she's shored up by the concern of Sinead
Cusack's older woman friend. ``Passion of Mind'' represents a step
forward in that neither version of Moore's character is anything
like a victim. In neither half of her split life can she forget the
other half. Still, distracted as she may be, she makes each
lifestyle work. The question is whether she'll be able to keep them
separate. In one sense, she doesn't. She lets each man know about
her other half.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a matter of time before each lover's brow begins
furrowing over her complicated dream life. Not only does each
wonder whether he'll be the one who gets her. Each must also worry
about whether he's the one who's real. Not that it's all worry. As
he demonstrated so delightfully in ``Ma Vie En Rose,'' Belgian
director Alain Berliner has a way with the trimmings of romance,
and he handles each set of courting rituals with a gossamer touch
all but unknown in mainstream filmmaking, especially in the segues
between the heroine's lives.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem with ``Passion of Mind'' is that there isn't
much passion in it. The screenplay, by the prolific Ron Bass, is
merely efficient when it must be incendiary, or at least urgent.
Never do we feel a sense of accelerating psychological tension or
internal pressure, just a set of logistical snags. So few films try
to be intelligent, adult, and gracious, as this one does, that it
seems a pity to reject it. But its sweet, decorous screenful of
Freudian dreams seems to have emerged from a gelatin mold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
