<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MUHAMMAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNSPARING BIO OF A BLACK LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MESSENGER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rise and Fall of Elijah Muhammad &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Karl Evanzz
</P>
<P>
   Pantheon. 667 pp. $28.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two years before his death, Elijah Muhammad stood just a few
paces from Louis Farrakhan during the Nation of Islam's Savior's
Day Convention and loudly proclaimed there was no such thing as
reincarnation. People who believed in the afterlife were practicing
what he called that ``crazy Christianity religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years later, a headline on the Web site of the
United Nation of Islam stood in stark contrast to one of the
strongest tenets of ``The Messenger'': ``The Honorable Elijah
Muhammad has returned,'' it proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   This apparent contradiction is symptomatic of a pattern of
deceit present throughout the career of Muhammad and the religion
he founded, the Nation of Islam, according to a new book. Karl
Evanzz, an online editor at the Washington Post, has assembled a
comprehensive study of the life and death of this controversial
black leader.
</P>
<P>
   Research for ``The Messenger'' draws extensively on voluminous
FBI files collected for director J. Edgar Hoover on Muhammad,
Malcolm X, Farrakhan, and other prominent Nation of Islam leaders
and members. The book contains a 24-page appendix, 74 pages of
footnotes, and a 46-page bibliography. ``The Messenger'' is
Evanzz's second book on the Nation. His first was ``The Judas
Factor: The Plot to Kill Malcolm X.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much research, Evanzz's conclusions are even more
disturbing. ``The Nation of Islam . . . has become the carcass of a
cat on a country road, its rotted flesh baked by the summer sun,''
Evanzz writes. ``Cultural vultures tear away its flesh in their
futile search for its mythical remaining lives. Today, there are
more groups called the Nation of Islam (or some variation of it)
than bicycles in China. The name no longer denotes a sect; it
denotes a twisted virtual reality game in which the cat lives all
nine lives concurrently.''
</P>
<P>
   Evanzz is not kind to Muhammad. He exposes the leader's envy of
Malcolm X, which ultimately resulted in the latter's murder. He
writes about the contradictions that cropped up throughout
Muhammad's life and preaching, most notably his practice of calling
Caucasians inferior, then hiring them to manage the sizable assets
of the Nation of Islam. Muhammad's numerous mistresses and often
cruel treatment of those perceived to be traitors are discussed as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Evanzz also highlights the powerful impact that Muhammad had on
blacks, however, starting in the 1930s and reaching a peak in the
'50s and '60s. The Nation's message of black independence, he
writes, filled the political void left by the often-token nature of
the victories earned by the civil rights movement. This message was
powerful enough to capture the imaginations _ and pocketbooks _ of
thousands of men. A young Cassius Clay was one. Singer Joe Tex was
another.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad preached black superiority, but the religious
underpinnings of the Nation were suspect. Evanzz recounts in detail
Muhammad's first meeting with a man key to the Nation of Islam's
theology called Master Wallace D. Fard.
</P>
<P>
   Fard, Muhammad said, told him about Yakub, a ``big-headed black
scientist,'' and Fard's belief that he and his followers would rule
the world through a religion-based science called ``tricknology,''
or the science of deception. According to Fard, Yakub discovered
during a genetics experiment that whites only had one white gene
for pigmentation, while blacks had two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This genetic discrepancy explained why a black man could
create a white man through selective interracial reproduction, but
a white man could never create a black man in the same way,''
Evanzz writes, citing Muhammad's ``Message to the Blackman.''
</P>
<P>
   Though one might calculate this would result in more white men
overall, Muhammad and the Nation preached otherwise: ``White people
knew that they would eventually be eliminated from Earth if
interracial marriages became routine, he said, so they had a
survival imperative to maintain a social system of racial
separation.''
</P>
<P>
   Evanzz concludes that the Nation is now little more than a
mirage: ``The Nation of Islam built by the team of Malcolm X and
the Messenger has disintegrated and become a pool of gross
mutations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6510 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SURGERY-DEVICE-ART-BO     05-26 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURGERY-DEVICE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ENTREPRENEUR HAS ALTERNATIVE TO SURGICAL STAPLING, SEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, N.H. _ If Jacqueline Eastwood is right, surgeons would
rather snip and solder than cut and grill.
</P>
<P>
   When surgeons need to remove cancerous tissue from a lung and
then seal it, or stop the bleeding from a diseased liver, the
process often requires staples, clips, and even burning the edges
of some organs to stop blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, medical staples can lead to air leaks in lungs. And
cauterizing tissue _ using intense heat to seal it _ often results
in smoke, charring, and tissue damage.
</P>
<P>
   Although surgeons have lived with these problems for decades,
Eastwood says she has an alternative: a hand-held device that looks
like a hair-curling wand with tiny pliers at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Her device uses a saline solution and radio-frequency generators
to cut, seal, and shrink many types of tissue, and at lower
temperatures than with electrocautery.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, she formed TissueLink Medical Inc. in a refurbished
women's shoe factory along the Cocheco River in Dover, to develop
and market a surgical device she says could be used to replace
electrocautery and other fasteners and sealants in 22 million
operating-room procedures.
</P>
<P>
   And some surgeons who have seen videotapes of prototypes of the
device in use are impressed. It was tested on dogs at the
University of Minnesota and Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sealing tissues with a minimum of scar tissue _ and possibly
replacing electrocautery, where you can end up burning material as
if you were holding a blowtorch _ is rather promising,'' said Dr.
Thomas B. Ferguson, a cardiothoracic surgeon who is emeritus
professor at Washingtion University School of Medicine in St.
Louis. He's also chairman of TissueLink's Physician Advisory Board.
</P>
<P>
   Others are skeptical that surgeons will readily change their
methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``TissueLink's device may have potential, but I don't know if it
will replace staplers and sealants,'' said Dr. John D. Wain, a
thoracic surgeon at Massachusetts General Hospital and director of
its lung transplant program.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood's company, which expects to begin marketing the device
in the fourth quarter, is among a passel of companies tha are
developing products for the surgical-closure and wound-healing
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some are the medical equivalents of hardware-store caulking,
substances that bond to tissue, organs, and blood vessels to
prevent leaks.
</P>
<P>
   These thin films, gels, adhesives, and sealants are expected to
constitute a $4 billion market by 2002, according to report
released last month by Stephens Inc., a medical device research
firm. Companies such as Focal Inc. of Lexington, Genzyme Corp. of
Cambridge, and Cryolife Inc. of Atlanta are leading the efforts to
bring new products to market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wound closure has become a big business because it can be used
in many different surgical procedures to help patients heal more
quickly with few complications _ a process with a financial
incentive to insurers because people spend less time in
hospitals,'' said Robert J. DePasqua, Focal's president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Focal's sealant to prevent air leaks after lung surgery, called
FocalSeal, recently received Food and Drug Administration advisory
board approval and will be marketed by Genzyme.
</P>
<P>
   DePasqua acknowledged, though, that surgeons have been
relatively slow to embrace sealants, gels, and glues. Genzyme, for
example, had to lower its initial expectations for Seprafilm, a
coating to prevent surgical adhesions after gastrointestinal
operations, because surgeons were not convinced it would make a
significant difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned how to market and educate surgeons a lot better
today than we did nearly five years ago,'' said Earl ``Duke''
Collier Jr., Genzyme's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme is betting heavily on biomaterials like FocalSeal,
Seprafilm, and a new mesh material for hernia operations. They are
part of its forthcoming BioSurgery division, which shareholders are
expected to approve next month when the company completes its
acquistion of Biomatrix Inc., a Ridgefield, N.J., developer of an
injectable material to treat arthirits in the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Some surgeons, however, are starting to use sealants in
combination with surgical staplers and clips. The Ethicon division
of Johnson &AMP; Johnson and US Surgical Corp. of Norwalk, Conn.,
dominate the $2.5 billion market for surgical staplers.
</P>
<P>
   Electrocautery, a technology that dates back to 1900, is an $800
milion market led in part by ConMed Corp. of Utica, N.Y., and
ValleyLab, a Denver company.
</P>
<P>
   TissueLink Medical's technology could play a role in all these
markets, Eastwood said. Iniitally, she has focused on converting
thoracic surgeons, who perform about 300,000 lung procedures a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Her confidence in building TissueLink comes from her extensive
experience with small and large companies in the medical-device
industry, including 11 years at Medtronic Inc., the Minneapolis
medical device company where she was vice president of corporate
ventures and licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Now in her mid-50s, she left Medtronic in January 1999 with a
goal of retiring to New Hampshire so she could paint and spend time
with her family, including her two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me two years ago that I would be starting a
business here, raise venture capital money, hire a staff, I would
say you were crazy,'' said Eastwood, who also moved her elderly
mother up from New York to live with her.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood's decision to postpone early retirement and start
TissueLink came after a Minneapolis surgeon tracked her down. He
told her about how he had lost a young woman, a mother of two small
children, who died on the operating table after an automobile
accident. He he could not stop the bleeding from her liver.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor remembered seeing a prototype of Medtronic's saline
and radiofrequency device that could seal tissues faster and with
fewer complications than cautery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me thinking that this technology had potential,'' said
Eastwood, who quickly acquired the technology and patent rights
from Medtronic.
</P>
<P>
   However, more than one executive in the surgical-device market
recalled that Medtronic peddled the technology, first developed in
1995, to others. And they balked at it, questioning whether it
could close large sections of the trachea, which leads to the lungs
and is typically sealed with staples or sutures.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood said TissueLink's device, which is expected to sell for
$1,500 per operation, is not aimed at all lung surgeries, but at
the majority of lobectomies, such as the removal of part of a lung
due to cancer or emphysema. Another use would be sealing the
openings after wedges of diseased tissue are cut out.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading surgeons to switch to TissueLink's unnamed device may
prove difficult, though. Hospitals are under cost contraints for
new medical equipment, and educating surgeons about new techniques
can take years _ a lesson Genzyme learned with Seprafilm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trained in what amounts to an apprenticeship where you
learn to do something well, so unless something new comes comes
along that is very effective, most surgeons won't change,'' Wain
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Medtronic, it has licensed its technology to TissueLink
in exchange for 18 percent ownership of the company. That gave
Eastwood the leverage to raise $4 million in venture capital, split
evenly between Crescendo Venture Management LLC and Vanguard
Venture Partners. The company is seeking $15 million more and has
commitments for $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding the money has not proven very difficult, compared to
finding the right partners that understand what we want to build,''
Eastwood said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
