<HEADLINE>
FRESHWATER FISHING: KNOWING THE ROPES HELPS WAY UP NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Vt. _ Since he retired from the local ovenworks three
years ago, WilsieWilliams does not miss a day of the trout season
on the Mad or Winooski rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Even a chilly dawn of spitting rain with rags of mist clinging
to the mountaintops finds Williams in his accustomed spot, sitting
on a milk crate casting nightcrawlers into the swollen river.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got 50, 60 right here on this point last year,'' said
Williams, who spends his spring fishing and getting next winter's
wood supply, ``but this year's been a little slow. Maybe the
water's too cold yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Green Mountains around here _ Camel's Hump, Sugarbush _ are
steep and thickly forested, with dozens of hidden streams full of
wild brookies.
</P>
<P>
   But since the state stocked the Winooski with good-sized
rainbows and browns last week, most local anglers find their own
stake out here.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Hayes and Joe Berry fish the Winooski at least four mornings
a week, and have nothing but high praise. They came with a portable
propane stove to cook the trout they expected to catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get a native fish up to 5 pounds here,'' said Berry.
``There are fish in the 2-pound range that they stock. But there
are some really nice big fish here. The best thing about the river
is even when there's a lot of fishing pressure, people can spread
out and find there own niche. You can catch fish anywhere along
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is only one stretch of the 90-mile Winooski, with its
several branches and tributaries that flow all the way to Lake
Champlain at Burlington. And as the fishing rounds into shape this
week down around Waterbury _ though some streams are still high and
muddy _ the pressure is not bad, almost nonexistent. Also nearby is
the Mad and the Dog River, the latter of which produced a
state-record trout.
</P>
<P>
   The Dog is a tributary into the Winooski that winds slowly
through farm fields. Wild brookie fishing is superb, as are the
stocked browns and rainbows, along with a few holdovers. Though
much of this land is posted, our small party had no trouble getting
permission from farmers to walk the fields along Route 12A.
</P>
<P>
   The gateway to this end of the Winooski and her tributaries is
Route 89 to Exit 10 at Waterbury, then the dirt road at the east
end of the village bridge. The road runs along the south side of
the river.
</P>
<P>
   Swinging east for a radical difference, we checked out two of
Vermont's prettiest and most fishable lakes, Willoughby and
Mephremagog in the Northeast Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   While Mephremagog _ the largest of the state's inland lakes _
jumps off at the busy tourist town of Newport (off I-91), the range
of services offered quickly has anglers fishing for wild trout,
lakers, and salmon. The salmon feed voraciously in spring, and most
anglers know the secrets of the spring run from the lake's spawning
grounds _ Barton, Black, Clyde, and Willoughby rivers. Hit these
spots at just the right time _ when fly hatch meets spring run _
and the fishing is unsurpassed in New England. The lake stretches
more than 25 miles into Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the oldest _ and almost by definition _ largest lake
trout live in the cold, 300-foot glacial depths of Willoughby,
whose soaring western cliffs and fjord make it uniquely
picturesque. Fishing Willoughby is best done in a trolling boat.
The lake is long and thin, with a launch ramp on the east shore and
up the Willoughby River about half a mile. Brown trout, rainbows,
brookies, lake trout, and landlocked salmon are all supported in
Willoughby. There are some nice guest houses along the east shore
of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Northern New Hampshire is between two of its early-season
glories. While the salmon run has slowed dramatically in the
Connecticut River in Pittsburg _ as the river has dropped and
slowed _ the watch is on for the large mayfly, Hexagenia limbata,
which are not due for at least a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When they hit, the fly anglers for whom this part of the world
is trout mecca come off the river and head out onto Back Lake, Lake
Francis, or the largest of the Connecticut Lakes. Salmon and trout
feed voraciously on Hex right into July, when the hatches tail off.
</P>
<P>
   This water system, which make up the headwaters of the 400-mile
Connecticut River, begins just below the Canadian border at Third
Connecticut Lake. (Actually, there is a Fourth Lake, into which
I've trekked only to discover why it is left off most fishing
maps).
</P>
<P>
   This is wonderful destination fishing. There are lodges and
fishing camps with all the ammenities from the town of Pittsburg
around Lake Francis and along Route 3, which heads north to the
First, Second, and Third Lakes, strung together by the river. Also,
check out Back Lake west of Route 3.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much up here that newer anglers are advised to hire
one of the many guides _ you'll see their cards on the notice board
when you stop for coffee at the Pittsburg General Store.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fishing changes from week to week, specific
information is vital. A guide or friend familiar with the region is
advised.
</P>
<P>
   Just below the northern end of New Hampshire are two more
stillwaters that are lovely and well worth the fishing anytime in
spring _ Big Diamond and Little Diamond Ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Reach these by driving Route 26 out of Kidderville (near
Dixville Notch). They are very different waters, Little Diamond a
shallow put-and-take brook trout water where anglers have a limit
of five fish or 5 pounds. The pond is in Coleman State Park, where
there is a boat launch ramp.
</P>
<P>
   If Little Diamond is rarely more than 15 feet deep, Big Diamond
has a maximum depth of more than 110 feet, so there are plenty of
holdover fish to be caught. Trolling is the usual technique _ there
is a launch ramp _ though some shore-casting flyfishers work the
west of the pond in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Route 16 out of the town of Errol brings anglers to a 3-mile
stretch of the Androscoggin River that supports populations of
brookie, brown, and rainbow trout, and salmon. The water is most
accessible from Route 16 down to Mollidgewock Campground, and is
perhaps best fished first at the confluence of Clear Stream
tributary.
</P>
<P>
   Indian and Perry Streams are long tributaries into the
Connecticut water system, and both are stocked with brook trout,
some of them wild. Last season on our trip to the Pittsburg area,
these two streams were among the most productive, hidden, and fun
to fish.
</P>
<P>
   In the lovely Rangeley Lakes region of western Maine, one of the
most overlooked still waters is Aziscohos Lake. While Rangeley Lake
and Mooselookmeguntic are usual destinations in this region,
Aziscohos, a 6,700-acre impoundment on the Magaloway River,
features both stocked and holdover fish.
</P>
<P>
   With good smelt forage, the state now stocks salmon again, after
a moratorium. Stocked and wild brook trout are the other game in
the Aziscohos. The south end has two launch ramps and numerous
campsites. With depths of 60 feet in the south end, fishing remains
strong through the summer and fly-fishing is popular. The season
closes Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Even despite recent development, the Moosehead region of Maine
remains what it always has been, a sportsperson's paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many rivers that flow in and out of the massive,
75,000-acre Moosehead Lake, the Roach River, which enters Spencer
Bay at the northeast corner of the lake, is well worth a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Near the entrance to the lake, the Roach is very fast moving,
especially during rainy springs like this one. There are fish in
the pools behind those rashing riffles, but this section of the
river is very challenging to flycasters.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the season, this stretch does support some very
large salmon along with wild brookies. Perhaps the best first look
is the stretch between First Roach Pond and Lazy Tom Stream. As the
river lowers in the spring, though, more fish are taken in the
section between First Roach and Moosehead.
</P>
<P>
   The Roach can be reached by driving west from Baxter State Park
or north from Greenville on the south shore of Moosehead. While
you're in the neighborhood check out the always breathtaking West
Branch of the Penobscot for large salmon and brown trout. This
river flows north to Chesuncook Lake, with decent access along the
Golden Road, a non-paved logging road.
</P>
<P>
   Maine is so large that its northern reaches stretch more than
100 miles north of New Hampshire and Vermont. So, reaching the
Allagash River and Wilderness Waterway requires a seriously
planned, and perhaps guided, trip. One reaches the river by canoe,
and anglers cast for wild brookies, though fishing is only one of
the attractions of this, one of the most spectacular wilderness
tracts in the country.
</P>
<P>
   June and September are the best months on the river. Fishing
tends to be better in June, but the black flies can be pretty
ferocious. Aside from literature about the region, prospective
anglers should also check out the lengthy canon of fishing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   And just when you think you've seen the most beautiful wild
place in the Northeast, the 125-mile St. John River creates much of
the border with New Brunswick, from Allagash Village to the Bay of
Fundy. This is wild territory, providing a canoe and fishing
expedition for true getaway aficionados. It does require planning,
permission, and guiding. All details about the St. John or Allagash
can be obtained from the North Maine Woods office at 207-435-6213.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
