u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-26 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMISING E-TAILER RUNS INTO A CASH JAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Our current tale of Internet capitalism takes a few moments but
involves a theme that should ring a bell: companies that need money
and find it hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com, based in Framingham, Mass., has made a name for
itself in the online world as the most popular site by far among a
field of retailers selling furnishings on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company almost made it as a public company, under the wing
of blue-chip underwriter Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., but timing conspired
against the planned spring offering. As we all know, the public
stock market window slammed shut and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   This was a problem because Furniture.com, though it gets at
least twice as much traffic as its closest online competitor, had
been burning through some serious cash.
</P>
<P>
   Total 1999 losses: $46.5 million. Remaining cash at the end of
the year: $31 million.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO would have raised about $50 million and probably valued
Furniture.com at a minimum of $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   For companies losing money like Furniture.com, that means
raising more cash privately, if you can find it. For later stage
ventures that missed the IPO window, that's no layup.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com decided to go back to its existing venture
investors for $40 million or more in a process known as a ``cram
down,'' according to people familiar with the situation. The
typical pitch: Put up more cash or most of your existing equity
position may get washed out.
</P>
<P>
   Companies running cram downs do so by assessing painfully low
valuations on their own existing stock, so the new round of
financing buys a big percentage of the business. Existing private
investors can step up and maintain their interest or lose out.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com, estimated to be worth at least $200 million when
it was trying to launch an IPO a couple of months ago, now carries
a valuation of $10 million in its latest financing efforts, we are
told. Add recast employee options and the number probably rises to
$20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com has not been able to close on the cram down so
far. President Andrew Brooks insists the company's capital-raising
activity is simply a work in progress and doesn't reflect any kind
of problem.
</P>
<P>
   The company's venture investors include big names like CMGI's
(at)Ventures and Bessemer Venture Partners. Brooks singled out
(at)Ventures in particular as having ``really shown leadership in
terms of the process of raising this next round of financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brooks said customer orders at Furniture.com
increased to $19.6 million in the first quarter of this year, up 46
percent from the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Funiture.com attracted nearly 1.1 million unique visitors in
March, double the figure for second-place Living.com., according to
online traffic tracker MediaMetrix Inc. Goodhome.com, the
third-place competitor, attracted 377,000 unique visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Furniture.com's cash jam, people familiar with all of
the online furniture retailers say competitors may have even bigger
problems. Some have cash but not enough customers. Others are
lugging big contingent liabilities as a result of partnerships with
retailing portals like Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   A more interesting story of diverging paths: Furniture.com and
MotherNature.com, the online health products retailer based in
Concord.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies began to grow from their very earliest roots at
about the same time and have many private venture investors in
common. Three people sit on the boards of both companies, including
MotherNature chief executive Michael Barach.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when both companies were still quite green, they were
approached about going public. MotherNature decided to take the
money while it could get it, accepting a second-tier underwriter as
the trade-off. Furniture.com chose to wait for its business to
mature a bit and the chance to go public with Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Now MotherNature has money, but a public stock that has plunged
86 percent since its December IPO. Furniture.com never got through
the stock market door and must pull off its current private
financing effort.
</P>
<P>
   Which decision worked best? We don't think the answer is in yet.
The tougher question: Does either have a chance to end up a winner?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
