<HEADER>
A6542 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     05-26 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV28-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHING MACHINE NO LONGER REMOVES SOAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 28, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  Our washing machine is 13 years old and is no longer
rinsing soap completely out of the clothes. Is this a problem of
the water or the soap, or is it time for a new machine?
</P>
<P>
   GINNY LAIRD, Easton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  There's something wrong with the spin dryer that squeezes
out the rinse water, or the pump. Call an appliance repair person
who will service any brand. He may find something simple and
inexpensive. If the repair is expensive ($100 or more), consider a
new washing machine. Your machine is two years beyond its life
expectancy of 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  My stucco house on the water in mid-coast Maine is peeling,
and needs to be painted. The painter who painted the house about 10
years ago said he'd scrape, and paint with latex paint. Is latex
the best to use on stucco?
</P>
<P>
   BILL COLCORD, Out there somewhere
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Any latex is OK to use on stucco. Be careful scraping it,
and perhaps wire brushing might be better than scraping to get the
loose paint off. Once everything is done and clean, use two thin
coats of a latex house paint. Or, perhaps better, two thin coats of
a latex solid color stain. No primer is needed in either case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  The landscape timber walls of my large planters have been
eaten by insects. I would like to put some concrete blocks in front
of the decyed timbers to create a bigger planter, but without
taking out the timbers, which will evewntully rot away. Would that
work?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN KINGSLEY, Westborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  I think it will work quite well, allowing bigger planters
without taking out all that earth. I suggest you install concrete
retaining wall blocks, which are designed to hold back earth, are
permanent, and look very good.
</P>
<P>
   If you saw insects in the timbers, make sure they (possibly
termites) do not get into the house. Or, if they are carpenter
ants, they nested in the wood, not eating it, but could find some
good wood in the house to nest in. Make sure they did not. If you
saw no insects, the timbers may have decayed simply from a fungus
or other non-insect organism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I am redoing my bathroom, with is 89 inches wide and 99
inches long. When I say redoing, it means gutting everything to the
studs and joists, new everything, including tile around the tub,
and all new fixtures. I got a bid of $12,000. Is that reasonable or
not?
</P>
<P>
   LOUISE KILROY, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  That's reasonable. Any other bids you might get are likely,
in my opinion, to be higher. With a bid like that, make sure the
fixtures are of the quality that you like.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I had a nice wood exterior door installed with a storm that
is one large piece of glass. I would like to finish it, and I like
the idea of the gel urethane. Would that work?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN PRICE, Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Yes, it should, if not sun hits the storm or door. Make
sure that gel urethane is for exterior use. But I think spar or
marine varnish would better. Three thin coats should give you
pretty good service. But if the door gets half a day or more, of
sun, I don't think the varnish will stand up for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  My end table has a leather insert. I put some plants on it,
causing a white water stain on the leather. Old Craftsman's spot
remover took some of the stain off, but not all. How can I get the
remainder off the leather?
</P>
<P>
   HELEN O'BRIEN, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Sometimes saddle soap will do it, but Apple Polishers of
Stow, Vt., makers of leather care products, took me to task when I
suggested anything but their products. That's OK with me; their
products will be probably be safe. Call 978-562-4333 or
800-800-5803.
</P>
<P>
   And, this too might work. Rub the stain lightly with a
toothpaste (not gel). But very lightly. Then apply a leather
conditioner, one of the Apple Polishers products.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  Do you have a list of good stucco people? I cannot find
any. And is there a way for the homeowner to patch stucco?
</P>
<P>
   LIAM VESELY, Sudbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Check the Yellow Pages under ``Stucco &AMP; Exterior Coating
Contractors'' and ``Stucco Mfrs. &AMP; Distrs.'' Several are listed.
</P>
<P>
   To make a patch, apply wire lath to the wall if there is no lath
in place; this is the best way for stucco to stick. Apply a coat of
a concrete mix (Sakrete makes one; just add water), wait 15
minutes, rub it with a wood float (a wood trowel), which produces
the rough finish of stucco. To reduce cracking, apply concrete in
two thin layers instead of one.
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton answers reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
