<HEADER>
A6550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-POLITICS-NYT     05-26 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE WILL DETERMINE FUTURE OF PEACE FOR NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Members of the 870-strong ruling
council of the Ulster Unionist party will convene here Saturday for
a crucial vote that will either give new life to the Northern
Ireland peace accord or likely finish it off.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome will turn on whether the pro-British party, whose
longtime slogan was ``Ulster says no,'' retreats to its
rejectionist past and renounces the current formula for stabilizing
the volatile sectarian politics of Ulster or follows the lead of
its moderating leader, David Trimble, who is proposing a future
based on a risk-taking accommodation with the pro-Irish republican
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, a Nobel Peace Prize winner, said Friday that he did not
want to characterize the balloting as a ``back me or sack me''
vote, but that if he is defeated, his five-year-old leadership is
almost certainly over.
</P>
<P>
   He is asking his party to accept an Irish Republican Army offer
to permit inspections of its secret arms dumps as a credible
disarmament move justifying the Ulster Unionists' return to
participation in home rule government with Sinn Fein, the political
representatives of the IRA. If he prevails, the currently suspended
Northern Ireland Assembly will be back up and running by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble succeeded last November in persuading his quarrelsome
party, the province's largest Protestant group, to begin joint rule
with its Catholic rivals in Sinn Fein, but that power-sharing
government was put on hold by the British in February, after only
nine weeks, when the IRA failed to make expected companion moves on
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   On May 6, the IRA announced it would let international
inspectors monitor its hidden arsenals and said it would
``completely and verifiably put IRA arms beyond use.'' The
statement came at a time of deepening gloom among peace negotiators
and lifted hopes that a stalemate over guerrilla disarmament that
had blocked progress in the peace settlement had been broken.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists have long said that they would not go into
government with Sinn Fein without assurances that its IRA allies
would disarm. Trimble says he believes the new action by the IRA
constitutes that assurance. His opponents, who have maintained a
stance they call ``no guns, no government,'' say it does not.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, both sides have campaigned feverishly,
employing door-to-door visits, telephone banks and province-wide
leafletting. At issue is whether enough Ulster Unionists can be
persuaded to give Trimble the benefit of a doubt a second time. He
called off a meeting originally scheduled for last Saturday when he
saw that his cause was losing at that point.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-agreement faction has broadened its demands for
concessions, reviving past ties to cherished symbols of national
identity. The debate that had been confined to weapons now turns on
additional issues like whether the British or Irish flag flies
above government buildings, the name for the new police force and
what emblems appear on police badges and caps.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly sensitive is the matter of what to call the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, the 93 percent Protestant police force that
enjoys little trust from Catholics and whose initials, R.U.C.,
feature in most of the graffiti scrawled on walls in their
neighborhoods. An international commission headed by former Hong
Kong Gov. Chris Patten recommended a new force with more balanced
recruitment and the name Northern Ireland Police Service, but the
hard-liners are insisting that the R.U.C. title be kept.
</P>
<P>
   A Belfast Telegraph poll showed Thursday that more than 70
percent of unionists favor Trimble's proposal, but the makeup of
the council is more hard-line than the Protestant population as a
whole. Trimble is planning reforms to do away with block votes on
the council held by a militant youth wing and the traditional
Orange Order, but he has not been able to do so in time to affect
Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   The rejectionist group is led openly by his most forceful
opponent in the party, Jeffrey Donaldson, 37, a member of
parliament who has coveted Trimble's leadership position and
appears to be seizing his chance now to wrest it away. He plans to
introduce an alternative proposal demanding IRA disarmament at
Saturday's meeting as a way of combating Trimble's claim that there
is no alternative to his own plan.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has lost the support of some of the people who voted
with him in November, but he has also picked up backing in
surprising places.
</P>
<P>
   Sean O'Callaghan, a convicted former IRA killer turned informer,
told unionist gatherings this week that he was convinced that the
IRA's new pledge constituted the long awaited pledge from the
republican side that ``the war is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,600 people have died in the past three decades in that
war, and the peace agreement, struck in April 1998 but still not
fully in place, was an effort to balance the interests of
pro-British Protestants and pro-Irish Catholics and turn their
dispute from a violent one into a political one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is the best possible agreement on weaponry
that we could have achieved,'' O'Callaghan said. ``I believe it is
an offer that unionists in Northern Ireland would be mad to turn
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
