<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-MUSTANG-HNS &LR;      05-26 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-MUSTANG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MUSTANG GT APPEALS TO BOOMERS AND THEIR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's face it.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is quite as exhilarating as driving along winding
country roads in a convertible with a big V-8 engine and the top
down.
</P>
<P>
   And almost nothing is quite like the 2000 Mustang GT convertible
to take on just such a drive.
</P>
<P>
   With all the retro-look cars that have come on the market
lately, such as the Plymouth Prowler, Chrysler PT Cruiser and
Volkswagen New Beetle, nothing is quite as authentic for
nostalgia's sake as the current Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been, and I hope always will continue to be, a
throwback to the late '60s, when muscle cars were king of the road,
and the Mustang led the pack.
</P>
<P>
   People like the Mustang; more than 6.9 million have been sold
since the car debuted at the 1964 New York World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, at middle age I felt a bit silly sitting down behind
the wheel of a zinc-yellow Mustang GT with boy-racer black stripes
and the big ``GT'' letters on the hood.
</P>
<P>
   This is a car for boys who are still trying to impress those
impressionable teen-age girls, and whose driving skills might or
might not be quite up to the car's power and performance.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, I instantly felt about 30 years younger as I fired up
the GT's 260-horsepower, 4.6-liter V-8, lowered the top, fastened
my seatbelt, and eased it (well, not really _ gunned it) onto the
nearest freeway.
</P>
<P>
   I had a girl at my side _ my own 16-year-old daughter _ who was
duly impressed with the car, and the fact that her old man could:
a) drive it as well as one of her young, male schoolmates, and b)
seem to enjoy it as much, too.
</P>
<P>
   She, of course, grooved on the GT (do they say ``grooved''
anymore? Am I truly dating myself here?), and wanted us to take it
on some really neat back roads, which we proceeded to do.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye out for restrictive speed limits, residential areas
and road hazards, we took it through the Texas Hill Country,
winding and weaving along some of the most beautiful roads the Lone
Star State has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool, really cool roads,'' the teen-ager said. ``And boy, this
car really handles them well!''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. It will as long as those roads aren't wet; if they
get wet, though, it's time to park the Mustang. All that power
going to the rear wheels and those (almost) racing tires can play
havoc with traction.
</P>
<P>
   But wait: For 2000, Ford finally has added traction control to
the Mustang, something that has been needed for years. (The
Connecticut Highway Patrol, which has used Mustang GTs as pursuit
vehicles for years, has had a policy of keeping those vehicles
parked when the roads are wet).
</P>
<P>
   For $230, the traction control can be added to any 2000 Mustang,
and it works at any speed to help limit wheel spin and stabilize
steering on slippery surfaces. The system uses antilock braking
sensors to detect excess drive-wheel spin, then reduces wheel
slippage by retarding ignition timing, reducing fuel flow, and
cutting off cylinders in conjunction with application of individual
wheel brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The driver can turn off the system using a switch on the center
console.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have the opportunity to drive the GT on any wet roads,
though, so I can't tell you how effective this system is at keeping
the rear wheels in place as the vehicle negotiates turns on
slippery pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Any improvement from the past would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Ford mildly restyled the Mustang last year, the first changes
since the current generation of the vehicle made its worldwide
debut at the Texas State Fair in Dallas in fall 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still strongly reminiscent of the Mustangs of the late
'60s, with the longer, rounded hood and beefier appearance than the
original 1964 1/2 model.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Mustangs were introduced when I was in high school,
they hold great nostalgic value for me (and most other baby boomers
who came of age in the '60s). It's nice to know that the current
model holds onto some of the original styling, including the
classic hood and the signature tri-bar taillights.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in last year's changes, the V-8 engine's horsepower was
increased by 35, giving an already zippy car even more go-power.
Torque also was increased slightly, to 302 foot-pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Although the five-speed manual transmission probably offers the
best performance from the V-8 engine, our test car came with the
four-speed automatic gearbox ($815 extra).
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice to have the option to shift the
automatic transmission manually like the feature that some other
cars with automatics offer, but clutchless manual shifting wasn't
available on the Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its retro look and feel, the Mustang has lots of modern
features besides the traction control and antilock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   There are second-generation air bags up front, remote keyless
entry, power rack-and-pinion steering, CFC-free air-conditioning,
stainless-steel exhaust, dual power mirrors, power windows and door
locks, leather-wrapped tilt steering wheel, AM/FM/cassette in-dash
stereo with separate in-dash compact-disc player, a power
convertible top (with glass rear window), and illuminated dual
visor mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Base price of the GT convertible, which includes all of the
above except the automatic transmission and traction control, is
$25,365 plus $575 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Extras on our test car, besides the transmission and traction
control, included the GT feature package ($995) that added 17-inch
machined-aluminum wheels, Z-rated 17-inch tires (top speed of this
car approaches 150 mph), and the black striping; an upgraded stereo
system ($395); a convenience group ($550) that added front floor
mats, power driver's seat, rear defroster and cruise control; and
leather sport bucket seats ($500).
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker was $29,440, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The car seats four people, but the rear seat is a bit cramped
for adults.
</P>
<P>
   It does have the new permanent anchoring system for two child
safety seats, though, so the car can accommodate a couple of little
ones.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the V-8 with automatic transmission
are 17 miles per gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the highway. But
don't expect to get mileage that high if you have a lead foot. It
just won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   The tank holds 15.7 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
