<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-SPORTS-MODELS-HN     05-26 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SPORTS-MODELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOT ALL SPORTY CARS BREAK THE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to lust after exotic cars such as the
half-million-dollar Ferrari or Lamborghini, the $130,000
Mercedes-Benz SL600 convertible, the $82,000 Jaguar XKR
convertible, or even the more realistically priced Chevrolet
Corvette soft-top, at just over $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, let's face it. Most of us can't afford any of these
cars.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of us can't even afford fun and sporty vehicles
such as the cheapest of the BMW Z3 roadsters, at $31,300, or
something as much fun as, say, the Audi TT coupe, with its $30,000
price tag, or the Ford Mustang GT convertible, which rings in at
nearly $26,000 before any extras are tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   Don't despair. You really don't need megabucks to buy a car that
has some zip, looks really cool, and is truly fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Some automakers are aware of our plight, and are making sure we
have a chance to own affordable yet sporty cars that put smiles on
our faces as we cruise down city streets or along country roads.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the rich folks don't hold the franchise on fun;
it's there for the taking for any of us who can afford to buy a new
car at or below _ even well-below _ the current average price of
new cars, $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   You need cruise no farther than any of your local Ford,
Chevrolet or Pontiac dealerships to find the first of the
affordable sporty cars that come to mind: the Ford Mustang,
Chevrolet Camaro and Pontiac Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   These cars thrive today in part because baby boomers who came of
age in the 1960s are on a nostalgia binge, trying to re-create
their childhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just us 40- or early-50-somethings who are gobbling
up Camaros, Firebirds and Mustangs; kids coming of age seem to like
them just as much as we did. It's not uncommon to see folks with
gray hair shopping for these cars with their teen-age children in
tow, being egged on by said teens as they consider buying such
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   At dealership after dealership, Camaros, Firebirds and Mustangs
were priced not in the low- to mid-$20,000s, but way down in the
mid- to upper-teens. Yep, that's right. There is a good selection
in the $16,500 to $19,000 range on many Chevy, Ford and Pontiac
lots.
</P>
<P>
   OK, these aren't the hottest of these cars on the market. For
these affordable prices, you won't get a V-8 engine or even a
convertible top. But the V-6 power in these cars _ 3.8 liters and
190 horsepower for the Mustangs; 3.8 liters and 200 hp for the
Camaros and Firebirds _ is plenty of power for most of our needs.
Even without a V-8 engine, these cars are plenty fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   If you can afford to break the $20,000 barrier, but still must
stay below $25,000, you can opt for a soft top on any of these
cars.
</P>
<P>
   The V-6 Mustang convertible lists for $21,370, and even with a
few popular options _ such as automatic transmission and cruise
control _ you can buy a Mustang convertible for about $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   A well-equipped V-6 Camaro convertible lists for $24,140, but
with readily available dealer discounts, that can be trimmed by
$1,500 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The Firebird convertible lists for just over $25,000, but can be
bought for less if you take the time to shop for a good price.
</P>
<P>
   These pony-car derivatives do have drawbacks. For those of us
with families _ who need four doors and at least a marginally
comfortable back seat _ two-door Mustangs, Camaros and Firebirds
are out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let the dreaded ``S'' word _ sedan _ scare you into
believing you can't have fun and carry your family everywhere with
you at the same time. Fun sedans are on the market. No kidding! And
they can be had for under $25,000 and, in some cases, way under.
</P>
<P>
   One excellent choice is the Pontiac Grand Prix GT four-door
sedan, carrying a list price of about $21,500, which can be
whittled down under $20,000 with shrewd negotiating or careful
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you can't bring yourself to buy a sedan, you can put the
kiddies _ even big ones _ in the back seat of the Grand Prix GT
two-door coupe, and they'll have plenty of room for their legs.
</P>
<P>
   The GT comes with a 3.8-liter, 200-horsepower engine (just like
the Camaro and Firebird). But if you really want to rock and roll,
upgrade to the GTP model, which lists for just over $24,000 (coupe
or sedan), and you'll get that same 3.8-liter engine with a
supercharger, boosting it to a truly fun 240 horsepower. Wow!
</P>
<P>
   Compact sedans, the stalwart of the economically challenged
family, can actually be exciting, too.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of the Pontiac Grand Am, of course. It's the
best-selling domestic compact on the market, and it comes with a
modest 150-horsepower four-cylinder engine. But forget the
four-cylinder, and snag a Grand Am GT, priced just under $20,000,
equipped with a 3.4-liter V-6 that cranks out 170 horsepower and
195 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Ford isn't to be outdone in this class. If you want sporty fun
in an affordable four-door compact, check out the Contour SVT. That
moniker designates this car as a product of Ford's special vehicle
team, whose job it is to take an average product and make it into
something, well, special.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the 170-horsepower, 2.5-liter V-6 in the standard
Contour, the SVT comes with a 195-horsepower version of this
engine. It has a stiffer suspension and much better road handling
abilities than the base car, and the list price is $22,715.
</P>
<P>
   There are more sporty cars to choose from at affordable prices
if you can do with two doors and a smallish back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the completely redesigned 2000 Toyota Celica,
which comes with a 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine. There are two
versions; to get the sportiest one, opt for the GT-S, with 180
horsepower (compared with 140 hp in the base car) and 140
foot-pounds of torque. The list price is just over $21,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi's Eclipse GT, though, can leave the Celica GT-S in
its dust.
</P>
<P>
   The Eclipse GT comes with a 3.0-liter V-6 engine rated at 205
horsepower and 205 foot-pounds of torque. A well-equipped Eclipse
GT lists for about $21,000, and it has some of the best
road-handling attributes in this vehicle class.
</P>
<P>
   Honda sells its sporty Prelude for about $23,500, with a
200-horsepower engine and five-speed manual transmission, or about
$24,500 with automatic transmission and 195 horsepower. But rear
seat room is quite limited.
</P>
<P>
   Two sporty, if not speedy, affordable convertibles on the market
include the Mazda Miata two-seat roadster, whose price begins at
$21,245, and the Volkswagen Cabrio, starting at just under $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Miata has a 140-horsepower four-cylinder engine that offers
decent performance, whereas the Cabrio's performance is a bit
challenged with its 115-horsepower four-cylinder engine. Yet both
cars are lots of fun on warm, sunny days with the top down.
</P>
<P>
   For those who need a truly affordable new car with some measure
of sportiness, Hyundai offers its redesigned Tiburon compact
hatchback for 2000, bearing a rather impressive 140-horsepower
2.0-liter four-cylinder engine and fresh styling that looks
something like the much more expensive Audi TT.
</P>
<P>
   The price? $14,000 for the model with manual transmission, and
under $15,000 with automatic. It comes with the best new-car
warranty in the business, too _ the drivetrain (engine and
transmission) is covered for up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
