<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6598 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-NYPHILHARMONIC-MUTI-I     05-26 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYPHILHARMONIC-MUTI-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTING MUTI, THE MAESTRO OF MILAN 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following interview with Riccardo Muti
(music director of La Scala opera house in Milan, Italy), who is a
top candidate to become the next music director for the New York
Philharmonic, can be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ by
contacting a New York Times Syndicate salesperson. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By KELLY BURKE  
 c.2000 The Sydney Morning Herald  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Riccardo Muti reaches Sydney in September, the world
will have an answer to the question that America's music
cognoscenti have been speculating over for months.
</P>
<P>
   Will he or won't he take up the baton of the New York
Philharmonic, when the prestigious orchestra's music director, Kurt
Masur, stands down in 2002?
</P>
<P>
   If the United States shared Australia's passion for gambling,
those following the succession saga would have to put the odds at
2-1. As Muti is the obvious front-runner for the job and happens to
be the personal choice of the musicians themselves, it seems likely
all roads will lead to New York for the 58-year-old Italian
maestro.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the telephone from his home base of Milan recently,
Muti wasn't denying his aspirations. But no contract had been
signed, he assured. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a love affair,'' he said, in his trademark style: equal
part arrogance, equal part charm. ``But it is not yet a marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   As music director of La Scala for the past 14 years, Muti's
subsequent enthronement at the New York Philharmonic would fulfill
the conductor's lifelong ambition: to follow in the footsteps of
the man whose legend he worships, Arturo Toscanini.
</P>
<P>
   And now twice wounded in his bid to seize control of the Berlin
Philharmonic, first by the fellow countryman he detests, Claudio
Abbado, and then by Berlin's decision to appoint Simon Rattle as
successor, the $2 million annual salary Muti is rumored to be
negotiating would help the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to discussing money, Muti will have no such
crudities. ``This is just gossip,'' he says. ``The salary is not
the point. I don't need to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are strong possibilities I will sign, but of course it
depends on the details because I do not want to leave La Scala,''
he says. ``So if I take the orchestra, it would have to be with La
Scala, not instead of La Scala.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rub. Muti is not about to sacrifice a long love
affair with Italy's glorious opera house for the sake of a New York
dalliance; despite the chemistry that sparked last year when the
Italian made his long-overdue debut with the notoriously
temperamental orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the days of Leonard Bernstein had the orchestra
apparently developed such an instant attraction to a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was mutual. But while Muti is assured of the
musicians' support and respect, these vital prerequisites for a
happy marriage between music director and orchestra will in no way
assuage other difficulties the conductor encountered in an earlier
American relationship, with the Philadelphia Orchestra during the
1970s. Muti's vulnerability to jet lag and an open distaste for
kowtowing to the philanthropic socialites who oil the financial
cogs of America's major orchestras and opera companies may make his
stint in New York, should he choose to take the mission, a rocky
one.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Muti is incapable of flexibility or even, on occasion,
compromise, as his recent handling of La Scala's partial
privatization proved.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, La Scala received 80 percent of its income from
government sources. With the opera house's conversion to a
nonprofit foundation, that shrunk to 60 percent, with business and
philanthropic funding making up the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Muti welcomed the move toward partial
privatization. But he tempered his optimism with a warning to the
multinationals jostling for a place on the new board: stay off the
delineated artistic turf of my opera house.
</P>
<P>
   Three years on, Muti remains satisfied with the level of
separation between the artistic and business arms of La Scala Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment I call La Scala a happy island,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, La Scala is an island. No other opera house comes
close to rival the style and drama on or off the stage that is La
Scala. Only the Oscars bunfight or a Cannes Film Festival premiere
can compare with the circus that takes place every December 7 when
La Scala opens its new season. And no other opera house has the
luxury of approaching its box-office health with such sanguinity.
That La Scala will be booked out for every performance _ be it
Verdi or Poulenc _ is a given.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a house where the audience has no sacred cows. If
it does not like what it hears, it is vocal in its disapproval, as
Luciano Pavarotti discovered to his mortification during a 1992
production of Verdi's ``Don Carlo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we do have a very difficult public, but this is good,''
Muti says. ``Certainly it is a public which does not sleep. People
experience the music like a passion for life. Sometimes here it is
a question of life or death. But it makes everything very exciting,
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet La Scala's resistance to change can be a mixed blessing.
Like the Vienna Staatsoper, it has defied all attempts to install
surtitles. It has also resisted the trend toward director-led
opera. The cult of regis is anathema to Muti.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the music there is already the idea of what should be a
dramatic realization ... a director's job is to visually put the
musical ideas of the conductor on the stage, that is all,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ethos Muti has stuck to from an extraordinarily young
age; from when the Neapolitan-born Milan Conservatory graduate
first took over the Maggio Musicale Fiorentino in 1969 at the age
of 28.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 30 years at the top of his profession, Muti comes
to a remarkably simple conclusion on the nature of opera: ``There
is no such thing as a conservative production or a modern
production. A production is simply either stupid or intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
