<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Middle East peace process hits the streets
 &HT;    (Eds: This column, which normally moves Mondays, is moving today
to accommodate early Memorial Day deadlines.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As thanks for trying _ and trying hard _ to make peace with
Syria and the Palestinians, Israel is being harassed by both. With
putative negotiating partners like this, who needs enemies?
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse way, the latest resort of the notorious
Palestinian street to stones, firebombs, turmoil and the other
familiar civilities of Middle East political discourse is an
encouraging sign _ evidence negotiations with Israel are entering
another crucial stage, perhaps even the end game.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat always winks at _ and may even order _ such
rioting until the casualties and chaos have proved anew the
dangerous itch of Palestinian ``frustration.'' Then he clamps down,
additionally proving anew, too, that only he can control the
menace.
</P>
<P>
   That seems the case again now, and Israel, also following the
script, has temporarily shut down promising off-site negotiations
that were narrowing the negotiating differences.
</P>
<P>
   By increments, something over 95 percent of the Palestinian
population already has come under control of the Palestinian
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Barak administration had even signaled the potential for a
deal over the hypersensitive issue of Jerusalem, tendering
unilaterally to cede Abu Dis and two other Palestinian villages on
the edge of the city. The offer, now on hold, strongly implied that
any new Palestinian state could claim part of an expanded Jerusalem
as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israel's (again) unilateral withdrawal from southern
Lebanon was gratuitously harried by extremist Hezbollah fighters,
unhelpfully undermining, at least with the Israeli population,
another broad gesture toward regional reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Israel blundered in 1982 when, instead of settling for cleaning
out the terrorist ministate Lebanon had been unable to keep from
developing on Israel's northern border, Israel sent its forces
roaring on toward Beirut in hopes of installing a puppet government
that would sign a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been mired since, and periodically bloodied, in the
narrow, supposed security zone that was all it could maintain
against contrary international pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, with some 35,000 troops stationed there, is the hand
inside the Lebanese glove. When Lebanon's fingers wiggle, it is
Damascus wiggling them. And it is Syria again when those fingers
ball into a fist, as they are doing now.
</P>
<P>
   Syria could have made sure that regular Lebanese army troops
filled the Israeli vacuum in southern Lebanon, a relative
reassurance that the area would not again become a launch site for
attacks on northern Israeli communities.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian President Hafez Assad prefers, for domestic reasons, to
keep the tension taut, even so far snubbing a de facto Israeli
offer to return the Golan Heights to Syria in exchange for full
diplomatic and economic relations_ hard goods for soft.
</P>
<P>
   Still, neither that tension nor the upheavals in the West Bank
mean negotiations are forlorn. In the Middle East, these are the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a Cox Newspapers columnist. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
