<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BARGAINS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AMMUNITION FOR DEAL HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARCIA RUFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who sell new cars like to start negotiating at the
sticker price. But savvy consumers know that it makes more sense to
bargain up from the invoice, or wholesale, price. If you don't know
the number on the invoice, you're just not trying; the figures are
ubiquitous in car buyers' guides and on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the invoice price when they start haggling end up
with deals that run $1,700 less, on average, than the salesperson's
first offer, according to a recent Consumer Reports survey.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even more price information is available, thanks to the
Internet, and the invoice is only the visible floor of the deal.
Beneath it are other sources of dealer profit that buyers can try
to tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were walking in and saying, `How much over invoice will
you sell me this car for?' and that wasn't getting them the
dealer's best offer,'' said Paige Amidon, director of Consumer
Reports' car price service.
</P>
<P>
   To get an approximation of the dealership's true cost for a
vehicle, one should also take into account two pots of money that
carmakers pay to dealers: sales incentives and holdbacks. By
subtracting these figures from the invoice, one comes closer to the
actual price that the dealer paid for the car.
</P>
<P>
   The holdback is money that is intended to help cover the
dealer's interest expense. Dealers, who must pay for cars when they
are ordered, not when they are sold, carry loans to cover their
inventory. By longstanding arrangement, most carmakers pay dealers
a percentage of the invoice price, usually from 2 to 3 percent, to
cover interest charges for the first 90 days. Automakers who pay 3
percent, for example, give a dealer $600 for a car with an invoice
of $20,000. Dealers get the same amount whether the car sells in
three days or three months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, carmakers offer incentives to dealers just as they
do to consumers to help move sluggish-selling models or to clear
out inventories. If, as the 2000 models rolled in, a 1999 model
carried a $1,000 manufacturer rebate for the customer, the older
car might have carried a $1,000 rebate for the dealer, too. These
incentives, for both customers and dealers, usually have expiration
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Dealer incentive information has been available in industry
journals like Automotive News for years, but it is now more
accessible to consumers. Edmunds, a company that has provided
automotive information for decades, has offered incentive and
holdback information without charge on its Web site
(www.edmunds.com) since 1996; those who want to save time seeking
this and other information can get a detailed report on a specific
model for $9.95. This spring, Consumer Reports started including
dealer holdbacks and incentives in calculating the bottom-line
price for a car in its new-car price reports. These sell for $12
each ($10 for additional reports ordered at the same time), and can
be obtained at www.consumerreports.org or by calling (800)
205-2445.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Wells, chairman of the National Automobile Dealers
Association, who is a General Motors and Chrysler dealer in
Whiteville, N.C., reluctantly accepts the reality that more price
information is available to consumers, but laments that too often
customers come in with outdated information. That, he says, adds to
mistrust when salespeople disagree with customers' figures.
</P>
<P>
   The experts agree that you should confirm the pricing as soon as
possible to the time to negotiations, because automakers are
shuffling incentives, prices and even holdback amounts more than
ever in their efforts to grab market share.
</P>
<P>
   How close can you get to this rock-bottom price? Bargaining
skills aside, strong demand keeps prices high. If you want a
popular model, expect to pay sticker price, or close to it. ``But
by showing you are aware of these factors, you can make the process
more businesslike,'' Amidon said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
