<HEADER>
A6617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-$ADV28-     05-26 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR U.S. SOLDIERS, KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING IS A DRAG AND AN HONOR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMENICE, Yugoslavia _ The radio crackle broke the late
afternoon stillness across the rolling wheat fields of eastern
Kosovo with bad news for U.S. peacekeeper Lt. Col. Jim Brown: an
81-year-old Serb man had been shot dead by two Albanian suspects.
</P>
<P>
   For Brown, from the Army's 1st Infantry Division, his daily road
patrols as part of NATO's peacekeeping force in Kosovo, called
K-FOR, resembles his usual life as a military police commander at
his home base in Hanau, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like a history of handling domestic disputes and petty
crime calls for preparing you for a mission as a peacekeeper,'' he
told a visitor, as he turned his three Humvee convoy toward the
town of Kamenice, 23 miles west of the Kosovo-Serbia border, to
investigate the murder.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the 5,500 U.S. soldiers taking part in the
multinational K-FOR force securing peace in the southern Yugoslav
province after last year's bombing campaign aren't cops,
law-enforcement duties comprise most of the day-to-day activities
for troops.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an assignment that U.S. soldiers say is partly a
drag and partly an honor, but typical of the complexities an
American soldier faces during times of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are contributing to peace here, no doubt about it, so in
that sense we're fulfilling an important mission,'' said Staff Sgt.
Christopher Callan of Newport, R.I. ``But, I was trained as an
infantryman ... not to apprehend robbers or stop traffic accidents,
which is what I do day-to-day in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of repression under Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's government, intense fighting erupted in mid-1998
between the Serb-dominated Yugoslav army and the separatist rebels
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA _ a group of ethnic Albanian
Kosovars fighting to win Kosovo's independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav military reprisals aimed at trying to root out the KLA
soon turned to attacks on Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority, and
thousands of people being burned out of their homes by Serb
paramilitary groups. The United States, unable to halt the fighting
during talks with the Milosevic government, last spring led a
devastating 78-day NATO bombing campaign of Yugoslavia, which beat
back the Serb army and allowed hundreds of thousands of Kosovar
Albanians to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the international community has worked to rebuild
the tattered Kosovo region and repair ethnic relations between
Kosovar Albanians and the minority Serb population. The
39,000-large K-FOR force has been the integral factor in
maintaining peace while the United Nations works to get civic
institutions like the police and judiciary system working.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. forces took command of Kosovo's east region, maintaining
road patrols throughout the hilly territory, foot patrols in each
town and village, and observation and checkpoints along the border
with Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the simmering tensions that still exist in mixed
communities, the U.S. sector has gained a reputation as being one
of the safest in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the sight of a U.S. patrol instantly commands respect
along the dusty streets of Gjilane, a town of 34,000 where Sgt.
Callan's platoon is responsible for maintaining order. Unlike other
NATO countries, U.S. Army regulations call for all patrols to wear
battle helmets and flak jackets and keep their automatic rifles at
the ready while on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Only once has a U.S. patrol come under attack from the local
community. On April 4, a squad of MPs arrived in the village of
Vitina to break up a riot staged by Albanians. The troops waded
into the fray, receiving hits from the crowd armed with sticks and
stones. Ten peacekeepers were injured, none seriously, before they
dispersed the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge disappointment. We spent months building trust,
and we saw it break down that day,'' said Lt. Col. Brown, who was
hit in the back of the head with a piece of wood and almost knocked
out by the blow.
</P>
<P>
   In Gjilane, a town with a mixed population of Serbs and
Albanians, the situation is less tense one year after the U.S.
soldiers arrived. In one neighborhood where Serbs still live next
to Albanians, the U.S. soldiers have nicknamed a road ``Tea
Street,'' because the residents always invite the troops into their
shady yards to drink tea and relax.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical 10-hour patrol, Pvt. Edward Karolasz of Kearny,
N.J., who just completed basic training before shipping out to
Kosovo, says he spends more time high-fiving little kids than
observing crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love us. The kids run out an shout 'NA-TO! NA-TO!' as we
walk by. How cool is that?'' Karolasz said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Callan says one year into the peacekeeping mission, it's
boredom, not violence, that is the biggest threat to his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a simple routine. We patrol, eat chow, work out, then
do it again the next day,'' he said. ``When we leave here, we are
going to have to spend time relearning some basic skills.''
</P>
<P>
   2nd Lt. Ady(CQ) Velasco, from Las Vegas, says his biggest
complaint is with the leave policy for U.S. soldiers assigned in
Kosovo. Unlike other militaries serving in the NATO-led
peacekeeping mission, American soldiers don't get any leave,
serving for as long as seven months in Kosovo without a break. The
troops are practically confined to the U.S. base, Camp Bondsteel,
and are forbidden from eating in local restaurants or drinking
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joke there are two prisons in the (U.S.-controlled) East
Sector,'' said Lt. Ian Fitzgerald. ``One is the detention center
for locals who have committed crimes and one is Bondsteel itself.''
</P>
<P>
   While many in Washington dispute whether U.S. soldiers should be
participating in K-FOR, U.S. troops interviewed here last week(CQ)
expressed agreement with the recent vote in the U.S. Senate not to
limit the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   K-FOR soldiers act in tandem with the nascent U.N. police force,
made up of officers from U.N. countries as well as local Albanian
and Serb officers. Currently, the police force is only
half-staffed, and K-FOR troops fulfill many tasks the police will
take over in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In the east sector, this transition is underway.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the scene here in Kamenice where the old man was
murdered, Lt. Col. Brown found the U.N. Police had already handled
the initial investigation and were pursuing two suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Brown described the shooting as an aberration, saying hate
crimes and violent ethnic attacks have dropped considerably over
the last year, mostly due to the fact that a steady trickle of Serb
families have left their homes in eastern Kosovo to live with
relatives to the north in Serbia. This has left fewer targets for
Albanian extremists intent on revenge attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Callan says the exodus of Serb communities is an
unfortunate, but highly probable, development in the near future.
While this makes life more peaceful on the streets and for his
patrol, sustained peace, he says, is a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Serbs) feel safe and walk around freely only because we
are here. One year isn't enough to patch things up in this part of
the world. These two communities have enough hate for each other
that if we leave, we'll see war here again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.kforonline.com/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
