<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-0527-C     05-26 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW CHOICES FACE MIDDLE EAST AFTER ISRAEL'S LEBANON WITHDRAWAL
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Eight centuries after crusader knights in
armor guarded its thick stone walls, the hilltop Beaufort castle of
southern Lebanon has fallen again.
</P>
<P>
   Beaufort was a mainstay of the Israeli army's two-decades
occupation in southern Lebanon until Wednesday. Now, a Hezbollah
flag flies there.
</P>
<P>
   As with every great turn of the Middle East, there will be new
peril and promise for its sheiks, presidents and generals _ and for
the envoys there from the West.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations troops moved into the south Friday to help ensure
order. They also began checking maps to see if Israel's withdrawal
was complete.
</P>
<P>
   They say Lebanon will support their ruling, important because
Lebanon so far still claims ownership of an Israeli-held piece of
unpopulated land, the Chibaa Farms.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal was a campaign promise of Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak. But prompted by the collapse of the South Lebanon Army,
which Israel had paid to be its barrier against the hostile local
population, the planned withdrawal came more than a month ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The international boundaries are not entirely clear and there is
no peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   While there is still some confusion about the details, the
withdrawal has clearly recast the region. Whether it brings peace,
however, depends on how the Middle East's leaders respond.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will have to show his people that air power can defend
them without their so-called ``security zone'' in Lebanon. But, he
will have to do so without the heavy-handed attacks in Lebanon that
have brought international condemnation in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah sheiks will have to decide if they are done fighting
Israel and want to focus on their political activities.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian President Hafez Assad faces new decisions, too, in his
quest to get the Golan Heights back from Israel. Will he seek
leverage by continuing to encourage attacks against Israel by
Hezbollah or other militias in Lebanon? Or, will he see more
benefit in coming back to the negotiating table?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials will be urging all sides to remain calm. They
want a peace deal before President Bill Clinton, apparently seen as
reliable by both Assad and Barak, leaves office in eight months.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is whether the border between Israel and
Lebanon will be peaceful. It is now lined daily with curious,
angry, and sometimes armed Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   They gawk at the Israeli towns and army patrols on the other
side of the fence. Those towns in the past have been frequent
targets for Hezbollah Katyusha rockets.
</P>
<P>
   For now, neither side wants to disturb the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have some sort of balance of terror, a sort of cold
war between Israel and Syria,'' said American University of Beirut
political scientist Nizar Hamzeh. ``Israel definitely has more
power but Hezbollah has the Katyushas.''
</P>
<P>
   The key is Hezbollah's 39-year-old, charismatic, leader Sheik
Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
   Nasrallah met with foreign journalists Thursday. It was in the
type of Spartan meeting room, with plastic chairs and peeling white
walls, that has enhanced the group's reputation as uncorrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Cordial and relaxed, Nasrallah basked in what he and others are
calling the first Arab victory over Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But, he was intentionally enigmatic about Hezbollah's next move.
</P>
<P>
   He said Hezbollah would keep attacking Israeli troops until
Israel vacated the disputed Chibaa Farms area and released war
prisoners. He said Hezbollah's victory should convince Palestinians
to drop their peace process with Israel and adopt armed resistance.
</P>
<P>
   But, he also said Hezbollah would not hurt civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any intention to attack civilians. But not all
Israelis are civilians,'' he said. ``Anything is possible, but in
regard to civilians we are extremely careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Israel and the SLA have killed far more Lebanese
civilians than Hezbollah has killed Israeli civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah might not want to risk Israeli reprisals that could
endanger its victory or anger Lebanese. Nasrallah is not just
concerned with rockets. He's also counting votes and Hezbollah's
popularity is soaring.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its guerrilla force, it runs hospitals and
schools and has seven members in the Lebanese parliament.
</P>
<P>
   With its ``liberation'' of south Lebanon, it surely won votes
for parliamentary elections in August. It had already moved three
mobile medical clinics into the south by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say that the platform for the parliament is
beginning today,'' Hamzeh, the political analyst, said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Barak is also basking in victory. A Gallup poll of
Israelis conducted Wednesday showed 75 percent supporting the
withdrawal, and Barak with a 54 percent approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He promised and delivered, and it wasn't only an election
slogan,'' wrote columnist Hemi Shalev in the Ma'ariv daily. ``But,
one cannot take away from Barak the fateful moment when he assumed
responsibility and made a decision. The end result may not yet have
been tested, but he has already passed the test of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   On trips throughout nervous northern Israel following the
withdrawal, Barak tried to explain how he would keep Israel safe
despite the Hezbollah troops at the border fence.
</P>
<P>
   Now, air power, without ground troops, compose the deterrence
against attacks. The strikes could be against Hezbollah or its
Syrian backers in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No target and no element of power in Lebanon will be immune to
a painful reprisal. Without our presence on Lebanese soil, there is
no restriction to a harsh reaction to aggression,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   While threatening Syria, Barak still hopes for the peace deal
with President Assad that is needed to truly bring peace to
Israel's northern border. Israel has given vague offers to give up
the strategic Golan Heights. Syria rejected the deal, saying it had
not been assured the Golan withdrawal would be complete.
</P>
<P>
   Assad could still use Hezbollah to exert pressure on Israel.
Sheikh Nasrallah said that Hezbollah owes Syria help in winning the
Golan.
</P>
<P>
   But, given Barak's warnings of reprisals and the lack of Israeli
targets in his backyard of Lebanon, Assad may opt to get what he
can through negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, who have tried hard to woo Assad back to the
negotiating table, have made it clear that they will blame Assad
for violence in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   One player in the arena, at least, is finished. The South
Lebanon Army has dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 SLA fighters have turned themselves over to Lebanese
officials, who will try them as traitors. About 6,000 SLA fighters
and their families were refugees in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   SLA commander, Gen. Antoine Lahad reportedly told an Israeli
newspaper that he felt ``conned'' by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is over, as far as I'm concerned. Don't call me
'general' any more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials later said that Lahad denied making those
comments, but by then he was headed to his home and family in
France.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: at larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.dailystar.com.lb, for the Daily Star newspaper of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
