<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-ACKERMAN-ART-NYT &LR;      05-26 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ACKERMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEAGUE PRESIDENT IN THE DREAMS BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a girl, thinking about what she would be when she
grew up, Val Ackerman just assumed she'd be an athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   After all, her grandfather ran high school and college sports
programs and coached her father's basketball team at Trenton State
College. When she was a teen-ager in Pennington, N.J., playing
field hockey; swimming butterfly and freestyle; competing in track
and field; and emerging as a star small forward in basketball, her
father was her high school's athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described tomboy and daddy's girl, Ackerman, 40, has
indeed kept up the family tradition, though in a way she could not
have imagined when she was decorating her teen-age bedroom with
posters of her sports heroes, John Havlicek and Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   For Ackerman has the ultimate athletic director's job, as
president of the Women's National Basketball Association, the
league she worked exhaustively to create. The WNBA, which expands
to 16 teams this year, begins its fourth season Monday in Houston,
with the Comets playing the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Having been team captain for three years at the University of
Virginia and then spending a year on a French team before she went
to law school at UCLA, Ackerman is also currently the only head of
a professional major league who has actually played its sport.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you been called intense, Ackerman?
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly the impression she conveys, sitting in her
Midtown office, speaking in bursts, her lanky limbs perpetually
shifting, long fingers gripping, twirling, flipping a basketball,
never losing control.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 100 million,'' she says, adding, ``But I'm a nice
person, too,'' and blushes, embarrassed at owning up.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that despite the magnitude of her accomplishments _
her boss, David Stern, commissioner of the NBA, which owns the
WNBA, has no trouble giving her most of the credit for what has
become the most successful of the 15 efforts to start a
professional women's basketball league since 1974 _ Ackerman has
difficulty taking credit for much, unless, like a sports statistic,
it is irrefutable. (``I was the top scorer my sophomore year.'')
</P>
<P>
   She uses ``we'' a lot as she recalls the early days when, as a
lawyer for the NBA, she harangued her company and USA Basketball to
join forces to build a women's Dream Team, which played together
for a year (52-0!) before storming the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
``We'' dominates the telling of how she persuaded Stern, team
owners, sponsors and networks that plenty of fans _ 2.5 million
expected to attend this summer _ believed a women's league was
worth shouting about.
</P>
<P>
   So why not say ``I,'' Ackerman? Is she just cautious, mindful of
corporate egos?
</P>
<P>
   The question startles her. Her reticence isn't about being savvy
and political, she says. Instead, she says, what she's gleaned from
sports as a leader of teams rather than, say, a golfer, is
collaboration. Taking sole credit seems anathema.
</P>
<P>
   ``And couldn't some of it be just shyness and modesty?'' she
says, flushing.
</P>
<P>
   Work with us, Ackerman. What can we say you did?
</P>
<P>
   She hesitates. ``I helped choose the colors of the WNBA
basketball,'' she offers at last, holding aloft the
orange-and-white object in question.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say she's a pushover. Ackerman's league, backed
by NBA millions, prevailed even as the rival American Basketball
League, which had a winter season, and better-paid and arguably
more stellar players, folded in December 1998. (``They were a
mom-and-pop operation and made some bad business decisions,'' she
says.)
</P>
<P>
   And she went head-to-head last year with union negotiators for
WNBA players in their first collective bargaining effort. As a
former player herself who had become the epitome of management, she
grew haggard trying to create a contract that would be fair to her
sister athletes even as she had to watch the bottom line of a
league that still operates solidly in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when asked about the dearth of female coaches in the league,
the modest salaries and short season, she answers like a careful
lawyer, invoking ``the need for patience.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the May/June swimsuit issue of Sports
Illustrated for Women, with a cover showing the WNBA star Lisa
Leslie in a midriff-baring suit, Ackerman, the mother of two young
daughters, mutters something about healthy body images versus
objectifying women athletes. She does not look happy.
</P>
<P>
   She prefers to dwell on the league's accomplishments. Noting
that 75 percent of arena fans are female, she says, ``We're not
just entertainment,'' the league represents something deeper. She
tells a story: in Charlotte, N.C., a 10-year-old girl, wide-eyed,
eager, asked for her autograph. A man watched intently. ``You must
be the dad, you must be proud,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, he wrote, thanking her. ``He said that at WNBA
games he found time and a way to bond with his daughter,'' Ackerman
says, ``and that becoming a fan of women players had increased her
self-esteem. And I thought: `Whoa! That is overwhelming to me!'''
</P>
<P>
   So, Ackerman, how would you describe your role in women's
basketball?
</P>
<P>
   She grins, shyly. ``I've been a beneficiary of it,'' she says,
``and a catalyst, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
