<SLUG> BC-ALCON-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NESTLE'S ALCON TO BUY SUMMIT AUTONOMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alcon Laboratories, the eye care unit of food giant Nestle
(NSRGY:Nasdaq ADR), announced Friday that it will buy laser eye
surgery concern Summit Autonomous (BEAM:Nasdaq) for $892.8 million
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The move gives Alcon entree into the laser eye surgery market,
which is fast growing in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Alcon will pay $19 for each
outstanding share of Summit. That's a premium of 50 percent to
Summit's closing price Thursday of 12 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Alcon makes eye care products such as eye drops, contact lens
solutions and office systems for opthamologists and optometrists.
Meanwhile, Summit, based in Waltham, Mass., develops and
manufactures the laser systems used to correct faulty vision. Last
year, the company bought Autonomous Technologies, which develops
the lasers used in eye surgery. Summit is the No. 2 maker of eye
lasers behind Visx (VISX:Nasdaq).
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-based Alcon's name has also been bandied about of
late as a possible third party to swoop in and buy Wesley Jessen
VisionCare (WJCO:Nasdaq) and Ocular Sciences (OCLR:Nasdaq). The two
contact lens makers agreed to a merger in March only to have Bausch
&AMP; Lomb (BOL:NYSE) come in days later with an offer for Wesley
Jessen alone.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Summit soared 46 percent, or 5 7/8, to 18 9/16 in
Friday afternoon trading. There was no action in Nestle's American
depositary receipts.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
