<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTEREST0527-COX     05-26 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEREST0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fixed-rate mortgage interest drops after recent increases
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first time this month, long-term, fixed-rate
mortgage interest rates stopped climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates on the 30-year and 15-year loans in metro Atlanta
dropped an average three basis points each this week from last
week. The 30-year mortgage averaged 8.30 percent, down from 8.33
percent; the 15-year loan averaged 7.99 percent, down from 8.02
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the one-year, adjustable-rate loan was again up, at 7.14
percent, vs. last week's 7.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rates more than a percentage point higher than this time
last year, the Atlanta housing market continues to be strong, said
Pat Flood, president of HomeBanc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home buying is far more linked to employment than to interest
rates. Look at 1994, when rates were down at 7 percent. We did not
have a real active housing market because we were just coming out
of a recession and people were afraid to buy, even with low rates,
because they still felt their jobs might go. Right now, employment
in Atlanta could hardly be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank Rate Monitor, which tracks mortgage rates, reported that
the 30-year loan carried an average of 0.76 discount points, while
the 15-year mortgage had 0.73 points. The ARM had 0.23 points. A
point, 1 percent of the loan amount, is a fee lenders charge at
closing.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD PLAN DESIGNED TO PROTECT HOMEOWNERS
</P>
<P>
   Tale after tale of predatory lending has documented how home
buyers have been lured into taking loans they cannot afford on
houses not worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   One of many agencies now interested in the problem is the
Department of Housing and Urban Development. It has come up with a
Fraud Protection Plan designed to shield the unwary from predatory
lenders. The plan, which resulted from forums held in several
cities this year, aims to protect families that get new mortgages
insured by the Federal Housing Authority, a HUD agency.
</P>
<P>
   The problem largely has been caused by good news, the booming
housing market that characterizes many U.S. cities, observed HUD
spokesman Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Predatory lending has gotten so big so quickly and so
explosively that we have to move very fast to get ahead of it,''
Jones said Thursday. ``Especially in hot markets like Atlanta, a
lot of people want to buy,'' and a lot of banks want to help them _
even unscrupulous ones.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jones, HUD already has regulatory authority to
impose sanctions on dishonest lenders and home appraisers, and it
will ask Congress to pass laws to cover the entire market, not just
FHA-insured homes.
</P>
<P>
   Elements of the plan, which will be funded from the FHA's
general budget, include:
</P>
<P>
   _ If a mortgage is based on a fraudulent appraisal, the FHA can
force the lender to rewrite it, based on true market value.
</P>
<P>
   _ Homeowners in danger of foreclosure will have access to free
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   _ The FHA will cap fees to prevent lenders from charging
unreasonably high points and closing costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a homeowner goes into default because of a predatory loan,
the FHA can make the lender issue a ``credit repair letter.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The FHA would refuse to insure flipped properties, or those
bought out of foreclosure and then resold at an inflated price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
