<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CARUSO-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HAPPIEST GUY AT THE MAXIMUM GOLF PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 28) 
 By ANTHONY LAPPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early Tuesday night, at a party for Maximum Golf, a
new magazine dedicated to the proposition that golf is a
beer-and-babes kind of sport, Michael Caruso could have used a
mulligan. The skies above the Central Park boathouse were
threatening rain. Guests were arriving, as frantic workers were
still constructing a 100-foot AstroTurf green, on which partygoers
would be given the chance to putt for what seems to be the only way
to get attention these days: a $1 million cash prize. Caruso, the
magazine's founder and editor in chief, had first planned for the
green to be floating on an artificial island in Central Park Lake.
But chipping balls into the water was not approved by the Parks
Department, resulting in last-minute chaos. The beleaguered editor
sidled up to the bar. ``Sorry, Buddy, the bar doesn't open for five
minutes,'' the bartender told him.
</P>
<P>
   Caruso smiled weakly. ``Throwing this party has been way more
difficult than launching the magazine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, he is used to rolling with punches. Maximum Golf is
the third magazine Caruso has edited; he left Los Angeles Magazine
during a dispute with its owner, Disney, over journalistic
standards, and he was fired as editor of Details last year, shortly
after boasting to The New York Post that he had raised circulation
and advertising so much he would soon get ``a big fat raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that he is having the last laugh. Under his
successor, Conde Nast pulled the plug on Details, and Caruso, 38,
has convinced Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. to finance his quirky
idea for a gonzo golf book. The first issue includes an expose by
Sylvester Stallone's estranged golf coach and a photo layout of
Melania Knauss naked in a bathtub of golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   Knauss looked as if she would rather be back in that tub as she
huddled for a photo with Caruso, Donald J. Trump and Isaac Hayes,
as a cold drizzle fell. The smiles disappeared as soon as the
camera flashes stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Caruso told Hayes that he was a fan of his work on ``Shaft'' and
``South Park.'' Hayes almost never plays golf. ``I just knock balls
into the water,'' he said. ``Jim Brown told me you are playing
against yourself. You have to block the rest of the world out.''
</P>
<P>
   It must be like performing in a concert, Caruso told him. Hayes
agreed. You get into a groove.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the party was supposed to be an appearance by a
3-year-old golf prodigy, but the child missed two six-foot putts
and ran into his mother's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Very little of the party focused on golf, or even Maximum Golf.
Among the nearly 1,000 people who turned up, there were many
friends, loyal former colleagues such as Tina Brown and family
members of Caruso. ``It's like a bar mitzvah,'' said Hilary Bass,
the publicity director for Talk Media.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the editor's fortunes changed.
</P>
<P>
   Caruso, who had begun to utter the mantra, ``I'm loving the
rain,'' was talking with his parents when Woody Harford, a
19-handicap marketing executive at British Airways, sunk the $1
million putt, sending the party into a frenzy. As guests chanted
``Woody! Woody!'' Caruso hugged the surprisingly nonchalant
Harford. ``I am the second happiest guy at this party,'' Caruso
said, explaining that he had taken an insurance policy out against
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Caruso moved the party downtown to Odeon. At 2 a.m.,
a final toast was made to ``Maximum Caruso.'' Caruso grabbed an
umbrella and began flagging taxis for friends. He was the last one
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
