<HEADLINE>
EARLY CLOSING OF UNIVERSITIES PROTESTED IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Several thousand students, teachers and
parents rallied Friday to protest the closing of universities a
week early by the government of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Under a decree issued Thursday by the Serbian minister for
higher education, Jevrem Janjic, Friday was the last day such a
rally could be held on university property. After Friday, students
and teachers will be allowed to enter their departments only for
final examinations, with their identity documents checked at the
door.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally Friday, in a crowded pedestrian space in front of
the Faculty of Philosophy, student activists of the Otpor, or
Resistance, movement and professors sympathetic to the political
opposition charged that the government was afraid of the students
and was acting illegally to shorten the school year and avoid a
student strike.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to the beating Tuesday night of several students
who had intended to stay the night in protest at the architecture
department. But when they ignored a janitor's demand that they
leave, the lights for the entire street were shut off and men in
surgical masks drove them out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rally is a general protest against everything that is
happening in this country, repression, media darkness, beating of
students,'' said an architecture student named Marko, 21, who was
in the school when the masked men came.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go anywhere we must to awaken a sleepy Belgrade,''
said Branko Ilic, an Otpor activist, who urged students to raise
their fists _ the Otpor symbol _ to show that ``you are not afraid
of the state of emergency'' and will gather again at the university
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Stevan Lilic, a law professor and member of the political
opposition, said the latest decree was a continuation of the law on
universities that put faculties under the state and has resulted in
the firings or forced resignations of nearly 200 professors in the
last three years.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lilic is the target of a campaign to fire him led by the Serbian
deputy prime minister, Vojislav Seselj, who was recently made a
professor of the law school. ``This is political intimidation and
an effort to threaten the faculty, and the reason for it is the
student protest movement, Otpor,'' Lilic said. He said he had
criticized his dean for not defending him against Seselj's threats,
which he said included having thugs follow him in the street.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Police officers watched the rally but did not interfere. Some
students later marched on Belgrade's city hall, demanding that
Serbia's political opposition act more vigorously to protest the
government's latest actions to shut the university, take Belgrade's
main television station, Studio B, from the opposition and carry
out a series of detentions of student and political activists
across Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has called a rally for Saturday in downtown
Belgrade and is hoping for a large turnout from all over Serbia.
The opposition political leaders have disagreed on the need for
stronger action, like civil disobedience. They are struggling for a
platform that might emphasize more than unity and the need to
prepare for the local and federal elections that are due later this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   They will hold down the number of speakers at the rally and
include speakers from Otpor and well-known personalities from
Serbian life to try to give the rally a fresh feel. But it will be
difficult for them to articulate a clear strategy of action that
will answer criticism that the opposition favors the status quo
more than confrontation with the regime.
</P>
<P>
   Three senior opposition politicians, Vuk Draskovic of the
Serbian Renewal Movement, Zoran Djindjic of the Democratic Party
and Vojislav Kostunica of the Democratic Party of Serbia intend to
travel to Moscow on Monday to seek Russian help to mediate with the
regime. But it is still not clear at what level they will meet
Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In general, the authorities' new, harsh push against the
independent media, the opposition and the students _ justified on
the need to keep civic order and fight those who favor revolution _
is also designed to show citizens that ``the state exists and will
defend itself,'' said a senior official of one of the ruling
parties. The official added that ``Studio B could have continued to
spew out political propaganda for Vuk Draskovic forever, but we
could not let calls for armed rebellion be transmitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say they are simply not going to allow the
university buildings _ spread throughout Belgrade _ to become
centers for resistance to the authorities instead of an academy.
They have accused the student movement Otpor of links to the NATO
countries that bombed Serbia and want to replace Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
