<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKER PUSHES BILL TO SPEED MEDICARE BENEFITS FOR AIDS
VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom A. Coburn, R-Okla., has introduced a bill
to eliminate the two-year period that disabled AIDS victims must
wait for Medicare benefits that cover drug therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Coburn's plan, which he introduced Thursday, disabled
people with AIDS who qualify for Social Security Disability
Insurance (SSDI) would immediately get benefits that cover the drug
treatments from Medicare, the federal health insurance plan for the
elderly and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, people with AIDS must wait five months after an
independent team of doctors determines that they are unable to work
before getting SSDI. To qualify, they must have been paying into
the Social Security system for 1  &QC;  to 10 years, depending on their
age.
</P>
<P>
   After qualifying for SSDI, disabled AIDS victims then must wait
an additional 24 months to get Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said Friday that people with AIDS and HIV, the virus that
causes the deadly disease, should not have to wait that long to get
treatments that can improve and prolong their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will help make AIDS a chronic disease rather than a
death sentence for patients with HIV/AIDS,'' Coburn said. ``By the
time individuals infected with HIV/AIDS can access proper treatment
it's too little too late.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no matching legislation has been introduced in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's press secretary, John Hart, said no groups have yet
opposed the bill. The Congressional Budget Office has not yet
estimated its cost.
</P>
<P>
   Terje Anderson, executive director of the National Association
of People with AIDS, a national advocacy group, hailed the measure
as a ``great bill'' that could help HIV and AIDS victims pay for
combination-drug therapy that costs as much as $12,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provides a safety net for people who have a fair amount
of work history, have been paying into the system and are disabled
but not poor enough to be eligible for Medicaid,'' Anderson said.
``If this were passed, a lot of people with HIV would benefit from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, the state and federal medical plan for the poor, also
covers the costs of drug therapies, but recipients need to be near
the poverty line, which is an annual income of $8,350 for one
person.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Stachelberg, political director for the Human Rights
Campaign, a Washington advocacy group for gays and lesbians, called
the plan crafted by Coburn, who is also an obstetrician, a ``a real
step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Stachelberg added, ``This is absolutely Dr. Tom Coburn at his
best. He understands that a 24-month waiting period for Medicare
benefits for people with AIDS is ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-JUDITH-KRANTZ-SHOP-$A     05-26 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDITH-KRANTZ-SHOP-$ADV28-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDITH KRANTZ: FROM CINDERELLA TO CHANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judith Krantz may live in Bel Air, but she's a New
York girl by birth and by temperament.
</P>
<P>
   When she still lived in Manhattan, in 1962, she despaired of
being able to glimpse John Glenn, the first American to orbit
Earth, in a Fifth Avenue parade being held in his honor. So, she
went to Saks, secured a corner dressing room with windows in the
maternity department, and bought a king's ransom worth of clothes
she didn't need in order to eyeball her idol. But when she returned
her enormous purchase a few days later, Saks balked and canceled
her account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't possibly do without a Saks charge,'' she said last
week, back at Saks, whipping through racks of Yves Saint Laurent.
``I wrote them and told them I had a miscarriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Krantz, 72, recalls the fib in her new memoir, ``Sex and
Shopping: The Confessions of a Nice Jewish Girl'' (St. Martin's).
She writes: ``Another step toward fiction? What's a short girl to
do?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This short girl _ 5 feet 2{ inches, she says _ has done just
fine. (Yes, her credit was reinstated.) Although she waited until
her two sons were grown before publishing her first novel, at 50,
the best-selling ``Scruples,'' she has published nine more best
sellers in the last 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Her books transcend the Hollywood gloss of a Jackie Collins, the
smarmy heat of a Danielle Steel. Rather, this Wellesley graduate
does diligent homework on all aspects of the fashion business, and
often the art, antiques and jewelry trades, spinning intricate
plots jammed with industry details, which also offer inside looks
at worlds of high-octane glamour. In today's runaway economy
they've taken on a practical dimension: a woman's guide to rubies
and Renoir.
</P>
<P>
   If Krantz's books celebrating Porthault sheets and the women who
love them seem oddly in style right now, their timeless appeal lies
in their compelling Cinderella stories. A Judith Krantz heroine is
beautiful but also smart, smart, smart. She learns a business along
with the reader as she works night and day, overcomes emotional
hardships (which only add depth to her natural beauty), and
eventually, with the aid of a handsome, powerful man and the
perfect Hermes bag, triumphs. No one whines. They act. The world
bursts with possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It's a winning formula. Her books have sold 85 million copies in
52 languages. ``The boys gang has always resented me,'' she said.
``Sidney Sheldon, Irving Wallace, Harold Robbins. It was like `How
dare she do that?' Being from Hollywood, the press would describe
my house as a mansion when it's a perfectly normal house. They made
me the glamorous character from my novels, but those characters
were written by someone in J.Crew sweats who's not glamorous at
all.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not when she's writing, but she was certainly
turning heads at Saks. Though she said she was ``out of uniform''
by not wearing Chanel, she was flawlessly dressed in a pink and
gray tweed pantsuit with a matching coat, custom made by a Milanese
tailor. The Van Cleef &AMP; Arpels Bois de Rose, a white coral pin in
the shape of a flower with diamonds at the center, reflected the
luster of her South Seas pearl earrings and _ just as they do in
her books _ seemed to add a glow to her ivory complexion. As she
tore through the meager offerings of Gucci and Fendi with the sharp
eye of a military commander, the sales staff instinctively stood
back. They, not to mention their merchandise, were distinctly
outclassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now look at that,'' Krantz fumed, holding up a transparent
lime green Fendi skirt and top. ``Tell me, have you ever seen a
woman in a restaurant in a transparent top? Well, me neither.''
</P>
<P>
   Gucci fared no better. ``That is the worst knocked-off thing,''
she said, fingering a python print dress. ``And the length is
wrong. The fitter at Chanel will always say, `Mrs. Krantz, hemlines
are going down.' But I don't care. My skirts stay 19 inches from
the floor. That's what looks best on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Krantz is a clothes connoisseur, it is a mistake to think
her books are about shopping, even though ``Scruples'' was the name
of a fashion boutique. They are instead about the transforming
power of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always use clothes for manipulation, to create an effect,''
she explained earlier at lunch at Le Cirque 2000. ``With the right
clothes, the character suddenly appears. In many cases, the clothes
reveal a personality that was obscured by poverty. I write about
clothes as magical things that can change you. I feel that women
are comforted by having clothes and accessories. I have every scarf
I've ever bought.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Krantz rarely goes shopping. ``I can't stand it,''
she said of going to malls. ``Anyway, California is not a dressed
up place. At every dinner party people wear black, which annoys me.
I don't wear black at night. I want to be more visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her other fashion dictums, Krantz says, she has never worn
jeans or a bikini (unflattering), swears by Hanro lingerie (no
seams) and thinks that as an accessory ``burgundy is the best
neutral.'' She also declares that she doesn't ``believe in plastic
surgery below the neck'' because people should diet and exercise.
What about breasts? She shrugged. ``So they droop,'' she said.
``Certain things just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Perched on a banquette in the restaurant, her coat bundled
behind her, the writer in Krantz took over from the strident
fashion expert. She appeared small and tentative as she watched
other women parade past, bedecked and bejeweled, as if they were
characters in her books. The closer she observed, the smaller she
seemed to become. You can see why she says that it is the character
of the best friend that reflects her in her books, not the
heroines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heroine bears the burden of the plot and always has
dramatic things happen to her,'' she said. ``Her mother dies, her
father dies, some guy leaves her. The best friend is along for the
ride having a wonderful time, wearing crazy clothes that wouldn't
be becoming to a heroine, who must have a certain dignity and
gravitas. The heroines I create are all bigger than life. But the
best friend is a life-size person.'' She smiled. ``Usually short.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her own outfit matched neither description; it belonged to the
grande dame character, the doyenne who long ago learned the value
of quality. She kept talking as she ate her shad and bacon _
possibly the only woman in the room not picking at a salad _ and
said that flying lessons had prompted her to start writing novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always so afraid to fly, and when I finally learned how,
I think it made me write `Scruples','' she said. ``I thought, What
else am I terrified of doing? Writing fiction. I'm not sure why. I
think I was a victim of a very good education. I majored in English
literature and said, `I know I can't do that, so why do it at all?'
But there is a real place for a book that's not George Eliot but is
still for intelligent women.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Krantz may have waited, she said, was because of
her mother. Mickey Tarcher sounds like a nightmare in Krantz's
memoir, though her independence was certainly exemplary. She
dropped out of school at 14 to work in a candy factory to help
support her family. After she married J.D. Tarcher, who became a
successful advertising executive, she earned her college degree, a
master's in economics and a law degree. She spent her career at the
Legal Aid Society and her time at home raising, and often
criticizing, her daughters, Judy and Mimi, and her son, Jeremy. She
also endured a lifetime of cheating from her husband. When he died
in 1960, she sold the weekend home he loved and its contents within
two days. She dressed her children cheaply, withholding material
rewards as consistently as she withheld emotional ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream was that my mother would come home with a big package
from Best with cashmere sweaters for me,'' Krantz said, her voice
growing full. ``That's where I got the magic of clothes, because my
mother didn't give them to me. If she had, I never would have known
the power, magic and mystery clothes could have. Out of that
yearning you get fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   It is probably no accident that in 10 Judith Krantz novels, six
of her heroines have mothers who die when their daughters are
younger than 8.
</P>
<P>
   In her real life, Krantz has been married to the film and
television producer Steve Krantz for 46 years. Their son Nick is a
stockbroker, their son Tony is the chief executive of Imagine
Television, and the couple have two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, she hasn't started her next novel.
``I have a crazy plan not to do anything and see what happens,''
she said. ``I'd love to do something different, have a life change.
There are so many things I don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, her blue eyes sparkled and the air filled with the
unmistakable sense of possibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
