<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6723 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     05-26 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A PRIVILEGE TO RECOGNIZE THIS COLONEL'S BRAVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disembodied voice of the pilot sounded through the
airplane's announcement system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, we have a distinguished guest flying
with us today. It is my privilege to recognize Medal of Honor
winner Mr. Lewis Millett.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr.'' Millett. What an incredible slight, however
unintentional, to a man who earned this country's highest military
honor for his bravery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scattered applause followed the pilot's introduction of Col.
Lewis L. Millett. Had the other passengers on the flight from
Charlotte, N.C., to Dallas/Fort Worth Airport heard what I had
about this remarkable man during the National Rifle Association's
annual meeting, one hopes that they would have leapt to their feet
in a thunderous ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Too many Americans don't even know what the Medal of Honor is,
much less what it takes to receive it. Is it too much to hope that
on this Memorial Day weekend, some Americans might actually pause
between the barbecues and the sales to think about the people who
made their freedom possible?
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Millett, a true American hero, is one tough old soldier.
The 79-year-old veteran may be slowed by time and may walk with a
cane, but he's still as mentally sharp as the fixed bayonet he used
to lead two platoons in the 1951 assault near Soam-Ni, Korea.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing easy about the mission that lay ahead for the
Wolfhound Regiment's Easy Company that February day. Millett,
leading his company against a fiercely held position, saw that the
1st Platoon was pinned down by enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Millett ordered the 3rd Platoon forward and led both
groups in an assault up the fire-swept hill.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old fighting man from Mechanic Falls, Maine,
bayoneted two enemy soldiers and then continued on, shouting
encouragement to his men while throwing grenades and clubbing and
bayoneting the enemy. He was wounded by grenade fragments but
refused to evacuate until the hill was secured.
</P>
<P>
   Easy Company killed 47 of the enemy that day, while another 60
had reportedly been wounded and evacuated off the hill during the
battle. Of the dead, 18 died of bayonet wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bayonet wounds. They were reportedly a rarity during the Civil
War, when the technology of death was much less sophisticated than
what was available during the Korean War. Imagine what kind of
fighting that must have been.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the high-tech, never-see-your-enemy, impersonal war
of today. This was down-and-dirty, hand-to-hand struggle, where
soldiers not only saw their enemies but looked them right in the
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes that faced down the enemy in 1951 still sparkle as the
man who served his nation during three wars tells his stories. What
you won't read in the official accounts of Millett's bravery, he
willingly tells about himself.
</P>
<P>
   He's the only Medal of Honor recipient to be court-martialed for
desertion.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, Millett joined the National Guard and then enlisted in
the Army Air Corps as an air gunner in 1940. When President
Roosevelt announced that the United States would not intervene
overseas _ and held firm to that until after the bombing of Pearl
Harbor _ Millett bolted for the north.
</P>
<P>
   He was a fighting man who believed in freedom for everyone, not
just Americans. The Canadian army had joined the fray, so Millett
signed on with it.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. brass frowned on his passion.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Millett and the United States, everything worked
out, but not until after he was convicted for desertion.
</P>
<P>
   After Korea, Maj. Millett attended the Infantry Officers
Advanced Course and Ranger School at Fort Benning, Ga. Then he was
assigned to the 101st Airborne Division, where he founded the
Recondo School.
</P>
<P>
   His Vietnam duties included the establishment of the Vietnamese
Ranger School and the commando training program in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Millett retired in 1973 after serving as the deputy
commander of the 2nd Corps. In addition to the Medal of Honor, his
awards include the Distinguished Service Cross, Silver Star, Legion
of Merit (with two oak leaf clusters), Air Medal (with numeral 2),
Purple Heart (with three oak leaf clusters), Vietnamese Cross of
Gallantry and Vietnam Campaign Ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   When asked last week whether he considers himself a hero, he
replied: ``No. I'm a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, colonel. From here, the applause is deafening
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
