<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-MEXICO:SUPER-WIRED-UN     05-26 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO:SUPER-WIRED-UNIVERSITY-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `TEC': THE MIT OF LATIN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives ANA PENA in
New York at 212-499-3333 or fax at 212-499-3382; or KARL HORWITZ in
Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; or New
York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH WEYDERT at
1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By ANDREA MANDEL-CAMPBELL 
 c.2000 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ATIZAPAN, Mexico _ When Rodrigo Sosa first entered the Instituto
Tecnologico two years ago, the 20-year-old industrial engineering
student didn't know how to turn on a computer. Now, from a
sun-dappled picnic bench, the clean-cut sophomore plugs his laptop
into one of 2,300 campus fiber optic hookups to check four e-mail
accounts and several online chat sites. At the same time, he
listens to the guitar licks of the Chemical Brothers, a soundtrack
he downloaded over the net.
 &HT;    Sosa spends between six and seven hours a day in front of his
computer, much of it admittedly playing Starcraft, a virtual
reality war game. Still, he says, his computer has become an
indispensable tool, not only for homework and research but for
finding class schedules, keeping tabs on upcoming assignments and
downloading assigned reading material.
 &HT;    Sosa had little choice but to enter the computer age. He is part
of a new generation of students at ``the Tec,'' perhaps Latin
America's most wired university. In 1997, the Monterrey-based
institution with 85,000 students at its 30 campuses across Mexico
introduced a novel educational approach. Each professor and student
received an e-mail account. They were then connected to ConectaTec,
the campus Internet system, and IntraTec, a second network that can
be accessed from home. These networks, coupled with the
institution's extensive distance-learning program, provide a
massive educational platform.
 &HT;    ``The future is technology and if we prepare our students
properly they will be the future,'' says Emilio Alvarado, general
director of the State of Mexico campus of the Instituto
Tecnologico.
 &HT;    The sprawling 26-hectare university, which is located on the
northern outskirts of Mexico City, affords a glimpse of that
future. In stark contrast to the rest of Mexico, where computers
are found in only 3 percent of homes, desktop computers and laptops
are everywhere _ crammed into bulging backpacks, crowded onto
library desks and sprawled across campus lawns. Some 80 percent of
students own their own computers, of which half are laptops.
 &HT;    In a bid to wire still more students, in January the Tec
introduced at the State of Mexico and Monterrey campuses the
WaveLAN radio card created by Lucent Technologies, making it the
first academic institution in Mexico to adopt the new technology on
a massive scale. The powerful wireless card, which works in
conjunction with 40 antennas stationed around campus, allows
limitless web access to the school's increasingly congested
conventional telephone lines. ``The only place students won't be
able to access the Internet is from the women's bathroom,'' jokes
Alexander Baber, regional director of business partnerships for
Lucent Technologies in Mexico.
 &HT;    The card will also give students the opportunity to connect to
the campus' new Internet portal, also launched in January, which
offers everything from news and weather to a search engine.
E-commerce will follow once the school receives approval from a
local bank to do online transactions.
 &HT;    The new portal is just the latest in the school's recent history
of innovations. In the 1990s, its Internet department designed web
pages for the office of the presidency, the federal Congress, the
environment ministry and Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex), the
state-owned oil company. Just this year, it started the use of a
smart card ID that can be used to monitor staff attendance or make
campus purchases.
 &HT;    Mexican businessman Eugenio Garza Sada, the former head of a
powerful industrial conglomerate known as the Monterrey Group,
founded the Instituto Tecnologico de Monterrey in 1943. In 1950,
the Tec became the first academic institution in the region to be
accredited by the U.S. Southern Association of Colleges and
Schools. In 1963, it purchased its first computer, and by 1980
began offering undergraduate degrees in computer science.
 &HT;    In 1994, the Mexico State branch created the school's first
computer laboratories and soon became the testing ground for the
local version of Microsoft Windows 95. Six years later, the campus
boasts 15 computer laboratories with 400 computers _ including a
new facility donated by Intel in January dedicated to e-commerce.
That lab, which includes 15 computers sporting Microsoft's
e-commerce software and another 15 with IBM's Internet commerce
program, is part of a master's degree in e-commerce introduced in
1998 that teaches students everything from designing a virtual
store to strategy and logistics. Fifty students have so far signed
up for the new program of study.
 &HT;    These initiatives are aimed at preparing tomorrow's leaders in
business and government, but the university's graduates already
include a veritable who's who of Mexico. ``It's the MIT of Latin
America,'' says Lucent's Baber. An estimated 40 percent of CEOs of
Mexico's 100 largest companies and 10 percent of government
bureaucrats are alumni, according to Expansion magazine. In fact,
the Mexican Congress even has a political clique known as ``the
Techies.'' Famed graduates include: Lorenzo Zambrano, the CEO of
the world's third-largest cement company Cemex; Roberto Servitje,
head of Grupo Industrial Bimbo, Latin America's leading bread
maker; Herminio Blanco, Mexican trade minister; and Carlos Medina
Plascencia, speaker of the lower chamber of Congress and member of
the opposition National Action Party.
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, graduates are quickly scooped up by such
multinationals as Microsoft and Procter &AMP; Gamble, which have
donated equipment and sponsored training courses. According to
university statistics, 70 percent of the school's students land a
job within a month after graduation.
 &HT;    Rodrigo Sosa, for example, has his eye on working for a U.S.
company such as General Motors. He is finishing a master's degree
in quality control, which will cost him close to US$8,000 a year in
tuition, but with state-of-the-art training in three-dimensional
design programs and assembly-line robots, he figures the investment
will pay off. ``For my family, it was a necessity that I go to Tec.
For me, it is a great opportunity to become someone important,'' he
says.
 &HT;    The university also coddles its students by offering perks
ranging from a new Olympic-size swimming pool and rock climbing
courses to satellite classes taught by such well-known public
figures as former U.S. President George Bush and Nobel Peace Prize
winner Rigoberta Menchu. Tec students can also participate in
exchange programs with 70 universities, including the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology (MIT), Stanford University and the
University of California Los Angeles (UCLA).
 &HT;    ``We are 50 years ahead of education compared with the rest of
the country,'' says State of Mexico Director General Alvarado.
``There is no other school like it in Mexico.''
 &HT;    But while the Tec has always prided itself on being a
leading-edge institution, students agree that great strides have
been made just in the past few years. ``If a student had a computer
five years ago, everyone turned around to look,'' says former
student Ricardo Lopez Castro, who now teaches a two-year course in
Cisco Network operating systems.
 &HT;    The Tec's technological re-engineering has also brought a change
in teaching methodology. Since 1997, professors must not only be
adept with computers but they must rethink their role in the
classroom as part of a new format dubbed the ``redesign.'' The
concept makes students responsible for their own learning and gives
computers a central role. ``The professor is no longer a
transmitter of information, but a facilitator, an administrator of
information,'' says Roberto Dominguez, professor of Latin American
literature.
 &HT;    Moreover, the web has given students more access to information,
causing teachers to offer more concepts than answers. ``For the
first time, students really have to study,'' says Dominguez. Adds
Lopez Castro: ``Before, the focus was on pedagogy and education.
Now we want to change the way a professor teaches and the way
students learn.''
 &HT;    Not all students, however, are able to adapt to these new
teaching concepts and professors say failure rates are increasing.
But those who do graduate complete the Tec's mission statement to
create ``internationally competitive'' students.
 &HT;    Take Danilo Escobedo. The 25-year-old master's candidate is
planning to move to Germany or Chile to work as a music producer
once he finishes his degree next year. Escobedo founded the campus
radio station in 1998 and designed a station web page that can also
be heard. ``I have a competitive advantage in terms of technology,
but the school also taught me how to work under pressure, organize,
administer and budget,'' he says.'' I am more prepared to work
abroad.''
 &HT;    But while the university continues to give its students an Ivy
League education, it also strives to put a human face on a new
generation of graduates. Administration officials are well aware
that many Mexicans blame past technocrats and number- crunchers _
many of who are Tec alumni _ for the neo-liberal economic policies
that have shut out much of the country's 60 million poor. From the
campus' privileged hilltop location, students have a constant
reminder of the nation's poverty each time they gaze on the dusty
concrete homes and dirt roads of the San Mateo slum that scale the
surrounding hills.
 &HT;    As a result, the high-tech university's curriculum also includes
real-world coursework, such as strategic planning for small
businesses. ``We are creating people, not machines,'' says campus
director Alvarado. ``We want students to develop a clear awareness
of what Mexico is all about.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Latin Trade 
