A6763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-WILLEY-NYT &LR;      05-26 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WILLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT REFUSES TO INTERVENE IN SUIT AGAINST CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court on Friday refused to
interfere in a lawsuit brought by a group that accuses President
Clinton of violating the Privacy Act. But the ruling was still a
partial victory for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges said there was no need to issue an emergency
order sought by the White House to block pre-trial information
gathering, or discovery, in the suit brought by Judicial Watch, a
conservative organization that has been a persistent foe of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Jim Kennedy, said Friday that White
House lawyers were disappointed by the decision on discovery, but
would submit to it nonetheless. But Kennedy said White House
lawyers were ``very pleased'' by other elements of Friday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel sharply criticized a lower court judge who
asserted in a March 29 ruling that the president committed ``a
criminal violation of the Privacy Act'' in releasing personal
letters sent to him by Kathleen Willey, a former White House
volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Willey accused Clinton on the CBS News program
``60 Minutes'' of making a sexual advance in the fall of 1993. Her
account added to the burdens of the president during the
investigation of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and the
sexual-misconduct lawsuit filed by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Willey's television appearance, the president
released her letters _ reluctantly, he said _ in the hope that
their friendly tone would undercut her accusations. She had written
them after the supposed sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   Willey is not a party to the suit by Judicial Watch, which
contends that the White House improperly obtained hundreds of files
from the FBI on former appointees and employees of the Reagan and
Bush administrations. Judicial Watch has focused on the handling of
the Willey letters in the hope of uncovering evidence that might
buttress its allegations involving misuse of the FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   On March 29, Judge Royce L. Lamberth ruled that White House
lawyers should submit to questioning by attorneys from Judicial
Watch. He went further, declaring that Clinton had acted unlawfully
in releasing Willey's letters, which were kept among White House
records. The Privacy Act generally bars release of information
about a person from federal records without that person's consent,
and violations of the law can result in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the appeals judges said Lamberth's ``sweeping
pronouncements'' about supposed criminal activity were
inappropriate, ``entirely superfluous'' and not binding on any
court that might have to weigh the question of criminality.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has contended all along that much of its
business is exempt from the Privacy Act, and that many lawyers from
both political parties have long said so. Friday, the appeals
judges said that, in matters unrelated to the Judicial Watch case,
the White House can continue to operate under that assumption
unless and until a court declares otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth was appointed by President Ronald Reagan in 1987.
Clinton and his allies have made no secret of their feeling that
the judge is unfriendly to the current administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
