<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT27-COX     05-26 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT STICKS TO TWO-WAY MICROSOFT BREAKUP PLAN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an amended court filing Friday, the government
stood firmly behind its original plan to chop Microsoft Corp. into
two pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The government's final submission in the historic antitrust
trial came in the form of an sweeping court order that U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson could sign, if he decides to
do so, as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   If put into effect, the order would eventually mandate the
breakup of the software giant while imposing strong curbs on its
business conduct during an inevitable _ and perhaps expedited _
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft must respond to the updated formula by Wednesday.
After that, Jackson would be free to issue a final decree of his
own design or adopt the government draft as it stands.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Jackson abruptly cut off further proceedings in
the case and swept aside a Microsoft motion that he summarily
dismiss the government plan. That final hearing was called to
review the remedies that would best cure what the court sees as
Microsoft's abusive monopolistic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But at that four-hour session, Jackson also questioned whether
the government and 17 states had gone far enough in their plan,
which calls for one company to market the flagship Windows
operating system and the other to sell applications such as
Microsoft Office and the Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who had earlier presided over a 77-day trial, voiced
a strong interest in splitting the company into a yet a third part
built around the browser and other Internet-related products.
</P>
<P>
   The government needed only five paragraphs Friday to summarize a
series of what it called ``minor, nonsubstantive changes'' to its
original proposal that it had made at Jackson's behest.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was to alter the way the government defines
``Microsoft'' to include the company's officers, directors,
employees, and assignees. Another was to alter the proposed stock
ownership provisions so that only Bill Gates, the co-founder and
current chairman, would be barred from owning shares in both new
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The latter change would accommodate Microsoft's other
co-founder, Paul Allen, who still serves as a director and holds a
large block of stock. It would also exempt Steve Ballmer,
Microsoft's chief executive, from having to sell his stock.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating Microsoft's argument that it was unfairly denied
its day in court, the government urged Jackson to ignore the
company's ``cynical ploy'' of offering Gates and Ballmer as
witnesses at extended remedies hearings. The offer was ``calculated
to raise diversionary issues on appeal,'' the government claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, for his part, has shown no inclination to hear from
either executive.
</P>
<P>
   Following a final ruling, the Justice Department must still
decide whether to send the case directly to the U.S. Supreme Court,
bypassing an appeals court that had overruled Jackson in an earlier
Microsoft antitrust case. The high tribunal must also concur in any
such expedited review.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, who would argue the case on
behalf of the government, would also have to agree.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the Memorial Day holiday, Microsoft shares closed
at $61.44, down 6 cents, setting another 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft: www.microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department: www.usdoj.gov/atr
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
