<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, May 27. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FOREIGN-POLICY (Washington) _ The most important
foreign policy vote so far this year, the 237-197 House approval of
the China trade deal, was no new affirmation of internationalism in
Congress but a reaffirmation of one of its oldest truths: members
vote their districts. But other foreign policy matters have far
smaller constituencies, and are much more subject to Washington's
political influences, especially partisanship. To put it meanly,
each party plays politics with foreign policy; to put it kindly,
each trusts presidents of its own party but discerns grave
weaknesses on the other side. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-MEDICARE (Washington) _ An influential Republican member
of the House and a Democratic senator announced Friday that they
would collaborate on a bipartisan effort to add prescription drug
benefits to Medicare this year. The effort, by Sen. Ron Wyden,
D-Ore., and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., alters the politics of the
issue in this election year, at least marginally increasing the
chances that Congress can break the deadlock on Medicare coverage
of prescription drugs. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ENVIRON (Assateague Island, Md.) _ President Clinton
signed an executive order Friday directing the EPA to develop Clean
Water Act regulations that reduce pollution of beaches, coasts and
ocean waters. In addition, EPA will identify areas where additional
protections are needed and possibly recommend that onshore and
offshore activities that generate pollution be restricted or
prohibited. (Summary from wires) By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DEATH-PENALTY (Undated) _ Cardinal Mahony of the
Archdiocese of Los Angeles urges Gov. Gray Davis to impose a
moratorium on executions in California. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Less than three years after a plunge
in the value of Thailand's currency triggered a devastating
economic crisis across much of Asia, the region is riding a wave of
growth reminiscent of the Asian miracle of the 1980s. The latest
evidence of the resurgence came today with a report that Hong
Kong's economic output rose 14.3 percent in the first three months
of the year. It was the territory's fastest quarter of growth since
1987, and seemed to make the Asian crisis a distant memory. Other
Asian economies, from South Korea to Singapore, are growing at
rates much faster than even the most optimistic forecasters had
predicted _ powered, to a large extent, by a booming demand for its
exports to the hot economy in the United States. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Justice Department
denounced the Microsoft Corp. on Friday, accusing the company of
cynical, irresponsible behavior, while also filing a modifed
version of its proposal to break up the company that includes only
a handful of small technical changes that the judge had requested.
By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ In an important advance against
diabetes, researchers in Canada are reporting that transplants of
insulin-producing cells have enabled eight patients with a severe
form of the disease to stop taking insulin injections. Two to 14
months after being transplanted in a simple procedure resembling a
tranfusion, the cells are still working in all eight patients, half
of whom were treated almost a year ago at the University of
Alberta, in Edmonton. The patients, who had Type 1 diabetes, in
which the body produces little or no insulin of its own, no longer
have any symptoms of the disease. Although they no longer need
insulin to control their blood sugar, they now must take other
drugs to prevent rejection of the transplants. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-WENDYS-MURDER (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced
Friday that the police are seeking a convicted felon with a history
of robbing fast-food restaurants in the murders of five people at a
Wendy's restaurant in Queens. By Robert D. McFadden
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SONTAG-HISTORICAL-NOVELS (Undated) _ Questions about how the
standards differ for historical novels and other written works have
been highlighted after the publication of Susan Sontag's novel ``In
America,'' which some critics have charged uses language from other
authors almost verbatim. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
