<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 230.
WASHINGTON, May 26 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: AID
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 91 to 4, a $15 billion spending
package that will reduce the cost of federal crop insurance and
provide over $7 billion in ``emergency'' spending for farmers.
Supporters said the package would help farmers in one of the worst
agricultural recessions in recent history. Opponents said the
package was crafted to win favor in an election year. A ``yes''
vote favors the package.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: PNTR
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 237 to 197, a measure granting
China permanent normal trade relations. The measure lowers tariffs
on U.S. goods going to China and permanently grants the trade
status that had been approved on an annual basis for 20 years.
Supporters said the measure opened up a giant market for U.S. goods
and without the trade status the U.S. would be left out of key
trade deals when China joins the World Trade Organization.
Opponents said it would move U.S. jobs overseas and leave no
incentive for China to improve its human rights record and labor
standards. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: AID
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved by a unanimous voice-vote a $15
billion spending package that will reduce the cost of federal crop
insurance and provide over $7 billion in ``emergency'' funding for
farmers. Supporters said the package would help farmers in one of
the worst agricultural recessions in recent history. Opponents said
the package was crafted to win favor in an election year. There was
no recorded tally of votes.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
