<HEADER>
A6799 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-26 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INTEL CHIP DELIVERS, BUT EXPECT TO PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp., which is used to being the market leader when it
comes to PC processors, was No. 2 when it came to scaling the
gigahertz mountain earlier this year. Advanced Micro Devices beat
Intel to the summit by a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Intel second in delivering a 1-GHz chip, it was
unable to deliver in volume. That's one reason that many PC makers,
including Intel's biggest customer, Houston-based Compaq Computer
Corp., opted to pass on Intel's fastest Pentium III, instead going
with AMD's 1-GHz Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies that did opt to build computers around Intel's
offering, such as Dell Computer Corp., figured there was limited
demand for a chip this fast _ and this expensive. They also were
counting on changes in the Pentium III's design that would boost
its speed past the Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   Early Athlons were faster in crucial aspects than the first
Pentium IIIs.
</P>
<P>
   So, now you can buy PCs that use Intel's gigahertz chip, but it
will cost you big bucks. But if it's speed you need, you'll find
there's nothing faster.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at Dell's Dimension XPS B1000r. It costs $4,309.
</P>
<P>
   Take a deep breath; calm yourself. Yes, you read that price
right. Four thousand, three hundred and nine smackeroonies. Take
out a second mortgage, sell your car or commit grand larceny, and
you can have this baby sent directly to your door.
</P>
<P>
   And what you'll have, of course, is the fastest Windows-based
computer you can buy. At least, until the next chip upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried was seriously loaded with goodies, which
boosted the cost. It came with 256 megabytes of high-speed memory;
a 30-GB hard drive that spins at a blistering 7,200 revolutions per
minute; an nVidia GeForce graphics card with 64 MB of DDR
(double-data rate) memory; a 12X DVD-ROM drive; an 8X4X32
rewritable CD-ROM drive; a 56K fax modem; a 10/100 Ethernet card;
Harman Kardon digital speakers with subwoofer; a SoundBlaster Live
sound card; and a 19-inch Trinitron monitor.
</P>
<P>
   There are several items here that kick the price into the
stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   This PC uses memory developed by a company called Rambus that is
supposed to perform better than standard memory. Bumping up from
the standard 128 to 256 MB adds almost $500 to the cost. The 64 MB
GeForce card is $240 more than the standard 32 MB version.
</P>
<P>
   The way Dell has configured the system on its Web site, the
19-inch Trinitron model is the cheapest display option. If you
leave it out completely, it knocks $430 off the price.
</P>
<P>
   By playing with these options, it's possible to drop the price
to just above $3,000, without a monitor. That's still awfully
steep.
</P>
<P>
   You can assuage your feelings of buyer's remorse with the thrill
of raw power. While I was initially skeptical of whether a user
could notice benefits from a 1-GHz chip, I have been convinced. The
Dimension B1000r responds faster than anything else I've tried _
including a 1-GHz Athlon-based Compaq _ and tests bear that out.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons why someone would want a computer this
powerful is for gaming. Serious gamers want the fastest machine
they can get, and don't see the absurdity of spending many
thousands of dollars to play with the fastest rig around. Computer
companies, in an attempt to remain dignified, call these users
``enthusiasts,'' but we know what's really going on here, don't we?
That's one reason why the timedemo feature in Quake III Arena from
id Software has become the de facto standard for testing machines
like this. Nothing stresses all the components of a PC _ from
memory to the graphics card to the processor to audio like this
game.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-GHz Dell did better in the timedemo test than any other PC
I've tried. With Quake III's graphics set to High Quality, the demo
delivered 88 frames per second, compared to 83.8 on the
Athlon-based Compaq. When I switched to the settings I usually use
to play the game, I got 60.4 fps, compared to 55.2 on the Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there are several specifications here that boost the
Dell over the Compaq. Both have the same amount of system memory,
but the Dell's is on a 133-MHz system bus (the route data moves
across the motherboard) while the Compaq's is just 100 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   Both use a GeForce card, but the Dell's has twice as much
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when you buy a PC, you're buying the whole package and
not just a processor. Dell has done a good job of building a
superfast system using state-of-the-art components.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect to get it for a song.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
