<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MUSIC FILES, IMAGE SCANS CAUSE MAJOR UPDATE OF PC SPECS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because the PC industry moves so rapidly, minimum PC
specifications have become a moving target.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, I have created a Web site with my minimum
specifications for different types of shoppers, from budget buyers
to power users. You can find them at my Web site at
www.dwight-ilverman.com/minspecs.htm, where they will be posted _
and tweaked _ year-round. There also is a separate page there with
portable PC recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, here are my current recommended minimum specs for
desktop PCs that would be running Microsoft's Windows operating
system:
</P>
<P>
   Processor: Shop for at least a 450-megahertz processor, either
from Intel Corp. or Advanced Micro Devices. But avoid systems that
share main system memory with the computer's graphics adapter.
These shared-memory designs often limit your upgrade options and
generally feature lower-quality graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Memory: You'll want at least 64 megabytes of RAM, and you may
want to consider 128 MB if you play games. Most PCs now come with
64 MB standard, although some budget systems still offer only 32.
It's worth the $75-$100 it will cost to go up to 64.
</P>
<P>
   Hard drive: A year ago, I was recommending four gigabytes as a
minimum, but the popularity of downloadable music files and home
image scanning dictates that it's time to double that, to eight GB.
If you already have a taste for these kinds of activities, consider
at least 10 GB.
</P>
<P>
   CD or DVD: A 24X CD-ROM drive remains the minimum, with a
DVD-ROM drive as an option. Software hasn't moved to DVD in a big
way, but having one keeps your options open because it also will
read CD-ROM software. If you are considering a rewriteable CD
drive, get one with a 4X write and rewrite speed and 24X read
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Video: My recommendation for video memory also has doubled from
a year ago, to eight MB, again based on the popularity of working
with digital images. More memory lets you display larger images
using more colors. It can also improve display speed, particularly
with 3-D games.
</P>
<P>
   Sound: All PCs come with sound cards that can deliver decent
sound, so you may want to pay more attention to the speakers.
Quality speakers _ particularly those with their own power supply _
can make a big difference in how a PC sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Modems: All PCs come with 56K modems, and the vast majority are
so-called winmodems, in which software does a lot of the work that
hardware used to do. While the current crop of winmodems are better
than in the past, cheap ones can still bring much pain. Look for a
modem that's a brand name.
</P>
<P>
   Monitor: Fifteen-inch monitors with a maximum .28 dot pitch
remain the minimum you should consider. If you can afford it,
consider a 17-inch model with a .26 dot pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Expandability: Some new ``legacy-free'' PCs have no way to
upgrade the system other than through USB connections. If you are
interested in these machines, be sure they come with all the ports
you think you might need, including an Ethernet connection if you
are considering or have DSL or cable-modem Internet service.
Otherwise, look for two free PCI slots, two USB ports and serial
and parallel ports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
