r f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-26 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WORK VISA LAW STILL LACKS TEETH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By L.M.SIXEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago the White House threatened to veto a bill that
would increase the number of high-skilled work visas available
unless U.S. workers were given first crack at the jobs and weren't
laid off to make room for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The protections were added, the visa limits were raised and
President Clinton signed the bill into law _ but companies don't
have to abide by it.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Labor Department hasn't gotten around to
issuing the regulations, which, among other things, spell out what
companies have to do to guarantee they haven't laid off any U.S.
workers six months before or after the immigrant came on board or
how they tried to recruit U.S.
</P>
<P>
   workers first.
</P>
<P>
   If the protections were seemingly such a priority with the
Clinton White House, why hasn't the Labor Department put the
regulations on the fast track? A senior Labor Department official
who didn't want to be identified called it ``prosecutorial
discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the department has limited resources and some
things have higher priority than others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, when the unemployment rate is at a 30-year low,
worker protection isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, older U.S. workers say there is rampant age
discrimination against high-tech workers over 30 and they need
those protections _ especially since about half of the temporary
work permits go to the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the Labor Department wanted to issue the
regulations, it's getting a little late. The three-year law is in
effect for only one more year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith is scratching his head over this,'' said Allen Kay,
spokesman for U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio, and chairman of
the House Immigration Subcommittee. Smith was a main sponsor of the
American Competitiveness and Workforce Improvement Act of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said that Smith has repeatedly asked the Labor Department to
give him a status report on whereabouts of the regulations.
Frustrated, Smith held hearings on the regulations Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Fraser, deputy administrator of the department's wage
and hour division, told Smith's subcommittee Thursday the
department received 90 comments when it asked the public to respond
to the regulations and it's taken time to sift through those
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser also testified the department gave a copy of its proposed
final rule to the Office of Management and Budget in January, a
typical step in the process. After the regulations are reviewed by
OMB for fairness and cost, the department will again review the
proposed regulations, a department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Regulations can take a long time to develop because so many
different effects have to be measured, said the senior department
official.
</P>
<P>
   There's the environment to consider, along with small
businesses, families, state and local governments, and the
relationship between costs and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, it takes six months to develop regulations but a
year is closer to average, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign worker visa law applies to companies that are
considered heavily dependent on immigrants _ that is, if 15 percent
or more of its work force is working under H1B temporary visas.
Such companies are known as ``job shops'' and they often pay lower
wages to immigrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   The number of H1B visas _ the category for skilled employees who
typically have bachelor's degrees _ increased from 65,000 a year to
115,000 in 1999 and 2000. In 2001, the number falls to 107,500.
</P>
<P>
   M. Nicole Morrison, an immigration lawyer in Houston, isn't
holding her breath waiting for the regulations. Morrison said she
doesn't expect the department to ever issue them because the law is
too convoluted.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what the government is trying to accomplish with
H1B visas, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is also stymied. The Clinton administration is asking to
raise the number of H1B visas to 200,000 per year but hasn't added
any protection for U.S. workers, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, Smith said the public doesn't much cotton to
increasing the number of immigrants coming in to work. During his
hearing Thursday, Smith cited a recent poll that showed only 20
percent of Americans want the H1B program to expand, while 80
percent are opposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
