<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV28-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOWN SIDE OF PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ This is no longer the squalid grotto of
``Angela's Ashes,'' the misnamed town with a lilting title, where
life was grim and grimy, and Frank McCourt's dreary boyhood row
house stank from the backed-up sewer.
</P>
<P>
   Things are now looking up, way up, for Limerick, as for the rest
of the Republic. For the first time, anyone who wants work can find
employment. You can't drive near any town or city without seeing
roadwork under way.
</P>
<P>
   And the massive new system of ``mains,'' as the sewer network is
called, is trumpeted with blue billboards carrying the starred
circle logo of the European Union, informing the Irish that the EU
budget is paying for ``80 percent'' of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The EU has been good to Ireland, as have the '90s generally, the
tourism boom, and the luck of the economic draw, which has spurred
a doubling of real estate values in the last five years, at the
same time mortgage rates are low at around 5 percent, and people
are flush with cash.
</P>
<P>
   But the speculative property boom triggered a series of massive
and overlapping political scandals involving payoffs, bribes, and
favor-swapping of every description.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of politicians and developers are enmeshed in an orgy of
influence peddling. Each day's headlines bring new revelations of
who got what for doing such-and-such in the property development
game.
</P>
<P>
   With slabs of new housing and shopping malls springing up in
what just was pasture and meadow, with the explosion of high-tech
industry and the sudden influx of returning Irish emigrants coming
home to earn and spend at a far higher level than when they left,
the political system became flush with payoffs and bribery at every
level.
</P>
<P>
   Including the very top. Bertie Ahearn, the popular prime
minister, got $3,000 from a contributor who owned land for which
Ahearn granted tax breaks when he was finance minister. He says he
didn't know who owned it. But his benefactor, Frank Dunlop, is at
the center of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ahearn's involvement seems marginal, though he's also been
toasted for taking soccer match box seats and free trips to
Manchester United games. But a current member of the parliament,
the Dail, was just caught voting against an inquiry into secret
funding accounts, when it turns out he has one himself. His penalty
was a wrist-slap, a 14-day suspension with pay, which is like
sending a hockey player to the penalty box for two minutes. Dozens
of parliamentarians have been named as recipients of floods of
cash, presumably for votes.
</P>
<P>
   The fixer at the center of the land rezoning grab in Dublin,
George Redmond, 75, former assistant city and county manager, was
paid over $300,000 over 20 years by one developer. ``It developed
almost as a habit,'' Redmond breezily informed a commission of
inquiry. On the average of every 10 days, he'd accept cash that
began as $250 but escalated to $500 a handout.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, a key official on zoning decisions, would then give
``advice.'' Redmond said he acted as a consultant ``on an
installment basis.'' He said he got the money partly out of
``affection.'' The value of an acre of prime industrial land might
double or treble, depending upon how the county government ruled on
its future use, and Redmond garnered a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The presiding judge accused Redmond of ``a selective case of
amnesia'' for getting vague on sums and coconspirators.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Dunlop was another fixer on a grand scale at the national
level. He's testified he once gave $50,000 in cash to ``a powerful
individual.'' The public inquiries have become daily media fodder.
Germany is enmeshed in its own fund-raising scandal, but Ireland's
is broader and deeper. ``Our sleaze is up there with the best of
Europe,'' boasts the Irish Times.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing the words of both fixers' testimony, Irish Independent
columnist Sam Smyth concluded: ``Getting George Redmond to admit
anything is like asking Frank Dunlop to deny something . . .. Frank
describes every donation he made to politicians as a bribe, then
George says he did nothing but give some developers `general
assistance and advice' to become a millionaire.'' The columnist
characterized Redmond as ``the recidivist old liar'' and Redmond as
``the repentant bag-man.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the United States, reformers are divided over how to
resolve the eternal dilemma of money in politics. Ahearn says there
is no support for full public funding. There is a debate over
banning corporate contributions in favor of individual ones; both
types are legal now. The public and the papers are fed up. ``Power
and money,'' hissed an elderly female shopkeeper in the South
coastal town of Timoleague. ``Please God the Irish still have
enough common people with their both feet on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Independent's editorial after two days of fruitless
debate on the subject was equally glum: It ``does not inspire much
public confidence that we will see early reforms. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But the public is caught up in the Roaring '20s atmosphere of
rampant prosperity, displaying a widespread contempt for the
money-grubbing pols and bureaucrats, and the venal developers who
fueled their habit. Ireland's economy grew a staggering 11 percent
last year, four times the EU average. All the numbers are going up:
consumer spending up 9 percent over the year, retail spending up 14
percent, industrial investment up 25 percent just in last year's
third quarter. The new danger is inflation. With membership in the
Euro Zone, Ireland cannot raise interest rates by itself; that has
to be done by the new European central bank. So the government's
only braking power can come from raising taxes _ which is never
easy anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Houses outside Dublin proper are going up in price at the rate
of 2 percent per month, surpassing a $125,000 average. Union
leaders demand fresh price controls so that the 50,000 new homes
built this year overall can be be bought by workers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity has a downside. Last year 37 percent of drivers
stopped by police on suspicion of drunken driving tested positive
for drugs. A lot of poor and underclass teens have become
glue-sniffers and school dropouts. And the cynicism and apathy
churned up by the money scandals will poison the well when it comes
time for politicians to take hard decisions on inflation.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
