<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-NEWSERIES-TEX     05-26 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURE THIS FOR FALL: A NEW TV LINEUP THAT ISN'T NEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Network television's annual rite of passage arrived and departed
last week with the usual bravado and high drama, but the
announcement of the 30 or so series that will fill prime time this
fall also had a sense of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when the networks lick their
post-sweeps battle wounds but are energized by the notion of wiping
the slate clean and by fall lining up shoulder-to-shoulder at the
starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Network presidents, production studio heads, high-level
executives and publicists are able to push their series and not be
laughed at for a lack of truth in advertising. For instance, the
project starring ``Seinfeld's'' Michael Richards, about a bumbling
private eye, was reportedly so poorly conceived and crafted that
NBC sent it back to the drawing board. But it didn't deter the
network from placing the unseen new version on its schedule and
sticking ``highly anticipated'' in front of its title.
</P>
<P>
   Commercially and creatively, the Big Four networks (only UPN
gained in audience numbers) are coming off a dismal year, if not a
rather odd one that will only get more complicated next season. The
biggest story of the season was the phenomenal success of ABC's
quiz show ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire,'' which energized the
network's schedule, skewed the ratings wars and is dictating ABC's
strategy for fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings and revenue races aside, the unexpected success of the
game show gave ABC so much scheduling leverage that it pushed the
development of its own slate of series to the back burner; it also
cut into the ratings of any other program it happened to face in
its time slot, with the exception of ``ER.'' One question is
whether ABC is compromising long-term programming for short-term
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, game shows and other reality series with big-money
payoffs followed the lead of ``Millionaire,'' which will be spread
over four nights, perhaps five or even six next fall as ABC milks
its popularity and, at the same time, sabotages the ratings of its
competition.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the other game shows has come close to duplicating
``Millionaire's'' success. Only one of the three game shows
introduced since ``Millionaire'' will return for a second season.
That's why, on May 31, CBS _ with a mixture of excitement and
trepidation _ is premiering ``Survivor,'' about marooned islanders
battling over a million-dollar payoff.
</P>
<P>
   The new series being offered by the six broadcast networks
differ only slightly in concept and tone from last season and, come
to think of it, each season since 1990. You can easily see how
ABC's ``Geena,'' with Oscar-winner Geena Davis as a career woman
who must readjust her life for her new guy and his two kids can be
mistaken for Shelley Long's 1998 fiasco ``Kelly Kelly,'' or that
the 14-year-old coping with his cash-poor family in NBC's
``Tucker'' sounds a lot like ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' There's
also the male version of ``Providence,'' called ``Ed,'' starring Ed
Cavanagh, who had a recurring role on ``Providence.'' It, too, airs
on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its faltering but still sizable audience, network
television remains tentative when asked to challenge its
cookie-cutter mentality, partly because ``shows that think outside
the box,'' as producer Tom Fontana puts it, take longer to catch on
with viewers, who are comfortable with proven formulas. (Perhaps
Fontana was referring to his cop drama ``The Beat,'' which, with
its mix of documentary style and live action, was a bit much.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the failings of a show like ABC's ``Sports Night,'' which
will not return but could turn up on cable, was its inability to
connect with viewers, who found the dialogue smug and its style of
moving freely between comedy and drama jolting and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   While the sameness of new shows is a familiar story, never has
the gap between the acting talent assembled on screen and the
mediocre material seemed so wide.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that first-rate actors are, year after year, tossed to
the wolves with third-rate scripts and weak supporting casts hasn't
deterred the networks from trying mightily again.
</P>
<P>
   Next season's star power includes Bette Midler, Gabriel Byrne,
John Goodman, Andre Braugher, David Alan Grier, Delta Burke, Katey
Sagal, and ``Wings'' stars Tim Daly and Steven Weber.
</P>
<P>
   None of their shows sounds that intriguing, although I'm dying
to see ``Don't Ask,'' the Goodman sitcom where he plays a gay man
who recently left his wife and family. Grier, terrific as an improv
player on ``In Living Color,'' plays a Secret Service agent demoted
to the job of protecting the first lady, played by Burke in NBC's
``DAG.'' In ``Madigan Men,'' on ABC, Byrne is Benjamin Madigan, a
divorced architect back in the dating game. Sagal is a prissy
perfectionist who must contend with the home invasion of a sister
and her 14-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Midler's ``The Bette Show'' is already being touted by
advertisers as a hit, but the same thing was said of Nathan Lane's
``Encore!Encore!,'' which failed to last a season, and Tom
Selleck's ``The Closer,'' which suffered similar humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is high on Davis' ``Geena,'' if only for the fact that she's
a well-known film actress. Someone needs to tell these programming
executives that film stars on their way down rarely bring along the
built-in audience they seek. Braugher's return as a doctor in ABC's
Gideon's Crossing is equally interesting because he was considered
one of the standouts in an unusually strong ensemble cast on
``Homicide: Life on the Streets.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Gideon's Crossing,'' set for ABC, Braugher will be in his
emotional element as a doctor who cares deeply for his patients.
But it's hard to say whether audiences will actually follow
Braugher solo.
</P>
<P>
   Other shows already gaining promotional steam are those with
producers who have delivered hits. ``The $treet'' is about Wall
Street traders, but more important, it's produced by Darren Star,
architect of HBO's smoldering series about female singles, ``Sex
and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Star's return to the networks is surprising, because the former
producer of ``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' ``Melrose Place'' and
``Central Park West'' left in disgust, saying the censors were
killing his creativity. Network money may talk loudly, but imagine
what he'll come up against now that he's had a taste of cable's
do-whatever forum.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is already figuring on David E. Kelley's ``Boston Public,''
an expos on high-school teachers, as a potential hit, even though
his ``Snoops'' didn't make it to Christmas and ``Ally McBeal'' has
fallen apart in overall quality. It would be nice to see Kelley
regain his focus and turn out another gem.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Wolf, whose WB drama ``D.C.'' died quicklypads his Law &AMP;
Order franchise on NBC with ``Deadline,'' about a newspaper
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is remaking ``The Fugitive;'' Fox is taking chances on
``Fearsum,'' a thriller from the makers of ``The Blair Witch
Project;'' and Aaron Spelling returns to NBC with the drama
``Titans,'' a serial (what else?) about a 26-year-old fighter pilot
who returns to Beverly Hills (where else?) and finds his rich
family torn apart.
</P>
<P>
   As for diversity, Grier, Braugher and Mykelti Williamson are
leads or co-leads, and it's hard to say how big a role Chi McBride
will play as a principal in Kelley's ``Boston Public.'' (James
McDaniels has said, what, four words on ``NYPD Blue'' in several
years?)
</P>
<P>
   While Ruben Blades is also a co-star in ``Gideon's Crossing,''
Hispanics are upset that CBS passed on the Edward James Olmos drama
``American Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Because NBC will air the Summer Olympics in September, the
official start of the season won't begin until sometime in October.
That will put the batch of new shows against the baseball playoffs
and World Series, which will lead into November sweeps, which will
lead into December's Christmas episodes and reruns.
</P>
<P>
   By January, when midseason replacements are hoping to fill
vacancies, it will be difficult to know which shows have potential
and which do not.
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, am looking forward to the disruptions. Anything that
can bump network TV out of its formulaic sleepwalking would be a
welcome change.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
