<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DEAN&AMP;DELUCA-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAN &AMP; DELUCA OFFER FACES UNCERTAIN MARKET APPETITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Kan., Calif., Mass.)   (For release Sun., May 28)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to Dean &AMP; Deluca, the Soho retailer of
fine food and gorgeous kitchenware, New Yorkers are happy to spend
$30 a pound for smoked swordfish or $2.00 for an Asian pear.
</P>
<P>
   But will investors prove as eager to put money into Dean &AMP;
Deluca stock when the company offers shares in its initial public
offering, expected in five to six weeks?
</P>
<P>
   As of last Friday, Dean &AMP; Deluca _ which hasn't turned a profit
in seven years _ had not set a price for the offering, nor had it
announced how many shares it would make available. But the company
hopes to raise about $69 million to finance a major expansion.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things an investor is likely to glean from the
prospectus is that Joel B. Dean and Giorgio DeLuca, the company's
founders, are no longer minding the store. Leslie G. Rudd, who
holds 64 percent of Dean &AMP; Deluca's shares, has been chairman since
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While Dean &AMP; Deluca's flagship venue on lower Broadway remains
one of Manhattan's famed culinary temples, the company has been
gradually opening stores nationwide for the past decade, and
channeling money into its catalog and Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dean &AMP; Deluca operates four other stores, in Washington;
Charlotte, N.C.; Leawood, Kan. (a suburb of Kansas City); and St.
Helena, Calif. The company wants to open one or two specialty
stores next year, and three or four stores in each of the five
years thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Dean &AMP; Deluca's expansion outside Manhattan and online has not
come cheaply. According to the prospectus, it has not been
profitable since the end of February 1993, a fact that must leave
purchasers of Dean &AMP; Deluca's $34-a-box rugelach scratching their
heads. Because of its expansion plans, the company expects to incur
sizable losses for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it lost $8.9 million on sales of $59.6 million,
compared with a loss of $5.7 million on sales of $49.3 million in
1998, and a loss of $9.3 million on sales of $34.4 million in 1997.
As of Jan. 30, it had $17.1 million in cash. Total debt stood at
$3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market for specialty foods _ Dean &AMP; Deluca's largest
business _ is growing, as is demand for premium-priced wine and
upscale kitchenware. The prospectus forecasts United States sales
of specialty foods alone to reach $54 billion by 2002, up from
about $38.8 billion in 1997. Forrester Research, a market research
firm in Cambridge, Mass., estimates that sales of specialty foods
online will rise from $248 million in 1999, to $6.3 billion in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   So the company's expansion makes sense, industry analysts say.
``Specialty food customers are the best food customers,'' said Phil
Lempert, the editor of the Lempert Report, an industry newsletter
in Santa Monica, Calif..
</P>
<P>
   But competition is increasing. The Internet gives consumers
access to the Web sites of food manufacturers, not just retailers.
Evie Black Dykema, a Forrester analyst, cautions that online
grocers, like Webvan Group, and general retailers, like Amazon.com,
are expanding their specialty food offerings, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lempert, for one, isn't surprised by Dean &AMP; Deluca's losses. He
thinks the future of specialty food retailing lies in companies
either creating strong, content-filled Internet sites that keep
customers coming back for more products, like Amazon.com, or
building superstores of 40,000 square feet or so, that can generate
high sales. Dean &AMP; Deluca's new outlets will average just 10,000 to
15,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of other food analysts, Lempert thinks the
retailer's Web site needs a makeover. Dean &AMP; Deluca is planning
such an overhaul, according to the prospectus, and will increase
product offerings and add new features. It also plans to use its
catalogs to promote its Internet business more vigorously by
sending out about 13 million catalogs this year, compared with 4
million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the climate for new issues is tepid. According to Steven
Tuen, director for research at IPO Value Monitor, a research firm
in New York, food-related initial offerings historically have not
fared well, with many sinking below their offering prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
