<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0527-COX     05-26 2041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: New kid on the block right up there
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newcomer is coming on strong in the race for the Senate seat
from New York. A new Zogby International poll shows Hillary Clinton
and Rick Lazio in a statistical dead heat. Lazio just entered the
race last week, 14 points down. The new numbers have Clinton at
45.8 percent and Lazio at 43.8 percent. The survey's margin of
error is almost 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO'S HOUSE SEAT IN PLAY
</P>
<P>
   When Rick Lazio announced his Senate candidacy last week, his
New York House seat was left invitingly open to Democrats seeking
to gain a majority in the House. ``It puts us in a difficult spot
right now in two ways,''said Suffolk County Republican chairman
Tony Apollaro. ``We need to find a candidate and we need to finance
a candidate.'' They'll meet within the next week to sort through a
short list of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   NOT PRO-LIFE ON THAT END OF IT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said today he supports the use of DNA testing if
it can ``erase any doubts'' about a murder case, but he still
stands firm in favor of the death penalty. Bush said capital
punishment deters crime: ``I believe it sends a chilling message
that there is a consequence to your actions.'' He made the comments
from Texas during a videoconference with the Catholic Press
Association, meeting in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   IS HE OR ISN'T HE?
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion Rights Action League threw its support
behind Hillary Clinton as her new GOP opponent's record on abortion
was attacked by activists on both sides. While NARAL accused Rick
Lazio of being anti-abortion, the Right to Life Party said his
position isn't nearly good enough for them. ``Rick Lazio is
pro-abortion; he can't get around it, it doesn't matter what NARAL
says,'' said Ken Diem, chairman of the Right to Life Party, which
says it intends to run its own Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   JUST THE SAME, HE'S GOT BETTER THINGS TO DO
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush will be skipping next month's Republican state
convention in Houston. Four years ago, the the party denied him a
governor's traditional role of leading the state delegation to the
GOP national convention. And rules changes by the Texas party two
years ago could deny Bush the traditional governor's say in who'll
attend the convention. But Bush spokesman Karen Hughes said his
schedule is built around winning the presidency, not any past
disagreements with Texas Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   `WARM-UP' DEBATES A POSSIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is kicking around the possibility of doing a
couple of early debates with Al Gore, perhaps as soon as late
summer, according to the New York Daily News. Some close close
aides believe one or two summer debates make sense, the Daily News
said. The rationale: Early debates would demonstrate that Bush
isn't afraid to duke it out and would lower the stakes for the
three fall debates. ``The more he does, the better he gets,'' one
Bush aide was quoted as saying. ``And it reduces the pressure on
him for October.''
</P>
<P>
   A GUY FOR THE LONG HAUL?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush may be a fun date, but he's not the kind of guy
you want to settle down with. So says the chairwoman of the Texas
Democratic Party, Molly Beth Malcolm, one of more than 70
Democratic officials from 34 states who met in Nashville with Al
Gore and his senior campaign staff. The officials said they
recognized that voters seemed to like Bush's personality more than
Gore's, but they suggested that the more voters saw of Bush, the
less they'd like him.
</P>
<P>
   THERE MIGHT HAVE TO BE SOME HALFTIME ADJUSTMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore reassured the national Democratic leaders meeting with
him that his campaign has a winning strategy. Several of the
Democrats said they were comfortable after their pep rally and
strategy session that Gore's lagging poll numbers aren't a serious
problem _ yet. Gore later told supporters at a $1 million
fund-raiser night that he expects ``a good healthy, hard fight
ahead of us and we're going to win it. And we're going to win it
solidly.''
</P>
<P>
   RUBBING SHOULDERS WITH MINORITIES
</P>
<P>
   With camera shutters clicking at his meetings with South African
President Thabo Mbeki and then with retired Gen. Colin Powell,
George W. Bush promoted U.S.-South Africa relations and
volunteerism, a pet issue of Powell. Trailing Al Gore among black
voters, Bush is making a concerted effort to court minorities by
surrounding the governor with a sea of brown and black faces. In
Detroit earlier this week, it was a row of inner-city school
children.
</P>
<P>
   IF IT'S BUSH, YOU CAN BET ON POWELL BEING SOMEWHERE, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Colin Powell said that although he's ruled out being George W.
Bush's running mate, he wouldn't close the door on a possible
Cabinet job a possible Bush administration. ``In any other
capacity, one has to listen when a president asks you to consider a
job,'' Powell said. Bush told Powell to be ready for a call.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI TO GIVE SOME OF IT UP
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani said he'll return $2.8 million to people who
contributed to his aborted Senate campaign and ask them to send
their money to Rick Lazio instead. Giuliani also said he'll
campaign with Lazio next week. Giuliani, who raised $20 million for
the race, has spent $13.8 million. Election laws require that
Giuliani give donors back the money they earmarked for the general
election rather than the primary; that's $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN POLICY ADVANTAGE TILTING?
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, it was widely perceived that one of Al Gore's
biggest advantages over George W. Bush was his foreign policy
experience. But Gore's foreign policy advantage may be waning. Bush
went to Capitol Hill to fight for the China trade bill, which
passed in the House, while Gore maintained a relatively low profile
on the issue because an ally, organized labor, opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   SOME WANT TO KNOW WHO'S PAYING
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Federal Election Commission welcomed a proposal
to require interest groups to identify their donors when they air
TV ads meant to influence elections. Republicans were opposed, but
they agreed to let it move forward. The commission's division along
party lines reflects a similar sentiment in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE OUTSIDE, LOOKING IN
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans of Texas, criticizing the state
Republican Party for not reaching out to gay and lesbian voters,
pledged to set up an exhibit booth outside the party's upcoming
state convention. ``Our group's message is simple: One can be a
Republican and oppose discrimination,'' said Steve Labinski, the
group's president. Log Cabin contends the Republican Party of Texas
has refused to respond to its request to operate an information
booth inside the state political convention June 15-17 in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   SOME SEE SAFETY IN LOW PROFILE
</P>
<P>
   Being Jewish may be closer to irrelevancy in American politics
rather than the handicap it once was may have been. The list of
potential Democratic vice presidential candidates includes at least
three Jews: Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, ex-Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin and California Sen. Dianne Feinstein. But
some Jews, particularly in the older generation, worry that
anti-Semitism lingers below the surface in society and could erupt
if too much attention is paid to too manyJews who become too
prominent.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN SHAKING UP THE PARTY
</P>
<P>
   The growing likelihood that Pat Buchanan will secure the Reform
Party's presidential nomination and the $12.5 million in federal
campaign money that goes with it has created another element of
conflict within the loosely organized, often chaotic party. Some
Reform leaders are trying to draft Ross Perot for a third
consecutive run. Another group is pushing for Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader. Still others are urging the leadership endorse no one
this year.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD PARTIES ON BOTH SIDES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was once seen as the clear beneficiary of a third-party
candidate, but not any more. Pat Buchanan, who bolted the
Republican Party last year, has yet to demonstrate he will
seriously hamper George W. Bush. But there's scattered evidence
that Ralph Nader, the veteran consumer advocate, could be
troublesome for Gore, especially in Western states the Democrat
will need to put together a winning Electoral College map.
</P>
<P>
   HE KNOWS WHAT HE'S LOOKING FOR
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a new warning by a prominent religious conservative,
James Dobson, against selecting a running mate who supports
abortion, George W. Bush called himself a ``pretty independent
thinker'' whose main criterion for choosing a vice presidential
nominee was an ability to assume the presidency. ``I'm looking for
someone who could be president, someone able to fill that job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   HUFFINGTON'S RECORD ABOUT TO GO DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Wall Street exec Jon Corzine already has spent almost $27
million going after the Democratic Senate nomination in New Jersey.
That's more than three times as much as anyone has ever spent on a
Senate primary and within striking distance of the most ever spent
on an entire Senate election. That record is held by Republican
Michael Huffington, the oil millionaire who lost to Sen. Dianne
Feinstein (D-Calif.) in 1994. His campaign cost nearly $30 million,
$28 million of which came out of his own pocket. Corzine's
opponent, ex-Gov. Jim Florio, has spent $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   PROUD DADDY AT GRADUATION
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush greeted his twin daughters' high school
graduation day in Austin with ``a tear in my eye'' and a plea to
the media to give them a little space. The 18-year-old fraternal
twins, Barbara and Jenna have told their parents they want to stay
out of the spotlight as their father seeks the White House. This
fall, Barbara will follow in the family footsteps and go to Yale.
Jenna is staying home to attend the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE HOUSE INTEREST? WHO, HER?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton said she understands why some people are
skeptical about her intentions in running for the Senate, but
insisted she wouldn't use the seat as a stepping stone to the
presidency in 2004. ``I don't blame people for being skeptical,''
she said during a voter forum. ``I feel I owe it to the people of
New York to serve a six-year term.''
</P>
<P>
   THAT WHAT YOU CALL REAL INDIAN GIVING
</P>
<P>
   California is the state where the most money is spent on
political campaigns. And in recent years, California's Indian
tribes have become the biggest-spending special-interest group in
the state, pouring about $114 million into campaigns since 1998.
Most of that money was spent on a successful one-time effort to
pass ballot measures permitting expansion of reservation gambling.
The second-biggest-spending interest group in the state, according
to Common Cause: the state's prison guard union, giving $1.9
million to candidates over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   AND IF HE EVER GETS THEM IN THE RING
</P>
<P>
   In a soon-to-be-published account of his first year in office,
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura uses his trademark blunt language to
tout his accomplishments, explain his forays into controversy and
thrash the media. With ``a few honorable exceptions,'' the ex-pro
wrestler says in a final chapter added to a forthcoming paperback
edition of his autobiography, ``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed,'' the
media are ``corrupt, shameless and irresponsible as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   BUT THEY WISH HIM BLISS JUST THE SAME
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich was a contribution magnet as speaker of the House,
but his big donors seem to have disappeared. Gingrich and former
congressional worker Callista Bisek plan to marry Aug. 18, and
their electronic Macy's registry, online magazine Salon reports,
shows plenty of pricey gifts remaining on their wish list,
including all the linen, bath accessories and all but one plate of
their wedding china. Most of the purchases have come in flatware,
by far the cheapest category.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
