</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGHTLIFE-$ADV28-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE VELVET ROPES OF NEW YORK'S NEWEST CLUBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you're the kind of person who likes to meditate to
the pounding beat of Run DMC, is there a club for you.
</P>
<P>
   It's Spa, a cavernous new dance scene on East 13th Street, which
has boldly attempted to graft a New Age ethos _ waterfalls! plants!
_ with a sound system so loud it makes your teeth chatter.
</P>
<P>
   So overwhelming is the decibel level that the club has hired a
jockey-size man whose job, apparently, is to take orders from
patrons, jump up on the bar (boing!) and tell the deafened barkeeps
what to mix. This lephrechaun-like go-between then hands the drinks
back to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I was watching some obscure alcoholic Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the surreal sights encountered during a recent
expedition around the night-life circuit, those mythical grounds
behind the velvet ropes, where club owners are constantly juggling
concepts and looks to try to satisfy the city's fickle night
crawlers.
</P>
<P>
   It is brutally competitive terrain, which has recently seen the
arrival of several major contenders for the crown of ``it'' club.
Before everyone who's anyone leaves for the summer, of course. The
roster includes three handsome new downtown establishments, Lotus,
Eugene and Luahn, which have each built good advance buzz with
private parties for gossip column-worthy outfits like Inside.com,
GQ magazine and the talent agency International Management Group.
These three newcomers joined two late 1999 entries, Centro-Fly and
Chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Brazilian-theme danceteria called Saci, which
opened in March off Times Square, and promptly became known as a
favorite spot of Sean Combs, which, of course, can be a mixed
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   With the no-dancing lounge scene feeling more and more tired,
night-life entrepreneurs are diversifying, creating increasingly
ambitious hybrids. Lotus, for example, fuses a restaurant, lounge
and nightclub into a single, three-level space _ divided, of
course, by a velvet rope or three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken a $3.5 million bet that people want to dine,
lounge and dance all in one space,'' said Jeffrey Jah, a former
promoter at the defunct Life nightclub, who is a co-owner of Lotus.
``We want to be everything to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   His partner Mark Baker put it more succinctly: ``You have so
many slightly older guys _ 28 to 40 _ who are most comfortable
sitting in a lounge sipping cocktails and seeing their friends. But
their 22-year-old model girlfriends want to dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Lotus; that is, when it does enter. Originally scheduled
to open in mid-May at 409 West 14th Street, the club is now aiming
for a June 8 opening. ``The policy at the door is to be friendly,''
Jah promised.
</P>
<P>
   This could be a trend. Many seemingly haughty door folk often
defy expectations. Last weekend I found easy, unannounced access to
such roped-off establishments as Serena, Joe's Pub, Moomba, Veruka
and Lot 61.
</P>
<P>
   Not that some places are not still practicing the ancient art of
sidewalk humiliation. For a demonstration of this ego-brutalizing
contact sport, I recommend Halo, a subteranean Greenwich Village
club whose crack two-person door team (he is big, she is blonde)
rejects all who aren't very goodlooking or flashing $5,000 shoulder
bags. Once inside the former after-hours club (49 Grove Street),
the beautiful, multi-racial crowd basks in fine amber lighting and
in the glow of celebrities like Harrison Ford and Taye Diggs.
</P>
<P>
   If you get in, of course. But it was here, on a recent Saturday,
that a bespectacled young man heard four of the most dreaded words
in masculinity: ``No more men tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that I was too upset. With their ever-present promise of
supermodels, $11 cocktails and long lines at the bathroom, many of
these ``scene'' clubs feel interchangeable. (Note to design
departments: There ought to be a permanent ban on red banquettes
and little white table candles.)
</P>
<P>
   After all, there were plenty of other places to go.
</P>
<P>
   I had begun my Cook's tour the night before at Luahn, a
lounge-cum-restaurant on Fifth Avenue near 13th Street. Luahn is
the brainchild of Jason Strauss and Noah Tepperberg, two promoters
in their mid-20s, who also run the club Conscience Point in
Southampton. (Stephen Baldwin, the Baldwin brother in those M&AMP;M
ads, is also a co-owner.)
</P>
<P>
   Already popular with the fashion set, Luahn (59 Fifth Avenue)
easily has the most velvet ropes per square foot of any
establishment in town. Visitors who get past the ropes outside are
immediately greeted by another set leading to the lounge
downstairs, manned by members of some new pro-stubble cult. Once
inside the lounge, there's even a third rope, on the back stairs
leading to and from the bathroom, guarded by an unhappy looking
fellow who apparently didn't know that the Census Bureau is still
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   For all that _ probably because of all that _ the lounge at
Luahn has the feeling of a hot-and-getting-hotter scene. The crowd
was standing-room-only last Friday at 11:30 p.m., as was the line
at the door. Some of that may be the size of the place; the lounge
fits about 50 average-size people comfortably or 75 models.
</P>
<P>
   The decor is minimal: red banquettes, little white table
candles, amber overhead lighting. The single decorative flair is a
series of small, blue-tinted X-rays framed on one wall. And, of
course, the kitchen-cam. Part of Luahn's see-and-be-seen vibe is a
series of small video monitors located around the restaurant and
lounge showing a live feed of the restaurant's kitchen. The idea,
Strauss said, is to allow ``patrons to watch their food prepared.''
Of course. The crudites will be televised.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody was looking at the monitors the night I was
there. Imitating the natives, I slouched behind a small table to
take in the scene, whereupon my cool was immediately under assault
from an over-enthusiastic middle-aged man. A Joe Pesci look-alike
with heavy-rimmed glasses, this gentleman began dancing while still
seated, launching into a sort of head-rolling, shoulder-gyrating
break dance. He looked as if he was being Rolfed.
</P>
<P>
   His suffering, and the overpacked crowd, left me longing for a
quieter, more peaceful domain.
</P>
<P>
   I chose Spa. As they often say in jail, it seemed like a good
idea at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in April, Spa (76 East 13th Street) is the direct
descendant of Life, the popular Bleecker Street dance hall that
closed last year. Several staffers from Life helped establish Spa,
and their influence is felt. The music is loud, the covers steep
and the crowd turnover heavy.
</P>
<P>
   That said, at 1 a.m. on a Saturday morning, there was a swarm of
people seeking admission. A security staff strolled the sidewalk,
warning people to remain in line. There were barricades and beefy
bouncers and vacant-eyed, clipboard-wielding doorwomen.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, on the other hand, the theme is the healing power of
water. Overhead video screens flash underwater scenes, the bar
stocks 16 varieties of bottled water and if you lean against the
slated walls you can hear water running.
</P>
<P>
   Holistic pretensions aside, Spa is all about commotion. Visitors
pack its bars three deep and the lines to the bathrooms (decorated
like saunas, get it?) snake out their doors. The club also traffics
in such notions as a two-bottle minimum (liquor, that is, not
water, at $250 a bottle) for all who wish to occupy its white
leather booths.
</P>
<P>
   In a booth elevated over the dance floor, Grandmaster Flash, the
DJ, lead the crowd through all manner of hip-hop, disco and rap.
The Virgil-like character guiding me and a date through the scene
was a polite fellow named Gianpaolo (``But everyone calls me
J.P.''). He lead us to a booth, one of about a dozen that circle
the main dance floor. ``This area is usually completely filled with
celebrities,'' Gianpaolo said.
</P>
<P>
   I had to take his word for it. I did spy, on the other hand, a
pair of ``American Psycho,'' Wall Street types in the next booth.
What did they think of Spa?
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is bullish,'' one said. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Spa also has a back room, a quieter, classier space where the
minimum-bottle business is less strict and the music is devoted to
rhythm and blues, trance and pop.
</P>
<P>
   We returned to the dance floor, where the crowd continued to
grow, and where I encountered, no kidding, another polyester rope,
this time in front of the bar. There, sitting on top with his legs
dangling, was the gymnastic man whose job it is to take my order.
He heard me out, jumped back atop the bar and efficiently delivered
a small plastic cup of cocktail. Diana Ross was singing, ``I'm
Coming Out.'' I drank my drink and did the same.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   While Spa is the newest, a couple of other recently opened dance
spots offer variations on a similar theme. The red-curtained
environs of Chaos (225 East Houston Street) are impressive, as are
its exotic sounding hideaways _ the Neptune Room, the Red Salon.
But the club also subscribes to the same obnoxious policy requiring
the minimum order of a bottle of pricey Champagne or liquor to
secure a table, and it is often beset by around-the-corner lines.
</P>
<P>
   The motif at work at Centro-Fly, meanwhile, at 45 West 21st
Street, is futurism, which from a decorative standpoint apparently
means Op Art spirals, plentiful plexiglass and a door staff dressed
in orange jump suits.
</P>
<P>
   Centro-Fly, which boasts a state-of-the-art DJ booth, has been a
hot spot since opening in December, drawing big crowds of
electronic music aficionados and just plain dancing fools. The
night I dropped in, the music was high-volume house, accompanied by
eye-dazzling lights. Toward the back is a dark hallway that leads
to the club's restaurant and lounge, a sleek, sedate space where
the walls are painted with a series of perspective-twisting
paintings. (The future, apparently, will not smile on realism.)
</P>
<P>
   It would be an ideal space for nondancers to drink and gossip _
it has a slight Los Angeles feel _ except for the fact that one has
to enter through the dance club, with its $20 cover, to get there.
(If you make a reservation for dinner, the cover is waived.) The
owners say they will soon open a separate entrance. I endorse that
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a complete weekend out, I felt slightly
under-fabulous. There was only one solution: I would Moomba.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the newcomers, for sheer celebrity quotient, the
prize still goes to that mother of all swank lounges, Moomba (133
Seventh Avenue South, near 10th Street). On the Monday night I
visited, the door to the third-floor V.I.P. room was crowded as
usual, with about 15 would-be hipsters bantering for entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, dude,'' said one suited young man to the skinny fellow at
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes?'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dude?'' said the suit, with a lilt in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   He might as well have been saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   The draw on this particular Monday, as it has been for the last
month, was karaoke, that cheesiest of art forms, which has somehow
snuck back intact from suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   The karaoke evening is overseen by Samantha Ronson, the
tomboyish younger sister of the celebrity DJ Mark Ronson. Her idea
for the evening is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get them drunk enough,'' she said, ``and anybody will sing.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd upstairs was wobbling room only, a sight reminiscent
of Moomba's very first days back in 1997, when Leo once juggled
four models at a single table and began work on his second chin. A
small stage is set up near the windows, lighted by a single
rose-colored spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   As I entered, the words of Tommy James' ``Mony Mony'' were
scrolling across the wall, and two buxom blondes were leading the
crowd in a cheer of ``Get laid, Get . . .''
</P>
<P>
   My attention was drawn away by Jeff Gossett, Moomba's
soft-spoken majority owner, who still spends an inordinate amount
of his time shuffling celebrities from door to table and table to
door. He gave me a quick lay of the land: the crowd included the
television talk-show personality Lisa Ling, the actors Liev
Schreiber and James Van Der Beek, the model Yasmine Bleeth, members
of the rock bands the Foo Fighters and the Black Crowes and ``some
of those guys from that show `Popular.'''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   There was also ample evidence of disposable income; a gentleman
to my left put his cigarette out in my drink and offered to buy me
another.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As I stood watching a soulful version of ``New York, New York,''
a well-dressed, bald, snaggle-toothed man approached me, eyed my
notebook and said: ``You should talk to me. I'm a big celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah right, buddy, and I'm the Duchess of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   He asked my name and I asked his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Moby,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it was Moby himself, the multi-platinum DJ, who
told me he is between European and American tours.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a singer by trade, of course, but this is his night;
he was clutching a bulky black notebook with the titles of hundreds
of potential karaoke songs. He had already made his choice: ``What
a Wonderful World'' by Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lure is watching celebrities humiliate themselves,'' he
said, a minute before taking the stage. ``And watching women
pretend to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Moby began to sing in a quivering voice, and for
a few minutes the din subsided. When he finished, the crowd went
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Moby slipped quietly out of the club _ I later spotted him
eating falafel in the East Village _ but the crowd kept cheering
for him.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed happy, having gotten what any decent prowler of the
night demands: an experience they couldn't have had anywhere,
anytime else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
