<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY SHAREHOLDER OF COMMERZBANK SEEKS MERGER OR OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Hansgeorg Hofmann says he is no corporate
raider. But if Hofmann has his way, Germany's fourth biggest bank
will lose its independence.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann, head of a small investment group called Cobra, has
acquired voting rights to 19 percent of the stock in Commerzbank AG
and he arrived at the bank's annual shareholders meeting Friday
with what management regarded as a chilling message.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he had received ``signals'' from potential buyers,
Hofmann warned that the bank's executives should brace for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have consolidation everywhere in the industry, whether you
think that is a good or a bad thing,'' Hofmann said. ``The world is
different now and the banks do not have too much time to reorient
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann is leading the kind of corporate crusade practiced by
Americans like T. Boone Pickins in the 1980s. Marching under the
banner of shareholder value, he has become what amounts to
Commerzbank's biggest shareholder and hopes to engineer a merger or
alliance for the bank that will allow his group to cash out with a
big profit.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra itself has acquired little if any actual stock. But it
says it has obtained options and voting rights to 19 percent and
could raise its share to 30 percent, enough under German law to
veto major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a month of polite exchanges with Hofmann,
Commerzbank's chief executive, Martin Kohlhaussen, denounced him
Friday, calling his assertions dangerous and irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Kohlhaussen was particularly incensed by Hoffman's claim that
Commerzbank's value was about 50 euros a share, far higher than its
current price of 38.11 euros.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual public clash comes more than a month after Cobra
announced it had accumulated a stake in Commerzbank and wanted to
help the bank define its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hofmann said he hoped to increase Cobra's stake
from 9.9 percent to 19 percent. Throughout the process, he has
portrayed his group as interested in mediating a friendly deal, not
a hostile takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann's main partners are Klaus-Peter Schneidewind and Clemens
Vedder, who control Rebon, a Netherlands investment group that is
Cobra's parent company. Schneidewind and Vedder have been involved
in takeovers elsewhere in Europe, but Hofmann, who ran Dresdner
Bank's investment banking business until 1996, is the main
strategist on the Commerzbank investment.
</P>
<P>
   All three men were highly visible at Friday's shareholder
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   They denied any interest in breaking up Commerzbank and selling
it off in pieces, but left little doubt they could apply pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we needed to assemble a blocking minority, it could be
done,'' Hofmann said.
</P>
<P>
   German bank executives have been speculating about possible
buyers. Kohlhaussen recently softened his long-held opposition to
any merger and said he might be open to talks with Dresdner Bank,
Germany's third largest.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner had reached a deal to merge with Deutsche Bank AG,
Germany's biggest bank, but the deal collapsed over the future of
Dresdner's investment banking subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann has suggested that a merger with a foreign institution
would be better for Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
   Many candidates have been rumored, including Citigroup, ABN Amro
of the Netherlands and HSBC Holdings of Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
