<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6899 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-DON-BLUTH:TITAN-A.E.-     05-26 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DON-BLUTH:TITAN-A.E.-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON BLUTH, ON ``TITAN A.E.,'' IS AS ANIMATED AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes photo of Don Bluth, the co-director of ``Titan A.E.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by STARBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though warm as a campfire and always soft-spoken, animator Don
Bluth, the man behind such features as ``The Secret of NIMH''
(1982), ``An American Tail'' (1986), ``All Dogs Go To Heaven''
(1989) and ``Anastasia'' (1998) calls a spade a spade, consequences
be damned.
</P>
<P>
   There's a no-nonsense tone in his voice, an edge that just might
benefit his latest animated epic, ``Titan A.E.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-directed by Bluth and his longtime partner, Gary Goldman,
``Titan, A.E.'' unfolds in 3028, as aliens called the Drej destroy
the Earth, leaving a million survivors stranded in assorted drifter
colonies. One survivor, a cynical 20-year-old name Cale (voice of
Matt Damon), learns that he is genetically coded to be a map that
will lead to the Titan, a ship with the power to create a new
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the earlier films I've done in my career are pretty
much in the area of Disney wannabes,'' Bluth says by telephone from
a screening room in Phoenix, where he's racing to finish the film
in time for its June 16 release. ``They would have a terminal
disease, a terminal disease that I call cute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is very soft and round and cute and harmless.
That's what Disney is. We tried to shift over to an edgier picture
with `Titan A.E.,' one that's not a wannabe. We were hunting for
something that had a little more quills on it, that was more
prickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of digs in the dialogue, a lot of sarcasm.
It's faster paced than most of my films. I don't think people can
look at it and say it's in the Don Bluth style.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluth laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's a good thing or a bad thing,'' he adds.
``I have no objectivity about this film. All I know is that it's
very different from anything I've done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluth and Goldman weren't supposed to make ``Titan A.E.'' They'd
crafted ``Anastasia'' at Fox's fledgling animation facility in
Arizona, followed that up with a direct-to-video sequel, ``Bartok
the Magnificent'' (2000), and then sat empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox president Bill Mechanic then phoned Bluth and Goldman. The
two directors assigned to ``Titan A.E.,'' (then called ``Planet
Ice'') were off the project. Mechanic asked Bluth and Goldman to
pick up the baton, warning that time was of the essence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fewer months than we'd ever had before, but we said,
`If there's nothing else ready, we don't have much choice, do
we?''' Bluth says. ``So we grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And like any good soldier I surrounded myself with sci-fi
brains who seemed to know all the genre movies that had ever been
made. I said, `Tell me why some sci-fi movies are really, really
exciting, why some of them work so well.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bluth, his predecessors had sunk $30 million into
artwork and scripting before he ever put ink to acetate. Damon,
Drew Barrymore, Bill Pullman, Nathan Lane and Janeane Garofalo had
already recorded dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Starting over, however, was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `We're going to take this artwork and reorganize it,
so it's something we can use.' I had a really good art director and
production designer. We shuffled through all of this stuff and
said, `OK, here's what we're going to do.' That seemed to work out
really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, when I got into the picture, it seemed to me that the
entire focus was on the hardware. I thought, `Who wants to look at
just hardware?' I was reminded that a lot of people do. But a movie
to me is about character, about how personalities come together,
how they relate to each other and what the ramifications of that
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back, crammed in more of the character material,
re-recorded some of the dialogue, and now character drives the
story. We were on this film for many months, and even in the last
week, new lines were being written.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that the film is about to be released, Bluth must face
his greatest nemesis: the Mouse House. As it has for ages, Walt
Disney Pictures will pit one of its own animated features directly
against Bluth's. ``Fantasia 2000'' will open nationwide on the same
day ``Titan A.E.'' hits the screens.
</P>
<P>
   One might think there's enough room in the world for a few
animated success stories. Bluth, however, doubts that Disney feels
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would often get angry,'' says Bluth, who toiled for Disney
as an animator on such films as ``Robin Hood'' (1973) and ``Pete's
Dragon'' (1978). ``I used to think, `How could they be so
uncharitable?' But business is business. I think that's the way
they look at it, that all is fair in business and they don't mind
who they kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is the giant. Even though I'm working with Fox, I still
think of myself as the David. Disney has a lot of muscle and I
don't suppose anybody really knows how much muscle they do have.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can block and can do anything they have to do to make
sure they win. And it's all done with a very beautiful veneer, so
no one ever suspects there's anything sinister underneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters further, there's more at stake with ``Titan
A.E.'' than meets the eye. It's conceivable that Fox might give up
on animation entirely if ``Titan A.E.'' tanks. Dreamworks, which
will release ``Chicken Run'' this summer, surely can't abide too
many disappointments along the lines of its most recent effort,
``The Road to El Dorado.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anastasia is in the black at this point, but it didn't really
go out there and change the world one bit,'' Bluth says. ``So we
went in for a second one and I believe everyone is saying, `Well,
if this one doesn't work, then what?'
</P>
<P>
   ``In tandem with what we've been doing is Katzenberg (and
Dreamworks). `Prince of Egypt' was going to blow the world away and
it didn't. It's not in the black yet. Right after that they did
`Road to El Dorado.' It was a little disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless somebody steps up, throws a spear and hits the coconut,
I think we're sort of pronouncing our own doom. It's no secret that
Fox has laid off a lot of our staff. A lot. There were 360 (people)
and it's down to 60. So there's a lot at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``''Titan A.E.,'' consult the
Fox Web site at www.foxmovies.com. And check out The New York Times
Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
