<SLUG> BC-EAGLE'S-DON-HENLEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLE'S DON HENLEY REVEALS HIS WIFE AND KIDS INSPIRED NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color slide of Don Henley.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by STARBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1984, Don Henley _ the once and future singer-drummer
for the Eagles _ lamented in song that there was ``Not Enough Love
in the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, on his first solo album of all-new material in 11 years,
Henley informs us that ``I'm very, very happy/And I know that's not
what you'd expect from me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley isn't kidding. He's been married since 1995 to Sharon
Summerall, a fellow Texas native. Together they moved from
California to a home outside Dallas, where they're raising three
children. He has found a life's calling outside music in the Walden
Woods Project, an environmental preservation organization. And this
year, he and Eagles partner Glenn Frey are being inducted into the
Songwriter's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the spirit of bonhomie saturates Henley's new
album, ``Inside Job.'' There are still plenty of pointed social and
political commentaries amid the 13 tracks, but they're balanced by
songs that celebrate the happy state of his home life, including
``Nobody Else in the World But You,'' ``Taking You Home,''
``Everything is Different Now,'' ``My Thanksgiving'' and
``Annabel,'' a lullaby for his oldest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has certainly had an inspirational effect,'' Henley, 52,
says of his family. ``At the risk of sounding like I've been in
some sort of self-help program _ which I haven't _ I've
rediscovered my better self. I feel in my mind and in my heart like
I did when I was in my early 20s, when I was in college _ and I'm
not drunk or high!''
</P>
<P>
   Henley is quick to add that he's always considered himself an
optimist, and as a songwriter he felt his mission was to point out
that things could be better. But he also acknowledges that the
sweet tenor of ``Inside Job'' will catch off guard those who are
used to the sharp observations of past hits such as ``Dirty
Laundry,'' ``Sunset Grill,'' ``All She Wants to Do is Dance'' and
the Grammy winning ``The End of the Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has crossed my mind that it might not be very well received
or it might even be ridiculed in some quarters,'' says Henley, who
moved to Los Angeles during 1970 with his band, Shiloh, before
joining Linda Ronstadt's band and subsequently forming the Eagles
in 1971. ``But you know, I don't (care) anymore. This woman and
these children have helped me to rediscover myself, and I don't
mind putting that out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a very liberating thing for me. I've gotten so
much strength and courage from my family that I can afford to be
totally open and honest about how I feel. If people like it, great.
And if they don't, that's great, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley has not run out of dragons to slay, however. ``Workin'
It,'' the first single from ``Inside Job,'' offers Henley's take on
the current state of American society. ``They're Not Here, They're
Not Coming'' pokes fun at the the UFO disciples, while ``Damn It,
Rose'' was inspired by a friend's suicide and deals with what
Henley calls ``empty rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   But where those kinds of songs used to dominate his albums and
seep into his other material, Henley feels they don't burn within
him in quite the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can always go home to the children and to the wife and the
world goes away for a little while,'' Henley says. ``That gives me
the strength and the serenity to live with those things. But, yes,
it has heightened my awareness and, yes, it has made me more angry.
But I think that's balanced because my life is more balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley _ who left his former label, Geffen, to move to Warner
Bros. for ``Inside Job'' _ does have a new battle he's waging. He
and some other artists, including his former backup singer Sheryl
Crow, Billy Joel, Bonnie Raitt and Hole's Courtney Love, have
joined forces to combat the music industry and Congress over what
the musicians feel are actions that are being taken to strip them
of their rights to own their work.
</P>
<P>
   Henley explains that the 1976 Copyright Act provided for the
full return of an artist's work to that artist after 35 years. But
the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA), which
represents the record companies, has quietly inserted an amendment
_ tagged on to an unrelated bill _ that re-classified recordings as
work for hire, which allows the labels to own them forever.
</P>
<P>
   This is part of the ``greed fest'' that has followed the recent
spate of entertainment industry mergers, Henley says, and he feels
that ``it's just the first shot across the bow from the record
company. I think they're going to keep on trying to ... cheat
artists out of the rights to their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley expects the amendment to be passed into law, and he
expresses frustration at a lack of willingness he's encountering
from other artists to lend their voices to the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists have managed to get organized for all other causes _
for the rain forest, for the environment in general, for
anti-nukes, for cures for cancer, for the homeless, for hunger ...
all manner of charity work we've done,'' Henley says. ``But we've
never been able to get our s--t together for ourselves. And we're
getting reamed in Washington by the record companies, by the
Internet companies, by big business in general. If we're not
careful we're going to sleep through it and have all our rights
taken from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want this younger generation of rock 'n' roll artists
(to join the cause). I know they resent a lot of us '70s artists. I
know (Smashing Pumpkins leader) Billy Corgan doesn't think very
highly of people like me. But whether they like me or my generation
or not, there's work to be done in the artistic community, and in
the world community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they all develop a social conscience at some point,''
he adds. ``They probably have one, but there's a lot of ways you
can waste your time thinking you're doing good things. There's a
lot of causes out there, but some are more important than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Any conversation with Henley, of course, winds its way into the
Eagles, the iconic Rock and Roll Hall of Fame group whose 1976
collection ``Their Greatest Hits 1971-1975'' has been the
biggest-selling album in U.S. history. The group dissolved amid
much acrimony during the early '80s but came back together during
1994 for a successful reunion tour that spanned two years.
</P>
<P>
   It also started work on a new studio album last year, but Henley
says a combination of factors conspired to put the Eagles on the
backburner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really at a point in my album where I thought I could
divide my time and my attention and my creativity between my
project and that project, and I found I couldn't do it,'' Henley
says. ``My album had to take priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, frankly, I don't think (the Eagles' album) was going
very well. We were definitely headed down the track towards making
a very mediocre record, and I think we needed some distance from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Don Henley, consult the Warner
Bros. Records Web site at www.wbr.com/donhenley. And check out The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;  &QL;
</P>
