<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOSHIBA-CHINA-NYT &LR;      05-26 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOSHIBA-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S TOSHIBA LAPTOP USERS ANGRY THEY WEREN'T OFFERED SETTLEMENT
DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Toshiba Corp.'s settlement of a class-action
lawsuit in the United States last year has backfired in China,
where consumers are charging discrimination because the Japanese
electronics maker has not offered them the same deal.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba, the world's largest supplier of laptop computers,
startled the industry last October by agreeing to pay American
consumers as much as $2.1 billion in compensation for laptops made
before November with a flawed computer chip that controls the
floppy disk drive. The settlement was meant to head off potentially
devastating damages from the class-action suit, which was brought
by two Texans.
</P>
<P>
   The company also offered a software patch to fix the problem for
Toshiba laptop owners worldwide, but that has not satisfied Chinese
consumers, who are ever ready to discern a slight from their
wartime aggressors. The Chinese want to be compensated, too, even
though no lawsuit has yet been brought in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel quite angry, they're being very unreasonable,'' said
Wang Jialiang, a Shanghai sales manager for Legend Holdings Ltd.,
Toshiba's only authorized distributor in China. Wang said he had
e-mailed friends to spread the word of what he called Toshiba's
misdeeds, and had even berated some Japanese. Toshiba is China's
leading laptop supplier, having sold 200,000 of the machines in the
country in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Resentment of Japan remains deep in China and commercial
disputes between the two countries can quickly flare into
nationalistic bickering. The Japanese are vilified on each
anniversary of the Imperial Army's rape and massacre of civilians
in Nanjing. And it is not uncommon for Chinese to tell Westerners
of their hatred for Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   But besides the nationalistic sentiments involved, Toshiba's
trouble in China reflects the legal naivete of Chinese consumers in
a country that is still developing the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   The problem began when Toshiba failed to fix an error in the
microcode of a chip designed by NEC Corp. In rare circumstances,
the flaw could cause users to lose data while saving it to a floppy
disk, although Toshiba says it has not heard of that happening on
any of the 15 million laptops it has sold worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the company decided it would be less costly and
better for public relations to settle the suit brought by the two
men in Texas rather than go through a costly, drawn-out legal fight
that it might lose.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long before word of the settlement was making its way
through Chinese Web sites and chat rooms and Chinese indignation
began to build. Earlier this month, China's state-run media picked
up the complaint with headlines like ``No compensation angers
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the company dispatched a vice president and other
executives to Beijing to try to repair the damage. But they got
little sympathy with their explanation that the flaw had not caused
any data loss that the company was aware of and that the American
settlement was a legal maneuver for that country only.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toshiba has tried to save the situation, but they're using
irresponsible methods,'' said a front-page article in China
Business Times on Tuesday. The China Consumer Journal dismissed the
executives' efforts, saying ``Toshiba's apology was not sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba's China headquarters in Beijing declined to comment on
the matter other than to say through a spokesman that the company
was still discussing the matter. But China's government-sponsored
Consumers Association said Toshiba had violated China's consumer
law with its delay in notifying Chinese consumers of the problem.
The announcement and instructions for fixing the potential problem
were posted in English on the company's Web sites but not until the
controversy grew were they posted in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups of Toshiba laptop owners in China are considering
a lawsuit against the company, according to the state media. Sales
of Toshiba laptops, meanwhile, have slumped. Wang of Legend said he
was not pushing the brand and on occasion had even inflated the
price to discourage people from buying the computers. ``I tell
people to buy IBM and HP,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
