</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO'S SAY STOCKS' DOWNTURN NOT OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors in stocks have endured a lot of pain since the markets
peaked a few months back. With the Dow Jones industrial average
down 10 percent for the year, and the Nasdaq composite down more
than twice that, investors are probably wondering when all this
agony will be over.
</P>
<P>
   Not just yet, according to L. Keith Mullins, head of emerging
growth research at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins believes the bloodletting in stocks will not be stanched
until investor fervor for initial public offerings goes completely
cold.
</P>
<P>
   The number of new stock offerings has dropped considerably in
recent weeks _ only 23 companies have offered shares to the public
in May, down from 65 in March, according to Richard Peterson, chief
market strategist at Thomson Financial Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse for investors, 61 percent of this year's new issues
are trading below their offering prices. ``It's ugly out there,''
Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Not ugly enough, according to Mullins. As long as there is any
life in the market for new company shares, he thinks stocks as a
whole remain vulnerable. Last Thursday's offering of Sonus Networks
shares indicates the IPO market still has a pulse. Sonus offered 5
million shares to the public at $23 each, and the stock closed its
first day of trading at $50.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``An enormous amount of damage has been done to investor
psyches,'' Mullins said. ``But the new-issue market continues to be
fairly resilient. My expectation is we will see the market continue
to be much more selective about what issues will be brought out.
The window will shut completely before the correction is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins bases this view on 20 years of initial public offering
data. New stock issues, he has found, are a perfect measurement of
investor sentiment. ``It's when investors know the least about the
companies and the information has been structured to have maximum
appeal,'' he explained. ``When investors are wildly bullish, you
can put anything through the channel. When they are bearish, if you
had a company turning dirt to gold, people would say gold is going
down.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Mullins thinks we still have a way to go in the
correction is that prices of new issues on their first day out are
still popping like champagne corks.
</P>
<P>
   During April and most of May, Mullins said, first-day gains in
IPO's averaged 13 percent. While that is well below the 109 percent
average pop seen last December, it is still above the average for
1994 through 1998, when the figure was 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And while the number of deals has declined in recent weeks, it
has not fallen enough for Mullins. Around the 1987 crash, for
example, the average number of deals each month fell from 63 to 9.
And during the Long Term Capital Management crisis in the fall of
1998, the number of deals fell from 53 monthly to 15. So the 23
stocks issued so far in May looks a bit high.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one piece of Mullins' data may indicate we are close to
the correction's end. That is the difference between a new stock's
offering price and the middle of the price range company management
expected when they presented their deal to investors.
</P>
<P>
   When investors are euphoric for new issues, the stocks typically
fetch prices well above the expected range. Last January, for
instance, the average IPO's price was an astonishing 45 percent
above the middle of the expected range. By comparison, between 1994
and 1998, the average IPO came out at a price 0.1 percent below the
middle of the expected range.
</P>
<P>
   This month, however, IPO's have been pricing at 30 percent below
the midpoint. Mullins said this was the lowest monthly average he
has seen in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the IPO market has further to cool before Mullins will be
convinced that the correction in stock prices is over. When
investor appetite for new issues disappears altogether, he said, be
on the alert for a ripping rally in small and mid-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
