<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 FUNDS ARE RELEASED FOR U.N. PEACEKEEPING IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., has released his hold on
$40 million in State Department funds appropriated for a U.N.
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, his spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's spokesman, Ed Amorosi, said Gregg decided to lift
his hold after the Senate defeated a measure to set a deadline for
withdrawing U.S. ground troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregg continues to use his power as chairman of a Senate
appropriations subcommittee to block the transfer of $328 million
in peacekeeping funds for U.N. missions in East Timor, Sierra Leone
and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg met on Wednesday with Richard C. Holbrooke, U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, to discuss his objections to the
release of the money. They reached no agreement, Amorosi said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on the Senate floor, Gregg explained that he was
blocking the peacekeeping money because of his strong objections to
a peace accord signed between the combatants in Sierra Leone, which
gave amnesty and a share of power to rebels who have murdered and
mutilated thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   Backing a peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone, Gregg said, was
tantamount to ``endorsing a policy that brought into power people
who had committed rape, murder and atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy being pursued in Sierra Leone was misdirected from
the start,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not have been making peace,'' he added. ``We should
have been taking a harder line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
