<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      05-26 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, May 27 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Less than three years after a plunge
in the value of Thailand's currency triggered an economic crisis
across much of Asia, the region is riding a wave of growth
reminiscent of the Asian miracle of the 1980s. The latest evidence
of the resurgence came Friday with a report that Hong Kong's
economic output rose 14.3 percent in the first three months of the
year. It was the territory's fastest quarter of growth since 1987.
Other Asian economies are growing at rates much faster than even
the most optimistic forecasters had predicted _ powered, to a large
extent, by a booming demand for its exports to the hot economy in
the United States. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ In an important advance against
diabetes, researchers in Canada are reporting that transplants of
insulin-producing cells have enabled eight patients with a severe
form of the disease to stop taking insulin injections. Two to 14
months after being transplanted in a simple procedure resembling a
tranfusion, the cells are still working in all eight patients, half
of whom were treated almost a year ago at the University of
Alberta. The patients, who had Type 1 diabetes, in which the body
produces little or no insulin of its own, no longer have any
symptoms of the disease. Although they no longer need insulin to
control their blood sugar, they now must take other drugs to
prevent rejection of the transplants. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-INSURNACE (Undated) _ After falling for two years, car
insurance premiums around the country are climbing once again,
resuming a steady quarter-century rise. Several big insurers _
including Progresssive, Geico, State Farm and Allstate _ have begun
putting higher prices into effect, and analysts say that by the end
of the year most other leading companies are likely to follow suit.
They cited rising expenses for repairs and treatment of injuries.
By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ENVIRON (Assateague Island, Md.) _ President Clinton
signed an executive order Friday directing the EPA to develop Clean
Water Act regulations that reduce pollution of beaches, coasts and
ocean waters. In addition, EPA will identify areas where additional
protections are needed and possibly recommend that onshore and
offshore activities that generate pollution be restricted or
prohibited. (Summary from wires) By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WENDYS-MURDER (New York) _ Mayor Rudy Giuliani announced
Friday that the police are seeking a convicted felon with a history
of robbing fast-food restaurants in the murders of five people at a
Wendy's restaurant in Queens. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT11,12.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BUTTER (Vologda, Russia) _ As any gourmand around here
will tell you, there are but two types of butter in Russia. There
is ordinary, bland butter, bought by ordinary, bland people and
consumed on ordinary, bland occasions. And there is Vologda Butter.
Vologodskoye Maslo: The name fairly trips off the tongue _ the
Russian tongue, anyway. This is butter so cultured that it was
originally called Parisian butter, even though it is made in
Vologda oblast, a vaguely Massachusetts-shaped, almost New
York-sized province 250 miles northeast of Moscow. This is
expensive butter. This is also profitable butter. This is why some
scruple-deprived people are making counterfeit Vologda Butter, and
pawning it off on hapless Russians as the Real Thing. And this is
why Vladimir Mizgirev is angry. By Michael Wines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
