<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BUSTAMANTE-PARDON-HNS     05-26 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSTAMANTE-PARDON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OUSTED TEXAS CONGRESSMAN LOBBIES FOR PRESIDENTIAL PARDON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT FLORES  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It has been eight years since Albert Bustamante
strolled the chambers of Capitol Hill, glad-handing with fellow
members of the House of Representative.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Bustamante, in his second year out of prison
after serving 32 months for federal racketeering and bribery
convictions, was back on the House floor shaking hands, this time
trying to drum up support from his former colleagues in an effort
to secure a presidential pardon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go to my grave saying I never committed a crime,''
Bustamante said. ``All my life, from the time I was a schoolboy
fighting segregation, I've fought for my civil rights. How can I
not fight this?''
</P>
<P>
   But the 65-year-old's appearance on the House floor was met with
a tepid response, even among some fellow Democrats, and it was a
far cry from the spirited receptions he routinely encounters when
visiting former constituents at gatherings on San Antonio's South
and West sides.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bustamante said he was greeted warmly by some House
members, others criticized the former four-term congressman,
suggesting his visit _ and his quest for signatures on a resolution
for the pardon _ was a self-serving lobbying effort and represented
at the very least a breach of decorum.
</P>
<P>
   Still others said Bustamante's action may have violated
congressional rules that allow former members to be heard on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this disgraced former member of Congress is doing is flat
out wrong, and his former colleagues ought to put an end to his
improper entreaties,'' said Charles Lewis, executive director of
the Center for Public Integrity, a Washington-based nonprofit,
nonpartisan organization that concentrates on ethics and
public-service issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante balked at the notion, saying once a member of
Congress, always a member.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments aside, Bustamante's trip to Washington represented
perhaps his best shot at clearing his name. Observers say his
chances of winning a pardon under President Clinton, albeit slim,
are better than they would be if a Republican were in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   As of October, Clinton had granted 161 presidential pardons over
his two terms. But that represented only 2.5 percent of the
applications his office had received seeking pardons. Using that
rate as a barometer, Clinton has been less prone to granting
clemency applications than his predecessors going back to Gerald
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Largely ceremonial, presidential pardons effectively clear a
felon's record after time is served. The right to vote, run for
office, carry firearms and certain licensing privileges _ otherwise
lost upon federal conviction _ also are restored, officials with
the Justice Department and U.S. attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has declined to name them, Bustamante said he picked
up signatures from 16 former colleagues. He plans to use those and
others he might obtain in a petition he will forward to the
president's staff in the next three or four weeks. The signatures
aren't required for the pardon, but Bustamante believes they could
help his cause.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it could be years before Bustamante's request may be
reviewed. The Justice Department, which weighs pardon requests,
historically has considered such petitions five years after an
inmate's release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   The effort represents an about-face for the former congressman,
who previously had said he wouldn't accept a pardon if it were
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante's political career began to unravel before he was
indicted. When word leaked of the federal probe into his business
dealings, the adverse publicity severely damaged his bid for a
fifth congressional term. Bustamante was defeated in 1992 by Henry
Bonilla, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted in 1993 of accepting a $35,000 bribe to help a food
services company win a new contract from Lackland Air Force Base
and for illegally receiving a $20,000 loan underwritten by his
partners in a business deal that could have netted him hundreds of
thousands of dollars more and the promise of future loans,
Bustamante steadfastly has maintained his innocence.``There are a
lot of people out there who come up to me and say, `You were
screwed,''' Bustamante said.
</P>
<P>
   He also maintains other House members have engaged in conduct
far more egregious without being charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bustamante may have trouble currying favor even with
Democrats in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles A. Gonzalez, a freshman House member and the son of
longtime Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, for whom Bustamante once worked as
an aide, said he would be reluctant to support a resolution for a
presidential pardon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically undoing something that another branch of
government has done, and, if you trust the system, the judge should
have known more about the case than the president or anyone else,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bustamante lives in The Dominion, a posh development in
San Antonio. He manages a strip center on the South Side and still
fields calls from former constituents who need help with their
personal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert has had a long public service career, and regardless of
what transpired, the bottom line is he was always available to the
people, and that's what they appreciated about him,'' said Walter
Martinez, a former city councilman who, with Bustamante at his
side, ran unsuccessfully for county commissioner earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
