A6954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DEATH-TEXAS27-COX     05-26 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-TEXAS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS DEATH ROW INMATE DESERVES NEW TRIAL, PROTESTERS SAY
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill., and former boxer
Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter said Friday a Texas inmate due to be
executed next month deserves a new chance to prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, our criminal justice system has been fraught with
errors, and there is a strong risk that innocent persons may be
condemned to die,'' Jackson said at a Capitol Hill news conference.
``I appeal to Governor George W. Bush and the Texas Board of
Pardons to grant Gary Graham clemency.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham is ``a man who has clear evidence of his innocence, has
not had a hearing yet, and is scheduled to die,'' said Carter. ``We
cannot ask for a perfect punishment coming form an imperfect
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who spent 19 years in prison on a murder conviction
before he was proved innocent, was the subject of the film ``The
Hurricane,'' starring Denzel Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 36, is to be executed June 22 for the murder of a man in
1981. He was identified by a witness at his trial as the killer,
and courts have reviewed his case 35 times.
</P>
<P>
   However, his attorney, Richard Burr, said he found witnesses and
evidence that could absolve Graham. Burr said the bullet that
killed the man could not have been shot by the .22-caliber gun
belonging to Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried endlessly to get courts to hear this evidence,''
Burr said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear Graham's latest appeal
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson introduced a bill in April calling for a seven-year
national moratorium on all executions until death row inmates have
an opportunity to restate their cases. Noting cases in which
innocent people have been convicted of capital crimes, Jackson said
the bill would save the lives of Graham and ``other innocent
persons'' sitting on death row.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking for immediate consideration of the moratorium.
That does not mean to free everybody on death row. It does not mean
let everybody get out of jail. But it certainly means no execution
should occur until everyone on death row has an opportunity to
present their case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson appealed to President Clinton and Attorney General Janet
Reno to instruct the Justice Department to send the Supreme Court a
``friend of the court'' brief on behalf of Graham.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush should not allow the possibility of executing an
innocent person.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can grant a 30-day delay in an execution if a majority of
the Texas Board of Pardons recommends it.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor can not commute a sentence if the board does
not recommend it, said Mike Jones, a spokesman for the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Jones noted that Graham received a commutation from Gov. Ann
Richards in 1993, but added that it does not bar him from
requesting another.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
