<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FUEL-CELLS-ART-2TAKES     05-26 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUEL-CELLS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H., N.J., N.Y.)  
 FUEL CELLS MOVE SLOWLY BUT SURELY TOWARD BECOMING BIG BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 13 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Jeff Colborn plunged into fusion energy
research in the late 1980s, first at the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory and then at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, filled with idealism about fusion's potential for
revolutionizing nuclear power generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the toughest challenge,'' said Colborn, recalling the
goals he had after studying engineering and physics at the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   But the entrepreneurial Colborn, who founded a business during
high school selling decals for the motorcycles he and his friends
raced, fretted that it could take 50 years before anyone could
build a business on fusion. No wonder he is more at home these days
as founder and chief executive of Metallic Power Inc., a
little-known entrant in the intense race to design and manufacture
fuel cells, low-pollution devices that generate electrical current
from chemical reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are similar in many ways to batteries, fuel cells
can be quickly regenerated by pumping in new chemical fuel. And
unlike fusion, they are teetering on the edge of becoming big
business. Several hundred units have been sold already, and some
analysts predict a billion-dollar market by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The last steps are not coming easily, though. No one is making
money yet, and the technology is not ready for potential home-run
markets, like power for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel cell companies' slow path highlights the difficulties
of innovating for the nuts-and-bolts dimension of the economy.
Though this is not the fusion world it is also not the Internet
world, where new services can be up and running within weeks and
barriers to entry are low.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have gotten used to the pace of change of information
technology,'' said Vincent R. Shiely, a vice president who oversees
new ventures _ including a research partnership with Metallic Power
_ at Briggs &AMP; Stratton Corp., the largest manufacturer of
nonautomotive gasoline engines. ``But this is pushing the frontier
of materials, and there are still basic technology and reliability
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuel cell companies are developing everything from replacements
for tiny batteries like those used in cell phones and hearing aids
to highly efficient power plants big enough to fit the needs of
electric utility companies.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is to come up with answers to conflicting demands
for, among other things, lightness, reliability, durability and low
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Metallic Power has been slowed down by annoyingly mundane
problems like making its early designs leak-proof. But there have
also been scarier roadblocks, as when Colborn and Stuart I.
Smedley, his chief technology officer, reached the painful
conclusion that a system they had adapted from other researchers
for converting wastes back into recyclable fuel was hopelessly
unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   Smedley, a former university professor from New Zealand,
eventually came up with a new design that was much simpler,
one-tenth the size, and, perhaps best of all, something that
Metallic Power's lawyer believes is patentable. But it took many
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiplying the ideal time for each stage by two has turned
out to be a pretty accurate predictor of what actually happens,''
Colborn said. ``Our schedule has stretched.''
</P>
<P>
   Metallic Power was founded in 1995 but did not produce its
first, primitive prototype until late 1997. The company faces steep
challenges. Not only is it a relative newcomer with far less
capital than many others; it is also using zinc as its fuel, a
radically different approach.
</P>
<P>
   Several venture capitalists unfamiliar with the energy business
got cold feet after looking closely at Colborn's plans. Among them
was a restaurant owner. ``I spent a lot of time driving to L.A. and
eating in his restaurant,'' Colborn said, but the prospect dropped
out when it came time to sign a check. ``Everybody thinks fuel
cells are cool, but when they get into it they discover they know
nothing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colborn got a better reception from energy-focused investors
like Robert W. Shaw Jr., president of Arete Corp., an investment
firm based in Center Harbor, N.H., that manages money for
utilities. ``Every fuel cell company is struggling with similar
problems,'' said Shaw, whose firm's fuel cell investments include
$2 million of the $8.6 million Metallic Power has raised in two
rounds of financing. ``At the end of the day, this company is going
to make something, and it could have a long-term, sustainable
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The payoff for fuel cell innovators could be breathtaking,
especially if someone can create products that meet the performance
needs of the auto industry. ``As soon as someone has a system that
operates in all environments at the cost of combustion engines,
which is about $50 per kilowatt, it will take over the world,''
said Patrick Grimes, an energy consultant in Scotch Plains, N.J.
``Some cell system will get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Colborn's company is focusing first on market niches that can
afford far higher prices per kilowatt and are more likely to
generate near-term profits, starting with portable generators for
homes and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   History supports a cautious approach. Fuels cells were described
in concept as far back as 1839, but when it came to designing
products, other power sources _ from batteries to internal
combustion engines to steam turbines _ always seemed to have a
better cost-benefit mix.
</P>
<P>
   So far, fuel cells' only big success has been on space missions,
where cells have been used for more than 30 years and cost has been
a negligible concern. But there has been renewed interest in recent
years, spurred by new electronic controls, better understanding of
which chemicals would make the best fuel cells and, perhaps most
important, government research grants and stricter environmental
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the interest has been focused on hydrogen-based
designs. Most hydrogen cells extract hydrogen from hydrocarbons
like gasoline, natural gas or methane. The purified hydrogen reacts
with oxygen drawn from the air to create electricity and water
vapor.
</P>
<P>
   Metallic Power, however, is working instead with zinc, which
produces electricity and zinc oxide, a harmless powder used in
cosmetics, when suspended in an alkaline liquid and then exposed to
oxygen. Zinc/air cells, as they are called, are in theory simpler
and cheaper than their hydrogen counterparts, according to Colborn.
Others companies experimenting with zinc/air fuel cells include
zinc/air battery makers like EVonyx Inc., a subsidiary of Reveo
Inc., in Elmsford, N.Y., and Electric Fuel Ltd. of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Zinc's biggest disadvantage is that nothing can match the
infrastructure already in place for distributing hydrogen.
Automotive fuel cells based on hydrogen, for example, could be
refueled by today's gas stations with relatively modest changes.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrogen-based fuel cells are the only commercially available
products, and numerous new variants are well down the development
path.
</P>
<P>
   The company most in the Wall Street spotlight is Ballard Power
Systems Inc., a publicly traded Canadian company that is 25 percent
owned by DaimlerChrysler. In recent months, Ballard has shipped a
stationary, 250-kilowatt fuel cell generator to European utilities
for testing; introduced an improved, compact version of its first
automotive cell, which Ford Motor is testing; and announced a
partnership with Sunbeam Corp.'s Coleman Powermate unit, a big
distributor of portable electric generators, to develop a
co-branded fuel cell.
</P>
<P>
   A newer entrant, Plug Power Inc. of Latham, N.Y., is developing
refrigerator-sized cells that run on natural gas or propane for use
as home power sources. Plug Power went public in October at $15 a
share and soared to a high of $149.75 on March 10. But investors
fled after a dose of reality about the pace of development: The
company passed a deadline without meeting design requirements of
the General Electric Co., a joint venture partner, which was to buy
485 cells. Shares ended Friday at $39.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Multinational companies have largely been participating as
investors and partners but some multinationals are more directly
involved. United Technologies Corp. owns International Fuel Cells
of South Windsor, Conn., the developer of the fuel cells used on
space missions and a stationary power system that has been
installed in more than 200 commercial and institutional sites. And
Siemens of Germany, with support from the Department of Energy, is
field-testing a high-temperature hydrogen cell that could operate
in tandem with gas turbines at power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Metallic Power, by contrast, is not scheduled to deliver its
first testing prototypes to partners like Briggs &AMP; Stratton and
potential customers like the Army by the end of the year. Its more
immediate goal is to complete a demonstration unit by July that
will show how a portable cell for backup power can be kept running
when fuel runs out simply by popping a new fuel cartridge in place.
The target audience is venture capitalists; Metallic Power hopes to
raise an additional $10 million to $15 million by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent staff meeting, Colborn and three other senior
managers pored over a chart showing the breakdown of the fuel cell
into scores of components. They pondered where weight could be cut
by design changes. Weight was not a concern for the July goals, but
promises had been made to Briggs and others about the year-end
prototypes, and Colborn wanted assurances the July unit could be
finished without compromising delivery of the prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   Colborn is also juggling the demands of raising capital, nearly
doubling his work force to about 50 by the end of the year and
moving to larger quarters. He is determined to move methodically,
arguing that in the turbulent world of fuel cells, Metallic Power
is not as far behind the hydrogen companies as it looks if the
finish line is defined as profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are ahead of us in what they've put in the field, but
they are too expensive,'' he said, predicting that Metallic Power
will be among the first to become profitable if it meets its goals
of commercial sales in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Colborn is quick to concede, though, that the hydrogen cell
designers are bringing down costs. ``Realistically,'' he said,
``the best thing that could happen for us is that they succeed _
but not a whole lot sooner than us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
