<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AUTO-INSURANCE-ART-2T     05-26 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-INSURANCE-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURANCE PREMIUMS ARE ON THE RISE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After falling for two years, car insurance premiums around the
country are climbing once again, resuming a steady quarter-century
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Several big insurers _ including Progressive, Geico, State Farm
and Allstate _ have begun imposing higher prices, and analysts say
that most other leading companies are likely to follow suit by the
end of the year. The insurers said they were forced to act by
rising expenses for repairs and treatment of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is clearly upward,'' said Thomas V. Cholnoky, who
follows auto insurance for Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   While the size of the increases has varied widely _ and some
companies are still cutting prices _ rises of at least 4 and 5
percent have not been uncommon. And a few companies have raised
prices in some states by more than 10 percent. Analysts and
industry executives say they expect more of the same next year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In New York and Connecticut, the first signs of the shift are
appearing. But the situation is less clear in New Jersey, where
spending on car insurance _ averaging $1,150 a year, compared with
$700 nationally _ has been the highest in the country. Last year
the legislature took the unusual step of ordering a 15 percent cut
in prices.
</P>
<P>
   While expenses for insurers may well be rising in New Jersey, as
elsewhere, industry executives said it was difficult to predict
whether those costs would be offset by legislative changes aimed at
reducing fraud and litigation and, if not, to what extent political
leaders would permit price increases.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say the increases may not be justified. J.
Robert Hunter, director of insurance at the Consumer Federation of
America, said that while some costs are rising, expenses for
insurers, overall, are still declining.
</P>
<P>
   Americans spent an estimated $126 billion last year on car
insurance, which is mandatory in all states. That was nearly four
times what they paid to insure their homes. There are many more
claims involving cars and passengers than for homes, though, and
liability claims in the hundreds of thousands of dollars are much
more common in car crashes than in incidents related to homes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides raising prices, insurers are reducing or eliminating
discounts and screening applicants more carefully so they can apply
the highest rates to the riskiest drivers and simply refuse to sell
to some. Several companies have also been hacking away at
administrative expenses, which in some cases has meant layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say that to make sure they are getting the
best deal as prices are rising, people should review their bills
and check prices with several companies. But rather than basing
coverage decisions on price alone, the advocates advise people to
talk with friends and insurance regulators to learn how different
companies treat customers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prices for auto insurance fell 3.2 percent last year and 2.8
percent the year before after rising steadily since 1973, said
Robert P. Hartwig, chief economist at the Insurance Information
Institute, an industry group in New York. Insurers said at the time
that they cut their prices to reflect falling costs for claims.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer and less serious accidents were occurring, partly because
of safety features like air bags and anti-lock brakes. There had
also been declines in drunken driving and auto theft, and signs
that aging baby boomers were becoming safer drivers. Hartwig said
body shop costs and medical expenses had leveled off.
</P>
<P>
   While many of those trends are continuing, Hartwig said, their
financial benefits are being eclipsed by a resurgence in costs for
repairs and treatment of injuries. He said repair costs are up
partly because many companies stopped using generic replacement
parts after State Farm was sued by consumers last fall and ordered
to pay $1.2 billion for not using original manufacturers' parts.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Stoddard, a top executive at Safeco, the nation's 15th
largest insurer, said that while the number of accidents was still
declining, ``the severity is up.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said: ``The new cars are smarter and more expensive
to repair. And people are more expensive to repair; we call that
medical inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he had no doubt that the insurers' costs per
accident were going up. ``But,'' he said, ``the number of accidents
is falling faster than the increase in costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Safeco, which reported a nearly $40 million loss in its auto
insurance business in the first quarter, has increased rates in 20
states so far this year, from just under 1 percent in Colorado to
8.2 percent in Michigan. Last year it cut prices in 18 states.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest companies _ State Farm and Allstate _ are still
cutting rates in more states than they are raising them, but they,
too, are showing the early signs of a shift. Last year, State Farm
cut rates in 48 states and increased prices in only one,
Massachusetts. So far this year, State Farm says it is cutting
rates in 15 states and increasing them in 10, including a 5.6
percent rise in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm is seeking a decrease of nearly 5 percent in
California, the state with the most drivers. But Cholnoky said that
an analysis of rates in California showed that State Farm's prices
had been among the highest in the state, 31 percent higher than
Allstate's and 55 percent higher than Progressive's.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Allstate has raised prices in two states _
Louisiana and South Carolina; last year there were no increases.
While it trimmed rates in 10 states last year, cuts this year have
been put into effect in four states.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where regulators have taken steps to ease costs for
insurers, just as they did in New Jersey, one of the largest
companies, Progressive, has raised rates 4.3 percent _ in contrast
to a decrease of 4.1 percent last year. Nineteen small companies
have put in place increases ranging from less than 1 percent to
18.6 percent; six other small companies cut prices. In Connecticut,
one of the largest insurers, Nationwide Mutual, increased prices by
4.9 percent and six other insurers have come in with smaller
increases. Five small insurers cut prices. Last year price
decreases outnumbered increases nearly 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   One small New Jersey company, GSA, has raised premiums 15
percent, and several others New Jersey insurers are also asking
regulators for even higher increases. But John Tiene, executive
director of the Insurance Council of New Jersey, said these
increases had been requested two years ago and did not reflect
current expenses. The increase for GSA, however, had the effect of
nullifying the 15 percent legislative rollback.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, Progressive and Geico have been leading a
price war and gaining market share at the expense of companies like
State Farm and Allstate, which have been either losing market share
or merely holding even as the number of drivers has been growing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, both Progressive and Geico, after suffering significant
losses in earnings, are shifting toward higher prices. Since last
year, for example, Progressive has increased prices by an average
of 7.4 percent in 41 states, according to Charles B. Gates, an
insurance analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston. Progressive has
raised rates about 4 percent in Missouri and is asking for an
increase of 9.9 percent in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As it announced an underwriting loss of $86 million in the first
quarter of this year, Geico said it expected to increase rates in
many states, but gave no details. Geico is a unit of Berkshire
Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said the increase in prices by Progressive and Geico,
which have been the fastest-growing big insurers, were likely to be
taken as a sign by other insurers that it was safe to raise prices.
Previously, he said, the others may have feared that price
increases would drive customers to Progressive and Geico.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said they expected State Farm and Allstate to
raise prices more slowly than other big companies because over the
previous two years they had reduced their prices less than many
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said that in their zeal to capture market share,
Progressive and Geico might have cut prices too much for their own
good. ``Those companies might have to raise rates,'' he said. ``But
some companies may be taking advantage of this opportunity to raise
their rates. I'm saying, `Wait a minute. You don't need to raise
your rates. You should be continuing to lower them.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
