<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REL-GREEK27-COX     05-26 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REL-GREEK27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Archbishop Demetrios, head of the 1.5 million Greek Orthodox
Christians in America, visits Atlanta
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ask Sandy Papadopoulos, ``How's business,'' and he's
likely to say, ``Thank God, everything's well.''
</P>
<P>
   He means it. As a reminder of their faith, his parents devoted a
section of their popular Athens, Ga., Pizza restaurant in DeKalb
County's Druid Hills community to religious iconography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do is a reminder of our faith,'' said
Papadopoulos, 26, who runs the restaurant with his parents John and
Asiemoula. And, he said, ``Anything and everything we do revolves
around the Greek community.''
</P>
<P>
   The two come together at the Cathedral of the Annunciation,
Atlanta's largest Orthodox Christian church. The cathedral is also
the seat of Bishop Alexios, head of the Greek Orthodox Diocese of
Atlanta, which is composed of about 30,000 Greek Orthodox families
across the Southeastern states. The Papadopouloses, who moved to
Atlanta in 1973, are one of about 1,400 families who make up the
cathedral's growing congregation.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the city's Greek Orthodox Christians are
strengthening their community ties by breaking ground on a new
family life and recreation center on the cathedral grounds. Besides
recreation and workout facilities, the new buildings will house the
cathedral's Greek language school and other cultural classes,
including Greek dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of growth in our cathedral, a lot of activity,''
said the Rev. Mike Kouremetis, dean of the cathedral. ``We've
noticed an influx in the community from conversion and people
moving into the area. Ever since the Iron Curtain fell and people
are traveling, we have people here from Georgia, Bulgaria, Russia.
It's becoming a pan-Orthodox cathedral. We're bursting at the
seams.''
</P>
<P>
   For longtime Atlanta Greek families, new converts to Orthodox
Christianity, and newly arrived immigrants, the church offers a
home base, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that our ministry is from the cradle to the grave,''
said Kouremetis. ``Looking at the Greek culture, the European
culture and how this country was established, one of the first
things people created was the church. They built their neighborhood
around the church. The church becomes the focal point, the
beacon.''
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral is not only a spiritual center, but a place for
cultural expression and education, he said. The family life center
will expand that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to keep in touch with your roots,'' said Steve
Alexander, a third-generation Greek American who is president of
the cathedral's parish council. ``We're all Americans, but we still
pay homage to our homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over the groundbreaking will be Archbishop Demetrios,
head of the 1.5 million Greek Orthodox Christians in America.
Demetrios, 71, was enthroned Sept. 18 after a tumultuous reign of
three years by his predecessor, Archbishop Spyridon.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accused Spyridon of mismanaging church funds, ignoring
reports of sexual misconduct at the church's seminary in
Massachusetts, and attempting to run the church autocratically.
After criticism escalated and some parishes began withholding
funds, Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I, head of the worldwide
Orthodox Church, removed Spyridon from office.
</P>
<P>
   At his installation, Demetrios called for better understanding
between generations, between clergy and laity, and between the U.S.
and the international church. The Atlanta visit is one of many to
cities across the country as Demetrios attempts to tend to the
flock and heal hurts of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The last visit of a Greek Orthodox archbishop to Atlanta
occurred a year ago when Spyridon installed Bishop Alexios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual for an archbishop to visit
</P>
<P>
   any time,'' said Alexander. ``To have him come for a
groundbreaking is extraordinary. He's brought balance and a calming
influence to our faith. He's brought our national community back
together. Our archdiocese is united.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 95-year-old Atlanta cathedral, the building program
represents not only a way to increase the identity of Greek
Atlantans, but an opportunity to raise the awareness of Greek
Orthodox Christians among practitioners of other faiths and other
Christian denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're scattered out through other Christian communities in
Atlanta playing soccer, baseball and basketball,'' said Alexander.
``We hope we can now host those things here and extend our family
hospitality to the Greater Atlanta community.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
