<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thundershowers will surround low pressure as it moves from the
central Mississippi Valley early Saturday to the eastern Ohio
Valley and northern Middle Atlantic states later Saturday and
Sunday. The low will travel along a boundary separating very warm
and rather humid weather over the Southeast from cooler air to the
north. Some of the thunderstorms in the Ohio and Tennessee valleys
late Saturday will bring damaging winds and large hail. There is a
threat of flooding, especially in the eastern Ohio Valley, where
recurrent thundershowers pass over the same areas.
</P>
<P>
   Stalled low pressure over eastern Canada will block the advance
of moisture, keeping mainly dry weather over New York and New
England on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will persist over the Southwest. The Northwest will
be drier with seasonable temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DELUGE
</P>
<P>
   When an inch of rain falls in 24 hours, it's a wet day. When an
inch of rain falls in 13 minutes, as it did in Nashville, Tenn.,
around midnight Wednesday, it's a deluge. Bursts of rain are most
common in summer when the vigorous air currents in thunderstorms
combine with moisture-laden air. Rainfall rates at the center of
thunderstorms are often more than 3 inches an hour; however, a
given spot typically stays in the heaviest rain for only a few
minutes. The greatest burst of rain ever recorded in the United
States occurred in Unionville, Md., on July 4, 1956, when 1.23
inches of rain fell in only one minute. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
