<HEADER>
A6997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AMERICAN-AUDIENCES-BO     05-26 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-AUDIENCES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MAKING OF AMERICAN AUDIENCES': BOOK CHRONICLES AUDIENCE
EVOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is the difference between a performance of ``The Marriage
of Figaro'' and a telecast of ``The Sopranos''? Or between a
Britney Spears concert and ``The Jack Benny Show? Or between a
gamelan performance and a pornographic Web site?
</P>
<P>
   The audience.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that is one way to look at it. It is so difficult to
evaluate arts, compare their virtues and weigh their achievements,
and the entire debate over what was once called high culture is so
politically charged that it is tempting simply to say that
different entertainments attract different audiences. No aesthetic
distinctions are needed. Mozart and Spears do not have different
statures, just different devotees. There is no high, no low, only
differing cultural attitudes toward what is high and what is low.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, though, is that if the audience is the measure of
all things, then art becomes a reflection of sociology and
dissecting audience tastes becomes the art. This approach lies
behind market research, movie previews, television programming and
most book publishing. Before anything is packaged, the producers of
cultural commerce ask: Who is the audience? How can it be reached?
What are the ages, incomes, professions, tastes and attitudes we
desire?
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, academic analysis of culture often does something
similar. Strip away the superstructure of cosmetics and form, and
the artwork's true meaning can be found in demographics. Who is
being addressed and why? What is being sold? The main difference is
that here the categories are political, not commercial. Now they
tend to focus on gender, race and class. Culture becomes a series
of coded messages in which genders, races and classes negotiate for
power.
</P>
<P>
   Rich insights can be gained by such market analysis, of course,
but the risk is that the art itself may become inconsequential.
This is one of the flaws of ``The Making of American Audiences,'' a
survey spanning 240 years of drama, minstrelsy, vaudeville, film,
radio and television. Richard Butsch, a professor of sociology at
Rider University in New Jersey, has combed archives and newspapers,
historical documents and recent histories, studies of television
advertising and circus audiences, penny arcades and fan mail; his
bibliography alone takes up 36 pages. The subject is fascinating
and so are some of Butsch's ideas, but as the content of art is
eclipsed by considerations of audience politics, culture ends up
seeming like little more than a reflection of political tastes.
</P>
<P>
   But what a transformation of tastes is chronicled. Beginning in
the 18th century and through the first half of the 19th century,
Butsch suggests, there was a tradition of ``audience sovereignty''
in the theater. Upper-class patrons might sit onstage and publicly
chat with the actors. In the 1830s Tocqueville found that Americans
``paid not the slightest attention to the stage but walked about,
drank together and argued as if nothing else were going on.''
``Prostitution,'' Butsch points out, ``was important to the
profitability of theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Such manners seemed to cross all classes. During the 1840s New
York had a coterie of working-class young men known as b'hoys who
treated the theater as an extension of the street. One observer of
a performance in the Bowery said that the audience ``heaves
continually in wild and sullen tumult, like a red flannel sea
agitated by some lurid storm ... the yells and screams, the
shuddering oaths and obscene songs tumbling down from the third
tier.'' The b'hoys were such knowledgeable regulars that they would
shout out prompts to Shakespearean actors who forgot their lines.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, though, class divisions increased. Rowdy
``lower-class'' behavior became restricted to other forms of
entertainment, like minstrel shows in the 1840s or vaudeville later
in the century, while the legitimate theater began to take on more
refined manners. Drama, once considered a masculine domain, was
feminized. Shopping districts grew around theaters; fashion became
important; a matinee audience of women developed. By 1910 women may
have made up three-quarters of the American theater audience.
</P>
<P>
   While the working classes were still actively engaged in variety
shows, within the theater an elevated notion of art was put
forward, encouraging passivity. Those who failed to appreciate art
were considered as rude as those who had once lobbied for silence.
One magazine mocked bored, wealthy theatergoers who ``came an act
late, left an act early, slept during the second act and talked in
between times.'' Silent attentiveness was expected.
</P>
<P>
   So the audience, once an active participant, became a passive
recipient, a transformation, Butsch argues, that was amplified by
the development of movies, radio and television. The participatory
tumult of the theater was supplanted by the private experience of
the screen. To Butsch, all this seems a decline of sorts, in which
political vitality and communal experience is sacrificed for the
sake of private entertainment. He often appears drawn to what was
lost with ``the establishment of middle-class decorum.''
</P>
<P>
   Butsch's two distinctions, active-passive and public-private,
are important. But the transformations are not clear-cut, and their
meanings are ambiguous. Was the debate over audience behavior, for
example, just a matter of ``class-based fears of lower-class
disorder''?
</P>
<P>
   Demands for decorum may not have been just political. There are,
after all, major differences between a vaudeville show and a
performance of ``Othello,'' differences in complexity, nuance,
beauty, construction, density and wit. More subtle aesthetic
perceptions may have led to demands for greater decorum.
</P>
<P>
   There are, then, distinctions to be made that go beyond gender,
race and class. And if, as Butsch asserts, the history of American
audiences raises many issues that are still urgent in contemporary
life, this one may be worth examining more closely.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE MAKING OF AMERICAN AUDIENCES'
</P>
<P>
   `From Stage to Television, 1750-1990'
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Butsch.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 438 pages. Cambridge University Press. $69.95
hardcover; $24.95 paperback.
</P>
</TEXT>
