<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-DOCTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP CONGRESSMAN HITS LEADERSHIP ON PHYSICIANS' BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom Campbell said Friday he is ``outraged''
that House Republican leaders blocked his bill that would let
physicians bargain collectively with health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a Republican from Campbell, Calif., said House Speaker
J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., blocked the bill from going to the House
floor because Republican House members feared it would cost them
campaign contributions from physicians or the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's bill to end the federal rule banning self-employed
doctors from joining together to negotiate with insurance plans is
supported by physicians and opposed by health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said his bill has 223 co-sponsors, enough for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said many of his House colleagues told him: ``Don't
force me to choose between two important contributors, doctors and
insurance.'' Campbell said House members urged him to delay the
vote ``so we can milk both cows.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association, a leading physicians'
organization that supports the bill, says the managed care industry
has been able to make doctors sign contracts that force them to
rush patients and cut corners on medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurers in the managed care industry claim Campbell's
plan would lead to higher medical costs and give physicians too
much clout.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999-2000 election cycle, physicians gave Democratic
candidates at the federal level $4.2 million and Republican
candidates about $7.6 million, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan Washington research group.
</P>
<P>
   Also during that cycle, insurance companies in general shelled
out $7.3 million to Democrats and $12.8 million to Republicans,
according to the research group.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said Hastert twice promised him to bring up the bill
for a vote and has twice broken his promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've gotten a promise face to face and
it's been broken,'' Campbell said. ``I want to express a sense of
personal outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he got a phone call from a staffer at 1:30 a.m.
Thursday telling him the House Rules Committee, which sets up rules
for floor debate at the speaker's behest, declined to bring
Campbell's bill to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert spokesman John Feehery said the House ran out of time to
take up the bill before the Memorial Day recess but that it would
come up again later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has little to lose in criticizing the speaker because
he has given up his House seat to run for the U.S. Senate seat held
by Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said Sens. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., and Chuck Schumer,
D-N.Y., have offered to bring up a companion bill in that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
