<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV28-     05-26 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TASTE OF THE TROPICS, BY WAY OF FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 28)  
 By MARTY ROSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My grandmother's fancy rose garden was just a short hop from her
screened porch, but I always preferred to play under the trees, and
my memories of the endless Southern summers of my childhood are
tinged with the cool colors of caladiums: pink, wine-red, silver
and white, touched with green, flashing in the shade under
evergreen oaks, in planters on porches, and at the hearts of formal
flower beds edged with dark ropes of liriope or tidy, knee-high
hedges of boxwood. Everyone had them, and ribbons of caladiums
seemed to lace the town serenely together.
</P>
<P>
   Caladiums were actually having a little renaissance when I was a
girl in the 1950s, and then they seemed to disappear for a while,
at about the same time so many families moved to the suburbs, to
large but relentlessly sunny gardens; caladiums do best in dappled
shade. Now that trees have grown up in the suburbs, caladiums are
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Caladiums are tubers, members of the arum family
(elephant's-ears are also arums) and native to tropical South
America. There are seven species in the genus (some experts say
12), but the varieties in commercial production today are hybrids
of only two: C. bicolor, called fancy-leaf caladium, which has
large, heart-shaped leaves and grows to two feet tall, and C.
picturatum, the parent of the lance-leaf caladiums, which grows to
only a foot and produces a mass of narrow, ruffled leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the world's commercial caladium crop is produced by 14
growers in Florida, who grow 50 million tubers a year in black
sawgrass fields around Lake Placid and Sebring, just south of
Orlando. After a heavy rain, alligators and otters are sometimes
encountered in the fields, under the low canopy of fantastically
splotched and marbled leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Caladium bicolor, which has green leaves with red and white
spots, was first described in print in 1800, by which time it had
been brought to France. There seems to be little word of fancy
hybrids until 1867, when Louis Van Houtte and Alfred Bleu exhibited
a number of new caladium varieties at the Paris Exposition.
Triomphe de l'Exposition, with bright red veins radiating from a
central star, was the pride of their display. As late as the 1950s,
it remained a staple of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Triomphe de l'Exposition has now almost disappeared from the
market, but Candidum, Monsieur Bleu's real masterpiece, which has
large translucent white leaves with dark green veins, is still one
of the most popular varieties available.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred new caladium varieties were introduced at the
Columbian Exposition in Chicago in 1893, and they were quite the
rage in the United States for the next four decades. Henry
Nehrling, who seems to have grown nearly every available variety in
his garden in Gotha, Fla., introduced perhaps 40 new caladiums to
commercial production before his death in 1929. Only a handful of
those are available today.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in caladiums has picked up again with the general new
enthusiasm for tropical plants of all kinds. For the last few
years, suppliers have been unable to keep up with the demand. New
hybrids are again coming on the market. Dr. Gary Wilfret, professor
of environmental horticulture at the University of Florida at
Bradenton, has been working to develop sun-tolerant caladiums and
varieties that can stand temperatures in the '50s. The market is
hot, and Wilfret says he expects to release a couple of new hybrids
every year for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful of Wilfret's introductions is Florida
Sweetheart, a rosy-leaved cross between fancy-leaf and lance-leaf
caladiums that looks very pretty in hanging baskets. It develops a
pink blush in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Caladiums are strictly annual plants for most American
gardeners. They thrive in moist, well-drained soil and require
warmth to flourish _ planting caladiums before temperatures are a
reliable 65 degrees damages the tubers. In temperate climates,
caladiums should be planted in early summer (June 1 to June 15 in
the Northeast), with two inches of soil over the tuber's smooth
top. Most varieties develop their colors best in shade. Given ample
moisture, the plants will produce dozens of leaves during the
summer. The tubers can be dug up and stored over the winter, but
they must be kept warm (70 degrees) or they will rot.
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinary powers, including the capacity ``to make children
teachable,'' have been attributed to species caladiums in South
America.
</P>
<P>
   They were highly valued as ``beenas,'' or charms, by the Indians
of British Guiana, who often rubbed caladium leaves on their skin
or clothing to secure love, happiness and a healthy appetite. The
swallow beena, Caladium humboldtii, had the power to bring back
distant friends. The effectiveness of the money beena, a caladium
with white blotches, was enhanced if a sixpence was tucked under a
tuber planted in a pot.
</P>
<P>
   I'm charmed. I'm going to put a dime under each caladium I plant
this summer and forget about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Caladiums are available by mail from Bates Sons &AMP; Daughters, 81
Bates Road, Lake Placid, Fla. 33852; (863) 465-3274; catalog is
free. And from Fancy Leaf Caladiums, County Road 621 East, Lake
Placid, Fla. 33852; (863) 465-0044; catalog is free. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
