 For Release SATURDAY AMs, May 27, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Roy Greene  &LR; at
the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD-BIAS (London) _ An honors student from working-class high
school in northern England accuses Oxford University, Britain's
most exclusive college, of elitism because it rejected her
application. By Kevin Cullen. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON-TOURISM (Tel Aviv) Israelis pour from tour buses
and private cars to look at the country's newest and probably most
unusual tourist attraction: Jeering Lebanese waving Hezbollah flags
as they pressed up against a wire fence that marks the border with
Israel. By Aliza Marcus. 900.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-TRADE (Washington) _ Twice this week, the House has faced
the same debate: Whether to liberalize trade with a communist
country, despite its lengthy history of violating human rights.
Lawmakers voted in favor of China, but are still fighting over
Cuba. Ann Kornblut. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The tracks animals leave behind tell
a story _ not always this exotic, but always evocative. By Vicki
Croke. 1,000 words. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DOT-COM (Moscow) A new catch-phrase has become all the
rage in Moscow's business community: tochka-ru _ that's Russian for
dot-com. As the Nasdaq has plunged, and dot-com mania has cooled in
the United States, e-commerce has come to Russia, bringing with it
promises of efficiency and hopes for big profits. By Brian
Whitmore. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMIT-ALCON (Undated) _ &UR;  &LR; Summit Autonomous Inc., a developer of
laser systems to correct vision disorders, agrees to be acquired
for nearly $900 million in cash by Alcon Laboratories Inc., a unit
of Nestle SA. By Ronald Rosenberg. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCDONOUGH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Amazing, isn't it, how diligent
politicians become when a local sports team asks for public help in
building a stadium or an arena. All of a sudden they know all of
the numbers: interest rates, parking fees, and revenue streams. By
Will McDonough. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-REVOLUTION (Boston) _ Joey Franchino, the Revolution's
newest addition _ from Los Angeles _ is acclimating to New England.
By Frank Dell'Apa. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
