<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ZOMBIE-INTERNET-REVIE     05-26 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZOMBIE-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZOMBIE COLLEGE': WEB SERIAL RIVETNG EXCEPTION TO USUAL FODDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Wed site notes are at end of review. No `www' prefix is
needed for 'hotwired' site in 4th graf.) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last year the Internet has bred its own school of
do-it-yourself mass entertainment in the form of Flash animation, a
relatively easy-to-use software tool that has made online animators
out of novices.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these shorts are amateurish, sophomoric or extremely
slow-moving, but there are exceptions. One is ``Zombie College,''
which for this critic has made the Internet a rival to television.
Nearly every Wednesday _ sometimes there are Internet reruns _ a
new episode of ``Zombie College'' pops up on the powerhouse
animation site www.icebox.com, which has amassed a team of
producers and writers associated with television programs like
``The Simpsons,'' ``King of the Hill,'' ``Seinfeld'' and
``X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Flash animation programs run just a few minutes and either
merge the chills of a science fiction cliffhanger with the warm
charm of a stuffed animal or, for the adolescent male, offer
interactive superhero stories. The programs lean toward the bizarre
and conceptual _ an extraterrestrial implanted with the brain of a
redneck, a freckled prepubescent pimp, a monkey and chicken working
for NASA _ but at the same time the plots are often light and about
everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Flash animation sites include www.mediatrip.com,
www.campchaos.com, www.shockwave.com, www.spumco.com and
hotwired.lycos.com/animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zombie College'' revolves around a pair of high school lovers,
Scott and Zelda _ the Fitzgerald allusion stops there _ who are
leaving for their freshman year of college. Scott turns down
admission to MIT so he can join his loved one at Arkford
University, also known as Zombie College, an integrated school
where living students warily mingle with undead ones _ the civil
rights allusion stops there _ who eat human brains.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins when Zelda tells Scott she wants to start
seeing other men, leaving the sensitive genius Scott stranded in
the ``Revenge of the Nerds''-like world of a zombie fraternity
house.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty silly, but in the hands of its creator, Eric Kaplan (a
producer of ``Futurama''), and the animation director, John Rice
(``The Simpsons,'' ``King of the Hill''), ``Zombie College'' comes
to life. The music is original and catchy, the characters are
animated with depth and personality, the voices are believable and
effective, the plot is relentless and irresistible, and, most
important, every episode is smart and funny. Each week the story
takes unexpected twists and turns until, at the end of the
program's four minutes, one is left wondering how Kaplan is going
to get his characters out of the corner he's painted them into.
</P>
<P>
   In the great Internet sweepstakes, well-financed sites like
Icebox have been racing to mine what they call content from an
entertainment world in which everyone seems to be available to the
highest bidder. This often results in well-known names being given
tantalizing stock packages to put any old thing _ a throwaway song,
200 words of text, a minute-long interview snippet, a photograph of
an old sock _ on a Web site to make it attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   But in the rush for content, entertainment is getting brushed
aside, a nuisance to deal with at some future date. ``Zombie
College,'' however, is a world crafted with care, in which the
quirkily drawn zombies are capable of sucking your brains out as
quickly as a Sunday night of prime-time animation on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   WEB PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Zombie Collage''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesdays on www.icebox.com
</P>
<P>
   Created by Eric Kaplan; animation direction by John Rice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
