<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TONGASS-ROADS-ART-122     05-26 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONGASS-ROADS-ART-1225(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONGASS FOREST, EXEMPT FROM ROAD BAN, STIRS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SITKA, Alaska _ Carved by ice and washed by as much as 12 feet
of rain a year, the Tongass National Forest stretches across
Alaska's panhandle, full of coastal fjords and majestic strands of
spruce, cedar and hemlock that John Muir described in 1879 as a
seemingly ``indefinite, on-leading expansiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at 17 million acres, the Tongass is more than three
times the size of any other national forest. But as the Clinton
administration promotes its far-reaching plan to safeguard the
forests by banning the building of new roads throughout much of the
system, the Tongass has a curious distinction: It is the one
national forest specifically exempted from such a ban.
</P>
<P>
   There are already more than 4,000 miles of logging roads snaking
through the rain forest here, built as part of the United States'
most heavily subsidized logging program, one that costs taxpayers
about $30 million a year but is fiercely defended by Alaska's tiny
but powerful congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   With 400 miles of new federal logging roads slated to be built
in the Tongass rain forest over the next four years, the exemption
has already set off a battle between national environmental groups
and the timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   And here in southeast Alaska, where the tourism industry now
outpaces timber as a source of jobs, the debate over whether to
build more logging roads in the world's largest remaining stretch
of temperate rain forest is also surprisingly spirited, in a way
that would have been unthinkable a generation ago when logging was
seen as the great spur to jobs in the sparsely populated area.
</P>
<P>
   While logging interests complain that environmental restrictions
have already cost the region hundreds of good jobs over the years
and closed down two big mills, many of those who make their money
by guiding tourists and sport fishermen through the spectacular
inlets and past the emerald forests favor more protections and even
an end to any clear-cutting in the Tongass.
</P>
<P>
   And while almost everyone here agrees that the United States'
largest, wildest national forest holds great resources, the core
question in the debate is how much of an economic resource the
untouched wilderness is.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Alaskans don't like what we are inevitably becoming _
a place where people come to see it, rather than to exploit it,''
said Richard Nelson, a writer and cultural anthropologist who is on
the board of the Sitka Conservation Society, an environmental group
that supports including the Tongass in President Clinton's ban on
new roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole frontier philosophy, the whole
conquest-of-wilderness mentality, is certainly alive and well
here,'' Nelson said. ``But there is a whole opposite ethic that is
growing fast.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that much of the battle over what to do
with the Tongass will be fought in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For environmentalists, ``leaving the Tongass out of this plan is
like deciding to protect all national parks except Yellowstone,''
said Matthew Zencey, the Washington-based manager of the Alaska
Rainforest Campaign, an umbrella coalition that hopes to get much
of the forest protected by a road ban.
</P>
<P>
   The timber industry is similarly animated, saying the Tongass is
already subject to a federal ``management plan'' that balances
wilderness protection in the area with a prudent amount of logging.
The administration, in fact, cited that plan in exempting Tongass
from its road restrictions, although other areas also have
management plans.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the exemption have suggested that the
administration was merely trying to avoid picking a fight with
Alaska's senators, who both chair committees that have authority
over the forest service.
</P>
<P>
   But as the land-use struggle continues thousands of miles away,
people who live here are also clearly divided over whether the
forest is chiefly useful for timber or tourism, or both in equal
measure.
</P>
<P>
   In Sitka, the one-time capital of Russian America, which is
ringed by forests, sea and a snow-covered volcano on a nearby
island, the city split a few years ago (1,702 against, 1,068 for)
when a nonbinding measure was put on the local ballot to make it
the city's official policy to oppose clear-cutting in the nearby
national forest.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism and fishing now outrank the timber industry as sources
of jobs in southeast Alaska, according to the state's Department of
Labor and Workforce Development, a radical change from the
situation 25 years ago. Logging industry officials attribute it to
protections that environmentalists have already secured for the
Tongass.
</P>
<P>
   One came in the Carter administration, setting aside more than 5
million acres as wilderness, and another in the Bush
administration, when Congress agreed to phase out much of a subsidy
that was allowing two major timber companies to pay as little as $2
for huge Sitka spruce logs that would fetch about $300 on the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidy dated to the 1950s, when the U.S. Forest Service
agreed to provide a steady supply of timber at low prices to two
companies that agreed to build pulp mills in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those mills are closed now _ one near here may be
reconverted into a privately owned water-bottling plant, under a
plan that is still being negotiated _ and the area now has about
700,000 tourists every summer, more than double the number a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many come in the cruise ships that glide by the magnificent
scenery and dock in and around the coastal towns. Others come to
fish with one of the dozens of guide companies that advertise their
services in what many call ``the salmon capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is all well and good, but there is no reason for that
industry not to coexist with continued logging, said Sen. Frank
Murkowski, R-Alaska, who is chairman of a committee that oversees
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``So a tourist in Alaska comes in on a boat, and he gets off in
Ketchikan or Juneau and maybe spends a little money here, spends a
little money there, and gets back on the boat,'' Murkowski said in
a telephone interview from Washington. ``That's important. It's a
significant contribution. But it's not sufficient. What we really
do well is, we grow timber and we grow fish. And they're both
renewable if you do it correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added: ``If we've done such a bad job with this
forest in Alaska, then why is it still so scenic today for tourism?
Why do so many people still want to come here?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's plan, the U.S. Forest Service would ban
road building in areas of the national forests where there are
currently no roads. The plan would protect about 43 million acres
that could be logged, roughly one-quarter of the 192 million acres
in the national forest system.
</P>
<P>
   That would reduce planned timber harvests, now at about 3.6
billion board feet a year, by about 700 million board feet. (There
are about 10,000 board feet of lumber in an average-size American
home.)
</P>
<P>
   But under the administration's recently announced preference, no
such ban would apply in the 17-million-acre Tongass forest, and a
decision on whether to impose a ban would not be made until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would thus let proposed road building proceed in about
2 million acres of the forest. Another 6 million would be protected
if the national standards were applied to the Tongass.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service's program in the Tongass already operates at
a deficit of about $30 million a year, meaning that the federal
government pays more to build roads and maintain the forest than it
takes in from timber companies, which grind most of the trees to a
pulp that is sold for export, mainly to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   That subsidy used to be even larger, and the existing program
remains popular in some quarters here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we manage forests at a net loss for the taxpayer,'' said
Bob Weinstein, the mayor of Ketchikan, a timber town at the
southeastern tip of the state. ``But that doesn't bother me until
such time as the United States government eliminates every direct
or indirect subsidy for any business.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein has tried to spark a campaign in response to any
possibility that the Clinton administration might include the
Tongass in its road ban. And he said that logging areas were
typically well out of the view of tourists anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are cuts,'' he said, ``the Forest Service has made
sure they can't be seen from passing cruise ships.''
</P>
<P>
   The lush growing areas most prized by logging companies,
however, are precisely the same areas that are most critical for
wildlife habitat, conservationists say. The region, roughly the
size of West Virginia, has one of the largest concentrations of
bald eagles and grizzly bears anywhere in the world and is also
considered one of the largest stretches left of temperate (as
opposed to tropical) rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   James Lyons, the assistant agriculture secretary in charge of
the Forest Service, said the Tongass was exempted from a road ban
under the recent proposal because it had already been subject to an
intensive review process lasting several years and resulting in a
1997 ``management plan'' aimed at balancing wilderness protection
with continued logging.
</P>
<P>
   Total logging in the forest now amounts to about 150 million
board feet annually, having steadily dropped from a high of 590
million board feet in 1973. Environmental groups said that areas
served by existing logging roads already provided enough land for a
sustainable timber harvest, and that the road ban should be
extended here.
</P>
<P>
   But Murkowski said the logging statistics indicated that
environmentalists had already gotten the upper hand in the Tongass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they want it all,'' he said. ``Have you ever met with an
environmental group that's satisfied? If they were satisfied, they
wouldn't have a cause. They'd have to shut up shop and retire.
That's what's going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Logging industry officials also said they were extremely
skeptical of environmentalists' claims that tourism would be the
economic lifeblood of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get finished shutting down logging, they're going to
go after the cruise ships,'' said Jack Phelps, executive director
of the Alaska Forest Association, a trade group based in Ketchikan.
``They think they're too many people coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed there is evidence that some Alaskans feel they are
overrun with tourists: Juneau has slapped visitors' fees on those
who arrive by boat, and Sitka residents voted down a proposal to
build a dock that would have allowed more cruise ships to moor in
town rather than out in the bay. (Many cruise ships offload their
passengers onto smaller boats to take them into town.)
</P>
<P>
   But Eric Jordan, a second-generation fisherman in Sitka who also
runs a guide business, said the local economy was stronger today
than when the mill went out of business. The air and waters were
much cleaner too, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the mill actually closed and that cloud of smoke was
lifted, both psychologically and literally, an amazing thing
happened,'' he said. ``Property values shot up, and they've been
going up ever since. The reality was more palatable than dealing
with this constant threat that the economy would collapse if the
mill went. I really think the psychology of the town has brightened
in a lot of respects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
