<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE LAWMAKERS SEEK TO BOTTLE UP RIVER FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARL HULSE &QC;  &QL; 
NYT Regional Newspapers &QC;  &QL; 
 &LR;  WASHINGTON _ After losing a Supreme Court challenge, conservative
lawmakers are following a more circuitous route in their determined
efforts to sink President Clinton's American Heritage Rivers
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the program created by executive order in 1997
quietly inserted a provision into a pending Agriculture Department
spending bill that would prohibit the agency from spending money on
revitalizing 14 selected rivers. Similar language adopted last year
blocked Pentagon and Interior Department funds from being spent on
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Since the initiative depends on using existing staff and
resources from executive agencies, congressional backers of the
program worry such restrictions will strangle an undertaking that
is popular in the river communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fear this legislative attack will spread like a computer
virus and infect the remaining appropriations bills,'' wrote
Democratic Reps. Corrine Brown of Florida and William Jefferson of
Louisiana in a letter urging their colleagues to kill the
provision. The effort has Republican support as well.
</P>
<P>
   Under the initiative, special ``navigators'' are appointed for
the individual rivers to help communities seek federal aid for
environmental and economic restoration projects. More than 120
rivers competed for the designation, which was bestowed upon the
Lower Mississippi in Louisiana and Tennessee, the St. Johns in
Florida and the New in North Carolina among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Heritage Rivers initiative ensures that federal
agencies become better partners with communities,'' wrote GOP Reps.
Sue Kelly of New York and Paul Kanjorski of Pennsylvania, both of
whom represent states containing American Heritage rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives have from the start objected to the initiative
as an illegal use of executive power and a back-door attempt by the
Clinton administration to gain more authority over land along the
rivers. Some GOP lawmakers specifically requested that waterways in
their districts be excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Four western lawmakers challenged the president's authority to
create the program but the high court in March refused to hear the
appeal of two lower court decisions rejecting the congressional
claims.
</P>
<P>
   DAY CARE DILEMMA
</P>
<P>
   Southern states are banding together to explore ways to help
low-income parents with one of their most persistent economic
problems _ how to find affordable day care that will allow them to
get ahead by working full-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of the Southern states, a young family with two-wage
earners at minimum wage could easily spend a third of their gross
pay on child care,'' said Louise Stoney, a child care consultant
working with the Southern Institute on Children and Families.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina-based institute has formed a task force
consisting of representatives appointed by Southern governors to
find ways to ease access to child care assistance for poor
families, many of whom might not know such help is available. Its
report will be issued next year.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTDOWN FOR ECSTASY
</P>
<P>
   The designer drug Ecstasy may be all the rave at dance clubs but
it is not too popular on Capitol Hill. A group of lawmakers is
pressing for stiffer penalties for importing, manufacturing and
distributing the drug that is becoming a favorite of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecstasy is a proven killer and it is on the loose,'' said Sen.
Bob Graham, D-Fla. ``We need to shatter the dangerous myth that
this risky designer drug is safe for consumption.'' He and others
say the drug can elevate heart rates to potentially fatal levels.
</P>
<P>
   The measure proposed by Graham and fellow members of the Senate
Caucus on Drug Control would equate trafficking in Ecstasy with
dealing in methamphetamine, which would significantly boost
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   GOING WHOLE HOG
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups fear new regulations on corporate farming
set to be issued by the Environmental Protection Agency are going
to be far too weak from their perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Based on their review of EPA drafts and discussions with agency
officials, representatives of the Southern Environmental Law Center
and other organizations say the rules could institutionalize the
animal waste lagoons blamed for pollution in some Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical hog farm produces as much waste as a small city,'
said Tim Searchinger, attorney for Environmental Defense. ``Yet the
anticipated policy would do little more than legitimize the
existing, nearly uncontrolled way these factory farms operate.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups are pushing for much more stringent regulations
opposed by the agriculture industry, which contends the lagoons are
safe.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
