<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 DISNEY UNlEASHES DINOSAURS ON NEW CD  
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is the movie: ``Dinosaur.'' There is the toy based on the
movie that is available from a nationwide hamburger chain.
</P>
<P>
   Through July 9, ``Sue,'' an exact cast replica of the largest,
most complete Tyrannosaurus rex fossil ever found, will be on
display at Walt Disney World's Animal Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   And Disney does not think the dinosaur theme is extinct yet.
There is, of course, the CD-ROM: Disney's Dinosaur Activity Center.
Disney also has taken the opportunity to cross-market products.
There is a pre-paid child's admission ticket included to see
``Dinosaur,'' which can also be used for any Disney picture running
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The CD has been released to coincide with the family feature
from Disney that opened last weekend. The Windows/Macintosh CD
(about $30) is designed for children ages 5 and up.
</P>
<P>
   There are a total of five games and activities to help children
learn about the evolution and eventual extinction of dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Line O'Dinos Puzzle Maker'' lets children create their own
dinosaur and then record their own voices, or use a pre-recorded
one from the program, to make the dinosaur roar. The puzzles can be
e-mailed to friends or printed.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Colossal Fossil Face-off'' is a strategy game to help
children with reasoning powers.
</P>
<P>
   The child leads a dinosaur team to take back an egg from a group
of carnotaurs. The game uses fact cards to help children learn more
about the characteristics of various dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   The three remaining activities are arcade games. The ``Lemur
Love Match'' teaches comparisons by having children match flowers
while racing a time clock in order to move to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stegasaurus Spelunker'' is centered around combining sets of
three objects to escape from rock-filled caves.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the company's Web site:
www.disneyinteractive.com.
</P>
<P>
   CARD STUDIO DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of holidays, birthdays and anniversaries left
in the year. The Hallmark Card Studio Deluxe can take care of all
of them _ including National Columnist Day on June 27. Some other
holidays that are equally obscure for card-sending: National
Splurge Day (June 18) and Employee Appreciation Day (March 10).
</P>
<P>
   The Windows-based program (about $50) has more than 3,000
ready-made cards that can be easily edited to personalize the
graphics or messages.
</P>
<P>
   SierraHome, the software's publishers, estimate there are
600,000 ways to create cards and projects for friends.
</P>
<P>
   The program has more than 150 project templates _ calendars,
photo greetings, envelopes, stationery, postcards and other items.
</P>
<P>
   It also has nearly two dozen specialty fonts, and 10,000 pieces
of clip art and pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes SnapShot Express, a set of editing tools
for adding photos to cards. An event planner, also included with
the program, has a ``kid lock'' feature to keep children from
seeing any content parents want to keep from them.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the company's Web site:
www.sierrahome.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
