<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rally to call for release of Al-Amin
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the country's most outspoken black nationalists will call
for the release of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin today at a noon rally in
Woodruff Park.
</P>
<P>
   Khallid Abdul Muhammad, the national chairman of the New Black
Panther Party, will be in town for an ``offensive effort to free
'H. Rap Brown,' our comrade and unjustly incarcerated brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, formerly known as H. Rap Brown, briefly served as
minister of justice for the Black Panthers in 1968. He is in the
Cobb County Jail, charged with murder in the slaying of a Fulton
County sheriff's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Malik Shabazz, the minister of justice for the New Black Panther
Party, said several veteran black activists from Atlanta will be
involved in the rally, although he would not release their names.
</P>
<P>
   Nadim Ali, a spokesman for the Community Mosque headed by
Al-Amin, said the mosque is not affiliated with the New Black
Panther Party or today's rally.
</P>
<P>
   The New Black Panther Party was organized in 1989 in Dallas.
Muhammad, the former national spokesman for the Nation of Islam,
was voted national chairman of the New Black Panthers in the
mid-1990s after Louis Farrakhan kicked him out of the Nation for
making anti-Semitic remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
