u i BC-PAKISTAN-TAX-545&AMP;ADD-     05-26 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-TAX-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN TO CRACK DOWN ON RAMPANT TAX EVASION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ ``WARNING!'' scream the big daily ads in
the newspapers. ``All taxpayers are warned that a comprehensive tax
survey is being launched soon in which your concealed income and
assets will be unearthed.''
</P>
<P>
   In many countries, such an admonition might strike fear among a
minority who forget, fudge or outright refuse to file. But here in
Pakistan, where taxes have yet to join death as one of life's
inevitabilities, the warning applies to just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The military government, nearly eight months after it seized
power, is trying to do what before has proven impossible: find out
who owes how much and make them pay.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Saturday, teams of soldiers and revenue officers will
start delivering tax survey forms to businesses and homes in 13
major cities. The government wants to know about inventory,
purchases, rents, utility bills and employees. The penalty for
ignoring the form can be as much as three months in jail, and the
punishment for lying is up to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Pakistan and elsewhere consider the tax crackdown a
major test of mettle for Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the military ruler
who uses the title of chief executive: The nation is $38 billion in
debt. Can he snatch solvency from the jaws of default?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever forbearance the international community has had for
this military government has come with the idea that it can take
decisions that a political government cannot,'' said one Western
diplomat. ``But this government has yet to take on any major
interest group and win.''
</P>
<P>
   While Musharraf presents himself as a tough-talking reformer, he
has backed down from several confrontations, most recently when he
withdrew a change to the nation's blasphemy laws that was opposed
by Islamic fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he is up against a business community that has
considered the payment of taxes as the behavior of suckers. Many
shop owners vow to shutter their stores as soon as the survey teams
enter the neighborhood. An indefinite strike has been threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Umer Sailya, part owner of a Karachi restaurant and chairman of
the Association of Small Traders Organizations, is championing the
resistance. He said that first, the government ought to root out
corruption among its own in the tax department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bureaucracy doesn't want our taxes; they want our
bribes,'' Sailya said in a telephone interview. ``Let the
government first survey the revenue collectors, the civil
bureaucrats, the army and the judiciary. Then they can come survey
the businessmen.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to Sailya's criticism, the government this week
leaked his income tax returns to the press, showing that he paid an
average of only $28 during the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if that is the case, then Sailya is one of Pakistan's
more upright citizens. In a nation of 150 million, less than 1
percent pay any income tax at all, according to the government. An
estimated 70 percent of the entire economy is run off the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shameful!'' Musharraf declared Thursday at a televised news
conference that was part pep talk, part fireside chat. ``We should
be ashamed. Only 1.2 million people pay tax.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is a very poor country _ and for some poverty may be
something of an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to the government, there are 2.5 million business
owners in Pakistan, and only 650,000 of them have even bothered to
register with the income tax authorities. Of those, a meager 17,500
are collecting sales tax, which is not only considered a nuisance
by shopkeepers but can also be used as incriminating evidence of
their own unreported earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task ahead is momentous,'' said Shaukat Aziz, a former
Citibank vice president who has returned to his native Pakistan as
finance minister. ``We are trying to inculcate a culture of
tax-paying. It is a defining moment for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's tax survey program has been preceded by its tax
amnesty plan, which is the subject of those newspaper ads as well
as similarly stern ones on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Deadbeats are being offered a ``rare opportunity'' to pay up on
money earned before June 30, 1999. At a bargain tax rate, too: only
10 percent. All else is forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you fail to avail the opportunity, you run the risk of
paying tax at normal rates plus penalty and imprisonment of up to
five years or both,'' the ads warn.
</P>
<P>
   The amnesty offer is four weeks old, and so far it has scared
the stuffing out of very few wallets, bringing in a scant $3
million. Aziz has greater expectations, estimating that 10 times
that amount will be recovered before a June 15 deadline. But even
that is a far cry from the additional 12 billion dollars the
government believes it ought to collect annually.
</P>
<P>
   The finance minister is not without sympathy for those who have
long evaded the tax net. He admits that many in the revenue
department are as dishonest as the day is long. Thursday, he fired
1,000 of the ``most corrupt.'' He said in an interview, ``Will this
eliminate corruption? No. Will it put a check on it? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Aziz was living in New York with a banker's set of
headaches; a year ago, Musharraf was commanding an army that was
fighting a near all-out war with India in the mountains of Kashmir.
These days, they worry a good deal about satisfying the
international lenders who hold the paper on Pakistan's debt.
</P>
<P>
   A team from the International Monetary Fund is in Islamabad this
week, trying to decide whether to re-open the valve on a suspended
flow of loans to Pakistan. For years, the lenders have been
demanding the kind of tax collection now being undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   This week, they will be hoping to see people paying up instead
of shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf, who has quite a folksy manner for a stiff-backed
military man, told his nation: ``It's high time we confronted
problems and catch the bull by the horns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
