u a BC-CAR-NASCAR-PETTY-NYTR     05-26 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-PETTY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTY FAMILY CARRIES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Richard Petty flashed the famous grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's doing real good. As long as everybody stays busy,
it's been real good,'' he said. ``Lynda gets a little emotional
sometimes, but...''
</P>
<P>
   Petty paused. In recent weeks, he and his wife have had to deal
with two enormous personal losses.
</P>
<P>
   First was the April 5 death of his father, Lee, which was not
unexpected. Lee Petty had been sick. Then on May 12, Petty's
19-year-old grandson, Adam, was killed while practicing for a race
at New Hampshire. Now, with great dignity, Richard Petty was trying
to explain the impact that had on the family.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty was the shining star of the Petty clan, the next
generation to get in the race car. He carried all the family's
hopes, their dreams, their plans for the future. Now he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pettys will carry on. Racing is their life, it has
always been their life, and it has been good to them. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   So Richard Petty did not find fault with his sport, although he
admitted, in the quiet reflection that followed Adam's death, he
had pangs of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking maybe if I hadn't pushed Kyle, maybe if I
hadn't worked with Adam, maybe this wouldn't have happened,'' Petty
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I picked up a paper and saw where two kids, 17 and 15,
had drowned in separate incidents. They were just trying to have
fun. That kind of lifted the cloud,'' Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   Petty understands that his family is not the first to lose a
child, that more is being made of Adam's death because of who he
was but that anytime a child dies, somebody hurts, somebody feels a
tremendous loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of living is dying, in this case, it just happened a lot
earlier than what we wanted,'' Petty said.``I'm 63, and when you're
63, you learn to go with the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how much impact Adam had. Very few 19-year-olds
touched as many people as Adam has. We've gotten calls and cards
from all over the world, not just from people who wanted to say how
sorry they were, but from people who actually met Adam. The
sympathy we've gotten has been great, and we do appreciate that,''
Petty said. ``But there's nothing we can do, nothing anybody can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Petty Enterprises will continue to field race cars. Kyle
Petty is not racing here this week in the Coca-Cola 600 but he'll
be back next week at Dover, Del. Someone will continue to drive
Petty cars them in the future, although it might not be a Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Petty, Kyle's surviving son, has no interest in driving,
according to Richard. He is 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I see him he's looking at a different career,''
Petty said. ``But as far as being a race car driver, I don't think
he's thought about that.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is time to move on, according to the head of the Petty
clan. One cannot dwell on death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll remember Adam for the smile on his face, the pat on the
back he gave everybody, the joking around. He was a pretty good
kid,'' Petty said. ``He always seemed to get along with everybody.
That's how I'm going to remember him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
