<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DODGE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATWOOD JOINS ELLIOTT ON EVERNHAM TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Dodge completed the foundation for its 2001
entry into Winston Cup this week when Ray Evernham announced that
Casey Atwood would join Bill Elliott as one of the drivers for his
two-car team.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham, formerly Jeff Gordon's crew chief, is heading up the
Dodge development program that plans a return to Winston Cup in
2001. NASCAR has not approved a design for the Dodge race car, but
Evernham recently tested an Intrepid at Homestead, Fla., and more
tests are planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making progress in the development of the car,''
Evernham said. ``The engine program is actually ahead of schedule,
so they are kind of dictating our testing program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have a car ready to present to NASCAR for approval
by late July or early August,'' he said. ``We were happy with the
first shakedown run and we will have some more announcements in the
next few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, who is 19, is regarded as one of the top young talents
in racing. At 17, he won the pole for the second Busch race he ever
ran. Last year, in his first full season on the Busch circuit,
Atwood won two races and two poles. He is the youngest driver in
history ever to win a Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey Atwood is an incredibly talented young driver,''
Evernham said. ``For 19 years of age, he's got a very good
understanding and feel for a race car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored to be part of this team,'' Atwood said. ``This is
what I've been working for all my life.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood now is competing in the Busch Series, where he has won
one pole and recorded three top 10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie to you, I'm nervous about moving up,''
Atwood said. ``But I've got the best behind me and it's a great
situation. If it were anything else, I wouldn't have taken it and
stayed in the Busch Series another year.''
</P>
<P>
   With Atwood under contract to Evernham, Dodge now has three
two-car teams ready to go at next year's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Enterprises and drivers John Andretti and Kyle Petty along
with Bill Davis' two-car team with drivers Ward Burton and Dave
Blaney are both switching to Dodge from Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
