<P>
   ELIAN-MEDIA (Washington) _ Proving once again that God has a
sense of humor, Elian Gonzalez has moved to the most media-centric
neighborhood on earth. The beast that has stalked the 6-year-old
Cuban boy since his shipwreck in November _ the tall-mast
television trucks and their cargoes of stand-up news personalities,
and the federal marshals with their yellow barricade tape _ now
lives on Newark Street in Washington's Cleveland Park. It and all
it represents have brought, shall we say, concern to the leafy
glade, home to an extraordinary concentration of prominent
Washington editors, publishers, political figures and power
brokers. A Cleveland Park journal by Tim Weiner. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   FREEH-RENO (Washington) _ The Justice Department considered but
decided against an independent counsel to investigate FBI Director
Louis Freeh for inaccurate congressional testimony in 1997 during a
hearing about the FBI laboratory's mishandling of cases. Attorney
General Janet Reno concluded that while Freeh's testimony was
inaccurate, there was no evidence of criminal intent that would
warrant the appointment of an independent prosecutor. By Neil A.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WILLEY (Washington) _ A three-judge federal panel
refuses to intervene in a lawsuit brought by a conservative group
accusing President Clinton of violating privacy law by releasing
letters of Kathleen Willey, who had said he groped her. The White
House had sought to halt pre-trial discovery, authorized by a
district judge. By David Stout. (500 words)
</P>
