<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: PREMIER APOLOGIZES
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori apologized for remarks last week
that seemed to endorse emperor worship. After several days of heavy
criticism, Mori, in a tense news conference, expressed regret that
his remarks had caused misunderstanding, but declined to retract
his statement altogether. In his original remarks, which critics
said echoed Japan's prewar militarism, Mori said Japan was ``a
divine nation with the emperor at its core.''
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: MILITARY PLEA
</P>
<P>
   The government asked those retired from the military and police
to re-enlist in the armed forces to bolster the 30,000 troops under
assault from separatist ethnic Tamils in the northern Jaffna
Peninsula. Those who rejoin would take the noncombat positions of
younger soldiers, who would then be moved to the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: ARMS BLAST
</P>
<P>
   An ammunition depot at a Taliban military base in Kabul exploded
close to a residential area, but no casualties were reported.
Officials accused the northern opposition forces led by Ahmad Shah
Masood of sabotage, but an opposition official denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: OPTIMISM ON TAIWAN
</P>
<P>
   After talks with Chinese military leaders and diplomats, an
American diplomat based in Beijing said he is hopeful China and
Taiwan can resume a dialogue regarding their differences. ``My
sense is that there's a genuine desire for a solution,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition he not be identified. He added
there had been no official change in China's policy that Taiwan
accept it is part of China, but ``somewhere in China's position
there's room for dialogue to start.''
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA: PLEA FOR AID
</P>
<P>
   North Korea plans to ask other countries for $250 million to
help people suffering from hunger and to achieve self-sufficiency
in food supplies by 2002, said David Morton, the top U.N. official
in the country. Morton said North Korean officials would present a
plan on June 20 to build agriculture production and reforest areas
stripped of trees.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: AFGHANISTAN WARNING
</P>
<P>
   The commander of Russia's border guards warned that Moscow risks
destabilizing part of Central Asia if it attacks outposts of
Afghanistan's Taliban, which Russian officials have accused of
training Chechen rebels. Gen. Konstantin Totsky said the attacks
could provoke violence in Uzbekistan and Tajikistan, two Russian
allies that are Afghanistan's neighbors. The Taliban has said it
would hold the two states liable for any Russian attacks.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: PRIME MINISTER CONDEMNS PREDECESSOR
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Poland, Prime Minister Bertie Ahern sharply
criticized former Prime Minister and Fianna Fail party leader
Charles Haughey, 74, saying his behavior ``offends against the
ethics and integrity of what our party stands for.'' A tribunal
will call Haughey, 74, to testify after amassing evidence of almost
$10 million he received between 1979 and 1996 in gifts, party
donations and bank loans that remain unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: E. COLI INQUEST
</P>
<P>
   Ontario's coroner will conduct an inquest into the deaths of
five people in an outbreak of E. coli bacteria in Walkerton, west
of Toronto. The outbreak, from polluted water, infected 10 percent
of the town's 5,000 people. Dr. Murray McQuigge, the area's medical
officer, has charged that the region's water company knew on May 18
the water was potentially contaminated, but maintained through May
21 that it was safe.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TEACHERS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Some 20,000 schoolteachers seeking a wage increase blocked
Mexico City's main street for 12 hours during a march to Ernesto
Zedillo's presidential compound, where they were blocked by
hundreds of riot policemen. Thousands of teachers from several
states have been camped in parks and on sidewalks for a week as
they press their salary demands, a yearly ritual.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: HARD-LINE PLEA
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that appeared to be a plea for peace with the new
reformist parliament, which convenes today, a senior hard-line
cleric asked legislators to solve their differences privately. ``We
must solve our problems among ourselves,'' said Ayatollah Ahmad
Janati, head of the Council of Guardians, an election watchdog.
``We must talk privately and avoid causing worry in the mind of the
public. National unity must be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA, ERITREA: NEW ADVANCES
</P>
<P>
   Despite renewed hopes for an end to the two-year war, Ethiopian
troops captured several more towns along its contested border with
Eritrea. Eritrea said it was complying with its pledge on Thursday
to stop fighting, pulling its troops back from the border and
withdrawing from two additional towns far to the east, Bure and
Bada. But Eritrea said it might resume the war if Ethiopia pushes
farther into its territory.'' &QR;
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA: GENOCIDE TERM CUT
</P>
<P>
   A former Rwandan mayor convicted in Switzerland for crimes
committed during the 1994 Rwanda genocide had his life sentence cut
to 14 years. A Geneva appeals court reduced the term given to
Fulgence Niyonteze, while agreeing he had incited Hutu extremists
to kill Tutsi and supplied them with weapons. Niyonteze fled to
Switzerland, and he was the first Rwandan suspected of genocide to
be judged by a foreign country's court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
