<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS MICROSOFT ACTED IRRESPONSIBLY IN TRIAL TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department denounced Microsoft Corp. on
Friday, accusing the company of cynical, irresponsible behavior on
the last day of its antitrust trial earlier this week. The
department also filed a modified version of its proposal to break
up the company that includes a handful of small, technical changes
that the judge had requested.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft now has two business days to file a response to the
form but not the substance of the revised proposal. That is
expected Wednesday, and the judge's final ruling in the
long-running antitrust case will most likely come in the following
day or two.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect prompted Microsoft on Friday to postpone a major
public event at the company campus in Redmond, Wash., at which
Microsoft leaders were to describe their visions of the computing
future. It had been scheduled for next Thursday, but was put off
for three weeks because ``there are strong indications'' that Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson will rule next week, a press release said.
</P>
<P>
   The revised government remedy proposal still requests a breakup
of the company and additional restrictions on conduct, exactly as
originally proposed on April 28. The changes are corrections of
typographical errors and small alterations of language to address
concerns the judge raised in court on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During that hearing, on the trial's last day, the judge strongly
suggested that he was leaning toward breaking up the company. And
Microsoft expressed surprise and disappointment when the judge
announced that he would not hold a separate phase of the trial to
consider a remedy _ complete with depositions, witnesses and
document requests. John Warden, a Microsoft lawyer, told Jackson he
found the idea ``that we would have some final resolution today
really incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a six-page brief filed along with its revised remedy
proposal this afternoon, the Justice Department called that ``just
a cynical ploy calculated to raise diversionary issues on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day on Wednesday, the brief noted, Microsoft
entered into evidence an ``offer of proof'' listing 16 academic
experts and Microsoft executives who would have been called as
witnesses if remedy hearings had been held, including the company
chairman, William H. Gates. A short time later, company
representatives also handed out dozens of copies to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The government's brief went on to say: ``The fact that Microsoft
had prepared but kept secreted in its briefcases a 35-page offer of
proof, concerning testimony from 16 different witnesses that it
allegedly wanted to offer, itself demonstrates both that Microsoft
was not genuinely surprised about what was expected of it and that
it was perfectly capable of being forthright with the Court but
chose not to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Mark Murray, called the government brief
``unfortunate,'' and said the company was genuinely surprised to
learn that the judge planned no additional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference in the judge's chambers on April 4, when
scheduling issues were discussed, the judge's remarks were in some
ways contradictory on this subject. On the one hand he said
emphatically that he intended to wrap up the remedy process within
60 days, by the end of May, saying: `What I do not want is to have
caused this thing to drag on through a number of months of
additional proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Warden, the Microsoft lawyer, asked him:
``Does your honor contemplate further proceedings of some kind or
another after the conclusion of this schedule?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the judge responded. ``I would assume that there would
be further proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department brief asserts that Microsoft has known
for many months that the government was likely to request a breakup
of the company ``and has had ample opportunity'' to express its
concerns. It says the company could have filed the statements from
Mr. Gates and the others along with its own proposed remedy on May
10, letting the judge know that Gates wanted to testify. But
instead, Microsoft's lawyers waited until after the judge had
already declared that there would be no more hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The government's evident suspicion from this is that the offer
of proof may not have been entirely genuine. But Murray reiterated
that Microsoft had no idea the trial would end on Wednesday.
Company lawyers brought along the offer of proof just out of a
sense of due diligence _ for the off-chance that the judge chose to
close the record.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been further hearings at which Gates had been called
to testify, the Justice Department would have been entitled to
subpoena additional e-mail and other documents from him relating to
the remedy question. Some of his e-mail messages obtained earlier
and shown during the trial undercut the company's legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   The government would also have been able to depose Gates and
cross-examine him on the stand. During his taped deposition in
preparation for the trial, in August 1998, Mr. Gates was halting
and forgetful as he slumped in his chair. His performance did not
help the company's case and may have done damage.
</P>
<P>
   The time to offer Gates' testimony, the government said, should
have been on May 10, the date the judge set for receiving
Microsoft's opinions on remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Murray responded: ``That kind of attitude is completely
unfortunate and completely groundless when you look at the facts.
``Microsoft lived up to its obligations in good faith, 100
percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
