<HEADLINE>
T-BIRD WATCHERS CAN SNARE A RARE OLD SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (For release on Sunday, May 28) 
(ART ADV:  Photos  are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The official announcement took no one by surprise: Ford said
last week that it would bring back the Thunderbird, this time as a
two-seat roadster closely modeled on a concept car that was a
sensation at auto shows last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 2002 T-Bird, which goes into production early next year,
will pick up where the 1955-57 left off. For '58, the T-Bird became
a larger, heavier four-seat car, and in later years it grew bloated
and overwrought. But Ford says the next-generation T-Bird is a
modern interpretation of the original, complete with turquoise
emblems and porthole windows in the removable hardtop.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stir up interest in the new car, even though
dealers have not begun to take orders, Ford is kicking off a
summerlong bird-watching contest that will culminate in a giveaway
of three original T-Birds.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this weekend in metropolitan New York, Southern
California and South Florida, three white mid-'50s roadsters will
drive through 144 communities. People who spot one of the cars _
they wear decals identifying them as part of Ford's American Dream
Car Tour _ can register to win one. Entries can be made over the
Internet at www.fordvehicles.com or by mail at Dream Car, Box 1955,
Young America, Minn. 55594; entrants should provide the day, city
and approximate location where they saw one of the special cars.
Winners are to be announced in October. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Price guides put the value of 1955-57 models _ the favorite of
collectors _ at $16,000 to $50,000. The '02 model, which will use
the rear-drive chassis and V-8 engine of the Lincoln LS sedan, is
expected to start around $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
