<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CLOSE LOWER, ENDING POOR WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks ended a tough week slightly lower Friday, with
the Dow Jones industrial average at its lowest level since
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Trading ahead of the three-day Memorial Day weekend was the
slowest this year, adding to the volatility during the day. But
though Friday's declines were small they added to a sharp drop for
the week. It appeared that the bearish sentiment sparked by the
Federal Reserve's short-term interest rate increase 10 days ago was
still intact.
</P>
<P>
   And when investors return Tuesday, they will still have to face
uncertainty about how much higher the nation's central bank will
push short-term interest rates. And they will be wondering if the
beleaguered technology sector has further to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Richard E. Cripps, the chief market strategist at Legg Mason
Wood Walker in Baltimore, predicted that all three major market
indexes would remain in a trading range, with the bottom a little
below where they are now, until investors sense that the Federal
Reserve has finished raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that investors will have to find new ``drivers''
for the market because he did not expect technology stocks ``to
continue the performance in the future that they have had in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index slipped 0.24 point, to 3,205.11,
while the Dow Jones industrial average fell 24.68 points, or 0.2
percent, to 10,299.24. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
dropped 3.5 points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,378.02. Volume on the New
York Stock Exchange was very light, with just 719.88 million shares
changing hands. The daily average for the year is 1.036 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the Nasdaq fell 5.5 percent. For the year, the
technology-heavy index is down 21.2 percent and is just above its
low for the year, which it reached Tuesday. The Dow fell 3.1
percent for the week and is off 10.4 percent for the year. The Dow
is also now below the level it fell to during the week ending April
14. That 7.3 percent decline was the Dow's worst week since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P declined 2.1 percent for the week and is off 6.2 percent
for the year. It is still 21.46 points above its April 14 level.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big losers for the week were General Motors, down 19
percent, and Georgia Pacific, down 18.3 percent. GM disappointed
investors by limiting participation in an exchange of its stock for
a stake in its Hughes Electronics subsidiary. Georgia-Pacific and
other paper companies fell over concern about falling prices and
fears that rising interest rates would slow economic growth.
Goldman Sachs Group, which dropped 17.4 percent, warned analysts
that second- quarter earnings would be less than expected.
</P>
<P>
   On the technology side, CMGI fell 16.9 percent, Broadvision
dropped 18.6 percent, Qualcomm declined 25.9 percent and Qlogic
slipped 26 percent. Microsoft also had a rough week, falling 5.6
percent. But Intel rallied Friday to finish the week off less than
one-third of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   With every investor looking for signs that the economy is
finally slowing under the weight of the Fed's higher interest
rates, the bond market got a lift from the report that orders for
durable goods fell 6.4 percent in April, more than forecast. The
yield on the Treasury's 10-year note fell to 6.32 percent, from
6.39 percent on Thursday. The price, which moves in the opposite
direction, rose 15/32, to 101 8/32. The yield was down from 6.48
percent a week ago. The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 6.06
percent from 6.11 percent on Thursday and was down from 6.20
percent a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of investor sentiment on how much higher the Fed
might push its benchmark federal funds target on overnight loans
between banks is federal funds futures contracts. The contract for
October now shows an average rate for the month of 7.03 percent,
down just slightly from 7.06 percent a week ago. The December
contract is at 7.16 percent. Currently, the Fed's target is at 6.5
percent after the half a percentage point increase on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have been undermining the technology sector. One
is that the flow of funds into the aggressive growth and technology
stock mutual funds that invest in the technology sector has sharply
declined recently. According to AMG Data Services, the pace of net
inflows into these funds was $6.8 billion over the four weeks
ending March 22. That fell to $3.1 billion in the week ending April
12 and is now down to $948 million in the four weeks ending May 24.
And for the last week, there were net outflows from these funds:
$169 million from technology and $496 million from aggressive
growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   Cripps of Legg Mason also said that money managers and
individual investors were still overloaded with technology stocks.
He said that as these stocks fall further, more investors and
managers will decide they have too many and sell, adding to the
downward pressure on this sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
