<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: `WE CAN'T WALK AWAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The violence and chaos of Zimbabwe
cast a shadow on its neighbor these days. South Africa is an
utterly different country, far more developed and sophisticated.
But some in the West fear it will go down the same road.
</P>
<P>
   I asked South Africa's minister of finance, Trevor Manuel, what
he would say to those doubters. What assurance is there that this
country will not follow Robert Mugabe's path to lawlessness and
autocracy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a very strong Constitution,'' Manuel said, ``and a
very strong, fiercely independent Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a Constitution that sets up a number of strong
institutions. And many of those provisions came from the African
National Congress. They weren't foisted on us.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first non-racial election, in 1994, the ANC has
dominated the government. But not long after that election
President Nelson Mandela emphasized the supremacy of the
Constitution and the court that interprets it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the Constitutional Court held that Mandela had acted
unconstitutionally in making rules for a provincial election
without parliamentary enabling legislation. Mandela, rather than
protesting the decision, said it ``confirms that our new democracy
is taking firm root. This is something of which we should be
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Will that spirit go on? I asked Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have to go on,'' he said. ``We lived in an
environment, under apartheid, in which power was abused. The
Constitution creates a sense of responsibility. We can't walk away
from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of establishing democracy was an internal
negotiating process, not under the aegis of a colonial power. And
the moving spirit was, `We're all going to have to live here
together.'''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the institutions created and protected by the
Constitution, Manuel pointed to the Reserve Bank of South Africa.
The Constitution provides that it should act ``independently and
without fear.'' ``Do I disagree sometimes with its monetary
policy?'' Manuel asked. ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   A financial consultant with whom I spoke, Doug Band, had a
similar view of the importance of the rule of law in keeping South
Africa free and stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been in Europe,'' he said. ``People talked about
Zimbabwe and said it foretold what's going to happen in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer was that we have a very strong Constitution _ and a
democratic disposition. It would be hard to move toward
dictatorship. There's an allegiance to law.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Africa wants to be part of the world. The government
well recognizes that if it doesn't show the world a real commitment
to the rule of law, the game is up.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many indications of public respect for law as the
foundation of the new South Africa. When an ANC official allegedly
charged that racial bias lay behind the conviction of a well-known
figure, Allan Boesak, for corruption, many voices criticized him. A
newspaper with a largely black readership, The Sowetan, said those
critics ``must be supported.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the homelier level _ in terms of crime _ respect for law
has a long way to go. The police, who under apartheid focused on
political repression, remain severely inadequate. Manuel said
changing the police had ``proved to be one of the most difficult
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course South Africa has profound problems. Unemployment is
estimated to be as high as 50 percent. Job creation is an urgent
economic need. Blacks were dispossessed of most of the country's
land; events in Zimbabwe have led to increasing calls from both
blacks and whites for orderly redistribution.
</P>
<P>
   But what is striking to a visitor is the sense of determination
and optimism. Several people in the business community used those
words, among them Bobby Godsell, the CEO of Anglogold.
</P>
<P>
   I interviewed Manuel after he spoke to a high-powered economic
group. The audience cheered when he said, ``The one thing we as
South Africans need is to believe in our souls and our future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
