u a BC-HARVARD-RUDENSTINE-NY     05-26 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-RUDENSTINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PRESIDENT SAYS HE'LL MISS UNIVERSITY'S `EFFERVESCENCE'
</HEADLINE>
  By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE , Mass. _ Neil L. Rudenstine doesn't even look tired.
</P>
<P>
   The last that many heard from Rudenstine, the 26th president of
Harvard University, was in 1994, when he slept through a series of
public appointments and abruptly took a three-month leave for what
he called, simply, exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   He returned, tanned, from a beach vacation and since then has
completed the largest fund-raising campaign in the history of
higher education, turned Radcliffe College into an Institute for
Advanced Study with a $300 million endowment and celebrated the
30th anniversary of Harvard's Afro-American studies department with
the dream team of black scholars he helped assemble during his nine
years there.
</P>
<P>
   He has done most of it quietly, rarely seizing the stage
afforded the head of the nation's oldest and most storied
university. This week, without so much as a news conference,
Rudenstine, 65, sent word that he would retire after next year's
commencement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is exhilarating _ the amount of total firepower it
has,'' Rudenstine said of Harvard, with its 364-year history and
its 18,000 students and 2,000 professors. ``It's hard to get
through a week without having some kind of a discussion that
doesn't really set you off thinking or reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Pondering his future, Rudenstine said he would miss the
``effervescence'' of the campus, sighing, ``It's awfully hard to
find that in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and a new place to live. Rudenstine and his wife,
Angelica, an art historian and curator, long ago sold their home in
Princeton, N.J., and have been storing their books and etchings in
the three-story Colonial, built in 1767, where Harvard's president
has lived since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Sipping Perrier in the house's library, with its
floor-to-ceiling bookshelves and sea-foam-green paint, Rudenstine
stared into space as he reflected on his time as president, once
rising to move his gaze out the window to the expansive lawn. A
scholar of 16th-century poetry, he could not select a verse, on the
spot, to sum up the experience, but said he had lately been leafing
through works that were more contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed very important to be in touch with this century
and what's going on,'' he said. ``Whatever roads of access I could
find, I chose.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Ossining, N.Y., the son of a Russian Jewish immigrant
and a first-generation Italian-American Catholic, Rudenstine
started his education at a one-room schoolhouse in rural
Connecticut, then climbed the ivory tower, earning degrees at
Princeton, Harvard and Oxford. After a dissertation on Sir Philip
Sidney, a 16th-century poet, he taught English briefly at Harvard
but spent most of his career as an administrator at Princeton. He
is only the sixth president of Harvard appointed since the Civil
War and, having arrived in 1991, will have had the shortest tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his predecessors, Rudenstine did not establish
himself as a kind of public intellectual, holding sway on the
issues of the day. He testified before Congress in support of
government financing of scientific research, and, in academic
circles, was a leading supporter of affirmative action, but never
penetrated to the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``My voice and voices like it haven't been paid much attention
to,'' he lamented. ``I think I assumed, given the welter of voices,
it probably wasn't going to be picked up. It's not easy to have
your voice picked up these days.'' In 1957, he noted, the president
of Princeton was on the cover of Time magazine; ``you can't even
conceive of that happening today.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rudenstine, like his colleagues at universities
around the country, spent much of his time raising money. And he
was awfully good at it, averaging more than $1 million a day for
six years, a pace that allowed him to shatter a staggering $2.1
billion campaign goal by $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if it's some kind of extra skill that you have to
develop,'' he said with a shrug. ``It fundamentally is an extension
of the extent to which you have ideals and goals you're persuaded
by. If you believe enough in those things, it resonates with
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern university president often seems more chief executive
than scholar, a paradigm Rudenstine rejects. While elsewhere the
job has been restructured ``so as to take people further and
further away from the things that connect you to the academic heart
of the institution,'' he said, Harvard demands that its president
stay engaged, by requiring him to oversee all tenure decisions
personally. ( Rudenstine has handled more than 250.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You come away with a constant probing of where things are
going and why they're going that way,'' he said. ``If you're not
recapitalizing your intellectual capital, you're not going to know
enough to lead anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know what to do next, what could possibly match
the prestige _ or the perks _ of a post that included trips to East
Africa, Latin America, France, Germany, England and, twice, China.
There was that astonishing meeting of Shanghai's Harvard Club that
silently spoke the geopolitical story of a century _ a room full of
elderly men who had graduated before World War II, another room of
young entrepreneurs with degrees from the 1980's and 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   He will undoubtedly get more rest, though ever since that very
high-profile collapse, he has been diligent about down time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't book yourselves a real vacation around here, six
months in advance, you just don't get it,'' he said. Now, the
Rudenstines take a week in January, two or three weeks in the
summer and lots of long weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just made sure,'' he said, ``that things didn't get
encroached upon and washed away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
