<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVELAND PARK JOURNAL: A MEDIA SHOW COMES HOME TO ROOST 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Proving once again that God has a sense of humor,
Elian Gonzalez has moved to the most media-centric neighborhood on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   The beast that has stalked the 6-year-old Cuban boy since his
shipwreck in November _ the tall-masted television trucks and their
cargoes of stand-up news personalities, the federal marshals with
their yellow barricade tape _ now lives in an estate on Newark
Street in Washington's Cleveland Park.
</P>
<P>
   It and all it represents have brought, shall we say, concern to
the leafy glade, home to an extraordinary concentration of
prominent Washington editors, publishers, political figures and
power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighbors are scared of the media frenzy that they had in
Miami,'' said Derry Craig, who lives around the corner from the
estate owned by the youth foundation, Youth for Understanding
International Exchange. Her husband, Gregory Craig, President
Clinton's lawyer during the late unpleasantness of impeachment, and
thus no stranger to such frenzies, brought his clients, Elian and
his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to Newark Street late Thursday
night to begin their latest experience of America.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not Little Havana. In fact, ``this is not America,''
said Debby Weil, 48, a dot-com marketing manager who lives on
Newark Street. ``It's an incredibly privileged, upper-percentile
place,'' _ replete with Volvo station wagons, private schools and
golden retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   The street is the heart of Cleveland Park, not Washington's
richest or most exclusive neighborhood but home to more than a few
media chieftains: Donald Graham, the publisher of The Washington
Post; Jim Lehrer, the public television news anchor; David
Ignatius, the next editor of The International Herald Tribune;
Michael Oreskes, Washington bureau chief of The New York Times;
Judy Woodruff of CNN and her husband, Al Hunt of The Wall Street
Journal, to name a few, are now Elian's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Because the neighborhood is such a media-rich environment,
``there is mild amusement that the chickens have come home to
roost,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and his son now live at the Rosedale estate, a 1793
dwelling surrounded by a greensward that was, until Friday, the
neighborhood's public dog run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That beautiful lawn was where we all walk our dogs,'' Weil
said. ``The first thought was: can we still walk our dogs?'' Yes,
but only on a narrow strip between the yellow tape and the street,
and only on a leash. So there was a muted howling at the dog run
Fraiday morning, and it was not coming from the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Directly across Newark Street from the Rosedale estate stands
the home of a 47-year-old conservative pundit who frequently writes
for the New Yorker and requested, no, insisted, on anonymity. He
finds the arrival of the Elian entourage in his neighborhood _
where he says ``Dukakis for President'' bumper stickers still cling
to those Volvos _ beyond satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment it was announced _ `Guess who's coming to dinner!'
_ all these Janet Reno devotees, who a month ago were saying, `Good
for Janet for getting him out,' are now singing a far different
aria,'' he said. ``Now that their little darling is in their
backyards, the cry has gone up _ `What about the dogs?'''
</P>
<P>
   A cynic (or a novelist) might foresee a turn in the
neighborhood's perception of the Elian saga, he said, now that
``the billion-footed centipede is leaving droppings on their
lawns.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward Just, a novelist who has chronicled the political culture
of Washington since the 1960s, foresaw exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict,'' Just said, tongue deeply imbedded in cheek,
``many op-ed articles about the intrusiveness of the press, some
written by newspapermen. There's going to be a lot of new interest
in normalizing relations with Cuba. And if all else fails, they'll
call for Reno's resignation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
