<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL COMMENTARY: TRADING MORE NOW FOR LESS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because it is so contentious, the debate over reforming Social
Security draws plenty of attention. So it is easy to overlook that
Congress has just reformed Social Security _ enacting a change that
should have been contentious but somehow wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, people in their late 60s have the choice of
collecting a full pension while also earning handsome pay. That is
dangerous. What America's senior citizens decide to do with this
choice will affect their level of income _ or poverty _ in deep old
age. Because of the way the new law plays to human nature, many
might make the wrong choice. Some already have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting to collect benefits is basically betting that you will
live beyond the average life expectancy,'' said Peter Orszag, an
economist and Social Security expert at the University of
California at Berkeley. That average for people who are already 65
is 81 for men and 84 for women, and rising for both. ``When you
give people in their late 60s the choice of collecting their Social
Security benefits now, then you raise the odds of their being poor
in real old age.''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics are simple enough. Previously, people between 65
and 70 who earned more than $17,000 a year had their Social
Security pension benefits reduced, and those who earned more than
$50,000 a year had them postponed entirely, until they turned 70 or
stopped earning so much. As a quid pro quo, the monthly pension
checks they ultimately received were higher the longer after 65
they had to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time, people in their late 60s can earn any
amount and still draw full pensions. But the old quid pro quo
survives: people can still voluntarily wait until 70 to get larger
checks thereafter. Those who take their pensions at 65 get a head
start in total benefits paid, but those who wait will overtake them
in their 80s, and the longer they live, the wider the gap grows.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly payment at 70, for example, would be $1,300 for
someone who passed up $1,000 at 65.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had been moving gradually in this direction, but the
new legislation, signed by President Clinton April 7, completed the
process in one leap.
</P>
<P>
   But that is politics. The real issues are work incentives and
adequate income in very old age, particularly the latter. It is
still possible to voluntarily hold off collecting pension benefits
until age 70, but hardly anyone has chosen to do so. Of 419,000
registered wage earners in their late 60s who were collecting
either reduced benefits or none at all when the new law took effect
in April, only 800 are still holding off until age 70.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean the others have all actively chosen not to
wait; many were probably swept passively onto the benefit rolls. To
minimize its clerical work, the Social Security Administration sent
out letters announcing that all 419,000 would receive full benefits
automatically, unless they called a toll-free number and
specifically opted to wait. Getting through on the often-busy phone
line was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   People who wanted to wait could also have sent back their first
checks. But in defiance of a main tenet of mainstream economics,
that people make rational decisions in their best interest, hardly
anyone returned the checks. ``People in their 60s in good health
whose parents lived long lives should rationally choose to defer,''
said Henry Aaron, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution.
``But there is a tendency to want your money now.'' Particularly
when it is in hand and substantial; the first checks averaged
$3,500, retroactively covering the first four months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   There is a second irrational tendency among people drawing both
paychecks and benefit checks: to spend it all rather than save for
future retirement, increasing the odds of poverty later. But
Congress gave in to an irrational outcry from working people in
their late 60s who complained with growing frequency that
withholding benefits was an unjust ``tax'' on work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real misperception out there that when the money is
withheld it is gone; they will never see it again,'' said Kenneth
Apfel, commissioner of Social Security. ``The number of seniors who
perceive this is not insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   So Congress acted. The budget and Social Security surpluses
helped to make the action politically palatable.
</P>
<P>
   So did another misperception: that in a robust economy suffering
labor shortages, removing the earnings limits would encourage
senior citizens to work a lot more. The most optimistic studies
fail to support this contention. Hours worked will rise 4 or 5
percent at most, or roughly the equivalent of 50,000 full-time
workers a year. That is what today's strong economy absorbs in a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is a lesson here for judging the Gore and Bush
proposals for Social Security reform: Look for the misperceptions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
