<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-INSECURITY-GATES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A NEW AGE OF RISK, OLD TESTS OF LOYALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, May 27, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By ROBERT M. GATES    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was surprisingly little shock when the General Accounting
Office revealed this week that investigators with forged badges
were able to gain entry into what are supposedly some of the most
secure of federal agencies. It was, after all, only the latest in a
series of similarly alarming stories about security lapses in the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The holders of the phony badges were intentionally testing
security at doorways of the Justice Department, Pentagon, CIA, FBI
and State Department. Earlier reports described security lapses
including the bugging of a conference room and the theft of a
laptop computer, loaded with highly classified information, at the
State Department; allegations of misuse of nuclear weapons
information at Los Alamos, and concerns about government officials
flouting security regulations.
</P>
<P>
   What is going on? Did security discipline inside the United
States government collapse along with the Soviet Union? Has
technology, including the proliferation of computers, Internet
access and e-mail, made security significantly harder to enforce?
Is there a lack of concern about security among senior officials
and a concomitant inadequacy of priority and resources?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to all of these questions would appear to be yes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, security problems are nothing new. Espionage from
abroad and violations of security rules at home were facts of life
during the Cold War and were found at virtually every department
and agency possessing sensitive information. All too often, misuse
of such information was attributable to senior officials.
</P>
<P>
   The technical problems in providing security are plainly more
difficult than they were a decade or two ago. The material on a
single floppy disk, carried out of a government building in a
pocket, once would have required a wheelbarrow to purloin. The
Internet creates an opportunity to send secrets anywhere in the
world without risky dead drops and brush passes. And there is the
temptation to bypass the rules by transferring secret information
to one's own computer for reasons as mundane as personal
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Still, new technological advances are naturally answered by new
rules and monitoring techniques. As before, good security is
primarily a matter of compliance with rules and procedures that
already exist.
</P>
<P>
   A deeper change is atmospheric. In World War II and, to a
somewhat lesser extent, during the Cold War, there was a very real
sense on the part of those with access to sensitive information
that security really mattered because of the stakes involved in
those struggles. This didn't stop a small number of Americans from
spying for others and a much larger number from leaking secrets.
Overall, though, there was more discipline, and more people cared,
because we were in life and death conflicts and few wanted to give
our adversaries any advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the risks seem smaller now to many _ including not
only people directly charged with protecting secrets, but also
those who control their budgets. As defense, intelligence and
diplomatic budgets have shrunk, resources for security _ physical
safety as well as protection of information _ often have been early
victims of the budget axes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, tone and attitude at the top are vital.
From the outset of the current administration, whether by allowing
people to work at the White House before security clearances were
approved by the FBI or showing indifference to and even disdain for
security as a manifestation of a ``Cold War mindset,'' a message
has been sent that these issues are no longer very important.
Individual senior officials in various departments and agencies
have reinforced that message, partly with arrogant attitudes
conveying the idea that the rules do not apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   Good security still starts and ends with trust, integrity and
seriousness of purpose. Agencies need more resources. But simply
observing the rules that already exist, from the top down, would go
a long way.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert M. Gates served on the National Security Council staff
under four presidents and was director of central intelligence
under President George Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
