A7057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-580&AMP;AD     05-26 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON IN ACCORD WITH U.N. ON ISRAELI WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ISRAEL-LEBANON-BORDER) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Lebanon has indicated that it will abide by
the United Nations' certification of Israel's withdrawal from
southern Lebanon, the U.N. special envoy to the Middle East, Terje
Rowed-Larsen, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Larsen's assessment proves true, it could smooth a
significant bump in the road ahead. A rejection by Lebanon of the
United Nations' certification would give the green light to
guerrillas of the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah, or Party of God, to
continue their violent struggle against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   With official Lebanese acceptance, however, Hezbollah, despite
its fiery statements, would probably incline toward restraint.
Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, the group's leader, has said many times
that he would not defy the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in another sign of the way Nasrallah and the Lebanese
establishment are embracing each other this week, the sheik
appeared for the first time in front of a Lebanese, rather than a
Hezbollah, flag at a large victory rally.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern town of Bint Jubayl, a couple of miles from the
Israeli border, he also went out of his way to pronounce the
Israeli withdrawal earlier this week from its former security zone
as a victory for all of Lebanon and not just for his fighters.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Nasrallah spoke freely and casually with
foreign journalists, analyzing events for the first time since the
Israeli withdrawal. He said the fact that the Israelis were able to
withdraw without any casualties was not for Hezbollah's lack of
trying. His fighters fired on Israeli troops but they did so under
heavy aircraft cover and at night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheik also said that Hezbollah's march through southern
Lebanon on Tuesday, when they retook village after village and
forced an overnight Israeli withdrawal from the zone, was so
spontaneous that neither Syria nor Iran knew about it in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found out like everybody else did,'' Nasrallah said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese president and prime minister have not made their
position on the U.N. certification process public, even as U.N.
teams fanned out across southern Lebanon on Friday to verify
whether Israel's withdrawal was complete.
</P>
<P>
   While lower-level Lebanese officials and their Syrian
counterparts insisted that the U.N. determination would be
discounted, they avoided the subject and spoke positively of
collaborating with the United Nations in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government's position has been murky since the U.N.
Security Council rejected Beirut's claim that the withdrawal would
be complete only if Israel also pulled out of a pocket of disputed
land beside the Golan Heights _ a remote, rugged area known as the
Shebaa Farms.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, rejecting the Security Council's position would
prove costly for Lebanon, which not only needs the United Nations'
assistance but seeks international backing to rebuild the
war-ravaged southern zone. On the other hand, Lebanon faces
pressure from Hezbollah and Syria to hold fast to its principles.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Lebanon a way to accept the United Nations' authority
without compromising its position, the United Nations underlined
that it was not determining sovereignty over the Shebaa Farms area,
which was under Syrian control when Israel occupied it. Lebanon and
Syria could draft new maps clearly defining their border, Larsen
said, and petition the U.N. Security Council to change its
resolutions governing the territories accordingly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Any nongovernmental organization that hopes to be treated as
legitimate has to adapt to the decisions of the Security Council,
too,'' Larsen said, referring to Hezbollah and other resistance
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has an interest in keeping the conflict alive, apart
from its ideological one. If the withdrawal is accepted, the
Lebanese army will eventually move into the southern zone and then
seek to disarm the guerrillas. But Hezbollah and the Syrian
government, which assists it, are not ready to lay down their
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   So it suits their purposes to insist that the occupation of
southern Lebanon still exists even if Hezbollah quietly agrees not
to take the initiative in any violence toward Israel. How this
contradiction resolves itself will be seen after the United Nations
certifies the Israeli withdrawal, which is expected to happen soon.
</P>
<P>
   Nasrallah said this week that Hezbollah would not attack
civilians across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again,'' he said, ``not all Israelis are civilians, so
anything is possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
