<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS UNDER WAY TO INVOLVE BRADLEY IN GORE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the more than two months since Vice President Al
Gore vanquished former Sen. Bill Bradley in the quest for the
Democratic presidential nomination, the two men have not spoken.
But there are signs there may soon be a rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bradley say they expect the former senator from New
Jersey to appear with Gore sometime before the Democratic
convention in August, and possibly as soon as next month. And in a
news conference Thursday night, Gore acknowledged as much.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected to appear publicly with Bradley, Gore
imitated a fortune teller, closing his eyes, pointing a finger to
his temple and saying, ``I see that in the future.'' He declined to
say when the appearance would take place.
</P>
<P>
   And though the two men have not spoken in weeks, Gore contended
that their relationship is ``in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are in regular communication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some people have doubts that those talks can overcome the
bad feelings left by the primaries. Disappointed by his failure to
win a single state and dismayed by Gore's brass-knuckle campaign,
Bradley disappeared from public view after bowing out of the race
on March 9. And Gore, who rarely even mentions Bradley on the
stump, has made little effort to draw him out, raising questions
about whether the vice president even considered Bradley's support
useful.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive
Republican nominee, held a splashy news conference more than two
weeks ago to announce the endorsement of his main primary rival,
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to the two Democrats have been in negotiations that
are expected to culminate in plans for Bradley to campaign for, and
possibly with, Gore. Conducting the negotiations are Tony Coelho,
Gore's campaign chairman, and Rick Wright, Bradley's close friend
and former campaign treasurer. The talks have focused largely on
Bradley's role at the convention and the number of delegates he
will be assigned.
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, Gore said Bradley will definitely be
given time to speak at the convention. Asked about negotiations
over delegates, the vice president replied, ``I don't think there
will be a problem of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bradley say talks between the two camps have been
reasonably smooth. But some friends of Bradley contend that Gore
should have acted sooner to unify the party and recruit Bradley's
help. They say one reason that Bradley has kept a low profile is
that Gore has not called him directly to request his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've obviously made a calculation that they don't need
Bradley's help,'' said one Democratic member of Congress who
supported Bradley during the primaries. ``But I think that's a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear if Bradley will formally endorse Gore. When he
withdrew from the race in March, Bradley said he would support
Gore, but refrained from using the word ``endorse.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bradley insisted that he was not playing word games
and that he intended to work hard for Gore _ even as he refused to
say the e-word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
