<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRTRAN0527-COX     05-26 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta subsidiary opposes AirTran flights to National
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran Airways' application for new rights to fly
between Atlanta and Washington's Reagan National Airport ought to
be tossed out, a subsidiary of rival Delta Air Lines says.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the U.S. Department of Transportation, Atlantic
Southeast Airlines argues that a law opening National to new
carriers is aimed at boosting service to smaller airports _ not
huge hubs like Hartsfield International.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unclear whether AirTran is requesting that the
department disregard the law entirely or merely ignore the fact
that all its flights from National will (oh by the way) stop in
Atlanta before going to cities which do qualify,'' ASA said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department should dismiss AirTran's application for
failure to qualify under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ASA, owned by Delta, also wants National flights. But it's
seeking approval for service to Jacksonville, a route it says fits
the law's intent.
</P>
<P>
   ASA and AirTran are among several carriers vying for ``slot
exemptions'' at National created in an aviation funding bill signed
into law this spring. Slots are airline-owned landing rights used
to control congestion at National and a few other airports.
</P>
<P>
   The exemptions will enable DOT-designated carriers to add
service at National without slots. They are intended in part to
foster more service between National and small and midsized
airports.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran, in an application filed May 5, sought approval for five
daily Hartsfield-National round-trips. It said it would also offer
one-stop service via Hartsfield to three smaller Southeast cities
and connections to many more. AirTran argued its presence on the
routes would bring down fares.
</P>
<P>
   But ASA called that a pretext to gain access to the
Hartsfield-National nonstop market, now served only by Delta and US
Airways. AirTran flies to outlying Washington Dulles International
but could generate more business traffic flying to National.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Marketing Director Tad Hutcheson said ASA's filing shows
that ``Delta, through a subsidiary, obviously wants to keep its
stranglehold on one of the nation's busiest air markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The DOT will award the exemptions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Friday, ASA said it plans to start regional jet
flights between Atlanta and Dallas-Love Field July 1, the first
service on the route. The flights will augment Delta's existing
service between Atlanta and Dallas-Fort Worth International, a
route also flown nonstop by AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
