<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS WITHDRAWS FROM FRENCH OPEN; SAMPRAS TO FACE
PHILIPPOUSIS
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Citing an injury to her left knee, Serena Williams
withdrew from the French Open Friday shortly before the draw had
been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a tough year for the Williams sisters, who thrived
on all surfaces and in all mediums in 1999. Because of tendinitis
in her wrists, Venus Williams has only played four matches and has
lost two of them. The younger Serena, the reigning U.S. Open
champion, has not played for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   The French Open is set to begin Monday, when fans will be able
to see how the Roland Garros complex has been transformed in a
hurry. The center court on which Steffi Graf and Andre Agassi
surprised the tennis world, and themselves, by winning last year's
singles titles, was partly torn down two weeks after their
victories. It was rebuilt to create more comfortable and spacious
environs for players and officials. The bad news is that there are
now 1,000 fewer seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year the French seem to try something different here, to
improve their facilities in one way or another,'' said Michael
Chang, the 1989 French Open champion. ``It's unbelievable how they
got this all up in 10 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Counting his victory here, Agassi has won three of the last four
Grand Slam events, but his play has been listless in recent weeks.
Even though he has a straightforward first-round match against a
French wild card, Anthony Dupuis, it might be considered bold to
pick the top-seeded player to defend his title here. To do so, he
would have to beat the likes of Gustavo Kuerten, Alex Corretja,
Dominik Hrbaty, Marat Safin, Cedric Pioline and Magnus Norman and
an abundance of what the French call ``les outsiders dangereux'' in
the draw.
</P>
<P>
   It would require even more pluck to pick Pete Sampras to win the
only Grand Slam trophy still missing from his Beverly Hills home.
Even though he is capable of beating anyone on his least favorite
surface _ witness that his victory over Norman on Thursday in
Duesseldorf, Germany, came in the relatively meaningless World Team
Cup _ he is also capable of faltering against anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening round, the second-seeded Sampras will face Mark
Philippousis. The hard-serving Australian was up a set on Sampras
in the Wimbledon quarterfinals last year before being forced to
retire with a knee injury. And for all of his natural force and
taste for risk, Philippousis is quite comfortable on clay and
played brilliantly indoors on it during Australia's Davis Cup
victory over France last December.
</P>
<P>
   Philippousis is not seeded here because his recent form has been
patchy, but then so has Sampras'. After an injury-forced layoff, he
was beaten in straight sets last week in the German Open by Arnaud
Di Pasquale of France. It was Sampras' only official clay-court
tournament so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   And lurking in the third round in Sampras' section of the draw
could be either Hicham Arazi, who usually saves his best for Roland
Garros, or Markus Hipfl, a huffing, grunting, clay-loving Austrian
who plays a bit like Thomas Muster.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Sampras-Philippousis, there are other intriguing
first-round matchups, including Marcelo Rios versus Tommy Haas;
Kuerten versus Sweden's newest teen-ager with talent, Andres
Vinciguerra; and Lleyton Hewitt, the Australian teen-ager who is
seeded for the first time in a Grand Slam event, versus feisty the
American veteran Jeff Tarango, who has played quite well of late.
</P>
<P>
   The women's draw has some first-round encounters worth
underscoring. Jennifer Capriati, seeded 15th, could have difficulty
against Colombia's Fabiola Zuluaga if she does not recover the
fitness and consistency that were missing in Rome last week.
Lindsay Davenport, seeded No. 2, could struggle against Dominique
Van Roost if her injured back is not sufficiently healed to let her
swing and serve away with her customary force and confidence.
Third-seeded Monica Seles also has a potentially tricky match
against Silvija Talaja, although Seles' focused and occasionally
ferocious play on her way to the Italian Open title make a strong
case for her winning here.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, top-seeded Martina Hingis lost the final, her
composure and a fair number of fans against Graf. Now, still seeded
first, she has another chance to win it all, opening in the first
round against Sabine Appelmans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
