<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURNED STUDENT ACCUSES OXFORD UNIVERSITY OF ELITISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Laura Spence doesn't look much like a revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   But when the unassuming 18-year-old honors student from a
middle-class high school in northern England accused Oxford
University, Britain's most exclusive, of elitism because it
rejected her application, she reignited the long-simmering class
war that divides this nation.
</P>
<P>
   If some here would like to dismiss Spence as a purveyor of sour
grapes who couldn't make the grade at Oxford, their case is
severely weakened by the fact that she has won a $100,000
scholarship to Harvard University. She will begin her freshman year
in Cambridge _ Massachusetts, not England _ next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's complaint that Oxford favors rich students from private
schools and privileged families has won her influential allies,
including Gordon Brown, chancellor of the exchequer and second only
to Prime Minister Tony Blair as the most powerful figure in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Brown called Oxford's decision to reject Spence ``an absolute
scandal,'' and said she was the victim of ``an interview system
that is more reminiscent of the old boy network and the old school
tie than genuine justice in our society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about time for an end to that old Britain where what
matters more are the privileges you are born with rather than the
potential you actually have,'' Brown fumed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Blair said the prime minister backed Brown's
comments, and government ministers hinted that they might cut
Oxford's subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford, already reeling from recent claims that it was resting
on its ``Chariots of Fire'' laurels and had long ago lost its edge,
has tried to defend itself. Andrew Hobson, the admissions director
at Magdalen College, the Oxford school to which Spence had applied
to study medicine, insisted that her socioeconomic background had
nothing to do with her rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's case has become front-page news in Britain, nearly all
of it sympathetic to her. In public debates, those who hold Oxford
up as a symbol of everything that's wrong with the smug,
self-satisfied element in Britain square off with traditionalists
who look down their noses at anything outside the realm and defend
the old ways as the best ways.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloids are gleefully rubbing the toffs' noses in it, while
even the more right-wing, traditional voices in the British media
are asking why such a bright English girl has to skip off to
America to get a top-notch education.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kelley, the head teacher at Monkseaton Community High
School in North Tyneside, where Spence is one of the most
accomplished students, believes Spence stirred a much-needed debate
in Britain about class and higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has touched a raw nerve, and that's a good thing,'' said
Kelley, an American, speaking from his office, while Spence sat
across from him, lamenting that yet another reporter wanted to talk
to her. ``Britain has a problem with discrimination, including
discriminating against people because of their class. But Britain
is in denial. Laura is forcing Britain to debate this.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Spence says Oxford believes someone who goes to a
posh school and speaks with a posh accent ``has more potential.''
She said when she sat down for her old-fashioned interview with
university dons, at least one remarked on her distinctive
``Geordie'' accent from northeast England.
</P>
<P>
   By Oxford's own admission, Harvard makes more spaces available
to the less privileged. Speaking by telephone from her office,
where she has been besieged by British journalists, Rebecca
Rollins, a Harvard spokeswoman, said that 70 percent of Harvard
students receive financial aid, the average yearly package being
$22,000.
</P>
<P>
   About 48 percent of Oxford students come from private schools,
compared with the average of 18 percent at other British
universities. Private schools in Britain don't have anything
approaching the scholarships offered at American private schools,
so Britons who go to private school tend to be wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, a native of Berkeley, Calif., said Britain lacks the
antidiscrimination laws that would long ago have transformed Oxford
into a university that better reflects the nation it serves. ``In
the States, Oxford would have been in court 30 years ago. They
would have been dead to rights on a class-action discrimination
suit,'' he said. ``But this isn't the States.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely, say Oxford's defenders. Some traditionalists view
Americans as gun-toting Philistines who are useful allies during
wartime but otherwise fairly useless. Even more reasonable critics
think American higher education is too market-driven and not as
dedicated to academic excellence as Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, Spence's most powerful ally, says that is elitist
poppycock. It was Brown's idea to get Cambridge University,
Britain's other premier institution, to form an alliance with the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology this year. Rather than
dismiss the greater ability of MIT graduates to start companies and
create jobs as evidence of the soulless American pursuit of the
almighty dollar, Brown wants to emulate it, so that more of
Britain's best and brightest engage in a pursuit of the almighty
pound.
</P>
<P>
   When Spence gets to Harvard, she'll be reunited with Lara Dixon,
who was one year ahead of her at Monkseaton and was also rejected
by Oxford. Dixon is at Harvard studying business. Kelley said seven
of his top students are considering enrolling in American
universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura is just the kind of person Harvard wants: bright, smart,
and someone who can do anything she puts her mind to,'' said
Kelley. ``You attack Oxford at your peril. But she is a young woman
of extraordinary character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
