<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER ATTRACKS THE CURIOUS ON BOTH SIDES OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FATIMA GATE, Israel-Lebanon border _ Israelis poured from tour
buses and cars Friday to view the country's newest and probably
most unusual tourist attraction: jeering Lebanese waving Hezbollah
flags as they pressed up against the wire fence that marks the
border with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shmulik, take my picture!'' shouted one tourist, Yael Levy, to
her husband as she posed on a pile of boulders a few hundred feet
from the border.
</P>
<P>
   The Levys said they had been on vacation in the north when they
heard it was possible to see Hezbollah fighters on the other side
of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid,'' she said. ``It's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The now-closed border crossing known as the Good Fence, used by
the thousands of Lebanese who worked in Israel until this week, has
undergone quite a change since the last Israeli soldier was
withdrawn from south Lebanon on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Once a site where tour groups came to learn why Israel occupied
a 9-mile deep strip of south Lebanon, the security zone set up to
protect northern communities from guerrilla attacks is now a spot
where people can glimpse the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   On the Lebanese side of the fence, an armed Hezbollah fighter
kept a close watch on the crowds of Lebanese also taking photos, as
well as the Israelis on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove three hours to see this,'' said Leora Sar, a
49-year-old Israeli carefully making her way up a pile of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers, who have been ordered not to shoot across the
border unless their lives are endangered, now simply patrol the
Israeli side of the fence and stop tourists who try to get too
close.
</P>
<P>
   The flower-filled park where tour guides used to bring people is
now off-limits because its edge is the border, prompting visitors
to climb the rocks on one side of the park to get a better look.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here many times but this time we came specially
because we heard last night that the Hezbollah were here,'' said
Rifka Sayad, 58.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's unilateral withdrawal fulfilled an election promise
made by Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who wanted to end an occupation
that was increasingly unpopular among Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   But the pullout has raised concern about whether Israel will be
able to protect the mountainous border, which it is hurriedly is
trying to fortify.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over whether Israelis in the north are more at risk
of attack because of the withdrawal was echoed among the tourists
on the rocks, some of whom shouted at each other while others
shouted at the Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let Barak come up here and live with us if he thinks it's so
safe!'' Keren Amar yelled at a man who was explaining to a friend
why Israel's withdrawal was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Amar, 22, from the nearby town of Kiryat Shmona, was one of the
few Israelis who said they were more frightened than intrigued by
what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to apply for a job in Metulla, but after seeing
those people I don't want to be so close to them,'' said Amar,
mentioning the town down the hill.
</P>
<P>
   While the sight of Lebanese demonstrators may be a draw for some
Israelis, shopowners who used to make a good living selling snacks
and trinkets to Lebanese workers, soldiers, and tourists are
worried that the pullout will mean financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Already about half of the shops are shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Even the tour guides sounded uncharacteristically downbeat.
``It's never appealing to see something like this,'' said guide
Menachem Hefetz as he shepherded an Israeli woman and her Italian
husband up the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   But his clients were in no rush to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to come here on a big tour,'' said Gabriella
David, ``but it was canceled because all the flights up here were
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we grabbed the guide and came. We wanted to see this and
I'm happy we did,'' she said, ``even if my blood pressure has gone
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
