<SLUG> BC-LEUCADIA-RELIANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUL STEINBERG WILL SELL RELIANCE TO LEUCADIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saul P. Steinberg, a corporate raider famous for
trying but failing to acquire such big-name companies as Walt
Disney and Chemical Bank, announced Friday what amounts to a final
withdrawal from a flamboyant career.
</P>
<P>
   Reliance Group Holdings, the insurance company that had
supported Steinberg's corporate sallies for three decades, is being
sold to Leucadia National Corp. for $295 million in stock and the
assumption of $725 million in debt. The company had suffered big
losses recently.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale is approved by regulators, Steinberg, who is 60,
will no longer control any U.S. company. ``He will continue to be
active in business and philanthropic affairs,'' a Reliance
spokesman said, ``although he has not made any specific plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale will bring him $93 million in Leucadia stock, if he
still owns the 36.4 million Reliance shares listed in his name last
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   But his fortune has clearly shrunk. The 36.4 million shares were
worth $364 million a year ago, and at a Sotheby's auction on Friday
Steinberg and his wife sold $12 million worth of his personal
belongings, mostly sterling silver and other furnishings from his
34-room Park Avenue apartment, itself sold in March for over $30
million. Steinberg has also been selling a collection of paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The Reliance sale will bring 0.11 of a share of Leucadia stock
for each Reliance share. That values Reliance at $2.55 a share, or
less than a third of the stock's $10 value when Steinberg took
Reliance public in 1986. In addition, Leucadia, an investment
company whose holdings include insurance companies, agreed to take
over $735 million in Reliance debt, much of it due this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a thorough review and careful deliberation, and
concluded that this was the best decision for our shareholders and
customers,'' the Reliance spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Reliance, headquartered in New York, with 3,000 employees,
reported an operating loss of $318.3 million last year, and $36.5
million in this year's first quarter. Recent blows included a major
setback in a workers' compensation insurance arrangement that went
sour. Steinberg stepped down as chief executive in late February,
on the day Reliance announced the sale of its profitable ``crown
jewel,'' a surety unit, for $580 million.
</P>
<P>
   These were the final chapters of a career that began to soar in
1961 when Steinberg, only 22 years old, pioneered the
computer-leasing business, and his new company, named Leasco,
quickly reported a profit. The young entrepreneur took Leasco
public in 1965 and the stock soared _ giving Steinberg the
wherewithal in 1968 to take over Reliance, a prosperous insurance
company nearly 10 times Leasco's size.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be Steinberg's only significant takeover. His
disastrous attempt to acquire Chemical Bank in 1969 failed when
Leasco's stock came under attack. And his subsequent attempts over
the years to get control of Walt Disney and other big companies
were no more successful, although he often walked away from these
raids richer for the investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
