<HEADER>
A7067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CUBA-TRADE-BOS &LR;      05-26 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBARGO AGAINST CUBA GROWS HARDER TO DEFEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twice this week, the House has faced the question:
Should the United States liberalize trade with a communist country,
despite its history of violating human rights?
</P>
<P>
   First, amid great fanfare, Congress passed a bill granting
permanent normal trade relations to China, a move Republican
leaders promised would help move the country toward democracy. But
when several congressmen tried the next day to apply the same logic
to Cuba, promoting legislation to allow the sale of food and
medicine, the idea was brushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same thing,'' said Representative Charles Bass, a
New Hampshire Republican, who voted for the China bill, but opposes
sending goods to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to see the distinction,'' Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference,'' agreed GOP presidential candidate
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   To a growing number of legislators, however, the distinction
between China and Cuba is becoming increasingly hard to defend,
given that Cuba has not posed a serious security threat to the
United States in years. Moreover, the Elian Gonzalez affair has
caused some lawmakers to reassess the Cuban-American lobby, which
has passionately defended the embargo for four decades, as out of
touch with US public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressmen this week said the difference in handling
the two nations was outright hypocritical, by members on both sides
of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The fault lines in Congress on trade policy are largely the
same, with a sizable number of Republicans supporting free trade
with China but not Cuba, and a number of Democrats doing the
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Representatives J. Joseph Moakley and James
McGovern, two Democrats who opposed the China deal, are helping
lead the campaign to bring food and medicine to Cuba and would like
to see the overall embargo disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lifted the embargo completely, the cell phones and the
e-mails would take over,'' Moakley said. ``The country would become
very economically sound. It's only 90 miles from the United States.
. . . It would be very difficult for a dictator to rule over an
economically successful country.''
</P>
<P>
   That political argument, almost identical to the one presented
during the China debate, appears to be taking root among a number
of moderate Democrats and Republicans. So is the economic argument:
Doing business with Cuba, as with China, could mean significant
profits for US companies. According to estimates by the US
agriculture industry, American farmers would stand to dominate
Cuba's $700 million-a-year food market if the embargo were
moderated.
</P>
<P>
   And according to several legislators, the embargo measure open
up markets of $7 billion to US firms. The legislation would allow
the sale of food and medicine to Cuba and four other countries:
Iraq, Iran, North Korea, and Sudan. It would grant the president
the power to reimpose sanctions in the event of war. And it would,
its supporters hope, lead to a more consistent US trade policy,
rather than one formulated, in McGovern's words, ``from a mindset
of the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, intellectually, to distinguish between Cuba and
China,'' Representative George Nethercutt, a Washington Republican
who sponsored the measure, said in an interview. ``They are both
totalitarian. They are both abusers of human rights.'' Asked about
the refusal of many free-trade advocates to extend their philosophy
to Cuba, Nethercutt said: ``I find it inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mann, a political analyst at the Brookings Institution,
agreed. ``Of course it's inconsistent,'' he said. ``The whole
strategy that the president and the majority of Republicans are
pursuing is a strategy of using economic engagement to bring about
internal changes in countries and move them in a more democratic
direction. That strategy would seem appropriate for Cuba as well as
for China. But alas. Cuba's close. It's governed by Fidel Castro.
And there's an important domestic political constituency engaged in
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nethercutt legislation to lift the embargo against Cuba for
food and medicine was scheduled to come to a vote on Thursday as
part of a larger appropriations bill. But House Republican leaders,
who backed the deal with China but oppose the Cuba provision,
canceled the vote out of fear the measure would pass.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt said he has at least 300 votes, far more than the
majority of 218, partly because of pressure from the farm lobby and
partly because the China agreement has thrust the US policy toward
Cuba in the spotlight, making it appear obsolete to some.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation may still come to a vote, depending on the
outcome of negotiations. Even if it does, however, it is unlikely
to have the powerful allies that secured the passage of the China
bill, most notably House Republican leaders and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   According to the terms of the 40-year-old Cuba embargo, and
under the administration's own interpretation of the 1996
Helms-Burton Act codifying the embargo, the president has the power
to alter sanctions on food and medicine. But the administration has
declined to promote trade with Cuba, and political analysts say it
is unlikely Clinton will do so before the November election,
especially given the opposition of the Cuban-American exile
community in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that South Florida constituency has drawn negative
attention to the Cuba embargo through its noisy protests of the
handling of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez. While the case has proven
the exile community's political strength, it has also raised
questions about how the US-Cuba policy has been formed over the
years, leading some critics to accuse political leaders of bending
to a vocal Cuban-American minority that despises Castro.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Republican leaders also oppose doing business
with Cuba on ideological grounds. They see an array of differences
between China and Cuba. China, many argue, is a vast and
diversified nation that has taken halting steps toward democracy in
recent years. Cuba, on the other hand, is an island that makes no
bones about its devotion to Communism. And it is run by a single
man: Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``By trade with China, we're encouraging a group of
entrepreneurs and small-business owners to be able to get a taste
of freedom,'' Bush said at a news conference Tuesday. ``That's not
the case in Cuba. In Cuba, we're trading, in essence, with a
government-controlled entity. And my worry is that capital flowing
into Cuba will help prop up the Fidel Castro regime.''
</P>
<P>
   And Castro, Lott said, has ``shown no repentance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is running a dictatorship, a repressive dictatorship,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the inclination to favor one country over the other is not
limited to the Republicans. On Wednesday, the China bill passed
largely with Republican support. Only one-third of the Democrats
voted for the bill. Smaller still was the number of politicians
with a consistent position _ either supporting free trade across
the board or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Although both Massachusetts senators favor free trade with both
Cuba and China, only Representative Patrick Kennedy, Democrat of
Rhode Island, has taken to the House floor twice in recent months
to label the leaders of China and Cuba with the same word:
``dictator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
