<P>
   CLINTON-ENVIRON (Assateague Island, Md.) _ Using the sand and
surf as a backdrop as Americans starting heading to the beach for
the Memorial Day weekend, President Clinton announces new
initiatives aimed at preserving the nation's fragile shoreline and
threatened coral reefs. Clinton directed the Commerce and Interior
departments, as well as the EPA, to beef up ocean protections
through administrative steps similar to the ones now applied to
large tracts of land protected as wilderness areas. Coming in the
final months of his presidency, Clinton's protections would not
require approval by Congress but could be undone by his successor.
By Marc Lacey. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BUTTER (Vologda, Russia) _ As any gourmand around here
will tell you, there are but two types of butter in Russia. There
is ordinary, bland butter, bought by ordinary, bland people and
consumed on ordinary, bland occasions. And there is Vologda Butter.
Vologodskoye Maslo is butter so cultured that it was originally
called Parisian butter, even though it is made in Vologda oblast.
This is profitable butter. And this is why some scruple-deprived
people are making counterfeit Vologda Butter. A foreign journal by
Michael Wines. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-CORZINE (Undated) _ The checks began cascading in a month
before the elections in New Jersey last November _ $20,000 to the
campaign arm of the Democrats in the State Senate, $15,000 to the
Democratic machine in Hudson County, $15,000 to the one in Union
County _ out of nowhere, it seemed, affluent guardian angels were
coming to the party's aid. The organizer of the donations, and one
of the chief givers, was Jon Corzine, the Democratic contender for
the Senate, a rookie candidate. By Clifford J. Levy. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FOREIGN-POLICY (Washington) _ News analysis: The most
important foreign policy vote so far this year, the 237-197 House
approval of the China trade deal, was no new affirmation of
internationalism by an often provincial Congress, but a
reaffirmation of one of its oldest truths: Members vote their
districts. That is, they vote their districts if their constituents
have an interest, and a trade bill is a singular foreign policy
measure because the question of jobs gained and lost commands
attention from lawmakers and constituents ordinarily not much
concerned about the rest of the world. By Adam Clymer. (Scheduled
to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   TONGASS-ROADS (Sitka, Alaska) _ At 17 million acres, the Tongass
is more than three times the size of any other national forest. But
as the Clinton administration promotes its recently announced plan
to safeguard the forests by banning new road-building throughout
much of the system, the Tongass is the one national forest
specifically exempted. This has galvanized many environmental
groups and conjured up the epic battles that have been fought over
this rain-forest wilderness since the 1970s. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
(The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FREEH-RENO (Washington) _ The Justice Department considered but
decided against an independent counsel to investigate FBI Director
Louis Freeh for inaccurate congressional testimony in 1997 during a
hearing about the FBI laboratory's mishandling of cases. Attorney
General Janet Reno concluded that while Freeh's testimony was
inaccurate, there was no evidence of criminal intent that would
warrant the appointment of an independent prosecutor. By Neil A.
Lewis. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) 750
words.
