<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: MORE MISSIONARIES NOW THAN EVER, EXPERT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Gerald H. Anderson has the sort of resume that, one
would expect, has allowed him an unusually broad view of trends
within Christianity worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   A United Methodist minister trained in church history, Anderson
has served as a seminary dean in the Philippines, a college
president in the United States, the head of two associations
dedicated to studying Christian missions, and the editor of many
books on that subject.
</P>
<P>
   As Anderson plans to retire next month after 24 years as
director of the Overseas Ministries Study Center in New Haven,
Conn., it seemed a good time to ask him what he thinks is the most
important development in Christianity during his professional life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happened to be giving a lecture on this last night,''
said Anderson, reached by telephone on Thursday at a retreat center
in Georgia. What he told his audience, he said, was that
Christianity was no longer ``a predominately Western religion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Christians live outside Europe and North
America,'' he said. ``And this represents a monumental shift in
what has been called the ecclesiastical center of gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the greatest momentum in the change has occurred
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The study center Anderson directs publishes an annual survey,
relying on statistics gathered by David Barrett, editor of the
World Christian Encyclopedia (Oxford, 1982). Among much else,
Barrett's statistics point to an explosive growth of Christianity
in Africa in the 20th century, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of what has happened, Anderson cited the
Moravians, a Protestant group with roots in central European and
American communities that date back to the 18th century. Worldwide
there are about 700,000, of whom about 50,000 live in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of all Moravians in the world today are in Tanzania, in
east Africa,'' Anderson said. ``And the annual membership increase
in that nation is more than the total Moravian membership in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The center that Anderson directs serves as a base for spiritual
renewal and study by missionaries and church leaders from around
the world. Typically, there are 50 to 60 people in residence, said
Jonathan J. Bonk, the associate director, who will succeed
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way from Russian Orthodox to Korean Pentecostal,
living side by side,'' Bonk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reflect the shift from the north to the south, and the west
to the east, in the demography of our residential population,''
said, adding that at least 70 percent of those who come to study at
the center are from outside North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said there is a common mistaken impression that
Christian missionary activity has been diminishing in the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, there are more missionaries at work today than ever
before in history,'' he said, adding that there are nearly 400,000
in the world including both Protestants and Roman Catholics, a more
than six-fold increase since 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed is at least 100,000 of these missionaries are
being sent out by Protestant churches in non-Western countries,''
Anderson said. He added one more example: ``There are now an
estimated 8,000 Protestant Korean missionaries serving outside
Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW EDITION OF SCRIPTURE GARNERS FAVOR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Diane M. Ritzie is an associate pastor, prison chaplain
and writer, but lately it is for another role that she has been
hearing a favorable response from around the country: work on the
``African American Jubilee Edition'' of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The edition, which combines the Bible's full text with
illustrated articles on the Scripture's relationship to Africa,
African-Americans and the black church, is a new publication of the
American Bible Society in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ritzie was the project's editor, taking over in December 1997
and arranging contributions from writers. The result is a Bible
prefaced with essays on subjects like ``The Relationship between
Hebrew and African Languages'' and ``The Presence and Role of
Africans in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim was to offer hope to young African-Americans,'' said
Ritzie, an associate pastor at a Baptist church in New Rochelle,
N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   Although the edition _ it has been published in King James and
Contemporary English versions _ is meant to call attention to the
presence of blacks in Scripture, Ritzie said, ``I don't call it a
black Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I feel God is an inclusive God,'' she said. Africans
and African- Americans are included in the Bible among God's
people, she said, adding, ``God is a multicultural God and all
nations are included in the Scriptures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
