<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-BORDER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANESE, AND SOME ISRAELIS, CELEBRATE WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes ``Shmona'' to ``Shemona'' in graf that begins ``Moshe
Biton ...'' and in graf that begins ``Assi Shaul ...'') 
(With ISRAEL-LEBANON) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   METULLA, Israel _ Ram Eisenberg, an architect from Tel Aviv,
leaned on a barbed-wire border fence on Friday and gazed at the
crowd that was chanting slogans and waving the red and yellow
banners of Hezbollah at the Lebanese village of Kafr Kila on the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you happy?'' he asked the group, many of whom had returned
to southern Lebanon after Wednesday's Israeli troop withdrawal and
came on Friday to celebrate victory at the Israeli border. ``We're
happy for you. Welcome home.''
</P>
<P>
   A Shi'ite Muslim woman covered head to toe in an Iranian-style
black chador said, ``It's our land,'' and Eisenberg agreed. ``We're
happy for you to go home,'' he repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Someone handed him a Hezbollah handbill, which he pocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Then the woman asked Eisenberg if he was Israeli, adding
matter-of-factly, ``If you are Israeli, I kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Eisenberg replied, ``I hope you change your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre encounter, impossible two days ago, was part of the
new reality that has swiftly taken shape here since the Israeli
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   A border crossing that had been run by the Israelis, known as
the Good Fence, where relatives of their Lebanese militia allies
used to come to work in Israel, vanished overnight as the Israelis
moved back to the international boundary.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the area was swamped by Lebanese visitors who walked
and cruised in honking vehicles on their side of the border fence,
hoisting banners of Hezbollah and another Shiite group, Amal, in
full view of Israeli soldiers and visitors to Metulla.
</P>
<P>
   A big yellow banner had the words ``Thanks to Hezbollah.''
Nearby stood a cardboard mock-up of a Katyusha rocket-launcher,
Hezbollah's favored weapon against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The defiant display of support for what Israelis have long
considered an archenemy caused hardly a ripple on the Israeli side.
The soldiers just looked on, and Israeli sightseers, kept at a
distance by the troops, peered at the convoys through binoculars,
trying to identify the militia flags by their colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let 'em blow off steam,'' said Yaakov Orbach, a visitor from
Petah Tikvah.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Biton, from neighboring Kiryat Shemona, a town that has
been battered by Hezbollah rockets, said as he watched: ``It
doesn't bother me. It's their territory and they have a right to do
what they want, as long as no Israelis are hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivka Sayag, from Holon, chatted on a cell phone with a friend,
describing the spectacle across the fence. ``It's kind of nice,''
she said. ``If we live in peace, it'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the withdrawal, residents of Israeli border communities
have been enjoying just that. After years in which the thunder of
artillery and the clatter of helicopters were the background noise
of daily life, a remarkable quiet has settled over the border zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quiet is ringing in my ears,'' said Yossi Beter of Kibbutz
Lahavot Habashan.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was happy with the changes across the fence.
Looking through binoculars, Yisrael Abramov, a contractor from
Herzliya, said that Hezbollah's victory celebrations were the
result of a hurried and disorganized Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that they're waving flags and we're not,'' he
said. ``We've lost faith in our flag and country.''
</P>
<P>
   Assi Shaul, a teen-ager from Kiryat Shemona, felt the same way.
``This is a disgrace,'' he said. Climbing a pile of boulders to
look at the flag-wavers on the other side, he shouted, ``We'll burn
you!''
</P>
<P>
   On the Lebanese side, people vented anger at Israel, bitter
after years of occupation, shelling and bombardments that had
caused thousands of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no peace with Israel, because they've killed
children and destroyed houses,'' said Hassan Rashid, a student who
returned to his village, Khiam, after eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Other people said there could be no guarantee of peace along the
frontier, because Israel was Arab land. ``Ask Hezbollah what will
happen,'' a woman shouted. ``If Israel leaves Palestine, there will
be peace.''
</P>
<P>
   There was evident pride that this time the Israelis had been
compelled to withdraw from Arab territory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A group of Druze from the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights arrived
at the border fence from the Israeli side to share the moment with
the Lebanese. Flashing V-signs high in the air, Saleh Abu Saleh
from Majdal Shams wished for a speedy Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan. ``God willing it will happen soon,'' he boomed. ``Victory to
the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the slogans and the display of symbols, there were
tentative signs of readiness to keep the border calm.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers kept a low profile, emerging from their base
only once to remove people on the Israeli side who had approached
the border fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a calm, not peace,'' said Issam Rashid, also from Khiam.
``We agree to be calm here. We are not aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg, the architect, said that his verbal exchange with the
Lebanese across the barbed wire was a modest achievement. ``It was
a chance for them to see that there's a human being on the other
side,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
