<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-AFRICA-MBEKI0527-COX     05-26 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-MBEKI0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Africa head honors King, activists
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ South African President Thabo Mbeki took the pulpit in
Atlanta's historic Ebenezer Baptist Church on Friday to acknowledge
the debt South Africa's freedom fighters owe to the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. and to declare common cause between Africans who
still live on the continent and those in the diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki was escorted into the church by Martin Luther King III, a
son of the famous civil rights leader. Mbeki, standing in the spot
where the elder King delivered many sermons _ and with King's
widow, Corretta Scott King, sitting behind him _ said King's
teachings and eloquence inspired black people in South Africa as
they fought to end apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. King was one of the first world leaders to call for a
boycott of South Africa,'' Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu, who spoke before
Mbeki, also paid homage to the encouragement given 30 and 40 years
ago by civil rights leaders from Atlanta to oppressed blacks in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Martin Luther King said, `I have a dream,' we dreamt the
dream with him,'' Tutu said.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's two-day stop in Atlanta was part of a trip that began in
Washington, where he was entertained at the White House by Harry
Belafonte, Stevie Wonder and others. It was Mbeki's first visit to
Washington since succeeding Nelson Mandela as president last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Mbeki and Clinton held talks on AIDS prevention
and treatment in South Africa, where one person in 10 is affected
by the disease. Mbeki also made a speech at Georgetown University
in which he warned that the global trend toward democracy and free
markets could be imperiled unless the crushing poverty that
afflicts much of the world is eased.
</P>
<P>
   Having met in Washington with Vice President Al Gore, the
presumed Democratic nominee for president this fall, Mbeki met
Thursday in Austin with Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who will be the
Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's speech in Atlanta Friday, his final day in the United
States, was attended by, among others, Gov. Roy Barnes and Atlanta
Mayor Bill Campbell, who also noted the historic and spiritual
connections between the city and South Africa. ``Atlanta stands in
a symbiotic relationship with the Republic of South Africa,'' the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   The South African president, who is a British-educated
economist, thanked Atlantans for having invested in South Africa in
the past, and urged them to do more as the country works to build
its economy and recover from the legacy of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need your skills, your expertise, your investment,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The country's leaders have set themselves the challenge of
ensuring that the 21st century is ``an African century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new century still shows signs of racism, evidenced by the
rise of xenophobia in Europe and the recent spate of hate crimes in
the United States, Mbeki said. He said people must work together to
make sure that the ``color problem'' _ which the scholar W.E.B.
Dubois warned 100 years ago would define the 20th century _ is
solved in the 21st, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   In that effort, he called for continued cooperation between the
people of Georgia and those of South Africa. ``The people of South
Africa are with you, not only at the resting place of Dr. King, but
always and at all times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking at Ebenezer Baptist Church, Mbeki visited King's
tomb, then went to CNN for a live television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
