<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      05-26 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMER IS FEELING AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joey Franchino, the Revolution's newest addition _ from
Los Angeles _ is acclimating to New England. In fact, Franchino has
reason to feel settled on the East Coast, since this is where his
family's roots were planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather was from Northern Italy and he landed at Ellis
Island,'' Franchino said Friday. ``He lived in New York before
moving to Los Angeles. If he hadn't declared US citizenship, I
would have qualified for Italian citizenship. It's something I
checked into, just in case I wanted to play in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo was concerned about
Franchino's transition. ``Did he really want to come to the East
Coast? Would he be happy here? He knows the guys and he fit in
right away, like he has been here forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchino, 23, began playing soccer in Southern California when
he was 5. He was a member of the Los Angeles Galaxy until last
week, when he was sent to the Revolution. New England has won both
games Franchino has played. Less than 24 hours after Franchino
arrived, the Revolution won at Chicago, 1-0, last Saturday, then
edged the Galaxy, 2-1, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition has been easy for me,'' Franchino said. ``It's
my job now to work hard and fight for these guys. It was very
satisfying to beat LA. I was upset at first, but now I look at it
as an opportunity to step up and bring my game to a different
level; I am working every day to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against LA, our guys were fighting and working for 90 minutes
from front to back and that is something you very rarely see with
LA. They are a bunch of superstars and they don't all want to work
defensively all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But LA has players who are winners and they are going to
bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchino kept a low profile with the Galaxy. But if the
Revolution continue to succeed, Franchino could become more
prominent. He is the oldest starter in the defense _ his birthday
(Aug. 9, 1976) just misses the cutoff date to be an Olympic team
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a hell of a player on the left side,'' said Clavijo.
``He knows his limitations and he has good work habits. He still
can improve. But it is hard to find a good left-side player, and
with (Franchino), it is allowing Ted Chronopoulos to be more
free.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronopoulos converted both Revolution goals and Franchino
helped limit Cobi Jones against Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
