<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-DANCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD OF GRAHAM TROUPE'S TROUBLES SHAKES DANCE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Note language 8th graf, `The news...' Time references, 1926
for founding of school and 1929 for founding of troupe, are cq.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Katherine Crockett's body began to shake when she
hung up the telephone on Thursday night after learning that the
Martha Graham Dance Company was suspending activity indefinitely
because of financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my life,'' Crockett, a leading dancer with the troupe,
said Friday afternoon as she arrived for the last scheduled class
at the school the company operates in the East Village. ``This
company is everything I have and everything I am. I came because I
had to say goodbye. There can be no closure. Martha's work is
timeless. You can close it, but there can be no closure.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to suspend operations, including the school and the
company's junior troupe, in the face of dire financial problems was
made at a board meeting on Thursday afternoon. Ron Protas, whom
Graham had chosen to direct the company after her death in 1991,
abstained from the otherwise unanimous vote. In reaction to the
board's decision, Protas, who licenses Graham's dances as the
director of the Martha Graham Trust and who has been feuding with
the board over the company's direction, withdrew permission for the
works to be performed by the troupe. Robert Solomon, a trustee and
the lawyer representing the company, said the troupe was contesting
the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The company was flooded with calls of support Friday. The
decision jolted a dance world accustomed to Graham's towering
presence even after death and to the legacy of works that helped
shape American modern dance. The shock was felt in ballet as well
as modern dance circles. The suspension pointed up the
vulnerability of a field where money is scarce and careers are
short.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which was founded in 1929 by Graham, has an
accumulated deficit of $500,000. The sale of its longtime
headquarters on East 63rd Street in 1998 enabled it to pay off a
deficit of $2.4 million but left it with no major assets. The
troupe was scheduled to move into quarters in a new building this
month, but the board was unable to raise the $750,000 needed to
convert the raw space into studios and offices.
</P>
<P>
   The company is to meet with Marvin Preston, executive director
of the troupe, on Tuesday to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers were to have begun rehearsals on Tuesday for an
engagement that would open the American Dance Festival season in
Durham, N.C., on June 8. Other canceled performances include an
appearance in ``The Legacy of Martha Graham and Paul Taylor,'' a
two-week festival at the Kennedy Center in Washington in September.
A three-week season at the Joyce Theater in Chelsea in November has
not been canceled in the hope that the situation will improve.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the suspension was received with surprise and
sadness in other dance companies. ``It's a damned shame,'' Kevin
McKenzie, artistic director of American Ballet Theater, said
Friday. Peter Martins, artistic director of the New York City
Ballet, said he had been saddened by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only made me realize how frail our world is,'' Martins
said. ``This would never have occurred in France or Germany or
Denmark. They would not let this happen. The arts flourish in this
country because of the people who pay for it. But it's not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Topping, the director of the Martha Graham Ensemble, broke
the news to his dancers on Thursday. The group, which is made up of
advanced students at the Graham school, was to have performed at
Marymount Manhattan Theater on the Upper East Side in mid-June.
Topping walked in on a rehearsal of Graham's ``Night Chant,'' a
rarely seen 1988 piece set to American Indian flute music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to stop them,'' he said. ``We waited a few
minutes. It was so painful to watch them dance so beautifully. They
were just bewildered.'' The school, which had been operating in
rented space at 440 Lafayette Street, draws students from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some dancers choked back tears as they arrived for the last
class Friday. ``I feel very empty and numb,'' Claudia Spahr, a
21-year-old dancer from Switzerland, said. ``But I'm not angry. I
have great hope.'' Several teachers have volunteered to teach
without pay next week.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Lang, who started dancing with the Graham company in 1942,
called the news devastating. Lang, a major interpreter of Graham
roles, teaches at the school, the prime source of training in the
Graham technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crucial, crucial moment,'' Lang said. ``It's the
first time since 1926 that there will not be a Graham school. It's
a question of saving the school, because out of the school later
there can be other activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Graham technique, Lang said, uniquely trains ``the inner,
visceral muscles'' to motivate movement from the center of the body
to its extremities, adding a dramatic third dimension to Graham
dance. ``It takes years of training for that center to illuminate
the rest of the body,'' she said. ``It cannot be learned just by
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dancers were angered by the suddenness of the decision.
``There was not even two weeks' notice,'' Crockett said.
</P>
<P>
   It is late for dancers to find work for the summer. ``The hard
part is, yes, I can always teach, but the life of a dancer is so
precious in terms of time,'' said Elizabeth Auclair, another Graham
dancer said. ``There is no time to waste.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SONTAG-HISTORICAL-NOV     05-26 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONTAG-HISTORICAL-NOVELS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW SONTAG NOVEL CREATES A STIR BY NOT CREDITING QUOTES FROM OTHER
BOOKS  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ellen Lee, an 81-year-old amateur historian, read Susan
Sontag's new novel about a grand 19th-century actress, she was
startled by words that seemed oddly familiar in language and tone.
</P>
<P>
   Two times more she read through ``In America,'' delicately
underlining passages that echoed to her from 30 years of lecturing
about Helena Modjeska, the Polish immigrant actress who had
inspired Sontag's historical novel and its main character, Maryna
Zalezowska.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was done, Lee had highlighted at least 12
passages in Sontag's 387-page book that were similar to passages in
four other books about Modjeska. They were presented without credit
or attribution _ other than a line in the preface expressing a debt
to books and articles about Modjeska ``for material and anecdotes
used (and altered.)'' No writers were credited by name in the
novel.
</P>
<P>
   The authors were a varied lot, ranging from Willa Cather to
Helena Modjeska herself and a Polish Nobel laureate who is also a
model for a character in Sontag's novel. The familiar passages
ranged from an elaborate description of Modjeska's rose-colored
cashmere robe to Cather's evocative account of a toast delivered by
the actress ``looking into the blur of the candlelight.'' In
length, they ranged from a sentence or two to eight lines of
rhyming verse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was really bewilderment,'' recalled Lee, a
volunteer museum docent who helped found the Helena Modjeska
Foundation in Southern California. ``Why would a writer of Susan
Sontag's stature and prestige use sources without quotation marks
and without documentation? And then it occurred to me that maybe
the rules have changed and there are different rules for fiction
now.''
</P>
<P>
   That question is oddly debatable in a literary arena where
popular writers have already pushed the limits of artistic license
to treat history as a melange of fact and fiction. But in the case
of ``In America,'' the issue is highlighted because in some
passages the language itself is taken almost verbatim from other
authors.
</P>
<P>
   For Sontag, whose wide-ranging writing career has encompassed
fiction, essays, plays and films, standards have evolved for a form
of literature, the historical novel. She considers it ``a work of
art'' that belongs to a new genre that doesn't require the
footnotes of traditional histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who deal with real characters in history transcribe
and adopt original sources in the original domain,'' said Sontag,
who noted that the passages in dispute amounted to fewer than three
pages in total. ``I've used these sources and I've completely
transformed them. I have these books. I've looked at these books.
There's a larger argument to be made that all of literature is a
series of references and allusions.''
</P>
<P>
   In her quest to capture a period with precision, Sontag offers
various explanations for using the language of others _ from
indulging in a whimsical inside literary joke, playing with
Cather's words, to drawing on the direct words of people she
considers primary sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I distinguish between writers and sources,'' she said. ``Willa
Cather is a writer, but the others are sources. The sources
themselves are working from sources and they are using quotations
of actual words. I don't consider Modjeska's memoirs the work of a
writer. So what interests me is the transformation. She's the
source of my character and you can use a sentence that's exactly
the same because it is from her words. Of course, I've used her
words to create a completely different character.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the writings of Helena Modjeska and the 1905 Nobel
laureate, Henryk Sienkiewicz, a Polish journalist and author of
``Quo Vadis,'' Sontag wove their own words into scenes involving
her fictional immigrant actress, Maryna Zalezowska, and an
imaginary journalist, much like Sienkiewicz, who is called Ryszard
Kierulck.
</P>
<P>
   In some passages, it does appear that Sontag used descriptions,
Polish quotations translated into English and verses collected and
written by an obscure writer, Marion Moore Coleman who in 1969
self-published ``Fair Rosalind: The American Career of Helena
Modjeska.'' But Sontag said the similarities derived from her and
Coleman's use of some of the same original newspaper accounts and
letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fair Rosalind'' was a title that Lee knew well because she had
befriended Coleman while she was researching the more than
1,000-page book.
</P>
<P>
   Lee started underlining passages after she was approached by an
Orange County Register reporter who described some language
similarities, but focused on differences between the facts of
Modjeska's life in a home in the Santa Ana foothills in the 1870s
and the fictional tale of Sontag's actress, Maryna.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was through, Lee had collected similar passages
from two other books of nonfiction, including Modjeska's 1910
memoirs, ``Memories and Impressions,'' and the translated letters
of Sienkiewicz, ``Portrait of America.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more detailed information and wording came from
Coleman's biography, which included extensive footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``In America'' contains a lavish description of
Maryna Zalezowska's dress that Coleman attributes to an 1878
Louisville Courier-Journal report: ``Cashmere robe of peach-blossom
pink, trimmed with a cascade of lace down the front and one narrow
flounce around the bottom, lace ruffles on the elbow sleeves, a
lace fraise at the neck and one shell-shaped lace pocket on the
left side ornamented with a pink rosette.''
</P>
<P>
   Sontag's description _ with a line eliminated and some minor
words changed _ closely parallels Coleman's. Sontag said: ``I have
that newspaper account where Marion Coleman got her information. I
have all this in my computer. It comes from a newspaper account, I
think from Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same biography, Coleman painstakenly chronicles the
verses delivered in tribute to Modjeska by various admirers and
critics. Some of them are virtually unchanged in Sontag's novel.
For example, Coleman's biography described a poem sent with a
bouquet to Modjeska by newspaper men.
</P>
<P>
   Hither, unheralded by voice of fame,
</P>
<P>
   Except as a fair foreigner you came:
</P>
<P>
   Light was the welcome that we had prepared
</P>
<P>
   Even our sympathies you scarcely shared:
</P>
<P>
   Not as the artist whom your people knew
</P>
<P>
   As some fresh novice did we look on you.
</P>
<P>
   In Sontag's novel, the same lines surface in an unsigned note
from an admirer to the fictional Maryna with slight changes of
wording and a character's interruption.
</P>
<P>
   For Sontag, the use of such lines reflects a zeal to capture a
historical period. In her previous novel ``The Volcano Lover,'' she
said, about 1 or 2 percent of the sentences or phrases came from
the written words of her real-life characters, like the letters
exchanged between Lady Emma Hamilton and Lord Nelson. ``There are
phrases and letters, part of a sentence in another sentence, all
reworked,'' she said. ``You get very haunted by this question of
fact, of making it absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly striking to Lee was a passage that was clearly
borrowed from Cather's own description, in ``My Mortal Enemy,'' of
a toast delivered by Modjeska.
</P>
<P>
   Cather wrote: ``When Oswald asked her to propose a toast, she
put out her long arm, lifted her glass, and looking into the blur
of the candlelight with a grave face, said: `To my coun-n-try!'''
</P>
<P>
   The Sontag version is slightly different: ``When asked to
propose a toast, she put out her long arm, lifted her glass, and,
looking into the blur of the candlelight, crooned, `To my new
country!''' Another character mutters, `` `Country,' not
`coun-n-try.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sontag said that she had not read ``My Mortal Enemy,'' but that
a friend had sent her the description of the toast and she had
incorporated Cather's material as a ``literary joke.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a reference that I hoped people would pick
up,'' she said, adding that she had transformed the passage because
her character delivers a toast to the United States, rather than to
Poland, as in the Cather version.
</P>
<P>
   With other similar passages, Sontag said, she used the words of
``not writers, but sources in the public domain'' that inspired
similar characters in her novel. For example, she draws on passages
from the memoirs of Modjeska, who wrote about her memories of
chasing away boredom by killing flies after rummaging through toys
and discovering ``two tiny little bows.'' Modjeska continues: ``The
arrows were simply made of matches, with a needle at the end. We
aimed at the drowsy, sprawling sleeping flies which ornamented the
wooden walls of the room, and one by one our victims fell at our
feet. What do you think of that kind of occupation for Juliet or
Mary Stuart?''
</P>
<P>
   Sontag also used some similar sentences from ``Portrait of
America,'' the letters of Sienkiewicz, who wrote of ``ripe acorns
breaking loose from their pedicles and rustling through the leaves
as they fell to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many writers experimenting with historical fiction,
there is some disagreement about exactly what the standard is for
using the words of others. Some purists argue they will not change
any historical facts, although they insert imaginary characters
into the mix. Others are more flexible about facts, but not
language; Russell Banks, for instance, created an underground
railroad stop that didn't exist in his novel about the real
abolitionist John Brown, ``Cloud Splitter.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a book like `Cloud Splitter,''' Banks said, ``the
contract with the reader is that I'm telling a story. I'm not
writing a history, so I will tell you things that may not have
happened. But the assumption is that the language is mine, and if I
have taken language from elsewhere, I feel obliged to make that
evident.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   It is an accepted technique to develop characters by employing
what the author Thomas Mallon calls the ``scraps and traces of
history.'' But many writers draw the line at borrowing the language
of other writers although some are willing to quote real-life
figures who become characters in historical novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're working in this genre, you're on a slippery
slope,'' said Mallon, the author of several historical novels and
also a book called ``Stolen Words: Forays Into the Origins and
Ravages of Plagiarism.'' ``A certain degree of pastiche is
acceptable and even necessary to the establishment of historical
figures as believable literary characters. But that doesn't absolve
the novelist from respecting the language that was crafted by other
contemporary scholars. Novelists should go to scholars for
information, not for language.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Chevalier, the author of the historical novel ``Girl With
a Pearl Earring,'' said that she had purposely chosen to write
about Vermeer and the anonymous model who posed for his famous
portrait because the 17th-century setting and scarcity of
information about the artist gave her great room to use her
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are taking an awful responsibility if you try to transform
the language of others,'' Chevalier said. ``For better or worse,
there aren't any standards that have been set out. I was trained as
an editor, so I'm somewhat anally retentive about getting
everything accurate. If I can verify a fact, I won't change it. But
other things are open to interpretation _ all that blurry stuff in
between. I think the interesting thing about the `Girl With the
Pearl Earring' is that we really don't know who she is. If I had
known, I probably wouldn't have written about her.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   For Lee, borrowing is unacceptable. But Sontag remains surprised
by such a reaction, given that her novel brought fresh attention to
a historical figure who had become obscure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought that they would be quite thrilled,'' Sontag
said. ``Modjeska was quite forgotten. She was a great figure. I
made her into a marvelous person. The real Modjeska was a horrible
racist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
