<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-COKE-BURTON0527-C     05-26 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-COKE-BURTON0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR's Grizzly Adams
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Ward Burton is focused on his Winston Cup team,
which is second in the standings and three points out of first
place. But he wasn't too busy to notice a flock of Canadian geese
flying over Lowe's Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about 13 of them trying to land in an open field,
but there were too many RVs out there,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's love of nature is equal to his passion for motorsports.
He says he can be just as happy walking through the woods as he is
driving his No. 22 Pontiac in front of 200,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   He started the Ward Burton Wildlife Foundation four years ago
and recently was picked to serve as honorary chairman of National
Hunting and Fishing Day, which is Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said he started his foundation so future generations
could experience some of the same things he has in his life. The
foundation started with a core tract of 1,200 acres in Burton's
home county of Halifax, Va. It now covers more than 2,000 acres,
including 404 acres Burton bought this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the foundation in 1996 to help preserve, protect
and manage some of our natural resources,'' Burton said. ``We want
to have some serene, natural places, mostly in real rural areas.
We're trying to leave it in its natural state for the next
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes to eventually purchase land in other states,
including Tennessee and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Before Burton discovered stock-car racing, he spent a two-year
stretch living off the land in a remote part of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit college after 2 1/2 years,'' Burton said. ``I couldn't
decide what to major in, and I didn't have a real good direction in
where my life was leading.''
</P>
<P>
   So he lived alone in a log cabin 45 miles from the nearest town,
trapping for a living and catching or shooting most of his meals.
</P>
<P>
   His only contacts with the outside world were occasional visits
from friends and a few trips to a couple of nearby farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably some of the most enjoyable times of my life,''
Burton said. ``I learned a lot and had a ball. I wasn't married,
and the only responsibility I had was to keep myself fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt a common bond with the out-of-doors. Life is
pretty simple out there in the forest. . . . It's a way to come in
touch with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's younger brother, Jeff, who is fourth in the Winston Cup
standings, also likes nature but not nearly as much as his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the outdoors, but I don't share his passion for it,''
Jeff Burton said. ``And he is passionate about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton says that for as long as he can remember, his
brother has been an outdoors person _ hunting and fishing and
catching snakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't just kill animals. He helps give the animals a way
to take care of themselves,'' Jeff Burton said. ``We're all
beneficiaries of his efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Ward Burton also is a strong supporter of the
right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   He said people who hunt and fish are the same people who spend
their money to conserve natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who weren't fortunate enough to have a dad or granddad
to take them fishing or hunting or canoeing don't understand that
the Second Amendment is one of the most important ones we have,''
Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton, now 38, eventually came out of the woods and joined
his brother as a stock-car racer. Although he was 26 before he
started driving, he joined the Winston Cup Series in 1994. Since
then he has won two races, placed in the top five 14 times and was
in the top 10 on 48 occasions. His career earnings are more than $7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said he plans to remain involved in some way in Winston
Cup racing, even after his driving days have ended. But he also
plans new adventures outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is going to go back to the simple way,'' he said.
``I'm going to spend a lot of time in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I want to learn to be a mountain man in the Rocky
Mountains. I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The address of the Ward Burton Wildlife Foundation is P.O. Box
519, Halifax, VA 24558.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
