<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ONLINE-BROKERS-ART-$A     05-26 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BROKERS-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MARKET SLIPS, E-BROKER SHARES WOBBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release on Sunday, Nay 28) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Thomas K. Lewis Jr. always wanted to be the sole chief
executive of a prominent, fast-growing company, Tuesday was his
lucky day. If, however, he did not want that company's stock price
to be at a 52-week low and falling as analysts retooled their
earnings forecasts into projected losses, then it was not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Lewis, 47, had shared the chief executive
title at Ameritrade Holding with the electronic brokerage firm's
founder and majority owner, J. Joe Ricketts, 58. In that time,
Ameritrade's stock price has plunged more than 80 percent from its
high of $57.75 to its low of $11 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   With technology stocks in a deep slump, the active traders
attracted by Ameritrade's $8 commissions have cut back on their
trading. The sharp decline in trading volume in the last several
weeks spells trouble for all brokerage firms, but none so much as
the slim-commission electronic trading firms like Ameritrade.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who officially succeeded Ricketts on Tuesday, described
electronic brokerage firms that had branched out into banking and
other services as ``broad and shallow.'' By contrast, he said,
Ameritrade will ``stay intensely focused on the self-directed
investor.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a long market downturn, that narrow focus could prove
painful, analysts say. ``It's the companies that are the most
transaction-dependent that get hurt the most,'' said Amy Butte, an
analyst for Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike bigger rivals like TD Waterhouse and ETrade Group,
Ameritrade has remained focused on providing cheap, fast trades
over the Internet. It has signed up more than a million customers,
many of them lured in by its big-budget ad campaign featuring a
computer-savvy character named Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Wrona, manager of the PBHG Technology and Communications
fund, sold all of the Ameritrade shares in his fund earlier this
year. ``I didn't see the competitive landscape changing for the
better for any of these e-brokers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrona started buying shares of Ameritrade in the fourth quarter
of 1999 because, he said, he was certain that the rising volume of
stock trading late last year would result in strong earnings for
electronic brokerage firms. He was right: Ameritrade and ETrade
posted slight profits last quarter. But he also thought that would
reverse the long slide in their stock prices that started a year
ago. On that score, he said, ``I was dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors feared the online brokers were engaged in a nonstop
marketing battle that would eat up most or all of their profits.
Ameritrade is spending $200 million on advertising and promotion
this fiscal year and plans to spend $250 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see profits _ and now,'' said Richard Strauss,
a Goldman, Sachs analyst. ``And even if they see profits _ and now
_ they're not necessarily going to be convinced in this market
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss, a longtime bull on Charles Schwab's stock, recently
told clients that TD Waterhouse, the discount brokerage arm of
Toronto Dominion Bank, was worth considering as an alternative. He
has not recommended buying Ameritrade or ETrade, even at their
depressed levels.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who have been recommending those stocks spent last week
revising estimates of how much they will earn, based on
expectations that the number of trades executed through those firms
during the current quarter will be at least 20 percent lower than
last quarter. Earnings should drop in step with revenue because the
firms are not cutting back on their marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade reported net income of 2 cents a share last quarter.
Matthew Vetto, a Salomon Smith Barney analyst, now expects it to
lose 3 cents a share this quarter, instead of earning 2 cents, and
expects it to add 205,000 accounts in the quarter, down from his
previous estimate of 240,000. He expects ETrade to break even this
quarter and to add about 300,000 accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vetto rates Ameritrade a better buy than ETrade and
ETrade a better buy than DLJdirect, the online brokerage arm of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. DLJdirect is less attractive, he
says, because it is smaller and not as well known as the others.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of scale will pose a growing problem for these firms as
traditional brokerage firms, including Merrill Lynch, and banks
start promoting their new online services, analysts say. Butte
points to the recent sale by National Discount Brokers of a stake
to Deutsche Bank of Germany as recognition of that looming threat.
</P>
<P>
   TD Waterhouse and DLJdirect have parents with deep pockets, and
most analysts believe that Schwab, with a market capitalization of
$31 billion, is big enough to remain independent. But some think
the smaller firms, including E-Trade and Ameritrade, will have to
merge to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade's stock jumped in late March on speculation that
Ricketts might sell the company. But those takeover hopes
dissipated as trading activity cooled well before the market's
usual summer slowdown. Not even the announcement this week that
Ricketts plans to start unloading his huge stake by selling 20
million shares could rekindle investor interest.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis waves off talk of a buyout, saying, ``We don't have any
serious discussions about that.'' Besides, he says, to appease
Ameritrade's shareholders, a buyer ``would have to pay such a
premium.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, says Steve Galbraith, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein,
it may be about time for opportunistic buyers to take notice of
electronic brokerages. ``The sentiment on these things shifts so
extremely that if they get sold down too much more, they could
represent decent value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
