<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PINOCHET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE PURSUING PINOCHET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if General Augusto Pinochet is never actually tried and
convicted for crimes against humanity that were committed in Chile
during his military dictatorship, the vote Tuesday by Chile's Court
of Appeals to strip him of the legal immunity he enjoyed as a
senator-for-life confirmed principles crucial to a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the court's ruling affirmed the centrality of justice
that is impervious to politics and rendered by an independent
judiciary. Chile's moderate socialist president, Ricardo Lagos, has
laudably refrained from any effort to intervene in the politically
charged case as it proceeds through the Chilean court system.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Chilean military took the opposite tack, making
gestures and statements meant to intimidate Lagos, the courts, and
the plaintiff families of Chileans who disappeared after Pinochet's
military putsch in 1973. Immediately after the Appeals Court
decision, the chief of Chile's army, General Ricardo Izurieta, paid
an ostentatious visit to Pinochet and called the visit a show of
``institutional support'' by the military for its old chief.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's son, also called Augusto, went so far as to intimate
that another coup could be provoked if the 108 lawsuits against his
father were not abandoned. He said the prosecution of the erstwhile
dictator ``is planting the seed of a deep division among Chileans,
and when this happens the result may be a situation like the one in
September 1973.'' All Chileans would recognize this allusion to
Pinochet's original seizure of power.
</P>
<P>
   In response, President Lagos firmly defended democratic
institutions and procedures, until Izurieta said that Chile's armed
forces regret, but will accept, the court's lifting of Pinochet's
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pinochet and his backers fought a Spanish effort to
extradite him from Britain on the grounds that only Chilean courts
could try him for crimes committed under his regime, Chilean judges
and elected leaders have become the ultimate defenders not only of
Chileans' human rights, but of a democratic justice that cannot be
thwarted or corrupted by power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BANKRUPT-BO     05-26 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BANKRUPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKRUPT VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In attempting to tighten bankruptcy rules that have sometimes
been unfairly exploited by sharp operators, Congress risks adopting
a system that is unduly harsh on innocent victims of hard times.
The bill nearing passage in the Senate deserves a veto by President
Clinton if it retains these features in its final version.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million individuals and households a year seek
bankruptcy protection. Most have relatively low incomes as the
consequence of illness, unexpected job loss, or other income,
divorce, or domestic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are some who turn to bankruptcy with the
express intent of bilking their creditors. Among the loopholes they
use, one of the more prominent is by investing heavily in expensive
homes that are shielded in some states _ notably Texas and Florida
_ allowing them to keep significant assets while repudiating
legitimate obligations. Attempts at closing or reducing this debtor
loophole have been resisted by Republican leadership in both House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Congress has used the rising number of bankruptcies
coupled with isolated abuses of the system to seek far heavier
retrictions on ordinary victims of economic disaster. They have
raised the standards under which debtors, once bankrupt, are
forgiven all obligations in order to speed their ultimate ability
to get back on their feet, over the objections of critics like
Senator Edward M. Kennedy. Under the new rules, debtors would be
required to live under unreasonably tight spending regimes while
attempting to repay creditors at improbably fast paces. Apart from
its bad impact at a human level, the system would likely produce
additional financial failures.
</P>
<P>
   Some people borrow unwisely or even with fraudulent intent. Some
institutions lend unwisely, are evasive about the terms of their
lending, and want more weapons for squeezing debtors when they run
into difficulty. Congress must do a better job of finding the
middle path between these conflicting situations than it has so
far. To do less penalizes victims of bad luck, to everyone's
long-term disadvantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7096 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NJ-CORZINE-2TAKES-NYT     05-26 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORZINE IS SOURCE OF MONEY FLOWING TO NEW JERSEY DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The checks began cascading in a month before the elections in
New Jersey last November _ $20,000 to the campaign arm of the
Democrats in the state Senate, $15,000 to the Democratic machine in
Hudson County, $15,000 to the one in Union County. Out of nowhere,
it seemed, affluent guardian angels were coming to the party's aid.
</P>
<P>
   The organizer of the donations, and one of the chief givers, was
Jon Corzine, the Democratic contender for the U.S. Senate, a rookie
candidate who has sought to create something of an insta-bloc of
support at the grass roots by raining his and his friends' money on
local party treasuries in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign said on Thursday that, as of May 17, it had
spent $24.9 million, nearly all of it Corzine's money, to compete
in the June 6 primary against former Gov. Jim Florio, easily a
record for a Senate primary.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the campaign has spent another $5.8 million,
according to documents filed with the Federal Election Commission.
The new money puts his spending ahead of the previous record for an
entire Senate election _ the nearly $30 million spent by Michael
Huffington in his unsuccessful California race in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The spending, largely on political advertisements, has vaulted
the once-unknown Corzine, a former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co., past Florio in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine has not just used part of his $400 million fortune
on 30-second television ads. With endorsements by local party
committees a pivotal factor in New Jersey primaries, he has also
funneled campaign cash directly to Democratic politicians and
political organizations.
</P>
<P>
   This month, in fact, the Corzine campaign donated $20,000 to
$30,000 each to 10 party organizations across New Jersey, from
Bergen County in the north to Ocean County at the shore.
</P>
<P>
   And when Corzine's donations to the committees neared or reached
legal limits, he recruited friends to make contributions _ friends
like Steven Roth, whose company is one of the largest commercial
property owners in Manhattan, and George Wellde Jr., who worked
with Corzine at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   This fund raising offers a primer on how a newcomer can
penetrate an often insular political culture and be embraced as a
candidate _ a strategy also followed by Eliot Spitzer, another
wealthy Democrat, who was elected New York attorney general in 1998
without experience in elected office.
</P>
<P>
   The donations in New Jersey, which helped the Democrats pick up
seats in the state Assembly last November and win some important
local elections, graphically highlight the question now dominating
the Senate primary: has Corzine's money turned the race from a
political contest to a financial one?
</P>
<P>
   Florio bluntly declares that Corzine is trying to buy the
loyalty of party leaders and voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's been successful to the degree that he has
gotten support from those who have been purchased,'' Florio said in
an interview. ``But I'm not sure that it is going to be successful
in the election, because I think that people have gotten to be
offended by this unrelenting auction that we are in.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine did not respond to several requests to be interviewed
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers say that the spending at the local level is
intended to revitalize a party that has been financially troubled
since it lost power in Trenton in the early 1990s. They point out
that Corzine has long been a generous contributor to the Democratic
Party on the national level, and is now merely redirecting his
donations to the state and local party.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jim Florio raises money from people who received jobs and
contracts from Governor Florio, he calls that principled support,''
said Orin S. Kramer, a financier who is a senior adviser and
fund-raiser for Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jon receives endorsements from Democratic organizations
which regard another Florio candidacy as the sequel to `Nightmare
on Elm Street,' the governor calls it bribery,'' Kramer said. ``If
Governor Florio hadn't virtually eviscerated the Democratic Party a
decade ago, we wouldn't have to work so hard at rebuilding it
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Local support is important in New Jersey because the candidate
endorsed by a county committee receives a better primary ballot
position in that county. Though Florio has been in politics for
much of his life, Corzine has received the endorsement of counties
that have about two-thirds of the state's registered Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has employed local chieftains _ an Essex County
freeholder is on his campaign payroll, as is the party chairman in
Ocean County _ and he regularly opens his checkbook for their
campaigns and pet causes. One day, his campaign was spending $1,070
on catering for the Black United Fund; on another, it was $1,000
for tickets to a dinner for the Hispanic American Association for
Political Awareness.
</P>
<P>
   And Corzine has added to this windfall for the party by
corralling donations from friends, many of whom are newcomers to
New Jersey politics.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, party committees can accept a maximum of
$30,000 annually per donor, while most candidates can receive up to
$1,800 from each individual per election cycle. Once Corzine hits
the limit, it is perfectly legal for him to ask his friends to
contribute.
</P>
<P>
   In October, for example, Roth of Vornado Realty Trust donated
$10,000 to the Democratic State Committee, $30,000 to the campaign
arm of the Democrats in the state Senate and $10,000 to the Mercer
County Democrats _ all at Corzine's request. Roth, who in recent
years has mostly given to Republicans in New Jersey, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Or take the campaign committee of Mayor Sharpe James of Newark,
who is also a state senator and one of the state's most influential
black Democrats. Corzine and his wife, Joanne, each donated $1,800
to James' committee, the maximum. So did Kramer and his sister,
Sari. And an array of other executives and their spouses, including
Wellde, the Goldman Sachs executive, made donations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wellde later gave $10,000 to the Assembly Democrats. Another
former colleague of Corzine's at Goldman Sachs, Eric Mindich,
donated $20,000 to the state party. Both men did not respond to
phone calls at their offices seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Another big Wall Street donor was Adam Solomon, chairman of
Shaker Investments, who at Corzine's and Kramer's urging,
contributed $15,000 to the Union County party and $15,000 to the
Hudson County party.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone committed to the Democratic agenda,'' Solomon said,
``I believe that it is very important that Jon Corzine be the party
nominee because he is our strongest candidate in November.
Supporting Jon is also an effective way of helping Democrats at
both the local and national levels.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Florio campaign has complained that many local
politicians have endorsed Corzine solely to get access to his
wallet, the politicians have usually responded that Florio is not
electable because of the tax increase he pushed through as
governor. And they maintain that candidates for major offices are
always channeling money to local committees.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats in the state Assembly received an array of
donations from Corzine and his supporters last fall _ several large
ones to their political committee, and smaller ones to the
candidates' campaigns. Their leader is Assemblyman Joseph Doria of
Hudson County, one of the most influential supporters of Corzine's
candidacy in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing different than what Jim Florio did when he was
governor,'' Doria said of the donations. ``Florio was helping us
with campaigns, providing money to the local parties. This is part
of the political process and part of political leadership. There is
nothing wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of Doria's comments, Florio scoffed and said nothing
in the state's political history approached Corzine's spending.
``This is truly an effort to purchase not just the nomination, not
just the job, but the party itself,'' Florio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
