<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CIVILIANS-B     05-26 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CIVILIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETHINKING WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 28, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans this weekend turn their attention to soldiers who in
past wars have sacrificed their lives for their country. It would
be fitting for them also to recast their thinking to take into
account a huge change in the nature of conflict around the world
during the 20th century. A brutal fact of modern war is that
civilians have become the target of much military action, dying by
the millions.
</P>
<P>
   America itself has been spared this horror for the most part.
The country has sent its military forces abroad in support of
allies and to protect national interests in other regions. There
have been no attacks on American soil since Pearl Harbor in 1941
and a brief Japanese intrusion in Alaska's Aleutian Islands.
American civilians have gone virtually untouched by any form of
violence, even to a large degree during the country's most horrific
conflict, the Civil War, during which 600,000 troops died.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the rest of the world it is a very different matter.
</P>
<P>
   World War I was spectacular for the squandering of lives in
bitter, largely stalemated trench warfare. Waves of soldiers were
ordered to attack heavily defended, deeply embedded lines only to
be slaughtered by the thousands. In the end, an estimated 8.5
million soldiers lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But civilians paid an even higher price. Although statistics are
less precise than those kept by the military, it has been estimated
that about 13 million civilians lost their lives from direct
military action or its side effects of hunger, exposure, and
disease. Notable among these are the 600,000 Armenians killed by
Turks in what has come to be regarded as the first major genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Systematic extinction of civilians played a major part in Soviet
dictator Joseph Stalin's treatment of opponents in the 1930s, when
as many as 20 million people perished through execution,
starvation, or gross neglect.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, a civil war caught thousands not directly engaged in
the fighting itself, and loyalties made targets of ordinary people
who would otherwise have been bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   World War II raised the ante, particularly with German
extermination programs targeting Jews, with more than 5 million
Polish Jews alone the victims of death camps. More than 7 million
Soviet civilians perished in the war. The Germans themselves lost
almost as many civilians as soldiers _ 3.4 million and 3.5 million
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Allies did not attack civilians per se, massive air
raids on German cities like Dresden, Hamburg, and Bremen inevitably
inflicted widespread casualties in residential areas. In the war
against Japan, air raids culminating in the nuclear attacks on
Hiroshima and Nagasaki killed more than 650,000 Japanese civilians,
compared with military deaths of about 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Worse was to come.
</P>
<P>
   In China, the fanaticism of Mao Zedong produced the vast turmoil
of his Great Leap Forward, in which perhaps 20 million died from
starvation and disease as Mao insisted on trying to restructure the
economy by bayonet-backed fiat.
</P>
<P>
   America's most agonizing war, in Vietnam, was destructive enough
in its own right, with 58,000 Americans dead, but the conflict led
to terrifying slaughter in neighboring Cambodia, when Khmer Rouge
forces killed an estimated 1 million in a country with about 10
million total population.
</P>
<P>
   Now Africa has become the seat of organized brutality against
civilians, who have become the target of choice for revolutionary
and military movements alike. In Algeria, orthodox Islamic
terrorists have staged repeated midnight raids on village
communities, slitting the throats of sleeping women, children, and
the elderly in attempts to discredit the regime in Algiers. Civil
wars in Sudan, Angola, and Sierra Leone have weighed heavily on
noncombatants. Perhaps worst of all was the slaughter of 800,000
Tutsis in Rwanda as the world watched in horror _ and did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Abuse of civilians has been morally contemptible from the
beginning of history and technically illegal as the result of
international accords like the Geneva Conventions. But the depth of
the problem is illustrated by current trials at The Hague of those
accused in dreadful crimes during ethnic strife in the wake of
Yugoslavia's disintegration. At best, a few individuals have been
brought to justice when tens of thousands perished.
</P>
<P>
   War is a grim and terrible business. Its military victims go
into battle knowing their lives are at stake. But civilians have
become participants exactly because they are nominally outside the
boundaries of direct conflict. Killing civilians, when it is not
just a move to exterminate competitors for land or other resources,
is an attempt to inflict wounds that will discourage opponents from
further resistance. It is an ugly, crude, and brutal technique _
and increasingly part of modern weaponry. This Memorial Day
weekend, victims belong in everyone's memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
