<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-DIAMONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE BEERS BEGINS SEIZING ANGOLAN GOVERNMENT DIAMONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ De Beers, the world's leading diamond company, has
begun seizing shipments of Angolan government diamonds following
the breakdown of a 10-year-old agreement with Angola to market
stones from a major concession, company officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The seizures coincide with an upheaval in Africa's
diamond-trading networks because of international pressure to end
the trade in so-called conflict diamonds, sold by African military
forces to finance wars.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, De Beers said it would begin certifying its
diamonds as untainted by conflict following the closure of buying
offices in Africa. It also said it would concentrate on sales of
its own proprietary stones from South Africa, Botswana and Namibia.
At the time, though, De Beers said it would continue to market
certified diamonds from areas under government control in Angola
that have traditionally been shipped to Antwerp, Belgium, for
cutting and polishing.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of shifts since then, though, Angolan authorities
have canceled De Beers' marketing agreement as they re-organized
the government diamond business, according to De Beers officials
and diamond industry executives in Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   And, as De Beers influence has waned, the Angolan government has
begun diverting its rough diamond shipments to Israel from Antwerp.
``This is a catastrophe for us,'' said an Antwerp diamond industry
official, who spoke in return for anonymity. He estimated annual
loss to the Antwerp trade at $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is one of the world's major cutting centers for rough
diamonds. But, in a United Nations report earlier this year on the
enforcement of sanctions against African rebel groups trading in
illicit gems, Israel escaped censure while Antwerp was singled out
for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of De Beers' Angolan contract left the diamond
giant with a $50 million outstanding loan owed by the Angolan
authorities dating to 1990. In an effort to recover the loan, the
company got a Belgian court order in March to seize two packages of
Angolan diamonds to establish whether they originated in areas
covered by the canceled agreement, company officials said. De Beers
experts examined the diamonds on April 3, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the diamonds had not originated from the
concession covered by the canceled contract. A De Beers spokesman
said, however, that the company would seek similar action to seize
packages of Angolan diamonds arriving in Israel if it suspected
they originated from the concession, which is under Angolan
government control.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the shift in Angolan trading patterns
was a result of the seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The shift away from De Beers in Angola reflects what some
industry experts see as a trend for smaller challengers with ties
to African governments to move in to areas once dominated by De
Beers. In Angola, diamond industry experts said, a newly formed
state diamond marketing company, Ascorp, had ties to smaller rivals
of De Beers.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, moreover, a new African diamond concern, Oryx
Diamonds Ltd., with ties to the governments of Congo and Zimbabwe,
will sell shares on the London Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
