<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-OFFMAN-RABBI-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYER OFFMAN'S DEVOTION TO INVESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
 By HILARY ROSENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last March, after attending synagogue morning and evening for
nearly a year, Mayer Offman decided to take a break from his
devotions.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a wise investment move, according to Offman, chief
investment strategist at Carlin Equities Group, a New York firm
that caters to day traders. Soon, Offman, who is an ordained rabbi,
began losing money on his trades. While others might have put the
blame on Nasdaq's sell-off, Offman believes other factors were also
at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Judaism, everything you do, there's reward or punishment,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once he resumed his synagogue worship, after a few weeks, his
returns improved. Year to date through May 19, his portfolio is up
more than 125 percent versus a loss of 3.8 percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Offman, 49, pursued rabbinical studies at Yeshiva University in
the mid-1970s. But he could not resist business school at night.
Eventually, the lure of finance won out: After a stint as a Hebrew
school teacher, he became, first, an auditor at Ernst &AMP; Young and
then a broker and trader. In 1993, he co-founded Carlin with Ronald
H. Shear, now its chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   A large man with flyaway graying hair and a yarmulke, Offman has
a rapid-fire style of speaking that reflects his trading style. As
it turns out, he seems to be good at what he does. Over the last
three years through May 19, he said, his portfolio has risen 2,300
percent to $43.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although he does not practice as a rabbi, Offman serves as
Carlin's in-house mentor, training less experienced traders and
conducting morning conference calls in which he recommends long and
short positions to the firm's 1,000 or so day-trading customers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether day trading is a noble profession, Offman has
strong views; it brings much-needed liquidity to the markets, he
said. Unlike day-trading houses that cater to ordinary investors,
Carlin generally welcomes only experienced brokers or traders, most
of whom are seasoned Wall Street professionals.
</P>
<P>
   About three-quarters of Offman's own portfolio is used to take
positions that are held for no longer than a day. Another 15
percent is reserved for investments of two to three months. The
rest is invested in what Offman calls ``quirks,'' such as merger
candidates in which he takes an arbitrage position.
</P>
<P>
   For his short-term investments, Offman said he usually follows
the trend, buying stocks that are hot and betting against the
stocks that are weakening by selling them short. He holds stocks as
long as they outperform: when they stop doing so, he sells. The
reverse is true when he shorts a stock.
</P>
<P>
   But such trading is not as off-the-cuff as it first appears.
Offman incorporates fundamental research in his decisions about
whether to buy or short. During the day, Offman devours analysts'
reports and scans news services. His aim is to understand as much
as he can about active stocks so that he can take a stand on
whether a stock or group of stocks is starting on an upward or
downward trend.
</P>
<P>
   Offman begins his day at around 8:30 a.m., watching premarket
trading in S&AMP;P 500 futures and stock trading on Instinet, the
electronic market. He pays special attention to the previous day's
five or so strongest and weakest stocks. When the market opens,
Offman often trades those stocks, expecting the trend to continue.
</P>
<P>
   He also watches stocks that open at prices significantly higher
than the previous day's close. ``If in the first half-hour, the
stock is down only a small amount from the opening, it will
probably make another run on the upside,'' he said. So he buys in.
For shorting opportunities, Offman does the reverse, looking for
stocks that open significantly lower than the previous close.
</P>
<P>
   Offman may make 500 trades a day in a particularly active rising
market. In the month of May, through Friday, he has traded about
350 different stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, in the last half hour of trading, Offman sells out
some positions and makes sure that the remainder are completely
hedged, balanced out by shorts on stocks in industries that he
views negatively.
</P>
<P>
   One of Offman's favorite longer-term stocks is NeoRx, a Seattle
biotechnology company that, among other things, is testing a
radioactive compound for the treatment of multiple myeloma. Offman
started buying at $5 a share in early February. He sold those
shares in the first week in March at prices ranging from $25 to
$40. The stock dipped in early April, and he began purchasing
shares again for an average price of about $15. Shares closed
Friday at $13.125.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite short position recently has been Amazon.com. ``I
began shorting it the day Time magazine made Jeff Bezos the Man of
the Year,'' Offman said, referring to Amazon's chief executive. At
the time, the stock was trading at more than $95 a share. It closed
Friday at $46.50. ``I think they're a long way from making money,''
said Offman, adding that he believes the stock will sink to $25 or
$30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
