u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      05-26 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S NEW STRATEGY TO BLEND PERSONAL LIFE WITH POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE-BRADLEY) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORDOVA, Tenn. _ After spending several weeks watching his
opponent grab headlines and project a more moderate image, Vice
President Al Gore is embarking on a new campaign strategy that will
blend personal, biographical details with policy matters in his
ongoing effort to reach voters on a human level.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Gore is to give the commencement address to the 944
cadets graduating from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point.
Aides said he would discuss both his plans for military
preparedness and his experience as an Army enlistee in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to elaborate on his Army experience on Monday,
Memorial Day, in a speech in western Pennsylvania. On Wednesday, he
plans to hold a conference on mental health with his wife, Tipper,
who has battled depression.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday he is to give a major speech on cancer research at a
time when scientists are completing work on the human genome
project, a long-running interest of Gore's. And on Friday he will
speak about the responsibility of fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of running for the presidency is introducing yourself to
the American people,'' said Chris Lehane, the vice president's
press secretary. ``People want to know about the experiences that
influenced his thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been introducing and reintroducing himself for some
months now, but some of his advisers worry that there is still a
gap in voters' knowledge about him and that this is hurting him in
comparisons with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his Republican
rival.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Gore campaign and the Democratic National
Committee are preparing television commercials, largely
biographical, for which Gore has been taping scenes over the last
few weeks. They will highlight his experiences outside of
Washington, including his time in Tennessee as a divinity student
and a journalist, and his family, including the fact that he has
been married 30 years and is a new grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice presidents are famous but not well known,'' Lehane said.
``Most people's notion of him is standing behind a podium.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Kamark, Gore's domestic policy adviser, noted that ever
since 1992 he has held annual conferences on topics related to the
family, medical care for children and stresses on the modern
family. She said these policy discussions bring out the best in the
vice president and give the greatest insight into both his
character and his views about what is important.
</P>
<P>
   Kamark said these family issues ``combine both policy and his
personal experiences as a parent, and you get a sense of how he
would use the bully pulpit'' as president.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Gore spent the day at the Cordova School, a
1,120-student magnet school here outside Memphis, his sixth such
visit to schools around the country since the end of the primary
season in March. His main message, as it was during previous school
visits, was to emphasize the involvement of parents in their
children's lives. The level of detail in which he becomes engrossed
was evident in his response to a question about the behavior of
children on school buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the school bus drivers in a school in North Carolina
made a suggestion that might go to your question,'' Gore said. ``He
said that when children bring home their report cards on how
they're doing in their course work that they ought to get a grade
in bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's West Point appearance this weekend has prompted criticism
from another veteran who wonders where the line is between allowing
a vice president to address the academy if he is also a political
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, a World War II veteran who was the Republican
presidential nominee in 1996, was invited informally five years ago
to deliver a speech at the academy, Doug MacKinnon, Dole's
spokesman, said in an interview. But MacKinnon said the invitation
was withdrawn ``at the last minute'' because it was deemed
political. The academy, which allowed members of Congress to speak
on the campus in the 1800s, now allows only the president, the vice
president and the speaker of the House to address the cadets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no ill will toward anyone,'' MacKinnon said. ``We just
want to try to get clarification on the policy, what the rules are,
who created the exceptions, why the Senate majority leader isn't on
the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. James Whaley, a spokesman for West Point, said in an
interview that ``speaking at graduation is normally reserved for
the president, vice president or speaker of the House, and Dole was
a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how those who attend the graduation ceremony might
distinguish Gore the vice president from Gore the presidential
candidate, Whaley said the vice president's right to speak ``to
future leaders of our nation and our Army'' cannot be taken away
from him because he is aspiring to higher office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
