<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY AND TIMING CAN OUTFOX THE BEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years, investors in technology stocks have become
accustomed to coping with mini-bear markets in the sector once or
maybe twice a year. But the bear they are looking at right now is
no koala.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, the Nasdaq composite index had declined 21.2
percent this year, and more than 36 percent from its peak on March
10. Even so, some Internet stocks still trade at triple-digit
multiples. And even with the fall, the Nasdaq index is still nearly
30 percent higher than it was at the start of the 1999 Memorial Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   With the Federal Reserve raising rates, there is every chance
that the selling will continue. But the fundamentals remain
excellent, and earnings are strong. Which makes you wonder if the
worst isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Berry, co-portfolio manager of the RS Information Age Fund,
took some time last week to talk about technology and timing. Here
are excerpts from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q. In the last three months of last year and the first three
months of 2000, a lot of folks were screaming about insane
technology valuations. Did you hear those screams?
</P>
<P>
   A. Up until the first quarter, we had been pretty much fully
invested. But in early March we became uncomfortable with
valuations. At that point we raised our cash position to 20
percent, which is a lot for this fund ... We started to get back
into the sector in early to mid-April. At that point we felt
overall valuations were attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the worst of the selling over?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think the true buyers are back in the market, but I
do believe most of the damage has been done. That doesn't mean
things won't be pretty volatile for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, investors will be focusing on economic
news more than on the fundamentals of these companies. If you
understand the fundamentals of the companies, and they are strong,
you could find some good entry points into a lot of these stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So what have you been buying?
</P>
<P>
   A. Semiconductor stocks are far and away the best value in
technology right now, and currently represent about 35 percent of
the fund's $320 million portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   They were the best performers in the first quarter, rising 68
percent. But from the end of March through May 24, the group fell
22 percent. This is despite rising earnings estimates and a huge
supply shortage ... Our largest semiconductor holdings are Xilinx,
Terradyne, Intel and Applied Materials.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Those are all big companies. Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have tightened the fund up into the dominant, more liquid
names. As the recovery expands, we will move down in market
capitalization to pick up some bargains.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the point, at the end of the first quarter, the
median market cap for the stocks in our fund was $49 billion. At
the end of last year it was $21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has that strategy paid off?
</P>
<P>
   A. Through Thursday, the fund is down 7.5 percent, so we are
beating the Nasdaq. We have outperformed largely due to the
semiconductor weighting and the fact we have been in larger cap
names.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which other sectors do you favor?
</P>
<P>
   A. We are overweight in communications equipment stocks. Those
represent about one-third of the fund's assets. Our holdings
include JDS Uniphase and Corning, wireless companies like Nokia,
Motorola and Ericsson and traditional equipment providers like
Telabs, Lucent and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You said that earlier this year you were leery of Internet
stocks. Are you still?
</P>
<P>
   A. In general, yes. But over the last week we have been buying
some Internet companies, like BroadVision. They are seeing a lot of
demand from bricks-and-mortar companies who are concerned they are
missing the opportunity to build on the Internet. We also recently
bought some Ariba, the business-to-business software company. And
we own some America Online as well.
</P>
<P>
   We don't own any Yahoo! right now, but I am doing a lot of work
on it. As we get back into the Internet sector, it will probably be
a name we add sooner rather than later. But at more than 225 times
next year's earnings, Yahoo! is pretty pricey.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What advice do you give someone who is just beginning to
invest in technology stocks?
</P>
<P>
   A. For someone starting off, we recommend investing in the
gorillas in each area, the Intels, Microsofts, Nokias, Ciscos and
EMCs of the world. Seek out the core names, because the
fundamentals look great.
</P>
<P>
   One statistic we always throw out is that the United States only
has 5 percent of the world's population but accounts for roughly 45
percent of all technology spending. About 88 percent of the world's
population is in countries that have not been significant spenders
on technology. That is changing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
