<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PEN-RUSSIA-ART-NYT &LR;      05-26 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEN-RUSSIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IN CHECHNYA ROILS WRITERS CONFERENCE IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT27  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Just a few years ago Moscow seemed a natural venue for
this week's annual International PEN Congress, an event that has
drawn writers from around the world pledged to fight the good fight
for freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Russian writers, some of them heroes of past PEN
campaigns, were still giddy from the collapse of communist
censorship, and their Western colleagues were eager to honor the
young Russian PEN club, founded in 1992, and boost its status as a
beachhead for Russia's new freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the glow from those early years of democratic euphoria has
faded. Russia is no longer in fashion among Western intellectual
circles. Quite the contrary, Russia is back in the dock, this time
on trial not for communist repression but for a brutal war in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-month war, Russia's second in the region, initiated by
President Vladimir Putin when he was prime minister and largely
supported by public opinion, cast a pall over preparations for the
first PEN Congress to be held in Moscow. As writers and
intellectuals reacted with horror to stories of indiscriminate
bombing, rape and pillage by Russian troops, several national PEN
centers protested against holding the Congress in Moscow and
threatened to withdraw their delegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had serious concerns about the Moscow conference, since
there is no tradition of the PEN club organizing its congress in a
country which is waging war,'' said Adam Pomorski, vice president
of the Polish PEN club. ``With our presence, we could demonstrate
support for one side or another in the conflict. It would be the
same as if, let us say, we had held a congress in Belgrade during
the conflict in Bosnia or Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The final decision to go ahead with the congress, which ends
here on Sunday, was made by the Russian PEN club, whose members
have also vigorously protested the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were certain that in order to uphold the ideals of PEN,
it was in fact essential to hold the conference in Moscow,'' said
Jane Spender, secretary of PEN International. ``To withdraw at this
point would have left the Russian PEN center painfully exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   So the conference has unfolded this week, with delegates from 74
of the International PEN's 130 centers present and the war in
Chechnya getting much attention. Friday the congress' official
delegates adopted a resolution, drafted by the Russian PEN center,
condemning the Russian government's attempts to ``resolve the
tragic situation in Chechnya by military means.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the agenda was a much more strongly worded declaration,
drafted by PEN centers from Central Europe and the former Soviet
Union, accusing Russia of genocide in Chechnya and of clamping down
on independent news media that have resisted the government's
propaganda line.
</P>
<P>
   In an opening speech, Gunter Grass, the German novelist and
Nobel laureate, called on the Russian government to end ``the war
against the Chechen people,'' which he said had been waged ``once
again, as earlier, without reason without mercy.'' He also called
for a United Nations investigation into war crimes committed by
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But mainly he appealed to writers to speak out against tyranny,
and to expose lies. Writers, he said, were often the first to
resist ``the changing ideological temptations of the 20th
century,'' whether in Nazi Germany or Soviet Russia. Literature, he
said, ``does not turn a blind eye, it does not forget, it does
break the silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Grass' speech and the focus on Chechnya have received mixed
reviews in Moscow, where some Russian writers and newspapers have
begun to chafe at what they see as the West's relentless criticism
_ and not only of the war _ which some feel has taken on a hostile,
anti-Russian tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I too am outraged by the war in Chechnya, but now the word
Soviet is being replaced by the word Russian, and I also don't like
it,'' said Andrei Bitov, a renowned Russian writer and president of
the Russian PEN center. ``I feel there is a certain nostalgia for
the `enemy' and a lowering of the Iron Curtain from the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Bitov, author of ``Pushkin House'' and other novels, said he
first began to sense a shift in attitudes last year, when on his
trips abroad he found himself being made to answer for Russia's
stance against NATO's war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't like is that as a private person, I was made to
feel responsible,'' he said. ``There is a kind of snobbism to some
of the criticism, and this readiness to call everyone a fascist.''
</P>
<P>
   The most outrageous example, Bitov noted, came at a PEN
conference at which Lev Timofeyev, a Russian dissident who in
Soviet times spent 10 years in jail, was told that to hold the PEN
congress in Moscow now would be like holding it in Hitler's
Germany. ``This is not a fascist country,'' Bitov said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Russian writers said that the local PEN center had
received ``hints'' from the Russian authorities that the
International PEN Conference might turn into an unwelcome
``political provocation'' that might best be avoided. In the end
nothing was done to prevent its being held here this week, but the
Russian government, unlike the governments of other host countries,
also did nothing to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Russian PEN have become hostages of East and West at the
same moment,'' Bitov said. ``But the great thing is that we managed
to have the congress anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   For some Russian writers who still remember the days when
anonymous censors could strike words and phrases from their books,
or even ban them altogether, holding the conference here, and
airing criticism of the Russian government's conduct of the Chechen
war, is what PEN is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is right that this conference should be about Chechnya, and
it is right that it should be held here,'' said Andrei Voznesensky,
a poet and vice president of Russian PEN. ``It is a war that
worries foreigners, and it worries us. But it is a good thing that
they can come here and we can all say what we think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0302 </DOCNO>
