<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-ECON-425(2TA     05-26 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ECON-425(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-TROUBLED EAST ASIA NOW SHOWS SURPRISING BOOM IN ECONOMIC
GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Less than three years after a plunge in the value of
Thailand's currency triggered a devastating economic crisis across
much of East Asia, the region is riding a wave of growth
reminiscent of the Asian miracle of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence of the resurgence came Friday with a report
that Hong Kong's economic output rose 14.3 percent in the first
three months of the year. It was the territory's fastest quarter of
growth since late 1987, and seemed to make the Asian crisis a
distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   Other East Asian economies, from South Korea to Singapore, are
growing at rates much faster than the most optimistic forecasters
had predicted _ largely powered by a booming demand for Asian
exports of computers, electronics, machinery and textiles into the
hot economy of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Salomon Smith Barney investment bank
raised its full-year forecast for East Asia's regional growth to
6.9 percent from 6.7 percent. This week, Salomon raised it again,
to 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. economy is showing absolutely no signs of slowing,
which is great for Asia,'' said Simon L. Ogus, an independent
economist here. ``The longer the U.S. keeps booming, the faster
Asia will grow.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ogus and other economists also warn that any downturn in the
U.S. economy could ripple harshly through Asia. They note that
stock markets in Asia have tumbled recently on worries about rising
interest rates and a possible future slowdown in demand from the
United States. Moreover, Japan, the biggest economy in the region,
is still trapped in a prolonged slump.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that East Asian countries have defied the
skeptics, who said the region would need a long convalescence from
two years of painful economic contraction, plunging asset values
and wholesale corporate insolvencies.
</P>
<P>
   The spreading rebound is good news for both the U.S. Treasury
Department and the International Monetary Fund, which had come
under heavy criticism in Congress and academia for mismanaging the
approximately $100 billion bailout of troubled Asian economies. The
critics charged that Treasury and the IMF prescribed a mix of
radical economic restructuring and fiscal austerity that threatened
to seriously prolong recessions in the region and leave millions
jobless.
</P>
<P>
   East Asia's stronger-than-anticipated rebound has largely
silenced those complaints. At the same time, however, it has also
lessened the pressure on East Asian governments to clean up the
debt-ridden banks and corporations that contributed to the crisis
in the first place.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think we'll get surprised further on the upside by Asian
economic growth, which will have the effect of reducing the
pressure for structural reform,'' Ogus said.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasm about the East Asian recovery began earlier this
year, when South Korea started posting double-digit year-on-year
gains in growth, putting the severe slump that began in late 1997
firmly behind it. South Korea's strong performance has also been
accompanied by progress in restructuring its most debt-ridden
conglomerates, though some economists still criticize the pace of
reform in that nation as too slow.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, generally regarded as the domino that set off the
Asian crisis with the devaluation of its baht currency in July
1997, the IMF decreed in a review two weeks ago that the recovery
``has turned out to be impressive: output growth this year is set
once again to exceed four percent, exports are growing rapidly, the
balance of payments position remains strong, and inflation is well
under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia, which flouted the IMF's prescriptions and imposed
strict controls on its currency and capital flows, has turned into
one of the region's export stars. After growing at 5.4 percent in
1999, Salomon Smith Barney predicts, Malaysia's economy will expand
7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Indonesia, widely regarded as the most fragile of the
East Asian economies ravaged by the crisis, growth is expected to
exceed 3 percent this year, although the government has said it
could fall to 1.5 percent if political instability persists. Unlike
its neighbors, Indonesia is still spurned by foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, talk of economic reform in East Asia has all-but
vanished as export-led growth has returned with more shipments of
clothes, toys and machinery. Hong Kong's exports rose 20.7 percent
in the first quarter, as it shipped more goods to China, the United
States, Europe, and other Asian countries. China, which uses Hong
Kong as a source for raw materials such as unfinished leather,
cotton and electronics components, was a particularly good
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted that Hong Kong's dramatic growth is partly a
reflection of its poor performance in the same quarter last year,
when output declined 3 percent. But they still said Hong Kong's
performance is remarkable, given that its currency is linked the
United States dollar at a fixed exchange rate. The export success
of other Asian countries, notably Malaysia, can be attributed in
part to their weaker currencies, which makes their goods cheaper
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hong Kong economy turned out a spectacular performance,''
said the government's chief economist, K.Y. Tang. ``Looking into
future months, we still see strong demand for our exports.''
</P>
<P>
   Tang said Hong Kong would be further strengthened by the vote in
the House of Representatives on Wednesday to grant permanent normal
trade status to China, which the Senate is also expected to
approve. That step will ease Beijing's entry into the World Trade
Organization, which Hong Kong estimates will add 5 percent to its
gross domestic product over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer run, a more open China could rob this former
British colony of its traditional role as a middleman between China
and the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   But few economists are thinking beyond this year. Following the
lead of private economists, Tang revised his official forecast of
Hong Kong's full-year growth to 6 percent from 5 percent. He said
the revision was conservative because he harbored nagging worries
about how long the economic boom in the United States would last.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a more distinct moderation in the U.S. economy,
somehow - directly or indirectly - the Hong Kong economy will be
affected,'' Tang said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ogus is more emphatic about the damage East Asia would suffer
from a slowdown in the United States. Given that so much of the
region's rebound has hinged on exports, he said Asia's recovery
would come to an abrupt halt if demand from the United States
diminished. At that point, he said, the lack of progress among
Asian countries in overhauling their financial sectors could come
back to haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   East Asia's stock markets reflect this sensitivity to the
outlook across the Pacific. Fears of interest rate increases in the
United States drove down markets everywhere Friday, with the
exception of Taipei, Bangkok and Manila.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in South Korea plunged 6.13 percent after Hyundai, the
country's biggest conglomerate, asked its main creditor for loans
to avert a cash shortage. Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng index
declined 1.4 percent to its lowest level in six months, despite the
buoyant economic numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong has also not emerged from the deflationary spiral that
has pummeled the prices of everything from apartments to luxury
goods. The local consumer price index fell 4.9 percent in the first
four months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One unexpected bright spot in Hong Kong's economic picture was a
surge in investment in computers and other information technology.
After the ascent and crash of Internet-related stocks here, there
is now evidence that Hong Kong is investing in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reflects a basic change in attitude toward the new
economy here,'' said Ian K. Perkin, the chief economist of the Hong
Kong General Chamber of Commerce. ``It's a belated response to
what's been going on in the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
