<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LBJ0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tapes reveal LBJ's post election struggles By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Just inaugurated to his own term after the biggest
landslide in presidential election history, Lyndon B. Johnson in
January 1965 dominated the American political landscape and was
pushing forward with his Great Society program.
</P>
<P>
   But tape-recorded conversations released Friday show that
Johnson already was feeling the pressure of the increased fighting
in Vietnam. At the same time, he was trying to quell racial
disharmony in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The LBJ Library on Friday issued a set of 27 cassette tapes
covering about 28 hours of telephone conversations that Johnson had
recorded while serving in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes include conversations in January through March 1965,
when American ground troops were first sent into South Vietnam and
local and state law enforcement officers in Alabama attacked a
civil rights march at Selma.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Johnson faced on March 6 was whether to approve the
military's request to send Marines to guard an American air base at
Danang from Viet Cong attacks. In February U.S. facilities in
Vietnam had been attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Johnson, in a conversation with Defense Secretary
Robert McNamara, approved the request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than have it said, `Well, we wanted protection for our
planes, he wouldn't give it to us,' my answer is yes, but my
judgement's no,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Before giving his answer Johnson told McNamara of his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the dangers are maybe 60-40 against our getting
involved in a big war with them, the Marines fighting with the Viet
Cong and really starting a land war,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the psychological impact of `the Marines are
coming' is going to be a bad one; and I know enough to know that.
And I know every mother's going to say, `Uh-oh, this is it.' And I
know what we've done with these B-57s is just going to be Sunday
school stuff compared to the Marines, and all they're going to do
is be a policeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damned if I don't know why we can't find some kind of
policeman besides the Marines, because a Marine is a guy that's got
his dagger in his hand and that's going to put the flag up,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson told McNamara to emphasize to the public that the
Marines were going in as a security force.
</P>
<P>
   The president's doubts about Vietnam _ and fears of using
Marines _ may have been stoked by an earlier conversation on March
6 with Sen. Richard Russell, a Georgia Democrat who Johnson had
cultivated in the 1950s as his mentor and a father figure while
serving with him in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Russell warned him that ``these Marines, they'll be killing a
whole lot of friendly Vietnamese. They're going to shoot at
everything that comes around those airplanes. They've been trained
to do that, and that's their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Replied Johnson: ``Dick, the trouble is, with this finally, the
great trouble I'm under _ a man can fight if he can see daylight
down the road somewhere. But there ain't no daylight in Vietnam.
There's not a bit. The more bombs you drop, the more nations you
scare, the more people you make mad.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day Johnson decided to send Marines to Vietnam, he
was briefed by Attorney General Nicholas Katzenbach on the attack
by Alabama law enforcement officers on civil rights marchers at
Selma.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. responded by vowing to lead
another march, from Selma to Montgomery. Johnson then began
pressing Alabama Gov. George Wallace to ensure the safety of the
marchers.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone conversation on March 18 with Johnson, Wallace
complained that protestors were coming in from all over the
country: `They are flying in nuns, priests and we got hundreds of
bearded beatniks in front of my capitol.''
</P>
<P>
   King led the peaceful march on March 25, but a civil rights
worker, Viola Liuzzo, was killed as she returned marchers to Selma.
Vietnam weighed heavily on Johnson, but his earthy and sometimes
profane humor is also on display on the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good God I'd rather (hear) your voice than hear Jesus this
morning. How you feeling?'' he told Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
