<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-AREFIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY AREFIN, 38, INFLUENTIAL GRAPHIC DESIGNER
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVEN HELLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tony Arefin, a self-taught graphic designer and art
director of periodicals, art catalogs and advertising who was
responsible for influential ad designs like the handwritten look of
the current IBM ``magic box'' campaign, died on May 19 at St.
Vincent's Hospital in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, his wife, Amanda, said. Arefin was
38.
</P>
<P>
   Arefin successfully straddled the often polarized worlds of
magazines and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an art director who thought like an editor,'' said Chee
Pearlman, former editor of ID magazine, who hired Arefin as
creative director in 1993. ``He could write smart headlines as well
as reduce complex subjects into clear visual forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Abed Arefin was born in Karachi, Pakistan. He was later
nicknamed Tony by his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Arefin moved with his family to Bangladesh, and in 1974 during
political strife there, moved to London. He left school early and
worked at various unskilled jobs that motivated him to improve.
</P>
<P>
   By chance, while working on a movie, Arefin was offered a job as
a curator at the Photography Gallery in London, where he organized
a retrospective exhibition of the popular magazine The Face,
designed by Neville Brody. Arefin credited Brody, whom he also
hired to design art catalogs, with indirectly helping Arefin
realize that he should pursue graphic design as a career.
</P>
<P>
   Arefin started designing his own art catalogs. He proved to have
a talent for typography and became so prolific that the design
critic Rick Poynor wrote in the British magazine Blueprint that
Arefin was ``single-handedly processing the print needs of the
entire British art scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ID magazine sent Arefin to New York. His work in New York drew
on everything that interested him, from polished professionalism to
street art.
</P>
<P>
   While he worked on ID he was also art director of Bomb, an arts
magazine, and Blind Spot, an art photography quarterly. He found
magazines too limited in terms of audience and earnings, however.
Leaving his wife and their two young sons in New York, he accepted
an offer from the advertising agency Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland,
Ore., to become an art director for the Microsoft brand.
</P>
<P>
   Arefin also created a striking print campaign for Nike,
introducing its ``I can'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a good working relationship at Wieden, Arefin returned
to New York after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Arefin joined Ogilvy &AMP; Mather as associate creative director and
senior partner, and worked most recently on the IBM ``magic box''
campaign. By using handwritten lettering scrawled over monumental
photographs of the ``box,'' which is a computer network server, he
gave the product a human aura.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked as a creative director on the Lotus Notes ``I Am
Superman'' campaign, which pulled individuals out of crowds to
indicate the personal nature of the product.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Arefin is survived by two sons, Rafi,
11, and Sami, 9, of New York; his parents, Shamsul and Abeda, and a
sister, Ayesha, all of London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
