<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS0527-CO     05-26 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush continued his political
rehab effort among Catholics Friday, the same day he incurred the
risk of upsetting Texas Republicans by deciding to skip their
upcoming state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke briefly from Austin, by satellite, with participants
at the Catholic Press Association meeting in Baltimore. He
customized his usual campaign speech by quoting well-known
Catholics, including Pope John Paul II, the late Cardinal John
O'Connor and the late author C.S. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   In February _ in an event Democrats love to rehash _ Bush spoke
at Bob Jones University in South Carolina, a school that harbors
strong anti-Catholic sentiments. Bush defended his appearance, but
later told Catholic officials he had missed an opportunity to be
``more clear in dissociating myself from anti-Catholic sentiments
and racial prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Friday speech, Bush said he favors maintaining the
Vatican's ``permanent observer status'' at the United Nations. The
private group Catholics for a Free Choice, which supports abortion
rights, is seeking a formal review of the Holy See's U.N. status,
saying the Vatican's claim to be a state is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some groups have been trying to silence that voice in the
United Nations,'' Bush said, add that ``the position of the current
administration is unclear.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Susan Elbow said the Clinton
administration has never called for any change in the Vatican's
U.N. status.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee spokeswoman Jenny Backus
criticized Friday's speech as part of Bush's ``Bob Jones Redemption
Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the Bush campaign said he will skip the June 15-17
state GOP convention in Houston to campaign in Kentucky and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, the governor's wife, will speak at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The news surprised Texas GOP officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party hasn't been officially notified of his intentions,''
GOP spokesman Robert Black said Friday afternoon. ``We are moving
forward with our convention planning. There will be 17,000 Texas
Republicans there, some of Governor Bush's most loyal supporters,
who, if he chooses not to attend, will be disappointed, but will
still be enthusiastically supportive of our governor and ready to
work for him the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   One GOP official privately said the party was shocked by Bush's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when the party was controlled by social
conservatives less loyal to Bush, the governor was snubbed when
then-State Chairman Tom Pauken was named to head the state
delegation to the Republican National Convention in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The current party chair, Susan Weddington of San Antonio, is a
Bush ally. Bush campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan said the decision
to skip the state convention is based solely on efforts to make the
best use of Bush's time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the governor's record and the many grassroots
activists and supporters in this state, Texas is solidly in the
Bush column,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis County GOP Chairman Alan Sager said he saw nothing wrong
with Bush's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not see any payoff for him coming to the state
convention. I agree with those who think he ought to be spending
his time where he needs to shore up his support,'' Sager said.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Democrats tried to make a big deal of Bush's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is trying to distance himself from the radical
right,'' said state Democratic Chair Molly Beth Malcolm. ``The
Texas Republican Party is the epitome of the extreme right wing and
out of touch with the mainstream concerns and needs of most Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Sullivan dismissed Malcolm's comments as ``the
type of partisan political rhetoric that has helped Texas
Republicans elect 29 out of 29 statewide officials, a majority of
the Senate and more than 1,500 local officials across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said Vice President Al Gore, the probable Democratic
presidential nominee, has been invited to the Texas Democratic
Convention next month but ``might choose to attend conventions in
other states.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
