<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BECKHAM0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Techno granny e-mails spiritual message
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jo Beckham's frail, age-spotted hands work
nimbly on the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   At 95, the woman once crowned the Pioneer Queen of Lamesa,
Texas, is running an e-mail ministry from the Buckner Villas
retirement home in Northeast Austin. Beckham uses her ministry to
encourage others more than half her age that faith can be fun as
well as inspirational.
</P>
<P>
   Her computer savvy gives her a worldwide window and the
opportunity to share the gospel as far away as Cambodia, Romania,
Hungary, India and Singapore. And she joins thousands of Christians
_ many of them senior citizens _ who are using the Internet as a
mission tool.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James A. Andrews, 75, of Burnet recently launched the
interdenominational First Internet Outreach Church site to reach
shut-ins, seniors and youth who feel disenfranchised from
traditional churches.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said he does not want to replace anyone's home church,
but rather augment their spiritual lives and reach out to those who
suffer from disabilities and have trouble attending churches.
</P>
<P>
   Beckham and Andrews said the best part about the computer is at
can be used at one's convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Beckham, a Southern Baptist, plans to keep her ministry a simple
one-on-one experience, offering up prayers, sending out devotionals
and sharing conversation with anyone who is interested. She
initially came in contact with missionaries through a granddaughter
who runs a ministry for the deaf in Hungary. One missionary told
another and her global e-mail list began to take off.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she has more than 80 folks on her ever-expanding e-mail
address list. Unlike Andrews, she has never ventured onto the Web,
saying she doesn't see that as advancing her ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, she sends out her ``Footprints,'' a short devotional
message that features Scripture, parodies, rewritten song words,
poems and uplifting prose to brighten the day. Her goal, she said,
is to spread God's word.
</P>
<P>
   Beckham accepts prayer requests from anyone in need, including a
group of bachelors she says are looking for a ``WOG.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That means Woman of God,'' she said with laughter. Beckham
never knows when one of those requests might pop up. Even the man
who fills her oxygen tank and regularly keeps in touch through
e-mail asked her to pray that he find ``a good Christian female to
share my life with,'' according to one message.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hyde, who lives in Cambodia, said in an e-mail interview
that Beckham is an uplifting influence in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cambodia, I am involved in leadership training and
publishing Christian books,'' Hyde said. ``I also run the only
Christian book store in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I were married a little more than a year ago and
Jo wrote us a song for our wedding. My wife and I were so touched
by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the missionaries know Beckham by e-mail only,
Hyde met her two years ago when he brought a child to Austin.
Beckham's son, Patrick, is an Austin doctor who operated on the
child's cleft lip.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Beckham, Hyde said, ``left a deep impression on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckham's ministry headquarters is a cozy, single room with
country-style decorations and pictures made by her
great-grandchildren. Room and office are one in the same, and she
keeps it well organized.
</P>
<P>
   On her bed are her fruit-of-the-month boxes (another gift from a
grandchild) packed with ministry brochures and Bible tracts she
prints out on her computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to put things in boxes and keep them organized because
when you get to be my age you get a little forgetful,'' Beckham
said.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends and holidays, workers at the retirement home bring
their children to Beckham's room where she holds a Bible study
class.
</P>
<P>
   Beckham said she plans to keep spreading the gospel, praying for
those in need and offering up some joy for as long as the good Lord
keeps her on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed of the gospel of Christ,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly quoted a verse from Isiah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not unto us be the praise. Let the Lord be glorified.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
