<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VASSER WANTS TO MILK HIS TIME AT INDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When he won the inaugural US 500 in 1996 _ an
event Championship Auto Racing Teams staged as a boycott to the
fledgling Indy Racing League and its flagship event, the
Indianapolis 500 _ Jimmy Vasser pulled into Victory Lane at
Michigan International Speedway and uncorked a bottle of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   He then made his own political statement concerning the
fractious CART-IRL split when he mocked Indy's traditional nectar
of victory and defiantly remarked, ``Who needs milk?''
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, though, Vasser has thirsted for a
sloppy swig of ice cold milk on Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   So when car owner Chip Ganassi decided to field IRL cars for
Vasser and Team Target stablemate Juan Montoya, the defending
champion of the CART FedEx Championship Series, Vasser feared the
words that spilled from his tongue in Michigan would come back to
haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expected to be dodging tomatoes when we came back,''
Vasser said.
</P>
<P>
   But, to almost everyone's pleasant surprise, that hasn't been
the case. There have been no projectiles to dodge and no catcalls
to ignore. Instead, Ganassi's Gladiators, winners of the last four
FedEx championships, have been bestowed with bouquet upon bouquet
of flowering praise for their return to the Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here holds Chip, Juan, and Jimmy in high regards,''
said 1999 IRL champion Greg Ray, whose four-lap average of 223.471
miles per hour knocked Montoya (223.372) from the pole position
during last Saturday's time trials. ``They didn't win four CART
championships by accident, you know? They're a damn good team with
two damn good drivers and having them here is good for the fans,
it's good for the media, and it's good for the race, because, at
the end of the day, if you're playing in the sandbox, you want to
make sure all your competition is in the sandbox with you so you
can say you beat the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a discouraging word has been uttered or written about
Team Target/Ganassi's much-anticipated return. In fact, the
harshest thing anyone has said or written has been by local scribe,
Robin Miller of the Indianapolis Star, who jokingly dubbed Team
Target as ``The Red Devils.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are the ones who are making that up,'' Ganassi said.
``I'm telling you, my guys are out there signing autographs more
than anybody and, yeah, they got a job to do and that's what
they're doing. But nobody is out here flying (CART) flags or
wanting to be the `Red Devils' or anything like that. We just want
to be the target, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, that's precisely what Vasser and Montoya will be to
the rest of the 33-car field when they fire the engines of their
Target-sponsored cars for the start of the 84th Indianapolis 500.
However, it will be their second race in as many days after
competing in Saturday's Bosch Spark Plug Grand Prix CART race at
Nazareth, Pa., which was snowed out April 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest part of doing this is thinking through all the
limitations _ the physical limitations of people and equipment,''
said Ganassi, who reportedly spent $1.7 million to hire a separate
crew of engineers and fabricators to work on his IRL program in his
palatial 70,000-square foot garage here. ``It's a pretty daunting
thing, in this day in racing. It's a pretty bold effort to go into
another formula, I don't care what formula it is. All formulas
whether it's IRL or CART or NASCAR or supermodifieds at Oswego,
when you get to that one level, it's very specialized. The question
is always, `Are you going to be able to adapt to those nuances?' ''
</P>
<P>
   So what are the differences between the open-wheel cars Montoya
and Vasser drive on the CART circuit and those they will man in
Saturday's IRL-sanctioned race?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well the horsepower is the biggest thing, for starters,''
Vasser said. ``You definitely can feel in the acceleration and
getting up to speed and if get out of the power, getting back on
the power and the response. I think there's like nearly 250
horsepower less and it's heavier in the back, so the car feels to
me like it has a kind of a pendulum motion after turning that kind
of swings around through the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, for me behind the wheel, you know, there's a
lot more similarities than there are differences.''
</P>
<P>
   The undisputed star pupil among the class of seven rookie
starters is Montoya, who quickly adapted to his IRL car when it
took him all of four laps to work up to 217 m.p.h. on his first day
on the track. During his qualification run, he blistered the track
with a warm-up lap of 221 m.p.h., before taking the provisional
pole with a four-lap average of 223.372.
</P>
<P>
   The brash 24-year-old native of Bogota has remained nonplussed
by the Speedway's daunting size or the weightiness of its rich
legacy. But that is not to say that he has been disrepectful of the
Speedway. He, like Vasser, is glad to finally have the chance to
race here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single fan here has been really good, and the drivers
and teams also,'' said Montoya. ``What really makes this place so
special is all the people. This is a really friendly area with all
the people, especially those `Alley Cats.' Have you seen them?
They're great.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser acknowledged winning the US 500 four years ago had a
bittersweet feeling because he knew his team was good enough that
day to win the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won a few 500-mile races and qualified up front at just
about every one of them,'' said Vasser, who will start in the third
row in the No. 7 starting position. ``Ever since I've been with
Chip's team, we've probably been most competitive and most
consistent in 500-mile races at superspeedways. Certainly we've
missed some opportunities to be (an Indy) 500 champion two times or
maybe even three times, but we can never get those back and I
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really taken a hard-line stance against the IRL or
for CART. I've always wanted to race here and I felt like this is
the place that you can hang your hat on for the rest of your
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
