<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-HOLDEN-$ADV28-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT'S CHIEF CHEERLEADER AND CHEESE WHIZ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Ill., N.C.)   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Ill. _ Betsy D. Holden, the new chief executive at
Kraft Foods, never disguised her ambitions for such a post, and
never saw her sex as an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in college, I said I really want to run a business
and I want to be CEO,'' she said in an interview at Kraft's
sprawling headquarters in this Chicago suburb.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, at the age of 44, Holden was granted her wish when
she was named to the position that makes her one of the highest
ranking women in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Only Carly Fiorina, the chief executive at Hewlett-Packard, runs
a bigger operation. Holden, a 16-year veteran of Kraft, a unit of
Phillip Morris, now heads the nation's largest food packager, with
more than $18 billion in revenue and some of the world's most
recognizable brands, such as Jello, Oscar Mayer, Maxwell House, and
Kraft cheese.
</P>
<P>
   But Holden, who stands 5-foot-4, does not want her gender to
receive too much attention. ``Sometimes, there's more emphasis put
on the fact that you're a woman than results,'' she says, standing
outside the door to her newly decorated executive suite. ``At the
end of the day, it's the results that count.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden has zoomed up the ranks at Kraft by delivering big
results, even while making her workplace more friendly for other
women. She was the head of Kraft's pizza division from 1993 to
1995, when Tombstone became a national brand and DiGiorno was
launched. In a business viewed as mature, she achieved record sales
and profit growth. Promoted to lead the cheese division, she became
known around the company as the ``Cheese Whiz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been a rising star in the industry,'' said John
McMillin, a food analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Texas on her brother's second birthday and
delivered by her own father, a former military flight surgeon who
later settled the family near Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, she was a cheerleader and a student council
member. She studied education at Duke, and graduated summa cum
laude.
</P>
<P>
   Children and teaching, she says, have always been her passion.
So she briefly taught fourth-grade before entering Kellogg Graduate
School of Management at Northwestern University. ``I loved the kids
and it was very fulfilling,'' she said of her teaching. ``But I was
looking for something to combine the creative and the analytical.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kellogg, she was a standout, and was named valedictorian and
outstanding marketing student. She worked first at General Foods
before moving to Kraft in 1984. ``Kraft was very good to me,'' she
says. ``Any time my learning curve started to falter, I was moved
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft executives were impressed by her teamwork, competitive
drive and inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   As a teacher, she created learning games for children, even
working part-time for Milton Bradley. She applied that same
inventiveness, colleagues say, to building Kraft's brands.
</P>
<P>
   She even invented cheers for her Kraft team, something her
colleagues kid her about. An example can be seen outside her
office: a framed picture shows an image of her face pasted onto a
cheerleader's body, under the signature cheer Holden created for
the cheese division: ``Every day and every way, grow Kraft cheese,
hey!''
</P>
<P>
   Holden also had a knack for organization, even regimentation.
She charted, listed, categorized and logically plotted not just her
rise to power, but her family life.
</P>
<P>
   She's not a workaholic, she says. But she has mastered the
balance between work and the rest of her life by setting priorities
and finding activities that fulfill many of her different
interests, like her volunteer work with the Off the Street Club, a
boys and girls club for impoverished children in a tough part of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The club gets financial support from the marketing community in
Chicago, so it's a way for her to network, teach, and spend time
with her own children, a son, age 12, and a daughter, 9, as she
invites many of the other children to her home for sleepovers.
</P>
<P>
   Holden still teaches Sunday School, along with her husband,
Arthur, the chief executive of a local company that is mapping the
human genome. When she became a mother she organized a group of
women at Kraft to form WOMEN (Working Mom's Exchange Network), a
group that delegated to its members everything from researching
pre-schools to writing wills.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Holden is delegating much larger duties. She says Kraft
wants to be the ``undisputed leader of the food industry,'' an
industry with a slowing growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, however, has outperformed most of its peers. Analysts
speculate that Kraft could make a bid for Nabisco, or that Philip
Morris could spin Kraft off as an independent company, but Holden
declines comment.
</P>
<P>
   Her task, she says, is to cut costs, make acquisitions, come up
with innovative marketing plans and further expand into nutritional
foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is look at the aging population and
genomics,'' she says. ``In a year or two you'll be able to get a
genetic profile of yourself, and be able to alter your diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is also focusing on creating more convenient,
ready-to-serve foods for meals and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are multi-tasking,'' she says, ``They're feeling
stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden's confidence that only the results of those efforts will
count was bolstered by hearing, after word had spread around Kraft
that she was the new chief, that her gender was not even a topic of
discussion. She also learned that there were several other women
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that, I said: `Yes!''' she said, pumping her
fist. `` `That's the way it ought to be.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
