</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ENVIRON-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES NEW MARINE CONSERVATION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Hawaii)   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASSATEAGUE ISLAND, Md. _ Using the sand and surf as a backdrop,
President Clinton on Friday announced new initiatives in an effort
to preserve the United States' fragile shoreline and threatened
coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton directed the Commerce Department and the Department of
the Interior, as well as the Environmental Protection Agency, to
strengthen ocean protections through administrative steps similar
to the ones applied to large tracts of land protected as wilderness
areas. Coming in the final months of his presidency, Clinton's
protections would not require approval by Congress but could be
undone by his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beach lines and coastlines are now our No. 1 tourist
destination,'' the president said, striding onto the sand on this
barrier island sporting sunglasses, short sleeves and cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our oceans, however, are far more than a playground,'' Clinton
continued. ``They have a central effect on the weather, on our
climate system. Through fishing, tourism and other industries,
ocean resources _ listen to this _ support one out of every six
jobs in the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who spoke over a roaring surf as sea gulls flew
overhead, directed the Interior and Commerce departments to set up
a system of ``marine protected areas'' to coordinate the hodgepodge
of federal protections now in place for beaches, reefs and other
marine habitats. His order did not specify any areas, but it
requested recommendations on shorelines in need of limits on such
activities as fishing, offshore oil drilling, mining and dumping.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the National Park Service protects 54 different marine
areas that span over 3 million acres of water, including Glacier
Bay in Alaska, the Everglades in Florida, and Assateague, an island
famous for the herds of wild horses that roam its marshlands. Other
marine areas have been set aside as wildlife refuges under
administration of the Fish and Wildlife Service or the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``These different protections have all been fragmented,'' said
David Hayes, deputy secretary of the Interior Department. ``And for
the first time under the executive order, there's going to be a
requirement that the agencies work together and look together at
the protections that we have, and determine whether we need new
protections or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the details remain to be worked out, some commercial
fishermen were nervous that their favorite spots might be declared
off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world is against watermen, and now you have the
world plus the president,'' Freeland Mason, past president of the
Virginia Watermen's Association, told The Associated Press. ``The
conservationists want to cut out all commercial fishing. They don't
want any fishing except by hook and line. The waterman is an
endangered species these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also directed the Environmental Protection Agency to
adopt tougher water-pollution standards to protect beaches and
coastal areas, and to identify areas where additional protections
are required.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to go back and look at their permitting process
for all of the ocean discharges that could have an impact in ocean
areas, and make sure that those are fully scientifically based, and
if necessary, to increase the protection,'' said James Baker,
administrator of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   As it is now, thousands of beaches are closed every year as
heavy rains cause sewers and drains to overflow, washing raw sewage
into the surf. That polluted runoff can cause a variety of health
hazards, including gastroenteritis, dysentery and hepatitis. It
also leads to toxic algal blooms and threatens marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Without better protections, polluted shorelines are expected to
only get worse as nearly half of all development in the United
States occurs along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also ordered the development of a plan within the next
90 days to protect the coral reefs off a 1,200-mile string of
uninhabited islands in northwest Hawaii. Coral reefs, which harbor
an abundance of marine life, are threatened worldwide from
pollution, overfishing and rising ocean temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawaiian reefs, first protected by Theodore Roosevelt's
creation of the Hawaiian Islands National Wildlife Refuge, make up
nearly 70 percent of the coral in U.S. waters and support
threatened sea turtles, Hawaiian monk seals and other marine life
found nowhere else on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan, which will probably increase the zone of
protected coral in the waters off Hawaii, would be developed in
cooperation with Hawaiian authorities, officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In announcing the initiatives, Clinton made both environmental
and economic arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old idea that we can only grow by putting more pollution
into our lakes and rivers and oceans must finally be put to rest,''
he said. ``Indeed it is now clear that we can grow our economy
faster over the long run by improving our environment, and it's
really not enough for us just to try to keep it as it is. We have
to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has used his executive authority to impose an
array of environmental protections, Congress remains in charge of
the purse strings, and Republican leaders have been reluctant to
fund all of what the president considers critical environmental
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the leadership in Congress is swimming against the
tide,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pete Jeffries, communications director for House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, said Clinton is acting unwisely by expanding
protected areas without giving enough resources to the ones already
on the books. ``Republicans want to take a responsible,
common-sense approach to our environment,'' Jeffries said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
