<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNSELFISH ACT THAT REKINDLES SPIRIT OF GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all the scandal and cynicism of the last 18 months comes a
lovely affirmation of the Olympic spirit from, of all places,
women's taekwondo. When Kay Poe, the world's top-ranked flyweight,
dislocated her kneecap before the finals of last weekend's US
trials, her childhood friend and training partner, Esther Kim,
forfeited the match rather than take a free pass to Sydney. ``If I
won, it wouldn't be fair,'' Kim told Poe before formally
withdrawing. ``It was the most heartfelt moment of my life,'' said
Poe, after she and Kim had hugged at the center of the mat. ``I
don't think it matters who won. We're both winners.'' Turns out
that Kim will go to Sydney after all. Poe is buying her a plane
ticket. And if Poe can't compete (she's sidelined for two months),
Kim gets the spot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A deficit reduction
</P>
<P>
   With more sponsors signing on (21 since Mitt Romney arrived a
year ago February) and more budget cuts, the Salt Lake organizing
committee's deficit has been chopped from $379 million to $83
million. Since SLOC has reserved nearly twice that much for
contingencies, the organizers are easily in the black with the 2002
Games still 21 months off. ``We've gone from the days of
guardrail-to-guardrail,'' said Romney, ``and we're back on track.''
Romney is breathing easier, too, since the US Department of Justice
announced last week that it won't seek an indictment of the SLOC in
the wake of the payoff scandal. Not that it's a surprise _ the
alleged wrongdoing was done by the bid committee, not the
organizing committee. The feds still can go after present or former
members of the committee, though . . . Bad month all around for the
Athens organizers. First, the Lords of the Rings put them on the
in-danger-of-failing list. Then the Olympic flame-kindling ceremony
turned into a fiasco after officials dithered so long that clouds
rolled in and blotted out the sun at Olympia. The torch had to be
ignited from a practice flame. ``How can we be expected to organize
Olympic Games,'' said Athens mayor Dimitris Avramopoulos, ``if we
can't get the ceremony right?'' . . . Off the hook is embattled
International Olympic Committee vice president Kevan Gosper of
Australia, after the committee's ethics panel found that he broke
no rules by letting his wife and children take a subsidized ski
trip to Utah when Salt Lake was bidding for the 2002 Winter Games.
Though the trip was worth much more than Gosper paid, the panel
concluded that he was misled about the cost by the bidders. ``I've
lived through controversy before,'' said Gosper, who's still
catching hell Down Under for letting his 11-year-old daughter be
the first Australian to run with the Olympic torch. ``I'll find my
way through it. Storms come and go.'' The question, though, is
whether there'll still be a lingering black cloud next year, when
Gosper is expected to be one of the prime candidates jockeying for
the IOC presidency when Juan Antonio Samaranch steps down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pedal pushers
</P>
<P>
   There was joy and heartbreak for local cyclists at last
weekend's Olympic road trials, which both came down to field
sprints on the flat Jackson, Miss., course. Wellesley's Nicole
Freedman came out of the pack to beat Pam Schuster by a length and
a half in the 64-mile women's race to win a ticket to Sydney. And
Norton's Derek Bouchard-Hall was nipped by Antonio Cruz by 6 inches
after 138 miles. ``It's a dream come true,'' said Freedman, a
28-year-old Stanford graduate who transferred from MIT and switched
from distance running to cycling. ``I don't believe it happened.''
The rest of the Olympic berths (four men, two women) will be picked
in July. Still in the chase are Bouchard-Hall, brothers Frank and
Mark McCormack (from Leicester and North Easton), Marblehead's
Tyler Hamilton, and Northampton's Jen Dial. Bouchard-Hall and the
McCormacks will be racing in next week's American Cup Pro/Am series
in six Massachusetts cities and towns. Check www.american-cup.com
for details . . . They were dancing in the streets of Prague and
Bratislava after the Czechs held off the Slovaks to retain their
men's world hockey title. Not that the Czechs were surprised _
they've never lost to their neighbors since Czechoslovakia broke
up. But the Slovaks, who'd never placed higher than seventh, were
ecstatic just to make the final. ``If somebody said before the
tournament we would come in second, we would have laughed,'' said
Slovakia's Lubomir Vaic. The Finns took the bronze ahead of the
Canadians, who left without a medal for the third straight year.
The Americans, beaten, 4-1, by the Slovaks in the quarters, ended
up fifth . . . The pre-Sydney sandbagging has already started
between the US and Australian swimming camps. After the Aussies set
four world marks (three by Ian ``The Thorpedo'' Thorpe) in Olympic
events at their team trials, US national team director Dennis
Pursley claimed that the Yanks would be underdogs at Olympus.
Nonsense, countered Aussie coach Don Talbot. ``It's a way of
transferring pressure onto us,'' he said. ``To tell me that they're
underdogs is just BS. Go ask the rest of the world who's No. 1.
They'll tell you the Americans are.'' Fact is, Talbot's right,
though his squad has all but closed the gap. The US outmedaled
Australia, 26-12, in Atlanta, 24-19 at the 1998 world meet, and
only 35-32 at last year's Pan Pacific meet in Sydney . . . Now that
Mary T. Meagher's 1981 world record in the 200-meter butterfly has
been broken by Susie O'Neill, the oldest Olympic-event mark on the
books is the 4-minute-3.85-second standard in the women's 400
freestyle set by Janet Evans at the 1998 Games in Seoul, a mark
that even Evans never came close to matching. Oldest men's mark is
the 21.81 in the 50 freestyle by Tom Jager in 1990 . . . Odds are
that the Pacific Cup victor will be determined on the first day
when the US women's soccer team plays China Wednesday in Canberra
in the teams' first meeting since last summer's World Cup final at
the Rose Bowl. Whoever earns the most points in the round-robin
format will be the champion, and the rest of the field (Australia,
New Zealand, Canada, Japan) is nowhere near the gold standard.
Except for injured starters Carla Overbeck (knee), Michelle Akers
(shoulder), and Briana Scurry (shin), the Americans will field the
full varsity . . . Off to California (and new coach Frank Carroll)
is skater Tim Goebel, who finished 11th at the world championships
after a stunning split with longtime mentor Carol Heiss Jenkins.
It's a smart move for Goebel, who needs to add polish to his
quad-filled program. Question is, can he handle practicing in the
shadow of three-time world champ Michelle Kwan? . . . That
familiar/unfamiliar face in the high school graduation line last
week belonged to Olympic skating champion Tara Lipinski, who got a
diploma from River Oaks Academy in Houston without ever seeing the
inside of the school. Lipinski, who trained in Michigan, did it all
by tutoring and correspondence. She says she'll eventually attend
college when she can do it ``the right way. I'm not going to take
any basket-weaving,'' said Lipinski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
