<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NOLAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD E. NOLAN, LAWYER WHO ADVISED CATHOLIC CHURCH, DIES AT 71 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard E. Nolan, a lawyer who represented the Roman
Catholic Church in some of the most important court cases involving
religion and government in the last 40 years, died Monday. He was
71 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He died at Lenox Hill Hospital in Manhattan of complications
from a stroke, said Geoffrey Goldberg of Davis Polk &AMP; Wardwell, the
law firm for which Nolan worked for more than 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of Nolan's cases that went to the U.S. Supreme Court
involved a 1980 New York State law requiring that parochial schools
be reimbursed by the state for providing state-mandated educational
services. A challenge to the law contended that it violated the
constitutional separation of church and state. But Nolan's argument
prevailed. He convinced the justices that the law was sound because
it required reimbursement only for statewide standardized services,
not religious education. His victory set the stage for similar laws
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a young lawyer, he took part in the unsuccessful battle to
keep organized prayer in public schools. The Supreme Court banned
such prayer in 1962 in its landmark decision in Engel vs. Vitale.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, however, Nolan was considered a successful
litigator, and his cases laid the foundation for lawsuits that are
being litigated today, said Robert A. Destro, interim dean of the
Columbus School of Law at Catholic University of America in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the politics at the time, he was litigating against
a brick wall,'' Destro said. ``Only now is the work that he was
doing in those years beginning to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Edward Nolan was born Nov. 28, 1928, in Brooklyn. H He
received his law degree in 1957 from Columbia Law School, where he
was notes editor of The Law Review. He joined the law firm of Davis
Polk &AMP; Wardwell that year, and remained there until his death.
</P>
<P>
   He served as a first lieutenant with the Army Signal Corps
during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic, Nolan advised Cardinals Terence Cooke and John
O'Connor on legal issues facing the church.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 41 years, the former Agnes Folk
Gillian; two daughters, Mariana C. Nolan and Katherine H.L. Nolan;
three sons, Anthony, Timothy and Christopher; a sister, Eileen
Solimano; and three grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
