<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-WILLEY-1STLD-     05-26 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WILLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE LOSES AND GAINS IN RULING ON A PRIVACY ACT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs 1st graf to insert `of 1974'; 3rd graf to change `submit to'
to `abide by'; 5th graf to insert `toward her'; 6th graf to change
`supposed sexual advance' to `time she said the advance took
place.') 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court on Friday refused to
interfere in a lawsuit brought by a group that accuses President
Clinton of violating the Privacy Act of 1974. . But the ruling was
still a partial victory for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges said there was no need to issue an emergency
order sought by the White House to block pre-trial information
gathering, or discovery, in the suit brought by Judicial Watch, a
conservative organization that has been a persistent foe of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Jim Kennedy, said Friday that White
House lawyers were disappointed by the decision on discovery, but
would abide by it nonetheless. But Kennedy said White House lawyers
were ``very pleased'' by other elements of Friday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel sharply criticized a lower court judge who
asserted in a March 29 ruling that the president committed ``a
criminal violation of the Privacy Act'' in releasing personal
letters sent to him by Kathleen Willey, a former White House
volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Willey accused Clinton on the CBS News program
``60 Minutes'' of making a sexual advance toward her in the fall of
1993. Her account added to the burdens of the president during the
investigation of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and the
sexual-misconduct lawsuit filed by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Willey's television appearance, the president
released her letters _ reluctantly, he said _ in the hope that
their friendly tone would undercut her accusations. She had written
them after the time she said the advance took place.
</P>
<P>
   Willey is not a party to the suit by Judicial Watch, which
contends that the White House improperly obtained hundreds of files
from the FBI on former appointees and employees of the Reagan and
Bush administrations. Judicial Watch has focused on the handling of
the Willey letters in the hope of uncovering evidence that might
buttress its allegations involving misuse of the FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   On March 29, Judge Royce L. Lamberth ruled that White House
lawyers should submit to questioning by attorneys from Judicial
Watch. He went further, declaring that Clinton had acted unlawfully
in releasing Willey's letters, which were kept among White House
records. The Privacy Act generally bars release of information
about a person from federal records without that person's consent,
and violations of the law can result in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the appeals judges said Lamberth's ``sweeping
pronouncements'' about supposed criminal activity were
inappropriate, ``entirely superfluous'' and not binding on any
court that might have to weigh the question of criminality.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has contended all along that much of its
business is exempt from the Privacy Act, and that many lawyers from
both political parties have long said so. Friday, the appeals
judges said that, in matters unrelated to the Judicial Watch case,
the White House can continue to operate under that assumption
unless and until a court declares otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth was appointed by President Ronald Reagan in 1987.
Clinton and his allies have made no secret of their feeling that
the judge is unfriendly to the current administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OCEAN0527-COX     05-26 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton promises protection for coastal areas
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - President Clinton pledged Friday that the federal
government would protect fragile stretches of seas and beaches in a
network of preserves resembling national parks and wilderness
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the roar of ocean surf at Assateague Island, Md., Clinton
ordered government agencies to draw up lists of coastal areas and
how they might be protected from fishing, drilling and other human
threats.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative parallels projects to safeguard the Florida Keys'
threatened coral reefs and species.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Keys are a microcosm for what is happening worldwide,''
said Kim Anaston, the Florida Keys project manager for the Center
for Marine Conservation, a Washington-based environmental group
that endorsed Clinton's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The center is among numerous private groups and government
agencies working to turn the 125 miles of Tortugas Bank, south of
the Keys, into an ecological reserve. It would be the largest
undersea preserve in America, and one of the largest in the world.
It would dwarf a patchwork of 23 near-shore preserves already
marked out in the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would join such countries as Australia, New
Zealand, Cuba, Kenya, the Bahamas and Mexico in designating part of
their oceans as parks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to bolster the government's commitment, saying he
envisions a network of protected marine areas resembling the
decades-old national parks system.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government already has set aside more than 200
million acres of wilderness and national parks to provide
sanctuaries for wildlife and plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do more with our seas and our coasts,'' Clinton
said. ``The old idea that we can only grow by putting more
pollution into our lakes and rivers and oceans must finally be put
to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   With millions of Americans living near a coastline, pressures
are mounting from development, pollution, fishing, and oil and gas
drilling, environmental advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to preserve our oceans and the wildlife that
resides in them, we need to take some steps that we have not taken
to protect them,'' said Roger Rufe, president of the Center for
Marine Conservation. ``It is long overdue, but it is much
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interior and Commerce departments would draw up lists of
threatened areas and weigh how best to protect them. Methods could
include bans on fishing, drilling or other activities. Or there
could be milder measures. A new federal office would administer the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government already has administrative power to
impose protections on federal waters and coastline, but it is not
often invoked. Those powers do not extend to private waters.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials questioned Friday whether Clinton's initiative
would have much impact on the Southern coast, beyond the Keys at
Florida's southern tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we can tell, it is a statement that he is going to
continue the status quo,'' said Mike Shanahan, spokesman for the
American Petroleum Institute in Washington. ``Everything he is
talking about is already out of bounds for offshore drilling,''
including the issuance of any new East Coast drilling licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Most U.S. oil drilling occurs in the Gulf of Mexico, in areas
Shanahan said are less environmentally sensitive than those found
elsewhere near Florida, especially around the coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to have limited relevance to the coastal
Southeast,'' said Howard Marlowe, president of the American Coastal
Coalition, a Washington-based advocacy group representing coastal
communities on issues such as beach renourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Marlowe said coral reefs are limited to the warm waters of
southern Florida, diminishing efforts to preserve those threatened
habitats elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it is limited to the Keys,'' Anaston said, but she
and colleague Marianne Cufong of the Coastal Management Council in
St. Petersburg said Clinton's initiative reaches beyond protecting
coral reefs to species elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Grouper and snapper are among the many south Atlantic species
considered to be overfished, said Cufong, the council's regional
fish conservation manager for the southeastern Atlantic and the
Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can draw your own conclusions from that . . . about
whether there should be a national mandate,'' Cufong said. ``We
favor maritime preserves as a management tool to protect species.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said oceans cover about 70 percent of the Earth's
surface and support all manner of economy and jobs. But, he said,
they are also among the world's endangered places, under siege from
pollution, global warming and other threats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
