<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COUNTERFEIT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULGARIAN PLEADS GUILTY TO COUNTERFEITING CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Canada)   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Amtrak train to New York rolled into Niagara
Falls last October, customs officers boarded it for a routine
inspection. What they found stacked and wrapped in a newspaper in a
bathroom stall was anything but routine: $200,000 in $100 bills.
</P>
<P>
   That chance find last October led to a counterfeiting ring whose
trail stretched from Queens County, N.Y., through Canada to
Bulgaria, where federal prosecutors say a group of men produced
some of the highest quality fake money now circulating in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the last member of the counterfeiting operation
pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in Manhattan to conspiracy to
distribute the $100 bills. Prosecutors said the man, Peter
Simeonov, a native of Bulgaria, was part of a group responsible for
distributing at least $500,000 in counterfeit money in 1999. Five
other men have also pleaded guilty to various charges related to
the case.
</P>
<P>
   After finding the money in the train bathroom, customs officers
alerted the Secret Service, which is responsible for pursuing
counterfeiters. The agents met the officers at the train and,
according to court documents, immediately identified the bills as
the type of counterfeit believed to originate in Bulgaria.
Documents filed in court say the agents checked the passenger
roster and identified one rider as a Bulgarian national. After
questioning by the agents, the agents were able to find the ring
members who were passing the money in New York City, court
documents indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents, who began an investigation of the
counterfeit $100 bill before the discovery on the train, quickly
identified the Amtrak find as part of the bills flooding in New
York City. Prosecutors said $35,000 to $40,000 worth of the bogus
bills were being passed in the New York area every week.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the U.S. Attorney's office in the Southern
District of New York said that the counterfeiting ring had been
passing both old and new versions of the bills. Court papers said
the men either gave the bills to unsuspecting merchants or sold
them at a discount, typically for 40 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce A. Townsend, the special agent in charge of the Secret
Service's counterfeit division, said the Bulgarian bills were of
high-quality, but that fakes of the new bills, with the off-center
portraits, were easily detectable by anyone familiar with the new
currency's security features. Townsend said that new bills have
security features that make them very difficult to copy.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend said the bills were made with an offset printing press,
which is a traditional way of making counterfeit money. Much of the
new counterfeit money detected by the Secret Service is reproduced
with computer technology, he said, although such bills tend to be
of lower quality.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend said that less than 1 percent of the more than $500
billion in U.S. currency in circulation throughout the world is
estimated to be counterfeit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A counterfeit-proof bank note does not exist,'' he said. ``But
what we do is add layers of security to make it as difficult as
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
