<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-LAZIO-HIGHSCHOOL-$ADV     05-26 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-HIGHSCHOOL-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY CLASSMATE, THE CANDIDATE FOR THE U.S. SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
 By BOB MORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I haven't seen Rick Lazio this much since high school. Back
then, he and I were in classes together in boring West Islip, N.Y.
He was barely memorable, not a star athlete, scholar, artist,
actor, surfer or class clown. He was simply decent in a way that
makes you not want to give someone the time of day as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, since he announced his race for the Senate in
the West Islip High School gym last Sunday (``I'm no celebrity,''
he declared), the entire country knows who he is. I'm not the only
former classmate reminiscing about the lackluster impression he
made back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to listen to my parents sing the praises of Rick
Lazio one more time, I'll vomit,'' said Judi Ford, a classmate and
single mother from Westchester. ``My mother tells me, `Listen,
Smarty Pants, when you're important enough to be on national TV,
we'll ask for your opinion.' It drives me crazy because he was so
unremarkable, and it makes me regret wasted opportunities in my own
life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know what to say to that. After all, where do
brains and talent get you without ambition? If Hollywood is high
school with money, isn't Washington just high school for
opportunists? Besides, since I've always seen West Islip as a
fishpond of banality, maybe it's apt that Lazio has become its
poster boy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the former classmates I called last week, some of them
Lazio's old buddies, recalled him as amiable, good at remembering
names and not much more. Of course, it's not unusual to feel
jealous or left behind when old faces achieve prominence and move
into a social stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea who he is,'' said Barbara Fasano, an
award-winning cabaret singer and classmate still striving for fame
in Manhattan. ``But then again, he looks just like the kind of guy
I would ignore in high school anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible to be a nobody and a somebody simultaneously? Is
it even fair to recall as a nobody a somebody who has made a name
for himself in Congress? If Rick Lazio, who now has the attention
of everyone from David Letterman to my Aunt Phyllis in Alabama (she
called to crow about how articulate he was on television), is ``no
celebrity,'' what does that make the rest of us squawking
onlookers?
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lazio was working the Staten Island Ferry Terminal's
morning rush hour. I went to see him. ``Say hello to your next
senator,'' one of many tough-looking men in suits around him yelled
at me and the commuters passing through turnstiles. A very high
school-like alarm bell rang for each departing ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi Rick, remember me?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I do, Bob,'' he said as he shook my hand.
</P>
<P>
   I did not say, ``Well that's good because I barely remember
you.''
</P>
<P>
   But, after talking briefly about friends and teachers, I stepped
back and watched him work the crowd, tucking his lean frame in to
listen, touch arms, grip shoulders and pose with children of color
for hovering photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Islip was a fairly monolithic community without much
ethnic diversity,'' he told me when I asked if his years in our
all-white, mostly Roman Catholic high school had prepared him for
politics. ``But college at Vassar and law school and my career has
made me more empathetic. I'm learning all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, he probably meant homogenous, not monolithic. Still he
seemed to be trying hard, as I know he's done as a representative.
A friend had told me that although Lazio wasn't a top honors
student in our class, he showed a cheerful press-ahead quality, and
I could see it now, as he worked wave after wave of rushing
commuters. Surely, there are easier ways to make a living and a
mark on the world.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many people around him that it was hard to have a
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you this popular in high school?'' I asked. An absurd
question. He laughed, and that's when I realized how little high
school matters now, how we have to let go of it and adjust to what
we've become and allow others their due.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
