<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-ART     05-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN DEATH, SEALY KEEPS TEACHING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the pulpit of Riverside Church Friday morning,
speaker after speaker gave witness to the short, productive life of
Malik Sealy.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Lisa, said she lost a soulmate when he was killed in
an automobile accident last Saturday. Sealy's older brother
Dessalines talked about Malik's wry humor and comical ways. Lou
Carnesecca described Sealy as a responsible, loyal star, always
focused on the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mitchell, who played with Sealy with the Indiana Pacers
beginning in 1989, when Sealy was a rookie, and who was a teammate
with the Timberwolves the past two seasons, described him as the
thread that brought Minnesota together this season. ``He preached
closeness,'' Mitchell said. ``He said that if we put all the
jealousy, all the contract business on the side, we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   Malik Sealy was a product of the multilayered culture of New
York City basketball, and Friday was a celebration of a basketball
life. All boroughs, several generations, all levels of his
basketball life converged on Riverside Church. Sealy was a perfect
synthesis of the New York City basketball underground, the
playground leagues and the legitimate theater of professional
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of St. John's players and New York players _ some
known, some mostly unknown warriors of the paint _ came to pay
tribute: Billy Singleton, Shawnelle Scott, Greg ``Boo'' Harvey,
whom knowledgeable folks hadn't seen or heard from in years.
</P>
<P>
   The New York city legends Tiny Archibald, Kenny Smith, Rod
Strickland and Kenny Anderson huddled in one area of the church
while the current and former NBA players Ray Allen, Joe Smith,
Cedric Ceballos and Terry Dehere and probably many more familiar
faces circulated through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Timberwolves team came for the service. Mitchell
spoke, Kevin Garnett was a pallbearer. During a smaller ceremony a
day earlier, Garnett wept as he spoke about Sealy. In a league in
which rich young stars aren't often inclined to listen, the
24-year-old Garnett looked up to the 30-year-old Sealy. As an
eighth-grader in Chicago, shy and lacking confidence, Garnett
watched St. John's play and recognized himself in Sealy: same body
type, same way of moving.
</P>
<P>
   When Sealy wound up with Minnesota in 1998, he became Garnett's
mentor, teaching him lessons of how to move in the interstices of
fame, how to enjoy notoriety without being devoured by it. Now in
death Sealy was teaching his young friend to absorb the lesson of
his life despite the tragic circumstances of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's service in the south hall of Riverside Church,
Garnett shook his head and said: ``This is real life. Real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Indiana Pacers flew in Thursday night to make Friday
morning's service: Mark Jackson, Chris Mullin, Dale Davis, Reggie
Miller and Al Harrington. What an odd juxtaposition of basketball
reality and respect. The Pacers were holding a 2-0 lead over the
Knicks, but the Pacers, for all the talk about ``hicks'' was more
New York than the Knicks. Mullin is from Brooklyn, Jackson is from
Queens, Harrington is from Roselle, N.J.; Miller's second home is
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Missing amid all this contemporary New York basketball history,
were the Knicks. The team arrived from Indianapolis at 3 a.m.
Friday. With a 10 a.m. service and 2 p.m. practice, the team
couldn't make it work. Charles Oakley, the former Knick who plays
with Toronto, was the closest the Knicks came to having a presence.
</P>
<P>
   Sealy's family, with the help of the NBA, put together a video
of his life: a collage of baby pictures; footage from Tolentine
High, slam-dunking days at St. John's, then fast-forwarded to draft
day with David Stern announcing that Sealy was headed to Indiana.
Fast-forward again to Sealy's successes with Minnesota this season,
replete with dunks and game-winning shots. The audience at
Riverside applauded and cheered and for a time we were all back in
that moment when Sealy was alive. Finally there was the wedding day
footage, just a few months ago, of Lisa and Malik Sealy, with their
son Malik Jr. The final shot showed Sealy in a dressing room.
Confident and assured, he said: ``I'm a Renaissance man. Artist, a
designer an athlete. There is nothing I can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   The large screen was rolled away, and we were confronted more
powerfully than before by the hollow echo of real life; the
finality of Malik Sealy's death at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   As mourners filed out of the church, a few went over to where
Miller was standing with Jackson. For all the sadness of Sealy's
death, the fact that Game 3 was being played in New York Saturday
was never far from the surface. This is the hard-edged New York
basketball tradition that produced Sealy. The game must go on.
</P>
<P>
   Fans lightly kidded Miller with respect and even warmth: things
like ``I'm a Knicks fan, but I respect your game.'' And ``Reggie,
you play hard, man, I got to give it to you. I still like the
Knicks.'' Miller, wearing sunglasses, nodded politely but said
nothing. He hugged a close friend and spoke quietly. But this was
not his day; he came, like all the others, to pay final respects to
a friend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0527-COX     05-26 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reputation of witness may be a boon for prosecution
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chester Anderson is a schemer, a liar, a convict and a
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He also might be the best thing the prosecution's got going so
far in its case against NFL star Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old con man Friday became the state's first witness
to testify that the All-Pro linebacker was an active participant in
the Buckhead melee that left two men stabbed to death Jan. 31 hours
after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he saw Lewis standing over and kicking a lifeless
victim who lay face down on the road. Prosecutors will say this was
5-foot-3 Jacinth Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him kicking the smaller gentleman,'' said Anderson,
currently in jail on identity fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   While Anderson's credibility was called into question during a
lengthy cross-examination by Lewis' lawyer, Ed Garland, Fulton
County District Attorney Paul Howard sought to buttress it with
corroborating witnesses. And Howard said he will call on more
witnesses next week to substantiate Anderson's account.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's testimony finished a day when prosecutors considered
whether to grant immunity to Carlos Stafford, a Houston man who was
in Lewis' stretch Lincoln Navigator limousine the night of the
killings. Lawyers for defendants Lewis, Joseph Sweeting, 34, and
Reginald Oakley, 31, contend Stafford was an active participant in
the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford's lawyer, Dwight Thomas, said any such notion is not
true. Thomas said Friday that prosecutors had told him they needed
Stafford's testimony but had not yet made the deal. If his client
testifies, the lawyer said, he will be ``helpful to some defendants
and damaging to others.'' He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Keiva Walls, a woman who rode in the limo, also testified
Friday, saying she heard Lewis in his hotel room after the killings
saying, ``I'm not trying to end my career like this.''
</P>
<P>
   She said after leaving the hotel, Stafford went to a Dumpster
behind a fast food restaurant and threw away a large bag containing
some items. Prosecutors are contending that the items thrown away
were the suit Lewis was wearing that night.
</P>
<P>
   After Walls, Cab driver Patrick Ozonu testified that he drove
upon the crime scene and saw a man with an athletic build standing
over one of the victims and pointing angrily.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a body I could envy . . . built like a V,'' Ozonu said.
But when asked by Garland if the man could have been Lewis, Ozonu
said no, that the man was smaller than the linebacker. Ozonu also
said he saw six men attacking the victims and then run away _ but
in the opposite direction of Lewis' limousine.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution saved Anderson for the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson came to Atlanta Super Bowl week impersonating himself
as ``long-time friend'' Byron ``Bam'' Morris, a former NFL football
player convicted of drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   On Super Bowl night, Anderson testified, he saw Lewis as he
walked to the Cobalt Lounge. Anderson testified that he and two
acquaintances, whom he identified as ``Frank Bruno'' and ``John
Giovani,'' walked over to another club nearby. Prosecutors later
said these two men were actually brothers Bruno and John DiSiena.
</P>
<P>
   When they left that bar, Anderson testified, the three men
walked toward the DiSienas' rental car parked near the intersection
where Richard Lollar, 24, and Baker, 21, were stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he heard John DiSiena say, ``Ray Lewis and them
are kicking someone's ass.'' Anderson said he looked up and saw it
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see him fight back?'' Assistant District Attorney
Clint Rucker asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Anderson replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he appear to be moving?'' Rucker asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Anderson answered.
</P>
<P>
   Rucker brought up Anderson's past convictions of fraud, theft
and passing bad checks, and the witness admitted to them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that have anything to do with what you saw?'' Rucker
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' Anderson answered, Anderson said he has no deal
from the prosecution for his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno DiSiena, a Cleveland restaurant owner, was called to
support Anderson's testimony. He said when the trio got to the
rental car, Anderson said he saw Lewis kicking a victim.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruno DiSiena said he never saw Lewis fighting, nor did he
hear his brother say he saw Lewis kicking anyone. John DiSiena, who
could have cemented Anderson's testimony, was not called to the
stand and will not be a prosecution witness, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a thick stack of certified court records, Garland then
began his cross-examination, questioning Anderson about his past
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson admitted to obtaining the social security number of an
Arlington, Texas, man named Chad Anderson. He said he ran up
hundreds of dollars in cell phone bills, rented an apartment and
purchased five cars under Chad Anderson's name. One car, a 1999 GMC
Yukon Denali, he said, ``ran like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point during his cross-examination, Garland paused gave
jurors a moment out of Perry Mason, bellowing, ``Stand up, Mr.
Anderson.'' The real Chad Anderson, wearing a brown blazer and
sitting behind the defense table, arose to muffled gasps throughout
the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   During a courtroom break, Chad Anderson said his appearance gave
him ``peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson conceded his admissions likely will lead to his
convictions on the identity fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're very successful as a fraud, aren't you?'' Garland
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraud, yes.'' Anderson replied. But he added that he was not
lying as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Garland then accused Anderson of accusing Lewis so he could
either gain his freedom from prison or make money.
</P>
<P>
   Walking back to the defense table, Garland had one final
question, ``Would you know the truth if it bumped into you?''
</P>
<P>
   As Garland knew he would, Rucker sprang out of his chair and
shouted, ``Objection!'' amid courtroom chuckles. Bonner sustained
the objection, but Garland's point already had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
