<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      05-26 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW WAVE OF GROWTH IN ASIA IS REMINISCENT OF 1980S
</P>
<P>
   Less than three years after a plunge in the value of Thailand's
currency set in motion a devastating economic crisis across much of
Asia, the region is riding a wave of growth reminiscent of the
Asian miracle of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence of the resurgence came with a report that
Hong Kong's economic output rose 14.3 percent in the first three
months of the year. It was the territory's fastest quarter of
growth since 1987, and seemed to make the Asian crisis a distant
memory.
</P>
<P>
   DEMAND FOR BIG-TICKET GOODS FALLS
</P>
<P>
   Demand for big-ticket goods in April registered its steepest
decline since late 1991, and consumer spending rose at its slowest
pace in nine months, the government said, indicating that the
economy may be slowing. Durable-goods orders fell 6.4 percent;
economists had been expecting a 0.5 percent drop. Consumer spending
rose 0.4 percent, while consumer income climbed 0.7 percent; both
figures matched forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-INSURANCE PREMIUMS EDGE UP
</P>
<P>
   After falling for two years, car-insurance premiums around the
United States are climbing once again, resuming a steady
quarter-century rise. Several big insurers have begun imposing
higher prices, and analysts say that by the end of the year most
other big insurers are likely to follow. The insurers said they
were forced to act because of rising expenses for repairs and
treatment of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   PUSH FOR PRESCRIPTION-DRUG COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   Bill Thomas of California, an influential Republican member of
the House, and Ron Wyden of Oregon, a Democratic senator, announced
that they would collaborate on a bipartisan effort to add
prescription-drug benefits to Medicare this year. The effort alters
the politics of the issue in this election year, at least
marginally increasing the chances that Congress can break the
deadlock on Medicare coverage of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   DE BEERS SEIZES ANGOLAN DIAMONDS
</P>
<P>
   De Beers has begun seizing shipments of Angolan government
diamonds after the Angolans scrapped a 10-year-old agreement with
De Beers to market stones from an Angolan concession. De Beers
officials said they were acting in part because of a $50 million
debt owed to the company by Angola.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING'S SATELLITE DEAL IS DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's proposed purchase of the satellite unit of Hughes
Electronics faces an extended investigation by European antitrust
officials, which may delay the deal.
</P>
<P>
   TOSHIBA FACES COMPLAINTS IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba's settlement of a class-action lawsuit in the United
States last year has backfired in China, where consumers are
charging discrimination because the Japanese electronics maker has
not offered them the same deal. Masaichi Koga, a vice president of
Toshiba, went to Beijing this week to try to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS CLOSED MEMORIAL DAY
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets, government offices and banks will be
closed Monday in observance of Memorial Day. Financial markets will
be open in other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
