<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-DOT-COMS-BOS &LR;      05-26 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DOT-COMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE HAS ARRIVED IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A new catch-phrase has become all the rage in Moscow's
business community: tochka-ru _ that's Russian for dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nasdaq Composite index has plunged and dot-com mania has
cooled in the United States, e-commerce has come to Russia,
bringing with it promises of efficiency and hopes for big profits.
</P>
<P>
   At a five-star hotel near the Kremlin on Thursday, the publisher
who brought Playboy and Cosmopolitan to the Russian market
announced the launch of Moscow's latest online business venture _
an Internet portal called eStart.ru, modeled on the popular
US-based Yahoo Web site.
</P>
<P>
   With their site displayed on a giant screen, co-editors
Konstantin Chernazatonsky and Matt Bivens gave 100 or so assembled
guests a virtual tour of what eStart will offer to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you will find everything you need here. How to plant a
tree. How to make cappuccino at home. What you can eat when you are
pregnant. What's on television,'' said Bivens, a US citizen who
also is editor of Russia's main English-language newspaper, The
Moscow Times.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers free e-mail, a search engine, news, sports,
health and lifestyle features, and chat rooms. Most of the content
is produced by eStart's majority owner, Independent Media, a Dutch
company that publishes 14 glossy magazines _ including the Russian
versions of Playboy, Cosmopolitan, Harper's Bazaar, and Good
Housekeeping _ and four newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Derk Sauer, Independent Media's CEO, said the company plans to
invest $5 million in eStart, and hopes to turn a profit after three
years.
</P>
<P>
   All this may seem old hat to Internet-savvy Americans, but
ventures like eStart are relatively new here. And although it is
much too early to talk about a ``new economy'' in Russia, an
e-commerce craze visibly has caught on in this vast nation's
capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards plugging online supermarkets adorn Moscow streets.
Television ads for Ozone.ru, an online bookstore aspiring to be
Russia's answer to Amazon.com, appear in prime time on most
channels. One of the country's hottest Web sites is Molotok.ru, an
Internet-based auction house that is Russia's version of eBay.com.
Web designers suddenly are demanding salaries from $500 to $1,000 a
month in a country where the average monthly wage is $70.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts expect Internet advertising revenues, just
$1.5 million last year, to increase to $45 million by 2005. With so
much cash at stake, eStart and several other companies are vying to
become Russia's Yahoo _ the site where Internet users start off on
when they surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a US-based investment fund paid $2.5 million for an
undisclosed stake in a web portal called Port.ru. In January, a
group of Russian and foreign investors announced plans to put as
much as $30 million into Russia's most popular search engine,
Rambler.ru, in hopes of making it Russia's premiere site.
</P>
<P>
   Online retail shops also have mushroomed.
</P>
<P>
   This is a potentially huge growth market, mainly because going
to the store here _ where surly clerks, inconsistent inventories
and long lines are the norm _ can be a nerve-wracking ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular virtual department store, called xxl.ru, boasts
more than 7,000 products ranging from bed linens to groceries to
office supplies to concert tickets, and offers free same-day
delivery for orders over $17.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more bad weather and heavy bags. No more traffic jams and
long lines,'' the site's advertisement reads.
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of 187 full-time employees, xxl.ru takes an average
of 100 orders a day. Kirill Modylevsky, the company's commercial
director, expects that number to increase dramatically in the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, five years from now people won't buy things in
stores at all,'' Modylevsky said. ``This is a waste of time. Why
trudge down a dirty street to a store when you could be reading a
book?''
</P>
<P>
   Like most online retailers, xxl.ru has yet to make a profit, but
Modylevsky said he expects the company to break even by the first
quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the optimism, online business in Russia remains limited.
The country's 1.7 million regular Internet users _ just over 1
percent of the population _ are confined mostly to big cities such
as Moscow and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Russian Internet generated just over $100 million
in turnover, most of which came from business-to-business
transactions. This is a far cry from the billions of dollars in
Internet sales the United States saw just over the 1999 Christmas
season.
</P>
<P>
   And financial analysts here say that no matter how slick a
Web-based retailer's Internet site may be, the industry is still
hampered by the same things that slow down Russia's traditional
economy: inadequate payment mechanisms, low disposable income among
consumers, and poor distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Few Russians have credit cards, and those who do, fearing fraud,
are reluctant to use them over the Internet. Distribution is
unreliable and the nation's postal system is notoriously slow and
inefficient. To get around these problems, Internet retailers are
creating their own courier services and accepting payment on
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are buying into the Internet in Russia are
making a bet on the future,'' said Kirill Gromov of Troika-Dialog,
a Moscow-based investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a good gamble. Internet use here is doubling every 18
months and e-commerce will grow as more and more Russians get
online.
</P>
<P>
   Is Russia on the verge of a Web-business boom?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is hysteria about e-commerce now, but a successful
business cannot be built with the snap of your fingers,'' eStart's
editor Chernazatonsky said. ``The main question is: Can you offer
people an efficient service? To do this you need to work at it day
after day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
