<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-ALCON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCON LABS TO ACQUIRE SUMMIT AUTONOMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summit Autonomous Inc., which pioneered laser eye surgery,
Friday said it had agreed to be acquired by Alcon Laboratories
Inc., a unit of Nestle SA, for $893.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which has been rumored at the American Cataract and
Refractory Surgery conference in Boston last week, pairs Summit,
the No. 2 maker of vision-correction lasers, with one of the
nation's largest manufacturers of contact-lens care solutions,
cataract surgical equipment and prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint announcement Friday, Alcon, based in Fort Worth,
Texas, said it will pay $19 for each of the 47.032 million shares
of Summit, based in Waltham, Mass. However, based on Summit's
closing stock price of $18.50, the deal is currently valued at $870
million. Friday's stock price is also $5.8125 higher than
Thursday's close _ a 45.8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large eye-care companies like Alcon can no longer ignore the
laser-vision correction market, which is growing a lot faster than
the cataract market,'' said Charles J. Olsziewski Paine Webber
senior vice president of research in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies, which are expected to discuss their agreement
with Wall Street analysts Tuesday, are part of an industry
consolidation, in which laser makers, surgical equipment and
pharmaceutical companies will bundle an array of products and
services for ophthalmologists
</P>
<P>
   In February, Bausch and Lomb Inc. of Rochester, N.Y., a leading
eye products company expanded into the laser vision correction
business by gaining US Food and Drug Administration approval for an
eye surgery procedure called Lasik.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summit without Alcon just does not have the power to compete
for business against Bausch and Lomb, which can practically give
away the laser to ophthalmologists and make its money on all the
other eye products it sells,'' said Irving Arons, managing director
of Spectrum Consulting, a Peabody-based company that tracks
laser-vision companies.
</P>
<P>
   Summit and long-time rival Visx Inc., the No. 1 laser maker,
control as much as 95 percent of the laser market to correct for
nearsightedness and farsightedness. Arons estimates that 1.65
million eye procedures will be conducted this year _ 76 percent
more than last year. Each of these operations costs $1,800 to
$2,200 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   Summit _ which changed its name from Summit Technology Inc. to
Summit Autonomus at last week's annual meeting _ has begun to catch
up to Visx, due largely to it $224 milion acquisition of Autonomous
Technologies Corp. of Orlando, Fla., early last year.
</P>
<P>
   That purchase, noted some analysts, saved Summit which had
relatively old technology and was saddled with a money-losing
network of company-owned laser-vision centers. It also had Lens
Expresss, a money-losing, mail-order contact lens business.
</P>
<P>
   Rober Palmisano, who joined Summit as chief executive 37 months
ago sold both the laser centers and Lens Express _ the hallmarks of
David F. Muller, the company's legendary cofounder and chief
executive _ and improved the company's satisfaction ratings with
ophthalmologists.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial Muller was successful in gaining FDA approval
for the nation's first medical laser system to correct
nearsightedness _ a 10-year effort that ushered in a new era in eye
care and pushed Summit stock to a peak of $50.75 in October 1995
</P>
<P>
   But life at the top was short, as Summit became embroiled in a
series of patent ownership disputes, shareholder and employee
lawsuits, and a Federal Trade Commission probe over fees that
Summit and Visx charged ophthalmologists. Summit's stock quickly
plunged to less than $5 a share as the FTC put pressure on both
companies to lower their per-procedure fees.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the the most controversial Summit issue was Muller's
mysterious receipt of stolen FDA documents about Visx newest laser
_ a theft that launched a FBI and subsequent congressional
investigation, which Palmisano said never went anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really a different company today,'' Palmisano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
