<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO TO REMAIN HOUSE MEMBER WHILE RUNNING FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio said Friday that he would not resign
his House seat while he runs for the Senate, but would balance the
demands of the campaign trail with the final five months of his
House term.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaigned in New York City for the second time Friday,
greeting commuters and visiting a center for the elderly on Staten
Island while his opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, campaigned on
Long Island, Lazio's home base, and got the endorsement of a labor
federation.
</P>
<P>
   When Lazio, who seemed to have anticipated the question, was
asked at a news conference if he was considering resigning to focus
on his campaign, he replied, ``It is not something I am considering
at all.'' He had taken a break from his travels on Tuesday and
Wednesday to vote on several bills, including the measure
normalizing trade with China, which he supported.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and Republican leaders said they did not think his
Washington duties would distract him from the race, but the issue
recalled the 1998 Senate race, when Sen. Alfonse D'Amato attacked
his challenger, Rep. Charles E. Schumer, for missing key votes
while campaigning. The tactic backfired when it was learned that
D'Amato, who lost the race, had also missed legislative votes as a
county supervisor campaigning for the Senate in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he had participated in all but perhaps one vote this
year, but he did not promise to maintain that record as the
campaign intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm going to be able to keep that pace up,'' he
said. ``I think the voters in New York are smart enough to
understand that I can't make this race, with five months to go,
without meeting them, getting to know them, being held accountable
and answering your questions. That will mean that some votes will
be missed. And so I'm just going to work very hard to make sure
that the most significant votes, I'm there for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's decision should have no effect on the contest to succeed
him as the representative from the 2nd Congressional District, in
Suffolk County. Lazio's two-year term, his fourth, is up this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, if Lazio resigned on or before July 1, the
governor would call a special election to fill the seat for the
remainder of the term.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Clinton would not comment on Lazio's decision
to retain his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders sought to portray the decision as a sign of
diligence to duty that is relatively risk free. Some noted that the
House would be in recess for much of the summer, and with all the
House seats up this year, few expected critical votes to be
scheduled in the fall while members campaigned to keep their jobs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Obviously with what Congressman Lazio has been able to
accomplish in one week, we believe he has the momentum going into
the convention,'' said Dan Allen, a spokesman for the state
Republican committee, which is expected to officially nominate
Lazio at its convention on Tuesday. ``He's got the ability and he
is doing his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio got a warm reception on Staten Island, a Republican
stronghold where Clinton has campaigned only once. In contrast to
the occasional heckler he encountered while campaigning in
Manhattan on Tuesday, Lazio accepted hugs and kisses from adults
and children.
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats said they would consider voting for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have put Hillary in there just because she was
Hillary and she was running against Giuliani,'' said Tony McBroom,
who works in medical-book publishing and lamented Giuliani's poor
standing with black residents. ``As a race of people, we are not
too cool with Mr. Giuliani right now. So we would like to hear and
see what Lazio has got to say.'' He referred to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who had been expected to be the Republican Senate nominee
until he withdrew from the race for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's latest endorsement was announced at an outdoor rally
held by the Building and Construction Trades Council of Nassau and
Suffolk Counties, a Long Island umbrella organization of 38 local
trade unions with 60,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The council has a history of endorsing candidates from both
major political parties, but its president, Jack Kennedy, said that
in the Senate campaign, Lazio ``wasn't even in the running.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The AFL-CIO sent us his record, and his record as far as
voting on labor issues and for working people has not been good,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance in Glen Cove, atop a flatbed truck decked
out with ``Hillary'' campaign signs, was her first foray onto Long
Island since Lazio replaced Giuliani as her opponent. She spent
almost an hour talking with people in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Mayor Thomas Suozzi of Glen Cove, a Democrat,
introduced Clinton to a cheering crowd. She said she was deeply
honored to win their support. ``I look forward to forging a strong
partnership as we work together on behalf of New York's working
families,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
