<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VATICAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOICES SUPPORT FOR VATICAN'S STATUS AT UNITED NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story, eliminated earlier, has been restored.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Speaking to a Roman Catholic group, Gov. George
W. Bush on Friday took the side of the Vatican in a battle over its
status at the United Nations, a clash that stems in large part from
its stands in international disputes over family planning and
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, criticized during the Republican primary campaign for
appearing at Bob Jones University, whose leaders have expressed
anti-Catholic views, brought up the effort by a number of groups,
many of them women's and health organizations that disagree with
the church on abortion and family planning, to downgrade the
Vatican's permanent-observer status.
</P>
<P>
   ``In world affairs, the Holy See has long been an influence for
the good, and never more than in the last couple of decades,'' said
Bush, speaking by satellite hookup to the Catholic Press
Association, which was meeting in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some groups have been trying to silence that voice in the
United Nations,'' he said. ``The position of the current
administration is unclear. The position of my administration will
be very clear and firm: America supports permanent-observer status
for the Holy See.''
</P>
<P>
   But aides to both Vice President Al Gore and Richard Holbrooke,
the United States' chief delegate to the United Nations, said Gore
and the Clinton administration backed the Vatican's
permanent-observer status as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is once again making foolish charges,'' said Douglas
Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk to the Catholic Press Association, Bush also spoke
of compassion and values, his remarks sprinkled with quotations
from both Pope John Paul II and Cardinal John O'Connor, the late
archbishop of New York. ``A truly welcoming society must be a
culture of life,'' the governor said, calling for the ``day when
every child, born and unborn, is welcome in life and protected in
law.''
</P>
<P>
   And he drew applause when he said that he supported legislation
to ban a kind of late-term abortion whose opponents refer to it as
``partial birth.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Bush defended Texas' record on
executions, saying that capital punishment, more common here than
in any other state, ``sends a chilling message'' that deters crime.
He said once again that he knew of no innocent person whom the
state had executed.
</P>
<P>
   As for the controversy over the Holy See, the Vatican has had
special observer status at the United Nations since the
organization's birth more than half a century ago. It cannot vote
in the General Assembly, but it takes part as a full member nation
in international conferences, where it has taken strong stands
against contraception and abortion. Groups that have called for the
Vatican to lose its special status argue that it is not a state,
but rather a religious headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said that his comments Friday about the Clinton
administration's position on the matter had been prompted by the
U.S. mission's sponsoring of a news conference in March by
Catholics for Free Choice, a group seeking a review of the
Vatican's status. A nongovernment organization, or NGO, has to be
sponsored by a member nation in order to hold a news conference at
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Glynn, a spokeswoman for Holbrooke, the chief U.S.
delegate, said the mission also granted sponsorship the next day to
another Catholic organization, which took the other side of the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is to sponsor legitimate NGOs if they want to use
the facilities _ nothing more, nothing less,'' Glynn said. ``It is
a nonpartisan policy.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the administration supported the Vatican's status. ``We
work very well with the Holy See on a variety of issues,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Bush who briefed reporters at the governor's campaign
headquarters here said a Bush administration would not have given
Catholics for Free Choice access to the United Nations. But this
aide spoke on the condition that he not be identified. Ari
Fleischer, spokesman for the campaign, was less definitive, saying
that if a Bush administration sponsored such a group, Bush ``would
make clear he didn't share their point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway, speaking for Gore, said of Bush and his visit to Bob
Jones University, ``If he's truly concerned about Catholics, why
did he address a place that calls Catholicism a cult?''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over Bush's campaign stop at Bob Jones, in South
Carolina, was stoked by Sen. John McCain, who was Bush's main rival
for the Republican presidential nomination. Bush later wrote to
O'Connor to say he regretted not having used his appearance at Bob
Jones to speak out against its leaders' views.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
