<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS IS LEADER OF THE PACK AT THE MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Every time Tiger Woods stood over a shot Friday
afternoon, people expected something special to happen. There was a
buzz in the air, like when a great singer steps to the microphone,
or when Mark McGwire steps in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity started on the front nine, when Woods made four
consecutive birdies, beginning on the fifth hole. That birdie
barrage set the tone for the day, with Woods on top of his game, in
calm conditions that were great for scoring, on a perfectly
manicured golf course that was at his mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Woods kept moving up the leader board until there was no one
left to catch. At one point during the second round of the Memorial
Tournament Friday, Woods was at 1-under, while Harrison Frazar was
already in the clubhouse at 9-under. At that point, the question
was whether Woods would catch Frazar this weekend. Instead, Woods
caught Frazar Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a brilliant 9-under 63, and closing with birdies on the
final two holes, Woods took a one-stroke lead over Frazar into
Saturday's third round. Woods was 10-under for the tournament
(134), one stroke ahead of Frazar (135), who shot a 69, and two
strokes ahead of Ernie Els, who shot a sensational 64, but who was
overshadowed by the world's No. 1 player. Olin Browne, Brad Elder,
Steve Lowery and Mike Weir were tied for fourth place at 5-under.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, Frazar and Els will be grouped in the final threesome
Saturday, with tee times moved up in an attempt to avoid the
expected rain. But Friday, it rained birdies at Muirfield Village
Golf Club, as Woods put on a show that displayed all of his
talents. There were many highlights during his round, like a chip
shot from 18 feet to save par at No. 16, and great approaches at
No. 17 and No. 18 that led to easy birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Woods closed with flair, hitting a 6-iron approach shot at No.
18 that almost ended up in the cup. It landed about 20 feet past
the hole, but it slowly sucked back toward the hole, and the
screaming from the gallery grew louder as the ball drew closer to
the cup. It finally stopped a foot away from the hole, denying
Woods an eagle finish. But he was smiling as he walked up the 18th
fairway acknowledging the crowd's cheers, and he tapped in for
birdie to end a memorable day.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods gets the kind of momentum he built Friday, birdies
come in bunches. After his round, which included nine birdies and
no bogeys, the defending Memorial champion talked about his superb
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit a few good shots, you tend to build on your
confidence, and you tend to string them together,'' said Woods, who
is trying to successfully defend a tournament for the first time in
his career. ``I've always been one of those players that can string
shots together. Once I get it going, I tend to keep it going. Maybe
that's because of how emotional I am when play. I get fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods had plenty to get fired up about, because all parts of his
game were working: his driver, irons, short game and putter. He
made a 12-foot putt for birdie at No. 5, then he hit a great wedge
shot at No. 6 to within one foot for an easy tap-in birdie. At the
par-5 No. 7, Woods' second shot went into a front bunker, but he
blasted out to 12 feet, then made another putt for birdie. Then, at
No. 8, Woods hit an 8-iron approach shot to 10 feet, and dropped
another putt for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Woods birdied the par-3 No. 12, hitting a 9-iron tee shot within
8 feet before making the putt. At No. 13, Woods hit another 9-iron
approach shot within 12 feet, before making another putt, pointing
at the hole as the ball disappeared, as the crowd roared. That was
followed by another birdie at the par-5 No. 15, set up by a
terrific chip shot to within a foot on his third shot.
</P>
<P>
   So while Frazar is still in position for his first tour victory,
and Els is hungry for his first triumph since February of last
year, they will both have to catch Woods. And that is something
that is never easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good shape going into the weekend,'' Woods said. ``I
don't know how many holes we are going to get in tomorrow, but it
was a good day to post a good number. We don't know how many holes
this tournament is going to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
