<SLUG> BC-NUN-VATICAN-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN DEFIES VATICAN REQUEST FOR SILENCE ON GAY MINISTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic nun from Maryland, ordered last year by the
Vatican to end a ministry to gay and lesbian Catholics, said Friday
that she would not comply with a new request by Vatican authorities
that she cease speaking and writing about the case.
</P>
<P>
   The nun, Sister Jeannine Gramick, said in a prepared statement
that the Vatican and the leaders of her order had asked her ``to
silence myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After finding my voice to tell my story, I choose not to
collaborate in my own oppression by restricting a basic human
right,'' she wrote. ``To me this is a matter of conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, Gramick and the Rev. Robert Nugent, a
Maryland priest, had collaborated in a national ministry to gay
Catholics, until they were ordered last July to end that work by
the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, the Vatican body
charged with safeguarding church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   In an official directive, which followed years of investigation
by church authorities in the United States and Rome, the
congregation said Gramick and Nugent had allowed ``errors and
ambiguities'' into their discussions of Catholic teaching on
homosexuality. The congregation said the two had not sufficiently
emphasized church teaching that homosexual acts were
``intrinsically disordered.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gramick and Nugent said they would comply with the
directive, they said later that they felt free to speak publicly
about the case itself.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday from its provincial headquarters in
Baltimore, Gramick's order, the School Sisters of Notre Dame, said
another Vatican body, the Congregation for the Institutes of
Consecrated Life and Societies of Apostolic Faith, recently
clarified the original directive. The clarification said Gramick
and Nugent were barred from writing and speaking about
homosexuality and discussing the directive or the procedures that
led to it.
</P>
<P>
   Gramick was told of the limitations Wednesday in a meeting with
the leaders of her order in Rome, who released a statement saying
they were deeply saddened that she would not comply.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent's religious order, the Society of the Divine Savior,
released a statement, saying that he too had gone to Rome this week
and been informed of the Vatican's views on its directive. The
society said Nugent ``has respected in good faith'' the directive
issued last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
