<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE UNDOCKS FROM SPACE STATION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Atlantis astronauts pulled away from the fledgling
international space station Friday, leaving behind a still
uninhabited but much enhanced orbital outpost ready to accept the
long overdue Russian crew module.
</P>
<P>
   The seven shuttle astronauts undocked from the two-room station
shortly after 6 p.m. CDT, as the two spacecraft soared more than
230 miles above Kazakhstan in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   After the separation, commander Jim Halsell and pilot Scott
``Doc'' Horowitz steered Atlantis slowly around the outpost while
their crewmates snapped dozens of photographs of the exterior,
imagery that will serve as documentation for engineers on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   With a final maneuver, Atlantis sped rapidly away from the
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, for leaving the space station in better shape than
when you arrived,'' NASA's mission control told Halsell and his
crew.
</P>
<P>
   During a six-day linkup, the Atlantis crew overhauled a
faltering power system in the station's Russian segment, repaired
the American communications system and latched down a wobbly
external cargo crane installed during a previous shuttle visit. The
astronauts left behind 3,300 pounds of new equipment, along with
food, water, clothes, computers and exercise machines for future
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Using the shuttle's steering thrusters, the astronauts raised
the station's altitude by nearly 30 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The mission prepared the station's first components for the
addition of the 43-foot-long Russian crew module, which will
furnish the station with an independent life support system,
including living quarters for three full-time inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   The crew module is scheduled for launching from Central Asia on
July 12.
</P>
<P>
   With the crew module attached, the station will be ready for its
first full-time inhabitants, American commander Bill Shepherd and
cosmonauts Sergei Krikalev and Yuri Gidzenko. The three men are
preparing to lift off in late October for a stay of several months,
during which they will direct the addition of an American research
module and other components.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's chronic economic problems, and the twin failures last
year of the country's workhorse Proton rocket, have contributed to
a more than two-year delay in the development and launching of the
crew module.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the two Proton losses was traced to the presence of
foreign debris, including a piece of cloth, trapped in rocket
engine turbo machinery fabricated in 1992. The manufacturing period
coincided with political and economic upheaval in Russia following
the breakup of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Modifications will include propulsion system filters and new
pre-launch cleaning and testing procedures to cut the risk of
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Once the crew module has been launched, the two currently
orbiting segments of the station will initiate an automated
rendezvous and linkup.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, the shuttle astronauts spent several hours
carefully retreating from the space station, a procedure that
required them to close and seal a half-dozen large hatches as they
backed out.
</P>
<P>
   NASA scheduled light duty for the astronauts during the
remainder of their 10-day mission.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis is scheduled to touch down at NASA's Kennedy Space
Center in Florida on Monday at 1:20 a.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
