<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHBISHOP URGES CALIF. GOVERNOR TO HALT EXECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Roman Catholic archbishop of Los Angeles has
urged Gov. Gray Davis of California to halt executions and appoint
a bipartisan commission to conduct a ``comprehensive and objective
study'' of a system that he called ``fatally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that an objective study will provide substantial
factual data to support moral and ethical questions raised by the
Catholic bishops of California and the United States regarding the
death penalty,'' stated the archbishop, Cardinal Roger Mahony, in a
letter to Davis that was made public on Thursday, after Mahony
addressed the National Press Club in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who is Catholic, has been an outspoken supporter of the
death penalty. He has drawn increasing criticism from fellow
Democrats for his tough stance on criminal justice in general,
including his refusal of any recommendation by the state parole
board in favor of early prisoner release.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony's letter noted the recent decision of Gov. George Ryan of
Illinois to impose a moratorium on executions there after 13 men
sentenced to death were exonerated by new evidence. It also noted
the New Hampshire Legislature's vote to abandon capital punishment,
though that was later vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has no less an obligation to conduct a thorough
assessment of its system in order to identify the inequities,
weaknesses and biases of the process used to try those charged with
capital crimes and administer the death penalty,'' Mahony stated in
his letter.
</P>
<P>
   California now has 565 inmates on death row, the most of any
state in the nation. In his speech, the cardinal noted that the
long-term goal was ``not simply to make the death penalty free from
bias, inequity or human error,'' but instead to open a ``public
dialogue that ultimately brings a permanent end to state
executions.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Davis in Sacramento, Hilary McLean, said the
governor ``will continue to enforce California's death penalty law
as long as it's on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter Mahony said he shared the concern of protecting
society from violent criminals, but added: ``Our support for
victims and their family members is not diminished by imposing a
moratorium on the death penalty. Instead, a moratorium is
recognition that we cannot heal society as we continue to
administer a system that is fatally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, Catholic bishops in the United States issued a
statement calling for Catholics to work for the end of capital
punishment. The statement came a few months after Pope John Paul
II, during his visit to St. Louis, made a dramatic appeal to Gov.
Mel Carnahan of Missouri to show mercy to Darrell J. Meese, a death
row inmate. A papal encyclical in 1995 said cases in which a
government would need to apply the death penalty were ``practically
nonexistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
