<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ, GALAXY CHALLENGE EARTHQUAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Newly acquired Mexican striker Luis Hernandez
returned from Mexico on Thursday night so he could get in a
training session with the Los Angeles Galaxy on Friday in
preparation for tonight's matchup with San Jose at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez made his Major League Soccer debut last week in a 2-1
victory over defending MLS champion D.C. United in front of 40,303
Rose Bowl fans.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left in the 72nd minute with pain in his left
shoulder, but an MRI showed no damage. He returned to Mexico
following the game to tend to personal business.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez joined the Galaxy for a scrimmage Friday, then was
taken aside by assistant coach Ralph Perez to discuss strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Coach Sigi Schmid) would like for me to make sure what's
being said and what we want from him,'' Perez said. ``I'm
explaining the tactical side so he's in tune to what's going on. He
also needs to know where we want him on corners and restarts,
that's why it's so critical to have him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that he has this training in, it's going to be a much
easier transition for him than it was last week.''
</P>
<P>
   After facing United, Hernandez wanted to know if the Galaxy
would have an easier time against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him there are no easy games because we're somewhat of a
target in this league,'' said Perez. ``I also told him to be aware
of (John) Doyle and (Mauricio) Wright, two big physical defenders
for San Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   After last week's game, Hernandez doesn't need to be reminded of
how physical the MLS can be. His injured shoulder is fine, but the
pace and roughness of MLS is something that takes time to adjust
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little more stronger and faster here than in Mexico,''
said Hernandez. ``It's more body to body. In Mexico, it's more
open, there's more liberty and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hernandez's speed, however, he shouldn't have a hard time
adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm already comfortable, I've done this all my life,'' said
Hernandez. ``With Argentina and Boca Juniors it was the same thing.
You just adapt to a different style of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``An understanding on the field is going to come fast. I have
the type of teammates that accommodate my style of play very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez missed the Galaxy's 2-1 loss in New England on
Wednesday, but he's arriving at a time when the Galaxy needs
scoring from their front line.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Mathis was the last Galaxy forward to get a goal, scoring
on April 15. Mathis is now with New York/New Jersey. Striker Cobi
Jones has not scored since April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now (the forwards) need to score,'' Schmid said. ``They
need to score and that's something that's important. We've talked
about it and there will be some pressure on them to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
