<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-INTERNET-CAFE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH ENTREPRENEUR PLANS MAMMOTH INTERNET CAFE IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT33  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It is an unlikely export from here, but come this fall,
a Britain-based entrepreneur will be taking his successful chain of
Internet cafes across the Atlantic to Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The company, called EasyEverything, has created the equivalent
of cybercafes on steroids _ the one being planned for Times Square
will have 650 to 1,000 Internet terminals with high-resolution,
flat-panel screens.
</P>
<P>
   Stelios Haji-Ioannou, the founder of EasyEverything and the
5-year-old low-cost European airline, EasyJet, signed a lease this
week for a 13,300-square-foot site at 8 Times Square on 42nd Street
between Seventh and Eighth Avenues. EasyEverything is part of the
same development where the new Hilton Hotel is being completed,
along with another British export, Madame Tussaud's, the wax
museum.
</P>
<P>
   If EasyEverything has even a smidgen of the success it has had
here, queues _ er, lines _ will begin to form around the
super-cybercafe before it even opens. The first EasyEverything,
which opened June 21, 1999, near Victoria Station here with 400
computer terminals, was greeted by so many Internet surfers on its
first day that the staff handed out coffee to the hordes that
gathered offline to keep them from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Internet cafes have never really taken off in the United States
the way they have here and throughout other parts of Europe, so it
may be somewhat of a surprise if Haji-Ioannou succeeds. Even he
concedes it may be a struggle, though one he expects to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have said that I'll never make it work in New
York,'' he said. ``But they said that about London, too. Have you
ever been to EasyEverything in London at 2 a.m.? It's packed.''
</P>
<P>
   The cafes themselves look futuristic, like a set from ``Star
Trek,'' with hundreds of people at rows of computers. They sell
coffee, snacks and sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons EasyEverything, which is open 24 hours per
day, may have succeeded in London are that most people here do not
own personal computers and that the telephone rates for dial-up
modem access to the Internet is significantly higher than in the
United States. Because local telephone calls are billed by the
minute here _ not a flat rate like American telephone companies
offer _ Internet users must pay the telephone company and the
Internet access providers, like America Online, every time they log
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``By itself, it is deadly dull for a U.S. audience,'' said Bruce
Kasrel, a senior analyst at Forrester Research, which analyzes
e-commerce. ``People already have Internet access at the office and
at home.'' He cited empty Internet access terminals at airports as
an example of a similar scheme that had not worked.
</P>
<P>
   One reason New Yorkers might log on is simply the sense of
privacy. ``I know a lot of people come in to go online to search
for jobs so their employer doesn't know,'' said Haji-Ioannou. He
also expects tourists to pop in to check their e-mail. ``Mobile
Internet access doesn't work and isn't cheap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Haji-Ioannou has always prided himself on offering customers
things cheap. His low-cost airline EasyJet, which has many of the
qualities of Southwest Airlines, offers tickets sometimes for a
third of the cost of the same flights on British Airways. At
EasyEverything, the pricing scheme is truly laissez-faire. The
price fluctuates depending on how many people are using the
computers, but the price usually hovers around $1.50 for an hour of
surfing. ``We'll charge whatever it takes'' to fill the (cafe),''
Haji-Ioannou said.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Square cafe is set to open in September or early
October.
</P>
<P>
   Besides London, where there are now six super-cybercafes with a
total of 2,800 terminals, Haji-Ioannou also opened one in Edinburgh
last week, with others on the way in Amsterdam and Rotterdam in the
Netherlands and in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kasrel is not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason Regis Philbin hosts `Who Wants to be a
Millionaire' in the States,'' he said, referring to the British
program that was successfully exported. ``We have different
tastes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
