<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, MAY 27
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NJ-FLORIO-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 23,
about Jim Florio's record as governor of New Jersey referred
incorrectly to the rarity of a defeat like the one he suffered in
1993. Florio was the second governor in the state's modern history,
not the first, to lose a bid for a second term. Gov. William T.
Cahill lost the 1973 Republican primary to Representative Charles
W. Sandman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HMO-LAWSUIT-NYT (moved on Thursday, May 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, May 25,
about a lawsuit by the California Medical Association accusing
three insurance companies of violating federal laws on racketeering
referred incorrectly in some copies to the companies' market share
among Californians. It is 4 in 10 members of managed care plans in
the state _ not 1 in 6 people who carry health insurance of any
kind.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TAX-REFORMS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 24,
about corporate tax shelter abuses referred imprecisely to the
source of an estimate cited by Treasury Secretary Lawrence H.
Summers for the shelters' cost to the government. The figure, $10
billion, came from a study by a Stanford University professor;
Treasury Department tax analysts have not issued an estimate.
</P>
<P>
   BC-EURO-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 3,
about the decline in the value of the euro omitted the source of
remarks made by Ernst Welteke, president of Germany's central bank,
and reported by Bloomberg News. Welteke, who doubted that
intervention to prop up the currency would be successful, was
interviewed by Market News International.
</P>
</TEXT>
