<SLUG> BC-FLA-TEACHER-SLAIN-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVENTH-GRADE BOY HELD IN KILLING OF TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ A seventh-grader shot and killed a teacher on
Friday on the last day of school, after he had been sent home for
throwing water balloons in class, the police in this Palm Beach
County community said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy returned at the close of the last period of the school
year and shot the teacher, Barry Grunow, once in the head with a
small .25-caliber handgun, the authorities reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shot Mr. Grunow! He shot Mr. Grunow!'' some children cried
after the shot shattered the midafternoon buzz of children
preparing to depart for summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The body of the popular 35-year-old language arts teacher and
basketball coach at Lake Worth Middle School was found in a puddle
of blood in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene all too commonplace on American school grounds,
wailing children were locked in classrooms by frightened teachers,
local police rushed to the school in well-rehearsed deployments to
cope with school violence, and panic-stricken parents gathered at a
school entrance to await news about their own children.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, identified as 13-year old Nathaniel Brazill,
flagged down an officer headed to the scene and surrendered minutes
after the shooting about one-quarter mile north of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief William Smith said the boy was carrying a
.25-caliber Raven semiautomatic pistol with three bullets in it. A
single spent cartridge was recovered at the shooting scene.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the boy had taken the pistol a week ago from a
dresser drawer in the home of his grandfather, who owned it.
</P>
<P>
   The chief called the gun a ``typical Saturday night special.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the boy would be sent to a juvenile center for
assessment and brought before a circuit court judge for a hearing
in the morning. The Palm Beach County state attorney's office will
determine what charges will be filed and whether the boy will be
charged as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   His grandmother, Eberlena Josey, later said Nathaniel had
returned from school early and ``seemed upset,'' but gave no
indication of what his problem or plans were. Josey accompanied her
daughter, the boy's mother, to police headquarters for questioning.
She said her daughter was recovering from recent cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the best boy. the grandmother said. He was
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel earned A's and B's and had perfect attendance, said
Nat Harrington, a spokesman for the school board.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no problems of any kind, prior to this,'' Harrington
said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Nathaniel was not in Grunow's classroom when the
balloon incident took place. He was sent home by an assistant
principal.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the boy rode his bicycle home, got the pistol
and then returned to school. He went to Grunow's class, where he
asked to see two students. Grunow stepped into the hall and would
not let him enter.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting happened quickly afterward, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not one shred of evidence,'' the chief said, ``that
he planned to do this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Children who witnessed the shooting said the boy returned to the
school shortly after 3 p.m., as classes were about to be dismissed
for the school year.
</P>
<P>
   They said he produced a handgun as he, Grunow and another
teacher faced one another in a hall outside a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nat, quit playing _ it's not funny anymore,'' one of the
children recalled the other teacher saying. ``Get away from me or
I'll shoot you, too,'' another pupil quoted the boy as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest nightmare any school system could possibly
face,'' said Ben Marlin, superintendent of Palm Beach County
schools. He rebuffed reporters' questions at a late afternoon news
conference on whether stepped-up security measures would be
introduced in county schools because of Friday's shooting. ``We
already have good school security,'' said Marlin, who was attending
another school's graduation when he was notified of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything more we can do. We do as much as we
think we can do, probably even more,'' Marlin said. ``Unfortunately
we can't control society's problems,'' he continued, pausing for a
moment before adding: ``Perhaps one thing we can do is turn off the
TV, when all we do is see violence and hear violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Legislature, in the wake of numerous shootings in
U.S. schools in recent years, recently passed legislation requiring
schools in the state to prepare ``school disaster'' response plans.
</P>
<P>
   The school system said counselors would be available this
weekend to help students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends linked arms as they walked slowly, heads
bowed and sobs heaving their shoulders, into the house where Grunow
had lived with his wife, 5-year-old son and newborn baby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
