<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH LIMITS ARM TALK
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Knoblauch said Friday night that he would
continue to speak candidly about his throwing problems. But the
second baseman added he was not going to seek out a sports
psychologist to help address the problem unless the New York
Yankees find one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait for the Yankees to come to me,'' he said.
``I'm not going to look for anyone. If they're going to recommend
someone, we'll see how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Yankees manager Joe Torre was asked about Knoblauch's
situation, he said: ``We'll explore it, for sure, if that's what he
wants to do. That's not all that easy. It has to be someone you're
comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who was removed from Friday night's starting lineup
because of a strained left forearm, wants to make sure that any
psychologist he sees would deal only with the throwing woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be someone who's just sports,'' he said. ``It's
got to be a person who can focus on that and that alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
