<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-AIR-POLLUTION-NYT &LR;      05-26 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIR-POLLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE GIVES NEW YORK 2 YEARS TO ISSUE AIR POLLUTION PERMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a harsh rebuke to the Pataki administration, a
state judge ruled Friday that the state had ``failed to come
anywhere close'' to complying with laws requiring that it catalog
clean air requirements and violations for hundreds of major
polluters.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Acting Justice Dan Lamont of the State Supreme Court
in Albany, found that the Department of Environmental Conservation
had dragged its feet in complying with the laws. He ordered the
department to greatly accelerate the pace of its work and complete
it within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The department and Gov. George Pataki's office said this
afternoon that they had just received word of the ruling and had no
immediate comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Congress amended the Clean Air Act to require that each
state determine which sites came under the act, based on their
emissions of any one of a long list of pollutants. The states were
then to issue a Clean Air Act permit for each site, listing the
emissions rules to which it was subject. The states were also
required to keep data on compliance with the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 law also allowed for ``citizen suits,'' so that anyone
could sue polluters for Clean Air Act violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many of these facilities, it has been just about
impossible to find out whether they were under any kind of air
quality requirements, and if they were, whether they were in
compliance,'' said Keri Powell, an environmental lawyer with the
New York Public Interest Research Group. ``This law was supposed to
make it easy for anyone to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   A state law for carrying out the federal requirements took
effect in December 1996 and gave the Department of Environmental
Conservation three years to issue the permits. The department has
listed more than 500 polluters; most are factories and power
plants, but they also include gasoline storage sites, waste
incinerators and even big commercial buildings, like hospitals,
that have generators or incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   By last December, when the three-year period was up, the
department had issued permits to just 21 percent of the sites, a
figure that has risen to 29 percent. When the three-year clock ran
out, the New York Public Interest Research Group sued the state to
force compliance with the law.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the state environmental agency argued that the
three-year limit was not an absolute requirement and that it was
free to use its resources in better ways.
</P>
<P>
   Lamont strongly disagreed. The department, he wrote, ``has
failed to come anywhere close to completing the permitting schedule
established by the statute and its own regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The state had asked the court to give it four years to issue the
remaining permits, about 400 of them. Even then, the state
maintained, it was required only to issue preliminary permits. The
judge, instead, accepted the research group's proposal for a
two-year timetable for issuing final permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge win,'' Powell said. ``It means the law will
finally be put to work. People will finally know the status of
polluters and will have the information they need to bring citizen
suits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000526.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      05-26 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SEEKS AN APOLOGY FOR HECKLING 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Friday that Hillary
Rodham Clinton and the state's Democratic leadership should
apologize for the reported harassment of a police honor guard at
the May 16 State Democratic Convention in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   In the incident, hecklers are said to have spit on the officers,
who were from the Albany Police Department, and derided them as
``members of the Giuliani Third Reich.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the Albany police should vigorously investigate
the incident, and those who instigated it should be charged with
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The calling of names is reprehensible, and there should be an
apology by the candidate,'' Giuliani said. ``The actual spitting
should result in an arrest. I mean, spitting is an assault.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident was reported in a May 19 editorial in the New York
Post.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's call for action was dismissed Friday by officials of
the state Democratic Committee and Albany's City Hall, a
traditional bastion of Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mayor Giuliani wants a firing squad, he isn't going to get
it,'' said John C. Nielsen, the Albany police chief. ``No apologies
are necessary'' from the state Democratic leadership, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said the convention incident had led to an
exchange that smoothed things over, at least within their own
party. A spokeswoman for Clinton, Karen Dunn, said the first lady
had called Mayor Gerald Jennings of Albany immediately after the
New York Post editorial appeared, and had said that she was
``appalled by what was reported.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, the chairwoman of the state Democratic Committee,
wrote the same day to Nielsen, apologizing for what she called
``despicable actions'' by a small group at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, Nielsen said that Giuliani's pique over the
incident would have little impact in Albany. ``We did ask the local
media if they had any video of what happened,'' he said, ``but we
figured if they had it, they would have used it.'' He said the
Albany police had ``no plans to take this further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
