<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH BYPASSES TEXAS CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush will skip the Texas Republican Party
convention in Houston next month. The decision, reported in
Friday's Houston Chronicle, has prompted speculation that the
decision grew out of skirmishes with conservative elements of the
party, but campaign aides insisted otherwise. ``The governor will
be campaigning in Florida and Kentucky at that time,'' said Ray
Sullivan, a campaign spokesman in Austin. ``But Laura Bush is
planning to address the convention as his representative.''
Sullivan denied that there were any lingering problems with
anti-abortion elements of the party which, during the 1996 Texas
convention, stripped Bush of a governor's traditional role as
leader of the state delegation to the national convention. ``This
decision is based solely upon the fact that time is precious on the
campaign trail,'' Sullivan said. ``Texas is solid Bush country, and
we're going to spend that time letting the rest of the country get
to know Governor Bush as well as Texans do.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN AGAINST WASHINGTON STATE'S GORTON
</P>
<P>
   Several American Indian groups said they have planned a series
of ads criticizing Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who is up for
re-election, The Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported. Gorton has
long feuded with some tribes over fishing rights and various
sovereignty issues. The Indian groups said they have raised more
than $125,000 so far, and expect to spend $1 million or more, with
some of the money coming from Indian gambling businesses in other
states. Ron Allen, chairman of a tribe on Washington's Olympic
peninsula, called Gorton ``the most vociferous opponent of tribal
sovereignty that Congress has seen in 40 years,'' and said the
advertisements would focus on environmental and health issues.
Gorton told The Post-Intelligencer: ``They have a total right to do
what they want in the political world. I have a very good record on
supporting the appropriate ambitions of Indian peoples, but I will
continue to fiercely protect the rights of their non-Indian
neighbors. If they don't like that, they have every right to try to
beat me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: no public events
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: West Point, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
