<HEADER>
A7191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FOOD-GUIDELINES-BOS &LR;      05-26 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GUIDELINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DIET RECOMMENDATIONS REFLECT INDUSTRY COMPROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government's new dietary guidelines that President
Clinton will unveil Saturday contain this seemingly innocuous piece
of advice: ``Choose beverages and foods to moderate your intake of
sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the word ``moderate,'' however, raged a three-year battle
that pitted the country's top nutritionists against massive
corporations and beet and sugarcane farmers. Eventually, some of
the most powerful voices in the US Senate intervened on behalf of
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is a compromise as messy as any bill that grinds
through Capitol Hill. In the end, the scientists were forced to
give ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision they made is sensible. We're delighted they
didn't go along with the (scientists') original recommendation,''
said Richard Keelor, president and chief executive officer of the
Sugar Association, which represents the industry and lobbied
heavily during the process.
</P>
<P>
   The prize is more than just a few words in a government slogan.
The dietary guidelines regulate what the nation's largest food
purchaser, the federal government, can buy for the 53 million
mouths it feeds daily in the military, prisons, schools and
numerous other programs. Billions of dollars can move with the
shift of a word.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the dietary guideline on sugar offers a glimpse
into the complex world of food politics.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines, which serve as the government's definitive
statement on food, contain more revisions than ever, though most
were uncontroversial. According to a copy obtained by the Globe,
the major changes are:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The 1995 guidelines suggested eating a variety of foods.
The new ones say, let the food pyramid guide your choices.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The new guidelines recommend eating a more plant-based
diet. The old guidelines were silent on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The wording of the fat guideline was changed to emphasize
avoiding saturated fats, rather than all fats.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The guidelines suggest striving for a ``healthy weight,''
rather than simply maintaining or improving weight.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)A new guideline recommends 30 minutes of moderate exercise
a day.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Another guideline addresses clean handling and preparing
of food to avoid foodborne illness.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Fruits and vegetables now have their own place in the
guidelines. Before, they were coupled with grains.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The alcohol guideline is more stringent, eliminating
language on the pleasure of alcohol and detailing its negative
effects, while still approving a glass a day for adults.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of nutritionists that studied the issue for three
years urged the following recommendation: ``Choose beverages and
foods that limit your intake of sugars.'' They felt the 1995
guideline, ``Choose a diet moderate in sugar,'' was too vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does moderate mean? It's fuzzy. `Limit your intake' is
much clearer because it suggests a change in behavior,'' said Margo
Wootan, director of nutrition policy for the Center for Science in
the Public Interest, a Washington-based consumer advocacy group
that has followed the process from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the US Department of Agriculture convened a committee
of 11 of the country's most respected nutritionists who were
referred to the committee by their peers. Their mission was a
thorough review of the scientific literature pertaining to the
guidelines, a task undertaken every five years.
</P>
<P>
   The panel included three scientists from Tufts University and
one from Harvard University. Panel member Alice Lichtenstein, a
senior scientist in Tufts School of Nutrition Science and Policy,
said she hadn't given the guidelines much thought in the past but,
once serving on the committee, said she found the process to be
honest and free from conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process itself was really impressive. We were given a very
clear mandate at the beginning to take a fresh look at the
guidelines,'' she said. ``I felt no pressure during the entire
process.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some who attended public sessions while the
guidelines were being drawn up in Washington, sugar interests were
the strongest presence.
</P>
<P>
   But Keelor, of the Sugar Association, said, ``when we saw the
appointments on this committee, we became very concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the scientists on the committee were renowned for their
work on the connection between obesity and sugar _ a position the
sugar interests disputed in public and written testimony with their
own experts.
</P>
<P>
   Decreasing obesity rates is one of the dietary guidelines' prime
goals. Keelor argued for keeping the 1995 guideline, asserting that
the word ``limit,'' favored by the scientists' committee, would
signal to the public to heavily reduce sugar consumption, perhaps
even eliminate it. ``Moderate'' was more acceptable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other sugar interests joined in, the most prominent being the
International Food Information Council and National Food Processors
Association. At one public meeting, they issued a vague threat to
punish the USDA if they went along with the scientists. Their
stated weapon was Public Act 101-445, which established the
guidelines and requires a ``preponderance'' of medical data to
support any changes in them _ an argument that would later be made
by some powerful advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists' committee plowed along. In January, the panel
issued its recommendation: ``Choose beverages and foods that limit
your intake of sugars.'' That left it in the hands of USDA
Secretary Dan Glickman and US Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The sugar interests were outraged. They represent almost 400,000
people, many of them farmers concentrated in northern states like
Michigan, the Dakotas, Idaho and Wyoming, where beets thrive, as
well as Louisiana and Florida, home of sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, USDA Secretary Dan Glickman received a letter signed
by 30 senators, 22 Republicans and eight Democrats, mostly from
sugar farming states. They included several members of the Senate
committee that sets USDA's budget as well as Majority Leader Trent
Lott (R-Miss.).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that these recommendations may not meet the
legal requirement of Public Law 101-445. . .we hope you will review
this matter and find it appropriate with government guidelines to
withhold any new recommendations until and unless they are fully
supported by sound science,' the letter warned.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the word ``limit'' was changed to
``moderate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
