u p BC-NJ-SENATE-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      05-26 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 GOP HOPEFULS FOR SENATE IN N.J. ATTACK DEMOCRATS, NOT ONE
ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In the last televised debate of the New Jersey
primary for U.S. Senate, the four Republican candidates cordially
discussed their differences Friday on gun control, school vouchers
and foreign affairs, saving their criticism for their two
Democratic opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the changing dynamics of the race, the Democrat
who received the most condemnation was Jon Corzine, the former Wall
Street executive whose $30 million in campaign spending has
shattered records for a Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Republicans had aimed almost exclusively at
Corzine's Democratic opponent, Jim Florio. Most recent polls now
show Corzine leading the Democratic race, however, and with
Corzine's record-breaking spending on the front pages of many New
Jersey newspapers, the Republicans have apparently changed targets.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Republican contenders, James Treffinger, the Essex
County executive, declared in Friday's debate that Corzine's
spending was ``obscene'' and that it ``perverts the process'' of
electoral politics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Franks ridiculed Corzine's calls for expansive new
social programs. He said the programs were out of touch with New
Jerseyans because they would be so expensive as to require a tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply can't afford it,'' Franks said. ``We're all not as
wealthy as Jon Corzine.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would support tighter campaign spending laws,
including a limit on the total amount a candidate could spend,
William Gormley, a Republican state senator from Atlantic County,
predicted that Corzine's campaign would disgust the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet the people of New Jersey are going to put a limit on
that personal fortune,'' Gormley said. ``He believes in spending
money and he believes in big government and the Republicans believe
in the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Murray Sabrin, the former Libertarian who is now running
for the Republican nomination, did not object to Corzine's campaign
spending. Sabrin said he also opposed any limits on campaign
contributions because he considers such restrictions an
infringement on the freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was sponsored by the League of Women Voters and is
scheduled to be broadcast at 3 p.m. Saturday and 10 a.m. Sunday on
WPVI in Philadelphia and WABC in New York. The league had also
invited the Democratic candidates to hold a separate debate to be
televised on network television, and Florio accepted. But Corzine
declined, so that debate was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   While Gormley and Franks are the two best-known candidates, the
only polls available show that at least 40 percent of likely
Republican primary voters are undecided. The three Republican
debates have allowed each candidate to sharpen his image with the
public, but none of the contenders claims to have scored any major
victories in the encounters.
</P>
<P>
   The format of Friday's debate consisted of a panel of
journalists who asked questions of each candidate. But candidates
were not allowed to rebut one another or ask one another questions,
so the tone of the discourse was tame, almost to the point of
courtliness.
</P>
<P>
   All four candidates said they supported the death penalty, a
plan to invest some Social Security funds in the stock market, and
expanded trade relations with China. Franks, Gormley and Treffinger
also said that Gov. Christie Whitman, who has not endorsed a
primary candidate, deserved praise for her efforts to stop racial
profiling by the New Jersey State Police. Sabrin tried to turn that
question into a denunciation of affirmative action, which he called
``the ultimate form of racial profiling.'' He urged his colleagues
to state their position on the policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue was not raised again.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, the only Republican contender who has served in
Washington, often cited his congressional experience.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about taxes, he took credit for helping to write the
balanced budget and for forcing President Clinton ``kicking and
screaming down the path to fiscal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, who appeared the most relaxed of all the candidates,
continued to emphasize his strong support of gun control
legislation, an unusual tactic in a Republican primary. Gormley
also sought to stress his opposition to the fiscal policies Florio
carried out as governor because Franks' campaign literature has
accused him of being a ``Florio Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger, a former Democrat, portrayed himself as the
candidate best able to broaden the Republican Party's appeal.
Citing his record at trimming Essex County's budget and his support
of vouchers for private schools, Treffinger said he could help
Republicans win back the working-class voters who now identify with
Democrats. ``We Republicans represent the working families,''
Treffinger said, ''and more importantly, we represent the forgotten
Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
