New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 05/26/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   EDS, please note the following correction:
</P>
<P>
   The congressman in the center of the following photograph was
originally misidentified. He was Rep. David Dreier, not Rep. Bill
Archer.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- May 24, 2000 -- SUB-CHINA-TRADE --
Celebrating victory on China's trading rights Wednesday, Rep. J.
Dennis Hastert, the House speaker, reads from a fortune cookie
given to him by Rep. Jim Kolbe, left. Rep. David Dreier is at
center. In a stunning triumph for the Clinton administration and
corporate America, the House on Wednesday swept aside economic
restrictions on China that were part of anti-Communist policy for
over a quarter century. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- NY-STEINBERG -- Two bidders
at the Sotheby's auction for Saul P. and Gayfryd Steinberg on
Friday sat on one of the items for bid, a contemporary salmon suede
sofa, which sold for $3,300. The auction raised $12.5 million. (Don
Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- May 26, 2000 -- OBIT-AREFIN-B&AMP;W -- Tony
Arefin, a self-taught graphic designer and art director of
periodicals, art catalogs and advertising who was responsible for
influential ad designs like the handwritten look of the current IBM
``magic box'' campaign, died May 19 at St. Vincent's Hospital in
Manhattan. The cause was a heart attack, his wife, Amanda, said.
Arefin was 38. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
ABOUT-CARS-TAHOE -- The full-sized sport utility market just keeps
growing. The interiors of the Chevrolet Tahoe (its exterior is
shown, above) and the GMC Yukon have both grown more comfortable.
Tahoe's cargo hold (below), set for a family trip. (Leonard M.
Apcar/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
CARSMART-TBIRD-2 -- The 2002 T-Bird (top), which goes into
production early next year, will pick up where the 1955 (below) -57
left off. Ford says the next-generation T-Bird is a modern
interpretation of the original, complete with turquoise emblems and
porthole windows in the removable hardtop. (Ford Motor Co./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) DEARBORN, Mich. -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- CARSMART-TBIRD-1 -- The 2002 T-Bird, which goes into production
early next year, will pick up where the 1955-57 left off. William
C. Ford Jr., chairman, and Jacques A. Nasser, chief executive,
raise the roof on a '56 Ford T-Bird to be given away. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) SEATTLE -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
POSTCOLONIAL-STUDIES -- Many professors and students see a link
between the latest generation of activists and the overtly
political courses that have been added to college curriculums in
recent years. Postcolonial studies - an attempt to look at the
legacy left by the major powers on the developing world - seem to
be a frequent reference point. Students demonstrated against the
World Trade Organization during a conference last year in Seattle.
(Scott Eklund/Seattle Post-Intelligencer)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) MOSCOW -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
PEN-RUSSIA --Even though Russia is no longer in fashion among
Western intellectual circles, the Russian PEN club, whose members
have also vigorously protested the war in Chechnya, decided to go
ahead with the annual International PEN Congress - a gathering of
authors from around the world which ends here Sunday. ``This is not
a fascist country,'' said Andrei Bitov, a Russian writer and
president of the PEN center. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- May 26, 2000 -- OBIT-KETY-B&AMP;W -- Dr. Seymour
S. Kety, a major figure in the field of biological psychiatry whose
contributions revolutionized the study of schizophrenia and other
major mental illnesses and yielded novel methods for studying the
human brain at work, died Thursday at his home in Westwood, Mass.
He was 84. Kety diagrammed a nerve synapse in 1997. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- May 26, 2000 -- DRUGS-MEDICARE -- Rep.
Bill Thomas, R-Calif., right, and Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.,
announcing Friday their plan to collaborate on a bipartisan effort
to add prescription drug benefits to Medicare this year. The effort
alters the politics of the issue in this election year, at least
marginally increasing the chances that Congress can break the
deadlock on Medicare coverage of prescription drugs. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) RICHMOND, Va. -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- ASSISTED-LIVING-2 -- The assisted-living industry was supposed
to be mounting record profits this year while expanding rapidly and
reaching new stock market peaks. Though that is what analysts were
predicting three years ago, it has ot exactly worked out that way.
Residents at Sunrise Assisted Living homes can work on motor skills
(like Lena Clore, 89, left), or take it easy (like Otway and
Virginia Chalkley, right, in their private suite). (Dean
Hoffmeyer/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) RICHMOND, Va. -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- ASSISTED-LIVING-1 -- The assisted-living industry was supposed
to be mounting record profits this year while expanding rapidly and
reaching new stock market peaks. Though that is what analysts were
predicting three years ago, it has not exactly worked out that way.
Residents at Sunrise Assisted Living homes can relax in a
comfortable setting (shown) or chose from a variety of activities.
(Dean Hoffmeyer/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NORTHFIELD, Ill. -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
28 -- PROFILE-HOLDEN -- Betsy Holden, who rose through the ranks of
Kraft Foods by delivering strong results in its pizza and cheese
divisions, has realized her ambition of running a business as the
chief executive officer. ``When I was in college, I said I really
want to run a business and I want to be CEO,'' said Holden, 44, who
now heads the nation's largest food packager. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- GRAHAM-DANCE-2 -- Due to
financial problems, the Martha Graham Dance Company is suspending
activity indefinitely. The decision to suspend operations in the
face of dire financial problems, which also affects the school and
the company's junior troupe, was made in a board meeting on
Thursday afternoon. Members of the Martha Graham Dance Company
performing ``Maple Leaf Rag'' at The Joyce Theater last year. (Sara
Krulwih/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- GRAHAM-DANCE-B&AMP;W -- Due to
financial problems, the Martha Graham Dance Company is suspending
activity indefinitely. The decision to suspend operations in the
face of dire financial problems, which also affects the school and
the company's junior troupe, was made in a board meeting on
Thursday afternoon. Graham and her dance group in her studio in
1965. (Sam Falk/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WICHITA, Kansas -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- KIDS-MUSEUMS-3-COX -- A wave of interest in informal family
learning has doubled the number of U.S. children's museums in the
last decade. A young child poked his head through a sunflower
sculpture in the ``Tots' Spot'' area of the $62 million Exploration
Place, which is opening in stages between April and July. (Gavin
Peters/The Exploration Place)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WICHITA, Kansas -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- KIDS-MUSEUMS-2-COX -- A wave of interest in informal family
learning has doubled the number of U.S. children's museums in the
last decade. The newest such effort, the $62 million Exploration
Place, is opening in stages between April and July. Its ``Kids
Explore'' area offers a feast of sights and sounds for the little
ones. (Gavin Peters/The Exploration Place)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WICHITA, Kansas -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- KIDS-MUSEUMS-1-COX -- A wave of interest in informal family
learning has doubled the number of U.S. children's museums in the
last decade. The newest such effort, the Exploration Place, is
opening in stages between April and July. The $62 million science
center sits on a 20-acre tract along the Arkansas River in downtown
Wichita. (Gavin Peters/The Exploration Place)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) GJILANI, Yugoslavia -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 28 -- KOSOVO-TROOPS-2-COX -- Cluster bombs that dropped during
NATO air strikes last year but did not explode pose a hazard to
Kosovo's citizens. U.S. peacekeepers examined what Albanian
villagers in Gjilani believed was an unexploded ordinance found
near a playground in eastern Kosovo. (Margaret Coker/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) GJILANI, Yugoslavia -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 28 -- KOSOVO-TROOPS-1-COX -- U.S. peacekeepers on patrol in a
traditionally Serbian neighborhood in Gjilani, which still has a
mixed Serb/Albanian population. Grafitti on the wall of a house
identifies the inhabitants as Albanian - a signal to protect the
family from extremist Albanian gangs causing trouble for Serbs in
the neighborhood. (Margaret Coker/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ATLANTA -- May 26, 2000 -- KNITTING-COX -- Knitting has
become a hot hobby amongst young people. Four million people,
mostly women in their 20s and 30s, took up knitting last year
alone, estimates the Craft Yarn Council of America. Keira Boddie,
25, who recently learned to work the knitting needles, finished up
a sock. (Sunny Sung/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CARLSBAD, Calif. -- May 26, 2000 -- FUEL-CELLS -- Jeff
Colborn, head of Metallic Power, Inc., on a cart powered by a fuel
pack produced by his company. Although they are similar in many
ways to batteries, fuel cells can be quickly regenerated by pumping
in new chemical fuel. And unlike fusion, they are teetering on the
edge of becoming big business. (Edward Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- NY-WENDYS-MURDERS-2 -- Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani stands opposite photos of John Taylor as he
announces during a news conference Friday that Taylor is a suspect
in the murders at a Wendys restaurant. At center is First Deputy
Police Commissioner Patrick Kelleher. (Ruby Washington'/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- NY-WENDYS-MURDERS -- Police
officials on Friday asked for the public's help in locating a
former employee of the Wendy's restaurant in Queens where five
people were methodically shot to death during a robbery Wednesday
night. Mourners outside the restaurant paid their respects for the
victims, Friday. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 26, 2000 -- FOOD-STEAK-COX -- But
Memorial Day weekend is the official coronation of the grilling
season, so it's time for the king of the grate - the steak. This
grilled sirloin steak, served with a side of grilled yellow and red
peppers, can be found in Tom Perini's book, ``Texas Cowboy
Cooking.'' (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- SEALY-FUNERAL -- Kevin
Garnett, of the Minnesota Timberwolves, left, grabs Tim Hardaway,
with the Miami Heat, as they carry the coffin containing the
remains of Garnett's teammate, Malik Sealy, out of Riverside Church
on Friday following funeral services. Sealy was returning from a
birthday celebration for Garnett last Saturday when he was killed
in a head-on car crash. (Barbara Alper/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DOVER, N.H. -- May 26, 2000 -- SURGERY-DEVICE-BOS -- When
surgeons need to remove cancerous tissue from a lung and then seal
it, or stop the bleeding from a diseased liver, the process often
requires staples, clips, and even burning the edges of some organs
to stop blood flow. All of these proceedures can have adverse
effects. Mike McClurken seals a pig's lung using a new surgical
device produced by TissueLink which uses significantly less heat.
(Jim Davis/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- May 26, 2000 -- TRIAL-LAWYERS-POLITICS --
In a few weeks, Fred Baron will be the new president of the
powerful Association of Trial Lawyers of America (ATLA), who has
vowed to do everything to defeat George W. Bush, who has made tort
reform a centerpiece of his campaign. But while Baron has given Al
Gore a great fundraising advantage, he has also given the
Republicans a ready target in their campaign to prove that greedy
trial lawyers are too cozy with Gore. Baron outside ATLA
headquarters in Georgetown. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
JUDITH-KRANTZ-SHOP -- Judith Krantz may live in Bel Air, but she's
a New York girl by birth and by temperament. The author of ``Sex
and Shopping,'' didn't bite her tongue during a recent trip to Saks
on Fifth Avenue. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
NITEOUT-CARUSO -- Michael Caruso, previously head of Details
Magazine, with Donald Trump at the Central Park boathouse during a
party for his new venture, Maximum Golf. After leaving Details,
Conde Nast pulled the plug on the magazine, and Caruso, 38, has
convinced Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation to finance his quirky
idea for his gonzo golf book. (Miles Ladin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 26, 2000 -- SONTAG-COMPARE -- In response
to questions about attributions in her new book ``In America,'' a
novel about Helena Modjeska, a 19th century diva of the American
stage, Susan Sontag says she considers her book ``a work of art''
that belongs to a new genre that doesn't require the footnotes of
traditional histories. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 26, 2000 -- BKW-ACKERMAN -- The Women's
National Basketball Association, which expands to 16 teams this
year, begins its fourth season Monday in Houston. Val Ackerman,
president and founder of the WNBA, in her office earlier this week.
(Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EASTCHESTER, N.Y. -- May 26, 2000 -- SCI-DIABETES -- In
an important advance against diabetes, researchers in Canada are
reporting that transplants of insulin-producing cells have enabled
eight patients with the most severe form of the disease to stop
taking insulin injections. The patients, who had Type 1 diabetes,
in which the body produces little or no insulin of its own, no
longer have any symptoms of the disease. Barbara Sesti with her
two-year-old son, Peter, who has juvenile diabetes, testing his
glucose levels in 1998. (Richard Harbus/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) METULLA, Israel -- May 26, 2000 -- ISRAEL-LEBANON-BORDER
-- Ron Eisenberg, from Tel Aviv, talks with supporters of the
Muslim group Hezbollah on the other side of the fence which
deliniates the Israeli-Lebanese border. After 18 years of
occupation, Israeli forces pulled out of southern Lebanon on
Wednesday. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
