<P>
   (NYT15) GJILANI, Yugoslavia -- May 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 28 -- KOSOVO-TROOPS-1-COX -- U.S. peacekeepers on patrol in a
traditionally Serbian neighborhood in Gjilani, which still has a
mixed Serb/Albanian population. Grafitti on the wall of a house
identifies the inhabitants as Albanian - a signal to protect the
family from extremist Albanian gangs causing trouble for Serbs in
the neighborhood. (Margaret Coker/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ATLANTA -- May 26, 2000 -- KNITTING-COX -- Knitting has
become a hot hobby amongst young people. Four million people,
mostly women in their 20s and 30s, took up knitting last year
alone, estimates the Craft Yarn Council of America. Keira Boddie,
25, who recently learned to work the knitting needles, finished up
a sock. (Sunny Sung/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CARLSBAD, Calif. -- May 26, 2000 -- FUEL-CELLS -- Jeff
Colborn, head of Metallic Power, Inc., on a cart powered by a fuel
pack produced by his company. Although they are similar in many
ways to batteries, fuel cells can be quickly regenerated by pumping
in new chemical fuel. And unlike fusion, they are teetering on the
edge of becoming big business. (Edward Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
