<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-26 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING DIAGNOSIS NOT SO BAD, BUT HIS RETURN ISN'T ASSURED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BKN-PACERS) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Just minutes after a group of subtly confident
Knicks took their places on the court to begin preparing for a
dramatic re-enactment of last year's Eastern Conference finals, a
black limousine eased into the parking lot of the team's practice
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing unfolded his body, emerged from behind the tinted
windows and walked with normal strides as a security guard ushered
him inside. Unlike last year on the day after Game 2 against
Indiana, he wasn't wearing an ominous cast as an accessory. Friday,
a partly disquieted but mostly relieved Ewing was fresh from a
magnetic resonance imaging test that revealed neither a tear nor a
rupture. The pain in his sore right foot, which caused him to exit
the floor six minutes into Game 2 on Thursday night in Indiana, was
diagnosed as acute peroneal tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Although the injury does not generate the same grave reaction as
the partly torn Achilles' tendon that ended Ewing's season last
year, the Knicks have no idea when and if their center will return
during a best-of-7 series that the Pacers lead, 2-0. A decision on
whether Ewing will return for Saturday's Game 3 at Madison Square
Garden will be made just before tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ice it all day today, get treatment, and
re-evaluate it tomorrow,'' said Ewing, who believes he injured his
foot when he pump-faked Dale Davis at the 5-minute-20-second mark
of the first quarter. ``It's a little better than it was last
night. Last night I could hardly walk. I'm able to walk around a
little better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the pain is bearable, I think I'll be fine. But if not, I
won't be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, Kurt Thomas will most likely slip into the
starter's role. And if Ewing is on the bench, the Knicks will
quickly find out if their serendipitous trip through the conference
finals last year was just a special and singular occasion or an
us-against-the-world performance that can be duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won last year without Patrick,'' Charlie Ward said.
``Nothing is going to shake us. It's the same situation, same
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is one pivotal difference this year. The Knicks did
not split the first two games, they dropped both. Their margin for
error is microscopic. And the pressure is much more intense. If
Ewing does not play, the miracle workers from last year will have
to perform. Can the team's remaining low-post threat, Larry
Johnson, find his same 3-point touch? Can Allan Houston and Latrell
Sprewell re-create their inspirational play? Will Marcus Camby
begin finishing with the same force around the basket?
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have already put a dent into the Knicks' ability to
answer those questions. In two games, Ewing's co-stars have
struggled. To be more effective, Houston cannot continue to be
lured into the kind of foul trouble that has reduced his playing
time to 34 minutes against Indiana. Although he is faced with the
flop-happy Reggie Miller, a crafty guard who can look like a bird
crashing into a glass pane at the slightest contact, Houston has to
play smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be aggressive and more assertive, but when you get
offensive fouls because he's flopping, that's hard,'' Houston said.
``I just want it to be called both ways. But I'm not going to do
the antics he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller does seem to major in theater. And it has gotten the best
of the Knicks beyond Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to make it look like you put a gun to him and shot
him,'' said Sprewell, who also picks up Miller on occasion.
``Marcus Camby barely touched him on a flagrant foul call last
night, and he's so good, he's on the floor. You'd think Marcus
killed him. He's good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is not the only foul magnet, though. Over two games, the
Pacers have taken 50 attempts _ 14 alone by Jalen Rose _ compared
with 35 for the Knicks. Down the stretch of Game 2, the Pacers
wisely made their way to the free-throw line while the Knicks lost
loose balls, became jump-shot-oriented and blew the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was part of the problem. He was zero for four in the
fourth quarter. Over the last 10 playoff games, he is a troublesome
four for 31. For the Knicks to have a chance without Ewing,
Sprewell has to decode the mystery to his fourth-quarter
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very aware of it,'' said Sprewell, whose last miss of Game
2 came on a made-to-order, game-tying jumper over the
5-foot-11-inch Travis Best with 5.8 seconds left. ``You're not
thinking about it when you're playing, but right now, of course _
you're wondering what's going on. But again, like that last shot,
you can't let that stuff affect you and how you play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
