<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING'S PRESENCE REQUESTED BY PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BKN-KNICKS) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reggie Miller's comments before the series
notwithstanding, the Indiana Pacers do have some mushy feelings
toward the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pacers hate that the Knicks have been their bane of
playoffs past, they are not beyond appreciating and admiring the
work of New York's basketball gladiator, the one who has been every
bit as long-suffering as they have been in his quest for a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Pacers hope to see Patrick Ewing in uniform
and in action Saturday at Madison Square Garden. Just before the
game, it will be decided whether or not Ewing, who sprained his
right ankle six minutes into Game 2 on Thursday, can play in Game
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather he played,'' Miller said Friday after a light
practice at John Jay College in Manhattan. ``He's a great warrior.
He's been a great competitor throughout the years, so I hope he's
suited up come Saturday. You always want the best players out on
the floor to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson, who was mentored by Ewing while playing for the
Knicks early in his career, said: ``Being a friend, I wish nothing
but the best for him. It's to no benefit of mine to hope he's hurt
and call myself a true friend. I hope he's fine and I hope he suits
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments of the Pacers, whose sentiments were supported by
their coach, Larry Bird, were made in all sincerity. But one can't
help wondering if the Knicks' success against them without Ewing
plays at least a small part in their desire to see him on the
block, calling for the ball and wheeling for that turnaround
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than anyone, the Pacers, who lead this series 2-0,
are aware of how the Knicks can morph into a different, sleeker
opponent when Ewing is sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers became the unwitting victims of a speedy, daring
Knicks team that no one knew existed after Ewing missed the final
four games of last year's Eastern Conference championship with a
partly torn Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   After Ewing went down with the series tied at one game apiece,
the Knicks of Latrell Sprewell, Allan Houston, Larry Johnson and
Marcus Camby beat the Pacers in three of four games.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Pacers somewhat remade themselves this season,
trading away the bruising Antonio Davis in the off-season in an
attempt to keep pace with the Knicks, who had overwhelmed Indiana
with their athleticism once Ewing went out.
</P>
<P>
   While saying that the Pacers subconsciously let up after Ewing
left the series, Miller acknowledged that the game became more
difficult for him and his partner on the wing, Jalen Rose, when
Ewing was not around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was tougher last year,'' Miller said. ``I think we
somewhat let our guard down when he went down. All it does is
really put more pressure on Jalen and myself because we know
Latrell and Allan will probably get 20 shots apiece now. I think
now the team knows that the offense really is going to run through
those two guys' hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also said that Rik Smits, the Pacers' 33-year-old center
who lumbers on bad feet, was better off playing against the equally
cumbersome Ewing rather than against Kurt Thomas or Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rik would prefer to go against Patrick size-wise and
age-wise,'' Miller said. ``They both move the same because they're
up there in age. I think when you put a younger, more athletic _
and in Kurt Thomas a little bit more physical player _ on Rik, it
kind of changes his game a little bit. He went from no fouls in the
third quarter to picking up four quick fouls, so I think he's going
to have to adjust a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits agreed, saying: ``I prefer playing Ewing. I've gotten to
know him a lot better than the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers refused to say that the Knicks were better without
Ewing, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not as good a basketball team without Patrick,''
Jackson said. ``No knock. But they're still a dangerous team.
They're still a team that knocked us out last year without him.
They do different things. We just have to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ewing plays or not, the Pacers said their mind would
remain set on avenging the stunning defeat last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart of hearts, I don't care if he plays,'' Rose said.
``I want to win the game. We've been down this road before with
Patrick in, Patrick out. He is a tremendous warrior for their team,
and I don't think they're a better team without him. Whatever it
takes for us to win, though, I'll take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
