<SLUG> BC-NY-STEINBERG-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING THE FARM, PARK AVENUE STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also LEUCADIA-RELIANCE) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette held a garage sale
before their downfall, it probably looked a lot like the scene on
Friday at Sotheby's, where Saul and Gayfryd Steinberg offered to
unload hundreds of their possessions, from a multimillion-dollar
commode to the living room curtains.
</P>
<P>
   That was not all Steinberg sold on Friday. Reliance Group
Holdings, the insurance company that he had owned for three decades
and which has been teetering on the brink of insolvency, announced
that an investment concern would buy Reliance for the fire-sale
price of $2.55 a share.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stunning twist in the story of a Wall Street wunderkind
turned corporate raider who, with his glamorous young wife, took
New York society by storm in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   While the Steinbergs were well known for their generous
charitable contributions, they were also infamous for a certain
``let them eat cake'' extravagance. There was, for example, the
million-dollar birthday party Gayfryd Steinberg gave for her
husband's 50th in 1989, at which models dressed up to look like his
favorite old-master paintings. (He is selling those, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the enormous Park Avenue penthouse, once John D.
Rockefeller's and, at 34 rooms and 19,000 square feet, very likely
the largest apartment in New York. (It, too, has been sold, to a
Wall Street financier for over $30 million.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the furnishings, well, based on the auction Friday, if it
wasn't gold, the Steinbergs did not own it. Unless, perhaps, it was
ormolu-encrusted, bronze-mounted, rose-strewn, fringed, tasseled,
brocaded, or covered with gilded sphinxes and sea serpents. Or
someone else's family crest.
</P>
<P>
   There were marble-topped gilt tables with gold lions' heads, and
brocade-covered gilt benches with gold lions' feet, and a
velvet-clad gilt settee wearing what looked like a gold-feathered
crown. There was a 21-foot-long dining room table and 23 mahogany
chairs. There was a pair of gold-and-red porcelain jars on
gilt-wood stands that were just shy of 5 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   The Steinbergs did not respond to requests, made through
Sotheby's, for an interview. According to the catalog, they plan to
move to a smaller place now that they have only one child living at
home.
</P>
<P>
   However grand (or grandiose) their furniture, the Steinbergs
were not the sort of people who worried that guests would put their
glasses on the furniture and make rings, said Duane Hampton, whose
late husband, Mark, decorated the apartment with the Steinbergs.
``It was much more comfortable than you could ever imagine,'' she
said. ``It wasn't as off-putting as you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of the Memorial Day weekend, only about 50
people were in the auction room at any one time during the almost
six-hour event, and much of the buying was done by dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The auction raised $12.5 million, including the commissions
charged to buyers, which is about what Sotheby's had estimated
before the sale. A few things failed to sell, including the
curtains and a pair of chintz sofas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There was a time when $12 million would have sounded like an
absurdly small sum to be mentioned in the same breath as Steinberg,
who began making his fortune shortly after graduating from the
Wharton School in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, he began Leasco, which leased out computers
in the days when they were new and expensive and the size of a
truck.
</P>
<P>
   When the company went public in 1965, it and Steinberg became
darlings on Wall Street, which was then in the throes of a
stock-market mania similar to the recent passion for technology
stocks. Just three years later, he took over Reliance, a stodgy
insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing decades, Steinberg bought and sold companies
right and left, but he became most famous for the deals he did not
make. His 1969 run at Chemical Bank failed. In 1984, Disney paid
him $60 million to go away, in what critics dubbed ``greenmail.''
It was a charge that would dog him throughout his deals in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, he married Gayfryd, his third wife, and she was
soon known for her elaborate dinner parties and her scarlet and
gold living room. The couple were fixtures on the charity circuit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 Gayfryd Steinberg quit her post as president of PEN, the
literary group, after the writer Ken Auletta said she and her
husband were trying to use the group to gain respectability (he had
previously called Saul Steinberg sleazy).
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, shareholders began to complain about
Steinberg's management, contending that he ran Reliance not for the
stockholders' benefit but for his family's. They continued to own
much of the stock, and several Steinberg relatives worked there.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Steinberg had a mild stroke, at 55.
</P>
<P>
   But he remained president of Reliance until February, when the
company's troubles could be ignored no longer. Reliance had lost
over $310 million in 1999 because of problems in the commercial
property and casualty business and its involvement in a
controversial workers compensation program. The stock price had
plunged from almost $20 in 1998 to well under $3.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened with more than $700 million of debt, much of which was
about to come due, Reliance was forced in February to sell its only
profitable business; Steinberg stepped aside as chief executive,
though he remained chairman.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, that all ended. Leucadia National Corp. agreed to buy
Reliance for the equivalent of $2.55 a share in Leucadia stock and
to assume the debt. Wall Street estimates that Steinberg will
receive Leucadia shares worth about $93 million.
</P>
<P>
   How much of that he will keep is unclear, in part because the
Steinberg family in the past has borrowed money against the value
of their shares. A year ago his shares were worth more than $350
million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their future, it seems unlikely that the Steinbergs
will soon resume their gold-plated place in New York's
consciousness. In the Sotheby's catalog, Gayfryd Steinberg suggests
that the family would be living in a less colorful way. ``Funnily
enough,'' she said, ``I have kept a lot of brown furniture, which I
never thought I would when I started years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
