<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS WANT EWING, BUT NOT AS HALF A HERO 
</HEADLINE>
  By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Sometime before the conventional strobes and
smoke and amplified din _ as appealing as a car alarm _ herald the
beginning of Saturday afternoon's amusements in Madison Square
Garden, Regis Van Gundy will sit down with a very tall person and
ask him, eventually, if this is indeed his final answer.
</P>
<P>
   The reply will simply be yes or no.
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, will be whether Patrick Ewing, his
starting center, can play against the Pacers, as the Knicks return
home, feeling as wan as if they'd found a caterpillar in their
salad. They are down, two games to none, in the Eastern Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be his call whether he starts or not,'' Van Gundy
said. ``It'll be my call as to how much he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Jeff Van Gundy, as he switches hats from quiz master to
basketball coach, will learn in just what shape is the large right
foot of Ewing, who sprained it during Thursday night's game in
Indianapolis and is suffering from acute tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is yes, that he can play, then that gives the
Knicks just one more arrow _ and a significant one _ in their
quiver. If it's no _ or even a yes, but one that turns out to be
spurious _ then there must be another mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Patrick,'' Van Gundy said Friday, ``that he should play
only if he feels he can be effective.'' In other words, half a hero
is no hero. ``I told our guys that we can't focus on Patrick being
there. I mean, Indiana is coming in for the kill. They're not
planning to give a game away. We have to be at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing is a no-show, or a diminished-show, how will that
affect the Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time that they had to go into a skirmish
without Ewing. Last year he also was injured in Game 2 of the
conference finals, in Indianapolis, and the Knicks went on to beat
the Pacers in the series.
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing went out Thursday 7 minutes into the game, the Knicks
played superbly until partway through the last quarter, when their
defense looked like they were vacationing in Aruba. And, despite
not having Ewing for the last 41 minutes of the game, they were
tied with Indiana with just seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   It is also no secret that the team is faster without Ewing, with
Marcus Camby and even Chris Dudley running in transition.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the opinion here that Ewing is playing some of the
best basketball of his life. Sure, at 37 years old, with banged-up
back, wrist, knees, and now foot, he has had suppler days, days in
which his body didn't feel as if it were being held together by
clothespins. But he is playing team defense, boxing out for
rebounds and taking better percentage shots than usual. The last
halves of the last two games in Miami _ the last shots of those
last games, in particular, the stuffed rebound and the base-line
drive _ were classics, the Hamlet, Beethoven's 5th, the Bart
Simpsons of game-enders.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are still vestiges, at least, of the old
Patrick. He still goes for head fakes as if it were impolite not
to. Last game, a hobbled Rik Smits lifts his head as if he has an
itch, and Ewing does his best Captain Marvel shtick and flies past
him in a vain attempt to block the shot that wasn't shot. And Smits
then pops in two points. And Ewing, after all these years, still
hasn't made a pretty pass, or it escaped me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Patrick was out before,'' said Latrell Sprewell, the
Knicks small forward who has a bruised left thigh, ``other guys
like Duds and Marcus and Kurt Thomas got the opportunity to play,
and stepped up. They knew we needed them, and they came through. We
stayed together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice Friday, they went through drills without Ewing, who
was nursing his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's feeling better today than it did yesterday,'' he said.
``Yesterday I could hardly walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, of course, he was injured and watched the last four
games of the Pacer series and the finals against San Antonio in
dress clothes on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important,'' said Chris Childs, the Knicks point guard
who himself has a painful knee, ``is that whoever steps on the
court gives a 110 percent. If Patrick is out there and helping us,
that's a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the worth of Ewing would be made clear by who is
rooting for him not to play. It's the Pacers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
