u s BC-OLY-MEMO-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      05-26 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MEMO-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO LISTS DELEGATES AND CASH PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salt Lake City officials on Friday released a document that
appeared to outline the plan for cash payments and other illicit
favors that blossomed into an embarrassing scandal in the securing
of the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Two delegates of the International Olympic Committee not
previously connected to the Salt Lake City scandal were implicated
in the document. They face possible sanctioning by the IOC's ethics
commission, which said it would investigate the 28-page document.
</P>
<P>
   Ten committee delegates resigned or were dismissed last year
after it was revealed that Salt Lake City officials had spent more
than $3 million on a program of providing cash payments, medical
benefits, scholarships and other favors in an attempt to win the
2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Revelations about other Olympic bids have implicated about a
third of the IOC's 114 delegates in some form of inappropriate
activity and clearly established that many people were aware of
which delegates had sought special favors in return for their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   The memo released Friday is known as the geld document, because
``geld'' _ the German word for money _ is next to the names of a
handful of IOC delegates. It cannot be fully interpreted because it
contains no dates. It is not known whether the document reflected a
strategy of influence or was an archive of payments or favors
handed out.
</P>
<P>
   The committee decided on Thursday to release the document after
the Justice Department, which had been given the document, said it
did not intend to indict the Salt Lake City Organizing Committee as
a whole. The department said it did not preclude indicting
individual officials involved in the bid. Three people have already
been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   The document was believed to have been retrieved from a computer
belonging to Dave Johnson, who, along with Tom Welch, was a chief
architect of Salt Lake City's bid for the 2002 Winter Games, said
an Olympic official who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Documents revealing the personal tastes of IOC members have
previously been made public. However, the geld document is the
first in which direct references to money were made. Some of the
references in the document were benign, like the notation that the
late Rene Essomba of Cameroon loved bow ties. But the word ``geld''
was also next to Essomba's name, as was the fact that his daughter
was in college in Washington. It was the revelation of her
scholarship that brought the scandal to light.
</P>
<P>
   The word geld also appeared next to the names of two persons not
previously linked to the Salt Lake scandal: Francis Nyangweso of
Uganda and Tony Bridge of Jamaica. They will be investigated by the
IOC's ethics commission. Nyangweso's name surfaced in regard to the
bid by Sidney, Australia, for the 2000 Summer Games when he was
promised $35,000 the night before Sydney narrowly defeated Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the IOC have asked how, with the same names surfacing
repeatedly in various bids, committee officials could say they had
not known about illicit favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to say I didn't know about the activities of Salt
Lake City,'' said Anita DeFrantz, a delegate from the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
