<HEADER>
A7218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-INDY-ARCHDEACON05     05-26 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-ARCHDEACON0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unser Jr. learns about determination from his daughter
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ She is the other teen-age girl who has a lot to
do with Sunday's running of the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, is charming, gutsy and seems wise beyond her years,
but she's not the one who qualified for the race at 220 mph. She's
not Sarah Fisher. She's Cody Unser and from the chest down, she
can't move at all.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the 13-year-old girl finally made her dad move in the
direction his heart had been pulling him for four years. Cody is a
big reason Al Unser Jr. is finally back where he belongs _ back at
the Indy 500, the race the Unsers, like no other family, have
defined with with five decades of blood, sweat and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are supposed to set the example for their children,''
Unser said, ``but sometimes it turns out to be the other way
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months ago, Cody _ she of the long blond hair, hazel
eyes and indomitable Unser spirit _ was playing basketball at her
middle school when she suddenly got an intense migraine headache.
The way she described it, ``on a scale from 1 to 10, it was 100.''
She felt a tingle in her legs, a dizziness and then she collapsed.
She was taken to the hospital and a day later she couldn't move.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors diagnosed her problem as transverse myelitis, a rare and
supposedly incurable neurological infection of her spinal cord. She
ended up confined to a wheelchair, but her dad wasn't sure quite
where he was anymore. ``It turned my world upside down,'' Unser
said. ``I felt helpless to do something for my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it was but another of a series of blows that left
Unser reeling: His 18-year marriage to Shelley _ his high school
sweetheart and the mother of their four children _ was
disintegrating into divorce. His once stellar racing career was
mired in a winless slump that would extend for an amazing 4 1/2
years and 73 races.
</P>
<P>
   This was the same guy who had won the Indianapolis 500 in 1992
and 1994, had won two CART championships, won in prototype sports
cars at Daytona and won two International Race of Champions (IROC)
all-star titles in stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   But after gulping milk in Victory Lane after the Indy 500 in
1994, he became the first defending champ ever to fail to make the
race the following year. He didn't qualify in 1995 and the
following year the sport was ripped apart by an open-wheel civil
war that found almost all of the top teams and drivers boycotting
the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   CART has run a Memorial Day weekend race of its own, but it's
never been an equal of the Indy 500. And no one felt it more than
Unser. He was one of the most popular drivers ever to race here and
his family had had more success here than any other. Unser faces
pop up nine times on the massive Warner Borg Trophy given the 500
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Unser's two wins, his dad _ Al Sr. _ won here four times
and his uncle Bobby has three victories. But the family legacy has
more than triumph woven into its fabric. There has been terrible
loss at Indy, as well.
</P>
<P>
   After Louie Unser failed to make the race in 1940, Jerry Unser _
a brother to Al Sr. and Bobby _ made his debut in 1958. On the
first lap, he got tangled in a 15 car pile-up and his car was sent
airborne over the first turn. He ended up with a bum shoulder. A
year later he was not so lucky. A fiery practice crash left him
with severe burns and two weeks later he died.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry's son Johnny is part of the third wave of Unsers. He
debuted here in 1996 and will start on the outside of Row 10 on
Sunday. Bobby's son Robby drove in the race the past two years and
then there's Al Jr., who debuted in 1983 and Sunday _ for the first
time in six years _ will be back in the line-up, starting on the
outside of Row 6.
</P>
<P>
   There has been at least one Unser in the Indy 500 field for 36
of the past 37 years and Sunday marks the 31st time that two Unsers
have started the same race.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Al Jr. was beside himself when he joined the CART
walkout in 1996: ``The low point came in May that year. We were
running a race (the quickly assembled US 500) at Michigan. I'm
going down the back straight and there was no grandstand. All the
way around the track, the seats were maybe half-filled. It was a
huge letdown not to be at the Indy 500. I just felt empty. I felt
like I had big hole in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The hole got deeper last May when he came to Indy on race day to
support his two cousins, who both were in the field. He walked with
them and his Uncle Bobby to the starting grid and the crowd began
to cheer him and call out his name. Suddenly, he found himself in
tears.
</P>
<P>
   About then is when his daughter came in and gave him the lesson
he needed. ``Cody never gave up,'' Unser said. ``From the day she
was diagnosed she went after what she wanted with all the power she
had. The challenges she faces everyday are well beyond anything I
faced here and she showed nothing but strength.''
</P>
<P>
   He told how his daughter became a guiding force to other kids in
the hospital. ``One girl wouldn't eat for months and pretty soon
Cody was down there with her and she was eating in 20 minutes,''
Unser said.
</P>
<P>
   When fans and race drivers _ Bobby Labonte sent $60,000 _
started to send money, Cody and Shelley set up the Cody Unser First
Step Foundation, a nonprofit fund to funnel money toward research
and awareness of all spinal cord injures.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her rehab, Cody went back to swimming, lifting
weights and riding a specially-equipped bicycle. ``She showed me
that you go after what you want,'' Unser said.
</P>
<P>
   For him, that was the Indy 500. ``After last year, I vowed I
wouldn't miss another,'' he said. ``I'm 38 years old and I'm in the
prime of my life as far as a race car driver. I'm in good physical
shape and I have experience.''
</P>
<P>
   His contract was coming to an end with Roger Penske and it was
becoming obvious it would not be renewed. As he went looking for a
new race deal, he was approached by other CART teams and some
NASCAR owners. ``I told them all my first priority was running the
Indy 500 and that pretty much ended he conversation with most of
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Rick Galles contacted him. He had been Unser's
original owner in 1983 and the two had teamed up for Al Jr.'s Indy
500 victory in 1992. They signed a five-year contract and instantly
Unser said ``I could breathe again.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was as if his whole world had gotten back in order.
``This place means so much to my family. To us, the Indy 500 is the
mother, the father and the granddaddy of all racing. It's the first
race, the oldest race and the best race.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, three races after signing on with Galles, he won the
Indy Vegas 300. Everyone _ especially friend and CART rival Michael
Andretti, who called him in Victory Lane _ was thrilled for Unser,
who has decals on his car to raise awareness of spinal cord
injuries. He dedicated the victory to his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally I could show her that if you fight and don't give up,
you can get what you want,'' he said. Then again, Cody already knew
that.
</P>
<P>
   That's why _ to insure her independence _ she's had the
handlebars cut off the back of her wheelchair. She doesn't want
anyone pushing her around. In true Unser fashion, she knows as long
as she's got a set of wheels under her, she going to be able to
move like few others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
