u p BC-BUSH-COMMENCEMENT-HNS     05-26 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COMMENCEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IS COMMENCEMENT SPEAKER IN SMALL TEXAS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas _ For the first time in history, Crawford High
School had a commencement speaker.
</P>
<P>
   His name: George W. Bush, the Texas governor who would be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all,'' Bush told the graduates, ``I hope that when you
look in the mirror you will always be proud of what you see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's only other commencement address this year was at Prairie
View A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was pretty much his initiative,'' principal Don Harris
said of Bush's offer to address the tiny class of 45. ``He could
have spoken probably just about anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But this tiny community, 18 miles west of Waco, is a new second
home to Bush and will be the Texas White House if he is elected
president. The governor bought a 1,600-acre ranch west of town,
near the Middle Bosque River, last August.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 people attended the 8 p.m. event in the football
stadium. Typically, the school's graduations draw fewer than half
that number. The town only has about 700 residents scattered over
the region's fertile hills.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's pomp and circumstance, an ice cream social
for the whole town and one last party for the graduates, most of
them were to board a bus at 2 a.m. Saturday to move the celebration
to South Padre Island on the Texas Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   When they return Monday night, and probably for years to come,
the graduates can reminisce about the time they mingled with the
man who might be president under the glare of network television
lights. And it all transpired in a simple rural town without even a
Dairy Queen.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who frequents the ranch on weekends, already has drawn
there a few famous visitors, such as ABC-TV journalists Barbara
Walters and Sam Donaldson and a steady stream of Secret Service
agents who provide him round-the-clock protection. But Friday's
event was Bush's first major coming-out party in his new hometown.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning, he encouraged national reporters to attend
the Crawford graduation and he invited them to the ice cream
social. Just the day before, he discouraged the media from
attending his twin daughters' graduation in Austin, saying they
didn't want special attention.
</P>
<P>
   While the Crawford community was glad that Bush joined the
festivities, Harris said, ``this is still graduation, and it's
still Crawford graduation,'' emphasizing the town's name.
</P>
<P>
   Harris expressed pride that the high school, which has about 270
students, has received ``exemplary'' ratings from the Texas
Education Agency for five straight years. In 1999, all sophomores
passed all segments of the state skills test.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being off the beaten path, Harris said, Crawford
attracts quality teachers who help inspire many students to attend
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very blessed and fortunate with a very strong
faculty,'' he said. ``Any accomplishments we have are a tribute to
them.'' The school's small size (class 2-A in sports competitions)
allows personal attention for students, said the principal, who has
been there 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 45 seniors, 20 are honor graduates and many will attend
college. The valedictorian is going to Texas A&AMP;M University and the
twin girls who ranked second and third are going to the University
of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Stacy Clark, 19, will be commuting to McLennan
Community College in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become really close,'' she said. ``Everybody knows
everything about everybody, for better or for worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, is still somewhat of an outsider, and some folks
here weren't thrilled that Friday's ceremony attracted so many
visitors who wanted to see Bush more than the graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get to invite everybody we wanted to,'' Clark said,
``but I think it's a really neat idea, because in a couple of years
I'm going to look back and say, `Wow, I shook the governor's hand,
but now he's the president!'''
</P>
<P>
   She believes Bush's moving to Crawford is sure to attract new
business and other growth.
</P>
<P>
   But there haven't been any big changes yet, said cheerleader and
senior class president Mandy Kelm, except for the excitement of
planning for the big event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make sure that all the graduates have enough
room for all their family to come,'' she said. ``Plus, we're trying
to accommodate the community to come and watch him (Bush).''
</P>
<P>
   Headed for Texas A&AMP;M this fall, Kelm works at a local
tent-making company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my friends work in Waco because there's really nothing
in Crawford,'' she said. ``We have a gas station and a burger
joint. We have a beauty shop, but two older ladies do that. And
that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
