<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ODD-VETO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN ODD VETO 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki is out of step with both the public and with
state lawmakers in vetoing an important bill that would require all
cigarettes sold in New York to meet new fire safety standards by
2002. Lighted cigarettes dropped on beds and couches are the
leading cause of fire-related deaths in the state, killing nearly
50 people a year. This deadly hazard can be significantly reduced
if cigarettes are designed to be self-extinguishing after a smoker
stops puffing on the cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Both the state Assembly and Senate unanimously passed the bill,
which was supported by medical groups, firefighters' associations,
consumer advocates and anti-smoking groups. The only opponents were
tobacco companies that argued against state regulation of their
products. The bill would have directed the state Office of Fire
Prevention and Control to create fire safety standards if a federal
standard was not enacted by 2001. Tobacco companies have the
technology to meet the new standards. A few brands may meet them
already.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, at the last minute Pataki surprised the
Legislature by vetoing the bill on the grounds that it did not deal
with the potential bootlegging problem. He argues that smokers may
not like fire-safe cigarettes, and may increase demand for
illegally trafficked cigarettes that do not meet fire safety
standards. He wants the Legislature to approve a separate bill that
will increase penalties on cigarette bootleggers and curb illegal
Internet sales of cigarettes to minors.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas deserve support, but they need not prevent enactment
of legislation that requires the industry to comply with new
fire-safe standards two years from now. The governor approved a
55-cent-per-pack increase in the state cigarette tax without
insisting on passage of anti-bootlegging measures. There is no need
now to link fire-safe cigarettes with anti-bootlegging measures,
which should be debated on their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
