</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FUZZY ABORTION DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   The abortion debate has gotten murkier in recent years as
pro-life forces have shifted their strategy. Whereas once they were
focused on wholesale repudiation of Roe vs. Wade, they are now
finding it more productive to chip away at a woman's right to
choose by imposing limitations. One result has been to blur the
meaning of ``pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   A good example of this confusion is the Senate race in New York
between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rep. Rick Lazio. Both call
themselves pro-choice. But they differ significantly on how far
government should go in limiting choice.
</P>
<P>
   This new fuzziness shows how successful pro-life forces have
been in limiting abortion rights one restriction at a time. Even
politicians who consider themselves pro-choice wind up siding with
pro-life groups by, for example, endorsing laws that mandate
waiting periods and parental notification. But the pro-life camp's
most important victory has been on the so-called partial birth
abortion ban.
</P>
<P>
   By seeming to target a single procedure that sounds particularly
distasteful, pro-life strategists have won support for partial
birth legislation from a broad range of politicians, including
Republicans like Gov. George Pataki of New York who are generally
pro-choice, and even pro-choice Democrats like Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan and Tom Daschle, the Senate minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because the partial birth ban is frequently
misadvertised as dealing only with a rare procedure used in
late-term abortions. In fact, the language of partial birth
legislation in Congress and in most of the statutes adopted by some
30 states is so vague that it could potentially apply even to
common procedures used before viability of the fetus. That is why
such laws have been blocked by nearly every federal and state court
that has reviewed them.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio says he is an abortion rights supporter, but he too favors
the partial birth abortion ban and has described Clinton as extreme
for opposing it. He has also voted for other restrictions, like
prohibiting women in the military from obtaining privately funded
abortions at overseas military hospitals and subjecting to criminal
prosecution anyone other than a parent who accompanies a minor
across state lines for an abortion in violation of parental consent
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The top three Republican candidates in the Senate race in New
Jersey also call themselves pro-choice though all support the
partial birth ban, a stance that allows them to reach out to
moderate voters without angering pro-life groups. This may be smart
politics. Other politicians who have refused to back the partial
birth ban have made enemies politically, among them New York's
mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, and Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are going to have to be alert this year to the nuances of
the abortion issue. There are candidates out there who promise to
support a woman's right to choose, but whose commitment is
compromised by their willingness to accept more government
intrusion into private medical decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
