</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS ADVANCE TO STANLEY CUP FINALS WITH 2-1 WIN OVER FLYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Devils accomplished what seemed impossible
six days ago. Friday night they made history.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey defeated the Philadelphia Flyers, 2-1, in Game 7 to
become the first team to advance to the Stanley Cup finals after
trailing a conference finals by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Elias scored both goals for the Devils, the winner with
only 2 minutes 32 seconds remaining, to send the Devils to their
second Stanley Cup finals appearance. In 1995 they swept the
Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur played a brilliant game in goal for the Devils,
making 26 saves. His only mistake was Rick Tocchet's goal that tied
the game early in the second after Elias had opened the scoring in
the first with his sixth in the playoffs against Brian Boucher, who
made 16 saves.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth Game 7 played by the Devils, and only their
third victory. The series seemed to turn around for the Devils
after coach Larry Robinson publicly chastised the team after their
loss in Game 4 at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd at First Union Center was silenced only 20
seconds after Keith Jones took the first penalty in the game, 6
minutes 24 seconds after the opening faceoff. That is how long it
took the Devils to capitalize on their man-advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Elias found himself unguarded in the slot to the left of Boucher
and had no trouble converting Jason Arnott's pass from the boards.
It was the sixth goal in the playoffs for Elias.
</P>
<P>
   A frightening moment came 66 seconds later when Eric Lindros was
leveled by Scott Stevens. The Devils' captain caught Lindros with
his head down as he entered the Devils' zone. Stevens blindsided
Lindros with a crushing check that knocked him off his skates.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros hit his head on the ice. He was attended to by the
Flyers' trainers, then helped off the ice and taken to a hospital.
Stevens was not assessed a penalty despite pleas by the Flyers'
fans, who thought Stevens had elbowed Lindros on the play.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening period, the officials awarded the Flyers three
manpower advantages, but the Devils escaped unscathed. They were so
busy defending after the goal by Elias that they went without a
shot for about 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Brylin and Alexander Mogilny had marvelous opportunities
to extend the lead early in the second period, but they fanned on
their shots from in close. Elias also had a good chance before the
period was four minutes old, but his shot sailed wide to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Colin White, the rookie defenseman of the Devils, took the
fourth penalty in the game for the Devils, and it proved costly
because the Flyers tied the game on Tocchet's fifth goal in the
playoffs. The score came on a rebound from close range with a crowd
in front of Brodeur, who had saved a weak shot from John LeClair
before Tocchet jumped on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came 6:01 into the middle period and it fired up the
Flyers. They dominated most of the period, but failed to tally
again, thanks to Brodeur's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's most hectic moment in the period came with three
minutes left when he made a glove save on Simon Gagne. The Flyers
took 15 shots against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
