</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES LOOK ORDINARY, OR WORSE, IN 4-1 LOSS TO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carl Everett speaks disdainfully of the Yankees,
infers they are unremarkable, a common team with lots of
championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   But Everett's description is charitable when applied to the
season's first meeting between the Yankees and Red Sox Friday
night. The Yankees played poorly and suffered the consequences,
losing by 4-1 at Yankee Stadium. Ramon Martinez began the game with
a 6.95 earned run average and allowed one run over seven and
two-thirds innings; David Cone is 1-4 after 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have help on the way, for they probably will
activate shortstop Derek Jeter from the disabled list in time for
Saturday's game. Jeter went 2 for 3 in a minor league game in
Tampa, Fla., Friday night and intended to return to the New York
area on a rented jet. Since Jeter strained an muscle in his abdomen
May 11, the Yankees have lost 9 of 13 games. It is expected that
Boston shortstop Nomar Garciaparra will also be activated.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this loss had not been to the Red Sox, even if it did
not force the Yankees out of first place, it would have been one of
the more frustrating defeats. Yankees manager Joe Torre has said
many times that he does not lose sleep over one-sided losses, but
he might have gone home last night and replayed the pivotal moments
when his team gave away runs _ some of those scored by the Red Sox,
and some the Yankees should have scored.
</P>
<P>
   First inning. The Red Sox had runners at first and third and one
out, and Cone was struggling; among his many pitches, only his
split-fingered fastball had any real quality to it, and Cone tried
desperately to get the Red Sox hitters to swing at this pitch.
Brian Daubach did so, hitting a one-hopper back to Cone.
</P>
<P>
   His entire career, Cone's first instinct has been to obstruct
all baserunners at third, prevent any runs from scoring, and he
immediately ran at Jeff Frye, the Boston runner at third. What he
should have done was throw to second for what would probably have
been an easy, inning-ending double play
</P>
<P>
   But Frye got into a rundown long enough for John Valentin to
take third and Daubach to reach second. The crowd of 54,470 cheered
Cone, but he knew better, berating himself behind the mound after
the play was over; ``stupid'' was among the many words he muttered.
</P>
<P>
   No runs should have scored, but the Red Sox scored twice when
the next hitter _ Everett _ lined a single into center field.
Cone's shoulders sagged when Daubach crossed the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Cone continued to labor, walking two batters in the second
inning, hanging a slider and surrendering a two-run homer to Mike
Stanley in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed to get loose in the middle innings, his control
improving and he pinned the Red Sox to their four runs. Clay
Bellinger ripped a solo home run off Martinez in the third. The
Yankees trailed by 4-1 after three innings, but they still were in
a position to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Their opportunity came in the fifth. Chris Turner singled to
right field to lead off, before Bellinger pulled a single through
the left side of the infield. Two runners on, nobody out, top of
the order coming up.
</P>
<P>
   With Chuck Knoblauch out of the lineup with a bruised wrist,
Ricky Ledee was the lead-off hitter, and he hit a soft line drive
toward center. Everett had been positioned extremely shallow in the
first few innings, as if he were daring the Yankees to drive the
ball over his head. But he was a little farther back with the Red
Sox winning and Ledee at the plate, and he could not reach the soft
liner.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinger, running from first base, realized this immediately,
racing around second, hustling toward third, and he was more than
halfway to the bag when he saw Turner standing near the bag. A
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Frye took the throw from Everett and ran with the ball at
Bellinger, tagging him out while Ledee reached second and Turner
held third. The Yankees should've had the bases loaded and no outs,
and Wilson Delgado, Paul O'Neill and Bernie Williams due to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was one out _ and then two outs, after Delgado
popped up, some fans booing and then more booing when O'Neill
grounded out. That was their chance. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are just another team, Everett has said. Friday
night, it would have been hard to argue the point.
</P>
</TEXT>
