u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NOTEBOOK-N     05-26 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS TO BE STARTER IF EWING CANNOT PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Kurt Thomas sat on a chair at the end of the
court Friday, staring ahead, past the reporters and his teammates,
perhaps all the way to Saturday at Madison Square Garden. He may
find himself the Knicks' starting center in one of season's biggest
games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Patrick Ewing's availability in question, Thomas is next in
line to assume the starting spot when the Knicks, already down 2-0
in the Eastern Conference finals, play host to the Pacers in Game
3.
</P>
<P>
   The 28 minutes he logged in Ewing's absence in Game 2 were 12
more than his next highest total in the playoffs and 15 more than
he played in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I get paid to do,'' he said Friday at Purchase
College. ``I hate to see Patrick get injured, but I've just got to
go out there and play. Of course I hope he can play. We need
Patrick if we want to make some kind of run in the playoffs.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The piercing stare from the 6-foot-9-inch Thomas that may worry
some forwards will be useless against the 7-4 Rik Smits. Still,
Thomas played well against Smits when he got his chance,
contributing 10 points and eight rebounds in Game 2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas has been foul prone and has displayed a quick temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to stay in front of him as much as possible, just try
to keep my body between him and the basket,'' Thomas said of Smits.
``He's 7-4 and he's so long. It's really hard for me to contest his
shots. Of course, he knows he can shoot over me at any opportunity.
I just have to try to get my hands in his face as much as
possible.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy added: ``It'll take guys who did not
play like they're capable to show mental toughness and bounce back.
And it's going to take us rebounding the ball and defending without
fouling.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has committed 35 fouls in 156 minutes in the postseason,
recording one more foul than his rebound total. The task on the
backboards is made more difficult by the presence of Dale Davis,
who has grabbed 16 rebounds in each of the first two games. But
there is little choice for Thomas, as well as for Marcus Camby and
Chris Dudley, who will probably play more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prepare as if he's not going to be there, but
hopefully he will be,'' Thomas said of Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, if he can not play I'll be starting at
the center. I go in and whenever he calls my number, whatever he
informs me I have to do, I go with the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Missed Signal
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs did not practice, nursing a sore right knee from
the fourth-quarter collision with Rik Smits. But that did not
excuse him from a critique by Jeff Van Gundy. With just over three
minutes remaining in Game 2, Van Gundy was signaling for Childs to
call a timeout with the Knicks holding an 80-77 lead because Childs
had been bumped to the floor by Smits on the previous sequence. But
Childs ignored the request and missed a 3-point attempt. Smits then
converted a 3-point play to tie the score. ``I was calling timeout
because he said he was hurt,'' Van Gundy said. ``Then he waved me
off and shot the 3. It was one of many bad plays in the last four
minutes by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra Practice
</P>
<P>
   In his first minutes of the postseason on Thursday, John Wallace
was 0 for 2 from the floor with a turnover in four minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Sealy
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson, Reggie Miller, Al Harrington, Dale Davis and Chris
Mullin flew to New York on a private jet after Thursday's game to
attend the funeral for Malik Sealy friday morning. The rest of the
team flew in this morning for a late afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough, but at the same time, it was one in which
we celebrated his life and the way he lived it and the impact he
made,'' Jackson said. ``There were a lot of tears but also a lot of
celebrating also. My prayers continue to go out to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Broussard &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
