<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPS-COMPONENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DROP IN COMPONENT ORDERS A SIGNAL OF SLOWING ECONOMY?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000 the San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although sales of cell phones, Palm Pilots and
other gadgets continue to climb, factory orders of electronic goods
and components plunged by a record 20.1 percent in April, the
Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and analysts were unsure what to make of the
seemingly contradictory trends. But they agreed that a sustained
decline in electronics orders would have serious repercussions not
just for technology centers like Silicon Valley but for the economy
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Valley has been the leading edge of the economy,''
said Michael Lehmann, a professor of economics at the University of
San Francisco. ``When it heads south, it's going to pull all the
wagons with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to caution that a single month's statistics do not
represent a trend and that April's decline in electronics orders
may be no more than a blip on the radar.
</P>
<P>
   But Lehmann said the unusually steep drop suggests that the
health of America's fastest-growing industry has taken a turn for
the worse, which does not bode well for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in electronics orders contributed to a 6.4 percent
drop in overall factory orders for big-ticket durable goods, the
sharpest such downturn in nearly nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in for a recession,'' Lehmann said. ``This
number could be the opening round.''
</P>
<P>
   But others insist that the long-term trend for electronics
orders remains one of growth. In March, orders for electronics and
electrical equipment, including semiconductors, circuit boards and
home appliances, rose 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   `Best of Times'
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the best of times,'' said David Levine, a professor
of economics at the University of California at Berkeley's Haas
School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Joseph Byrne, a technology analyst at the Gartner Group's
Dataquest research unit, noted that the record size of April's drop
in electronics orders merits closer scrutiny under any
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you see orders fall by 20 percent, you ought to pay
attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne was left scratching his head by the Commerce Department's
implication that demand is down for electronic gadgets and
components.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our working assumption has been that supply was straining to
keep up with demand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this is the most puzzling aspect of the department's
findings. A 20 percent drop in factory orders of chips and other
tech tidbits should mean that manufacturers of electronic goods are
tightening their belts.
</P>
<P>
   But sales of personal computers expanded 20 percent in the first
quarter, according to International Data Corp., and a number of
electronics companies have said recently that production is being
slowed by a shortage of chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a problem all right,'' said Kurt King, an analyst with
Banc of America Securities. ``But it's supply, not demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo Co., said this week that it will postpone the debut of
a more powerful, highly anticipated Game Boy player in the United
States until next March because it cannot find enough chips and
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Factories in Full Throttle
</P>
<P>
   Chip factories in Taiwan, South Korea and elsewhere are working
full throttle to keep up with demand. But analysts say there just
are not enough plants to provide semiconductors for all of today's
increasingly ``smart'' devices.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about 435 million cellular phones are expected to
be shipped this year, surging to more than 900 million by 2003,
according to Forward Concepts, a semiconductor market researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these phones will be competing for scant supplies of
chips and displays with Palm Pilots, Game Boys and other handheld
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, Calif.'s Intel Corp. this week said that to meet
growing demand it will invest $2 billion to expand chip production
in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the semiconductor industry as a whole underinvested in
1998 and 1999,'' Intel's chief executive, Craig Barrett, said.
``I'd expect some shortages of components for the next 12 months or
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary Findings
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist at Wells Capital Management in
San Francisco, noted that the Commerce Department's findings are
still only preliminary, and said the picture may become clearer
when more concrete numbers are released next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there must be something dragging that statistic down,'' he
admitted. ``Maybe the government is only looking at certain types
of chips.''
</P>
<P>
   From a broader view, Schlossberg said the 6.4 percent drop in
total factory orders indicates that a series of increases in
short-term interest rates over the past year finally may be
accomplishing the Federal Reserve's goal of slowing economic growth
and keeping inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, nearly all economic indicators pointed toward
continued expansion. In March, for example, factory orders for
durable goods climbed 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said in a separate report
yesterday that Americans' incomes in April rose at a faster pace
than spending for a second straight month, indicating that
consumers are growing reluctant to shell out for cars,
refrigerators and other heavy-duty purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Schlossberg said it will take considerably more
evidence of an economic slowdown for the Fed to call a halt to
raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   He said another quarter-point increase is likely in coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
