<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SERBIA-NYT &LR;      05-26 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SERBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SERBIA'S MUZZLED MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   When masked police staged a 2 a.m. raid on Serbia's most
important opposition television and radio stations last week, it
signaled an escalation of Slobodan Milosevic's attacks on the
media. Independent journalists throughout Serbia have been beaten
and arrested, and their transmitters are mysteriously failing.
Milosevic is apparently desperate to control the news as elections
approach, which makes it particularly important for friends of
democracy in Serbia to help these broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic previously attacked the independent media mainly by
yanking their licenses, suing them and imposing steep fines. A
small group of radio and television stations managed to broadcast
anyway. The most important are Studio B, controlled by Vuk
Draskovic, an opposition leader whose party runs Belgrade, and
Radio B2-92. Both were closed last week.
</P>
<P>
   The raids are the culmination of an increasingly desperate
campaign to label independent journalists as terrorists and to
paint them as shills for the NATO alliance. The Serbian government
is also threatening to pass a new anti-terrorism law, which would
certainly be used against these journalists.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Milosevic's panic is that polls show his support
dropping, and the Constitution provides for local and parliamentary
elections by the end of the year. His political opposition is
hapless, divided and easily manipulated, and has responded to the
media crackdown with silence and confusion. But a new student
movement, called Otpor, is drawing substantial public support.
</P>
<P>
   The independent media can reach much of their public with help
from outside. Serbia's sister republic, Montenegro, which is in
open rebellion against Milosevic, has offered its satellite
stations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when B2-92's predecessor was briefly closed, the Voice
of America broadcast its news programs. The VOA, BBC and other
foreign stations can be heard on FM radio in Serbia. Their
transmitters could allow B2-92's news to reach a large audience.
Western governments and news outlets are also increasing aid to
Serbia's independent journalists. A new fund for the legal defense
of persecuted journalists will be particularly important as
Milosevic intensifies his campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
