<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-26 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7354 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CHOCOLATE-GHIRARDELLI     05-26 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-GHIRARDELLI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GHIRARDELLI SMELLS SWEET SUCCESS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The first thing you notice is the smell _ a
sweet, fudgey scent that permeates the neighborhood and suggests
what it must have been like, 150 years ago, when Domingo
Ghirardelli was cooking up his confections for pioneers and miners
and San Francisco society folk.
</P>
<P>
   Those confections have changed little over the decades _ the
recipes remain a closely guarded secret _ but the
multimillion-dollar company that Ghirardelli founded has
experienced considerable growing pains and is only now looking to
extend its famous brand to international markets.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Ghirardelli is known to most people overseas only
as that really good chocolate made in that fun factory near
Fisherman's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   What they tend not to realize is that Ghirardelli Chocolate Co.,
America's oldest continuous chocolate-maker, vacated its red-brick
factory in San Francisco 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists who visit the Ghirardelli Chocolate Manufactury in
Ghirardelli Square are seeing only relics of an earlier day. No
chocolate is manufactured at the manufactury.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company occupies an unexceptional,
265,000-square-foot plant in an industrial section of San Leandro,
where a $45 million expansion project will conclude next month,
quadrupling production capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion marks yet another turning point for Ghirardelli,
which, in its long history, has been owned at various times by the
maker of Rice-a-Roni and the company behind Cap'n Crunch cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Ghirardelli was purchased in 1998 for an
undisclosed amount by Swiss chocolate giant Lindt &AMP; Sprungli.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Anton, Ghirardelli's chief executive since 1992, said he
had agonized about selling off the company. Sitting in the
company's shiny new boardroom beneath a large, grim-looking
portrait of the founder, Anton said his original plan to raise
much-needed capital for growth had been to take Ghirardelli public.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Lindt, here was a company whose total focus was
chocolate,'' he said. ``The more I thought about that, the more
excited I got.''
</P>
<P>
   Anton's excitement was quickly justified as Lindt steered
Ghirardelli toward investing millions of dollars in new equipment
for producing filled chocolates _ bars and squares crammed with
caramel, orange and mint fillings, and, not coincidentally, the
kind of treats that Lindt itself specializes in.
</P>
<P>
   Making such things is a lot harder than you might imagine, and
Anton, who has worked in the food industry almost his entire
career, is more than happy to detail every intricate step of the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The filled chocolates premiered on store shelves last month, and
Anton has high hopes that they will be a strong addition to a
product line that already brings in about $160 million in annual
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Along with chocolate bars and squares, Ghirardelli produces
fancier chocolates for special occasions, chips and bars for
baking, hot chocolate mix, cocoa, flavored coffees and even the
chocolate powder sprinkled on cappuccinos.
</P>
<P>
   The company has about 20 retail outlets nationwide and is hoping
to soon penetrate Japan and other Asian markets. Anton said total
sales are growing by 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the right place at the right time,'' he explained.
``The Baby Boomers are of an age where they can be more discerning,
which means they go for premium chocolates.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's a good time to be a Ghirardelli or a Godiva
and not the most opportune moment for a Hershey or Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've waited more than 145 years for this to happen,'' Anton
said. ``But it's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Americans are suddenly turning up their noses at Milky
Way bars and Baby Ruths. According to the Chocolate Manufacturers
Association, an industry group, the typical American consumes about
12 pounds of chocolate a year, mostly the sort that comes tumbling
out of vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover:
</P>
<P>
   -- Americans spend $1 billion each Valentine's Day on candy.
</P>
<P>
   -- The country's retail chocolate business is worth $13 billion
a year.
</P>
<P>
   -- Chocolate manufacturers use 40 percent of the world's
almonds, 20 percent of the world's peanuts and 8 percent of the
world's sugar.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nougat, the gooey substance inside many chocolate bars, is
made from almonds, pistachios and other nuts, stirred into a sugar
paste.
</P>
<P>
   -- Science has yet to prove conclusively that chocolate is an
aphrodisiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``But chocolate is still sensual because of the way it melts in
your mouth,'' insisted Susan Smith, a spokeswoman for the
association.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that, contrary to widely held beliefs, there's no
scientific connection between chocolate and migraine headaches or
acne.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the myths that people think about chocolate just
aren't true,'' Smith said. ``People think that if something tastes
good, there must be something wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of U.S. candy companies make their own chocolate.
Because the process is so complex, most candy companies buy their
chocolate in bulk from a manufacturer and then melt it into desired
shapes and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Ghirardelli is one of the few to handle everything itself. To
emphasize the point, Anton donned a white lab coat and hair net,
removed his watch (``If the crystal broke, it could fall into a
vat'') and led the way onto the factory floor.
</P>
<P>
   The smell is intense, almost intoxicating, as if the world's
biggest batch of brownies had just been removed from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most Ghirardelli workers say they don't even notice. ``You
just stop smelling it after a while,'' said Azara Edwards, who runs
the machines that each day churn out thousands of chocolate chips
for cookies. ``It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Anton agreed. ``I have to be away for a while before I notice it
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He led the way through the warehouse, where about 9 million
pounds of finished chocolate is stored, to a pile of 140-pound
sacks of cocoa beans from Africa, South America and Indonesia.
Anton explained how the trick to really good chocolate is to remove
the shell and get at the center part, called the nib.
</P>
<P>
   The nib is the primary source of what the chocolate industry
euphemistically calls cocoa butter, but which is in reality cocoa
fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fat carries all the flavor,'' Anton said.
</P>
<P>
   After the beans are processed, they are converted to flakes and
then liquid form, and mixed with sugar and lecithin. The resulting
chocolate is pumped to various machines throughout the plant via
overhead pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the production is automated, and Anton said each machine
is custom-made in Europe and costs many millions of dollars.
Because Ghirardelli has been around for so long, though, the
factory contains a mix of old and new equipment, with some
requiring tender loving care from workers and others humming along
under the control of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Do workers sample the merchandise as it comes off the line?
Anton said it's not company policy, but a good deal of tasting
might fall under the heading of ``quality control.''
</P>
<P>
   Factory employees smile when asked how active they are in
quality control. ``Look at my hips,'' said Yolanda Caro as she
monitored endless rows of chocolate chips traveling along a
conveyor belt.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing his tour of the plant, Anton plucked off his hair net
and recalled how he once worked for a company that made soy
proteins for food products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd talk about it at a cocktail party, and people would be
snoring on me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't happen anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I talk about chocolate,'' Anton said, ``and people light
up. They ask if I have any samples. How's that for a good job?''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
