<HEADLINE>
KOBE GETS PIPPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Psychological warfare didn't work, so Phil
Jackson took a different approach to stopping his onetime protege,
Scottie Pippen, in Game 3 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' coach used the best weapon he had left: Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson switched defensive assignments, placing Bryant -- the
Lakers' best open-court defender -- on Pippen, the Portland Trail
Blazers' best and most creative open-court player, to start the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant opened this series guarding Damon Stoudamire, but Pippen
forced the issue by punishing the Lakers with 21 points and 11
rebounds in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   It was a matchup Bryant relished. He went out of his way to ask
for the assignment last year in the playoffs, when Pippen was
playing for the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bryant) didn't say anything to me about it,'' Jackson
said. ``He wanted to play him at the start of this series.''
</P>
<P>
   With Pippen acting in the role of point guard at times in Game
2, Jackson said the move was designed ``to try and stem their
attack early on. And Scottie's represented that for them. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's a guy who moves his feet the best from the starting
crew out there, so we picked him to go against Damon, because we
anticipated that frontal attack that they give you through him is
the one that could hurt us potentially the most, and has during the
course of the season in the opening parts of the game. But that's
been pretty limited by Damon's inability to play him the last game
through the fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy produced mixed results. Pippen scored just four
points in the first half, while Stoudamire, working initially
against Ron Harper, scored nine points in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Good gauge: Jackson didn't even try to downplay the magnitude of
this weekend's two-game set in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a critical point of our year,'' he said. ``You
know, find out how well we're going to do when odds are against us,
chips are down and we've got to come back from a disappointing
loss. How we right ourselves. This is a real important weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to them is that we gave (the Blazers) a lot of
momentum coming out of Game 2 and it depends upon how quickly we
find a way to stem that momentum is how quickly we get back in this
series again and carry that home-court advantage again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Rookie swingman Devean George was diagnosed with a
severely sprained left ankle and did not make the trip, leaving the
Lakers with only 11 players in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   George, who injured himself in practice Thursday, will not join
the team this weekend. He is scheduled to visit team orthopedist
Dr. Stephen Lombardo early next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
