u k BC-EDIT-TOUR-BUSES-NYT &LR;      05-26 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOUR-BUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DOUBLE-DECKER MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Walker, a 71-year-old actor, had the right of way on
Monday afternoon when a large red New York Apple Tours bus ran him
over at a corner crosswalk.
</P>
<P>
   The bus driver did not have a proper license. The bus was not
supposed to be turning onto a side street. The tour company that
owns the bus has been issued 1,800 summonses for traffic
violations, many for reckless driving. The buses, imported from
Britain, have had trouble meeting national safety and environmental
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Given this appalling record, the question is why it has taken
the death of an innocent person to finally persuade New York City
to ask an administrative law judge for an immediate suspension of
the company's license.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood activists in the areas near Broadway and Times
Square have been protesting these oversized vehicles since they
first appeared almost eight years ago. The main complaints have
been that the buses pollute the air when they are idling, then
threaten life and limb when they hurtle down side streets.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents suspect the city has ignored their complaints
because it is more interested in promoting tourism. They have a
point, especially when the same city administration has cracked
down on drunken drivers, motorists blocking traffic, speeding taxis
and wayward pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's death should have given this problem more urgency, but
an administrative law judge for the Department of Consumer Affairs
delayed even a temporary suspension of the company's license Friday
until after the Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, protesters have been trying to scare bewildered
tourists away from the Apple Tour bus loading areas, and city and
state officials are dickering about who has authority to suspend
quickly any operation with this many bad marks against it.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility that should be examined is revoking the
Department of Transportation license that allows buses to pick up
and discharge passengers. That license can be revoked for chronic
violation of traffic rules, which is certainly the case here. State
agencies that control licensing, insurance and emissions standards
should also be working to make certain vehicles are not operated in
an unsafe manner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, these big red machines should not be out there on the
city streets. Though they delight sightseers who ride them, they
menace those on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-00 2340EDT &QL; 
