<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS WALK TO 5-2 VICTORY OVER CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Despite a few standout individual performances, the
New York Mets have been a mediocre offensive team. Coming into
Friday night's game against the St. Louis Cardinals, they ranked
12th out of 16 National League clubs in runs scored and batting
average, 11th in homers and 10th in hits.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets know how to walk, just as they did last year. They
ranked second in the league in walks, and they drew nine Friday
night. The Mets strolled away with a 5-2 victory, the fourth in a
row for the starter Mike Hampton, who also contributed with his
bat, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (6-4) went eight innings, allowing two runs on nine hits
and two walks, lowering his earned-run average to 3.99. He also had
two singles and a sacrifice fly, improving his batting average to
.296.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied, 2-2, in the seventh inning, Cardinals
reliever Mark Thompson walked Derek Bell, Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike
Piazza with two outs. That brought up Robin Ventura, who singled to
right off left-hander Mike Mohler, scoring two runs. Ventura is now
batting .364 in his career with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   That was the second Mets rally aided by three two-out walks.
With two outs in the first, Alfonzo doubled off the wall in
left-center. Cardinals starter Pat Hentgen threw 12 balls and a
strike to the next three hitters _ Piazza, Ventura and Todd Zeile _
and the walks forced in Alfonzo with the game's first run. But
Benny Agbayani struck out looking, leaving the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Four batters into the Cardinals' first, the bases were loaded
again in similar fashion. Edgar Renteria doubled down the
left-field line, and consecutive walks by Hampton loaded the bases.
It was a good time for Hampton to be wild _ he walked the most
dangerous Cardinals, Jim Edmonds and Mark McGwire _ but it brought
up Eric Davis, who had six hits in 10 career at-bats off Hampton
coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's ability to induce ground balls makes him less
concerned about walks, and he showed why against Davis. Davis
grounded to shortstop Rey Ordonez, who started an inning-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals loaded the bases again in the second inning, on
three two-out singles, but again Hampton escaped trouble, getting
Edgar Renteria to strike out on a checked swing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets (26-22) were having little luck against Hentgen _
besides a single Hampton chopped over the infield in the second _
but they manufactured a run in an unusual way in the fourth.
Agbayani grounded a single to right to lead off the inning, then
stole second when Hentgen threw Ordonez a curveball.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was on deck, and his average was more than .100 better
than Ordonez's. So instead of having Ordonez swing away, Manager
Bobby Valentine called for a sacrifice bunt, which Ordonez
executed. Hampton then came up and delivered the sacrifice fly to
left, giving the Mets a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (28-19) got a run back on a ground out in the
fourth, then tied the score in the fifth when Jim Edmonds led off
with a mammoth home run to right center, his 16th of a blistering
season that recently earned him a six-year contract extension worth
nearly $10 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   Joe McEwing made his first appearance at Busch Stadium since the
Cardinals traded him in spring training. He was sought before the
game by round after round of Cardinals employees, greeting each
warmly. A sign above the last row of seats read, ``We Miss U Joe,''
and the bidding started at $75 for an autographed McEwing photo at
a Cardinals auction.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing received a prolonged ovation as he came to bat to lead
off the game. The crowd's cheering droned out his name as it was
announced, and many fans stood in recognition of his strong '99
season, when he impressed fans and teammates with his hustle.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing's attitude has endeared himself to the Mets. ``His
approach is refreshing in that he's always into it,'' Valentine
said. ``He seems to be always enjoying it.'' But McEwing has not
hit much as a Met. He went 3 for 4 with a home run last Sunday, but
just 4 for 29 in all other games before Friday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
