<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MEXICAN CANDIDATES CLASH IN HIGH-STAKES DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The three leading presidential candidates clashed
in a harsh nationally televised debate Friday night that all three
acknowledged was crucial to their chances in the July 2 balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter came after a week of unusual on-camera
confrontations between the candidates as they struggled to decide
whether to hold the debate at all. By midweek, when they finally
agreed on the debate Friday night, it had become the focal point of
the race and had proved that television was wielding new power in
the quickly changing and highly competitive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes were highest for Vicente Fox Quesada, the strongest
opposition candidate, who faced off for 90 minutes with Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, the ruling party candidate, and Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas Solorzano, a leftist contender who has been running far
behind the other two. Earlier this week Fox dismayed voters with a
show of pique aired on live television during a meeting with his
rivals, knocking momentum from his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of his campaign feared that if Fox failed to repair
his image in the debate, he could never recover the lead he held
briefly earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Fox opened by attempting to explain the intransigence he
demonstrated before the videocameras on Tuesday, when he tried to
force the other two candidates to hold the debate that same night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people thought I was a little stubborn,'' Fox said.
``Even my mother said that. But it takes character and firmness to
put an end to 70 years of corruption and poverty,'' he said,
referring to the seven decades that Labastida's Institutional
Revolutionary Party has held presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   Fox came on with a battery of positive proposals to support
small business, create equal opportunities for women and improve
education. He tried to stay away from the blunt, cowboy-style
insults to Labastida that marked a first debate on April 25, which
included all six presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida sought to stay away from negative attacks and stressed
that he represents ``change with certainty, no going back, no leaps
into the void.''
</P>
<P>
   A surprisingly aggressive tack was taken by Cardenas, who is
running for president for the third time. Cardenas kept swinging at
both of his rivals throughout the debate, although he targeted his
most sustained criticism at Labastida and the PRI government.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Labastida and President Ernesto Zedillo of managing
the economy ``only to seek personal profit.'' He came down hard
against an $80 billion bank bailout that he said was the product of
a corrupt alliance between Fox's National Action Party and the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   After Cardenas and Labastida allied against Fox earlier in the
week to agree to hold the debate on Friday night, many Mexicans had
the impression that the two were somehow allied. Cardenas went out
of his way to dispel that notion.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll commissioned by The Dallas Morning News that was
published Friday, Labastida and Fox are tied at 33 percent and
Cardenas has 19 points, a nine-point surge over where he stood as
recently as two weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
